<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>[Romance of Alexander the Great.]<LB>[<I>MS. Ashmole</I> 44;<MILESTONE N="1a" UNIT="folio">]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHen folk ere festid &amp; fed &middot; fayn wald &thorn;ai here</L>
<L>Sum farand &thorn;ing efter fode &middot; to fayn &thorn;are her[t],</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ai ware fourmed on fold &middot; or &thorn;aire fadirs o&thorn;er.</L>
<L N="4">Sum is leue to lythe &middot; &thorn;e lesing of Sayntis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lete &thorn;er lifis be lorne &middot; for oure lordis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lord = lordis <I>perhaps.</I></NOTE> sake;</L>
<L>And sum has langing of lufe &middot; lays to herken,</L>
<L>How ledis for &thorn;aire lemmans &middot; has langor endured.</L>
<L N="8">Sum couettis &amp; has comforth &middot; to carpe &amp; to lestyn</L>
<L>Of curtaissy of kny&yogh;thode &middot; of craftis of armys,</L>
<L>Of kyngis at has conquirid &middot; &amp; ouer-comyn landis.</L>
<L>Sum of wirschip I-wis &middot; slike as &thorn;am wyse lattis,</L>
<L N="12">And sum of wanton werkis &middot; &thorn;a &thorn;at ere wild-hedid;</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai wald on many wyse &middot; a wondire ware it els;</L>
<L>For as &thorn;aire wittis ere with-in &middot; so &thorn;er will folowis.</L>
<L>And I forwith &yogh;ow all &middot; ettillis to schewe</L>
<L>Of ane Emperoure &thorn;e a&yogh;efullest &middot; &thorn;at euer armys hauntid,</L>
<L N="17">&THORN;at was &thorn;e athill Alexsandire &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a&yogh;te euyn as his awyn &middot; all the werd ouire.</L>
<L>For he recouerd quills he regnyd &middot; &thorn;e regions all clene,</L>
<L N="20">And all rialme &amp; &thorn;e riches &middot; in-to &thorn;e rede est.</L>
<L>I sall rehers, &amp; &yogh;e will, renkis &middot; rekyn &yogh;our tongis,</L>
<L>A remnant of his rialte &middot; &amp; rist quen vs likis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oute in &thorn;e erth of Egipt &middot; enhabet vmquile</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e wysest wees of the werd &middot; as I in writt fynd.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai &thorn;e mesure &amp; &thorn;e mett &middot; of all &thorn;e mulde couthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sise of all &thorn;e grete see &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e grym wawys;
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ordere of &thorn;at odde home &middot; &thorn;at ouer &thorn;e aire hingis</L>
<L N="28">Knew &thorn;e kynd, &amp; &thorn;e curses &middot; of &thorn;e clere sternys,</L>
<L>Of Articus the aghill &middot; tre<NOTE PLACE="foot">So in MS.; <I>read</I> athille &middot; thre.</NOTE> airis &amp; o&thorn;ire</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fold &amp; of &thorn;e firmament &middot; wele &thorn;e fete cuthe;</L>
<L>And Antarticus also &middot; &thorn;at all<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> all.</NOTE> apon turnys,<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e pasage of &thorn;e planettis &middot; &thorn;e poyntis &amp; &thorn;e sygnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware &thorn;e kiddest of &thorn;at craft &middot; knawyn in &thorn;aire tyme,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sotellest vndere son &middot; segis in &thorn;aire lyfe.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ware &thorn;ai breued for &thorn;e best &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis;</L>
<L N="36">All &thorn;ai lerid of &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. '&thorn;at o,' <I>but</I> o <I>is expuncted</I>.</NOTE> lare &middot; &thorn;at it lere wald.</L>
<L>As wide as &thorn;e werd was &middot; went worde of &thorn;aire teching,</L>
<L>Of sorsery &amp; slike werkis &middot; sle&yogh;tis enogh.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;at contre &middot; was a clerke noble,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;e athelest ane of &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; Anec was hatten.</L>
<L>He was wyse eno&yogh;e &middot; wirdis to reken,</L>
<L>When he &thorn;e heuyn beheld &middot; of lede[s] opon lyfe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e iapis of all gemetri &middot; gentilli he couth,</L>
<L N="44">And wele as Aristotill &middot; &thorn;e artis all seuyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;er preued neuer nane his prik &middot; for passing of witt,</L>
<L>Plato nor Piktagaras &middot; ne Prektane him seluen.</L>
<L>Emang his duykis on a day &middot; as he on dese syttis,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;an was him bodword vnblyth &middot; bro&yogh;t to &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Artaxenses was armed &middot; with &thorn;e men of his rewme,</L>
<L>&THORN;e proude king of Persy &middot; to pase him agayn.</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh;e he &thorn;a sawis herd say &middot; &yogh;it samyd he na princis,</L>
<L N="52">Ne ost ordand he nane &middot; of na kyd kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Bot airis euen furth him ane &middot; &amp; entirs his chambre,</L>
<L>To knaw by his clergi &middot; &thorn;e come of his faa.</L>
<L>He takis a Boll of bras &middot; burneschid full clene,</L>
<L>And full he fillis it of the flode &middot; at fell fra &thorn;e heuen.</L>
<L N="57">On hi&yogh;t in his a hand<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hand hand, <I>the latter underlined</I>.</NOTE> &middot; haldis a wand,</L>
<L>And kenely be coniurisons &middot; callis to him spritis.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;is water as he waitis &middot; was he ware sone
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="3"></L>
<L N="60">Of his enmys in &thorn;at Element &middot; ane endles nombre;</L>
<L>He sa&yogh;e &thorn;am in &thorn;e hi&yogh;e see &middot; sailand to-gedire,<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Was neuer sene slike a some &middot; vnder &thorn;e son bemys.</L>
<L>Carrygis comand he knew &middot; keruand &thorn;e ithis,</L>
<L N="64">Dromonds dryfes ouer &thorn;e depe &middot; with dukis &amp; Erles,</L>
<L>Gales &amp; grete schipis &middot; full of grym wapens,</L>
<L>And full of breneid bernes &middot; bargis a hundreth,</L>
<L>Of slik a naue is noy &middot; to here or to tell.</L>
<L N="68">For all &thorn;e largenes of lenth &middot; at he luke my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Slik was &thorn;e multitude of mast &middot; so mekil &amp; so thike,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all him &thorn;o&yogh;t bot he treis &middot; a hare wod it semyd.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e enteris of Egipt &middot; as Anec had beden,</L>
<L N="72">Ware peris of his prouynce &middot; &amp; princes of his cytes,</L>
<L>Was comandid of &thorn;aire kyng &middot; to kepe &thorn;a landis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nane aproche it to paire &middot; of Persy ne othire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was a wardan ware &middot; oute in &thorn;e wale stremys</L>
<L N="76">Of all &thorn;e naue &amp; &thorn;e note &middot; I neuenyd be-fore;</L>
<L>La&yogh;t li&yogh;tly his ledis &middot; &amp; leuys his warde,</L>
<L>Comes to courte to &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; on kneys fallis,</L>
<L>Anec bi his awyn name &middot; he onane gretis,</L>
<L N="80">Sais, "&yogh;are &thorn;e now &yogh;apely &middot; or &yogh;ild vp &thorn;i rewme;</L>
<L>Artaxenses is at hand &middot; &amp; has ane ost reryd,</L>
<L>And resyn vp with all his rewme &middot; to ride vs agayn;</L>
<L>For he him-self is on &thorn;e se &middot; with siche a somme armed,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at any hathill vnder heuen &middot; ware hardy to rekyn.</L>
<L>For &thorn;er is comyn with him kny&yogh;t[es]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kny&yogh;t.</NOTE> &middot; of landis dyuerse,</L>
<L>Segis of many syde &middot; oute of sere remys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e perseyns &amp; a pupill &middot; &thorn;at parthy<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. panthy.</NOTE> is callid,</L>
<L N="88">Men of Mesepotayme &middot; &amp; of Mede bathe,</L>
<L>Of Syre &amp; of Sychim &middot; a selle nounbre,</L>
<L>Of Capidos &amp; Caldec &middot; kene men of armes,</L>
<L>Fell fe&yogh;tand folke &middot; &thorn;at Faire we call,<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">&THORN;e Arrabiens &amp; all &thorn;a &middot; [of] &thorn;at origyne,</L>
<L>Bernys out of Batary &middot; batails arayed,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ire out of &thorn;e orient &middot; many od hundrethe."
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;en Anec onane ri&yogh;t &middot; efter &thorn;ire wordis,</L>
<L N="96">A lowde la&yogh;ter he lo&yogh;e &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e lede said,</L>
<L>"Haue &thorn;ou na care," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "bot kepe to &thorn;e marche,</L>
<L>As I have demyd &thorn;e to do &middot; &amp; dred &thorn;ou na ferryre;</L>
<L>For soth it is vnsemely<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. vmsemely.</NOTE> &middot; slike sawis of a prynce.</L>
<L N="100">I kan no&yogh;t knaw at &thorn;ou carpis &middot; as a kny&yogh;t suld,</L>
<L>Bot as a frek at ware ferid &middot; &amp; feynes ri&yogh;t nowe.</L>
<L>Ert &thorn;ou no&yogh;t hurtles &amp; hale? &middot; lat no&yogh;t &thorn;i hert faile.</L>
<L N="103">For vertu vailes no&yogh;t all &middot; if &thorn;ou avaied worthe,</L>
<L>Emang &thorn;e multitude<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. multitudo.</NOTE> of men &middot; quare mane ere togeder,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;er aboute as &thorn;ai ere blend &middot; with bignes of will.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai be folke bot a fa &middot; oft tydis &thorn;am &thorn;e better.</L>
<L>Or elis wate &thorn;ou no&yogh;t wele &middot; &thorn;e witles berne,</L>
<L N="108">How it is comonly carped &middot; in contries a-boute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at anelepy leon &middot; &thorn;at ouer &thorn;e land rynnys,</L>
<L>Will make to fange to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t &middot; &amp; flay many hertis?"</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e segge<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. 'gegge,' but the line is marked for correction.</NOTE> all him selfe &middot; silis to his chambre,</L>
<L N="112">And in &thorn;e brasen boll &middot; full [of] blak watere</L>
<L>He shapis him of shire wax &middot; litill schipis many,</L>
<L>And &yogh;apely &yogh;arkid in his hand &middot; a &yogh;erd of a palme.</L>
<L>&THORN;en con he chater &amp; enchant &middot; with all his chefe mi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="116">A-vysid him in &thorn;e vessell &middot; &amp; was avaied sone,</L>
<L>How &thorn;e powere out of Persy &middot; pellid doune his kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>And how his land suld be lost &middot; withouten lett mare.</L>
<L>When he was ware of &thorn;is wathe &middot; how it worthe suld,<MILESTONE N="3a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;an wendis he wi&yogh;tly furth &middot; &amp; his wede changis,</L>
<L>Clede him all as a clerke &middot; &amp; his croune shauys,</L>
<L>And with a bytand blade &middot; he his bered voydis.</L>
<L>&THORN;en takis to him tresour &middot; &amp; trusses in baggis,</L>
<L N="124">As many Besandis on his bake &middot; as he bere mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ire necessari notis &middot; as nedis to his craftis,</L>
<L>To sike salmary dangell &middot; as him self vyses.</L>
<L>He toke traimmes him with &middot; to tute in &thorn;e sternes,
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="5"></L>
<L N="128">Astralabus<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Astralalus.</NOTE> algate &middot; as his arte wald,</L>
<L>Quadrentis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. In adrentes.</NOTE> coruen all of quyte &middot; siluyre full quaynte,</L>
<L>Mustours &amp; mekil quat &middot; mare &thorn;en a littill.</L>
<L>When he was gra&thorn;ed with his gere &middot; a gladen he waytis,</L>
<L N="132">And passis fur&thorn;e at a Posterne &middot; preualy alane,</L>
<L>Fur&thorn;e on his fete withouten fole &middot; he passis his way,</L>
<L>Vn-wetandly to any wee &middot; &thorn;at wont in his wanes.</L>
<L>&THORN;us airis he out of Egipte &middot; &amp; his erde leuys,</L>
<L N="136">Fled for ferd of his fais &middot; fere fra his kythis,</L>
<L>It was na bote him to bide &middot; ne batill to &yogh;elde;</L>
<L>For all his kyngdome he knew &middot; suld be kast vnder.</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e partis of Persy &middot; he past bot a littill,</L>
<L N="140">And euyn so &thorn;ur&yogh;e Ethyope &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar him eft clethis,</L>
<L>All his liche in lyn cla&thorn;e &middot; for ledis suld trowe</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e puple persayue &middot; a prophete<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. proplete.</NOTE> he were.</L>
<L>&THORN;en metis he furthe to Messadon &middot; full vn-mete gatis,</L>
<L N="144">And quen he come to &thorn;at kith &middot; as &thorn;e chance tellis,</L>
<L>Oft with his instrumentis out &middot; he openly deuynes,</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er hild he it ne hid &middot; bot here qua sa likid.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an was methe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> meche.</NOTE> for to mele &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e men of his bur&yogh;,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at he by-hind him at hame &middot; withoute hede leuyd.<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Slik care kindils in his curte &middot; quen &thorn;ai &thorn;er kyng myssid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it ware tere any tonge &middot; of &thorn;ar tene to reken;</L>
<L>Princes of his palas &middot; preses in-to chambre,</L>
<L N="152">To laite &thorn;ar lord at was lost &middot; with latis vn-blythe;</L>
<L>Kairis in-to closettis &middot; kny&yogh;tis &amp; Erlis,</L>
<L>Sekand &thorn;ar souerayn &middot; with many salt terys;</L>
<L>Barons &amp; bachelers &middot; balefully gretis,</L>
<L N="156">Swiers swemyle &middot; swouned ladys,</L>
<L>And many was &thorn;e bald berne &middot; at banned &thorn;ar quile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer he dured &thorn;at day &middot; vndede opon erthe.</L>
<L>Bot quen &thorn;ai wist he was went &middot; &amp; wald no&yogh;t be foun,</L>
<L>Couth &thorn;ai na bote &thorn;am ebland &middot; how best for to wirke,</L>
<L N="161">Bot silis to ser Sirraphis &middot; at sittis in his trone,
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;ar god al&thorn;ire-graythist &middot; on &thorn;e ground samen.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ai supplyed &amp; so&yogh;t &middot; &amp; him ensence castis,</L>
<L N="164">Honourd him with offyrings &middot; &amp; elkend him fayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld say &thorn;am &thorn;e sothe &middot; &amp; sorely &thorn;am teche</L>
<L>Queder &thorn;aire kyng was becomen &middot; at &thorn;ar care kyndils.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd Syraphis him selfe &middot; he sayd &thorn;am &thorn;ir wordis:</L>
<L N="168">"Anec, &yogh;our athill kyng &middot; is out of his awyn land,</L>
<L>For Artaxenses a&yogh;e &middot; is all him ane foundid,</L>
<L>&THORN;e proude kyng of Persee &middot; &thorn;at passes vs a-gaynes.</L>
<L>Full wele he wist, or he went &middot; quat suld wor&thorn;e efter,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e fourme of &thorn;e fare &middot; &thorn;at fall &yogh;ow be-houys.</L>
<L N="173">For all &thorn;e erth of Egipt &middot; fra end vn-to othire</L>
<L>Bees conquirid &amp; ouercomyn &middot; clene alto-gedre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple out of Perse &middot; is purvaid all samen;<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="176">&THORN;e kyng is comand full kene &middot; with his kene ostis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sall oure renkis all rayme &middot; &amp; oure rewme bathe,</L>
<L>And we be all at &thorn;are will &middot; &thorn;us is wirdis schapen.</L>
<L>Sen it is sett to be soo &middot; &amp; slipe it ne may,</L>
<L N="180">Ne schewid to be na no&thorn;ire schap &middot; ne we to schount nouthire,</L>
<L>Bot gefe &thorn;aim vp &thorn;e girdill &middot; vs gaynes no&yogh;t ellis.</L>
<L>Bot seses, seris, of &yogh;our syte &middot; &amp; soru&yogh;es na mare;</L>
<L>For certayn," quod Syraphis &middot; "my-selfe I it knawe,</L>
<L N="184">&YOGH;our king sall in a no&thorn;ire kithe &middot; kast out his elde,</L>
<L>And come a-gayn eft &yogh;onge man &middot; &yogh;it to his rewme.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;at victoure &yogh;ow venge &middot; on &yogh;our vile fais,</L>
<L N="187">And &thorn;e province of Persee &middot; purely distruye,</L>
<L>And gett agayn his avyn gronde &middot; at he forgais nowe,</L>
<L>And ane of &thorn;e oddist Emperours &middot; of &thorn;e werde worthe."</L>
<L>&para; When he &thorn;is talis had tald &middot; &thorn;en tuke &thorn;ai be-lyfe,</L>
<L>And efter Anec on-ane &middot; ane ymage gert make;</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;e buke sais, of blake stane &middot; all &thorn;e bode ouyre,</L>
<L>With corone &amp; with conyschantis &middot; as it a kynge were.</L>
<L>Quen it was perfite &amp; pi&yogh;t &middot; a place &thorn;ai it wayted,</L>
<L>And stallid him in a stoute stede &middot; &amp; sti&yogh;thed him faire.</L>
<L N="196">Lordis lift him on loft &middot; &amp; lawe to him bowid,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>In reuerence of &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; at had &thorn;er rewme gydid.</L>
<L>Quen he was semely vp set &middot; with septour in hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;en ledis at ware lettird &middot; on lawe at his feet<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fortes; <I>cf.</I> 'at his feete' <I>in</I> Alex. A. 570.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">All &thorn;e sawis of &thorn;aire Syre &middot; as Siraphis tald,</L>
<L>&THORN;are gan &thorn;ai graithly &thorn;am graue &middot; in golden lettirs,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e wordis at he &thorn;aim werpid &middot; of &thorn;aire ware kynge.</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;ai wrate &thorn;am I-wis &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Supposand &thorn;aim in sum tyme &middot; for sothe to be knawen,</L>
<L N="205">And men to make of &thorn;am mynd &middot; euer-mare efter.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at &thorn;aire enmes &thorn;ar erde &middot; was entird with-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;e powere oute of Persee &middot; with many proude ostes;</L>
<L N="208">Bot of &thorn;ar batails to brefe &middot; it botis me na ferrire.</L>
<L>For all &thorn;ai conquirid clene &middot; &thorn;is cithe at &thorn;aire will,<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And Anec<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Anes.</NOTE> is all his ane &middot; ferre of his awyn landis,</L>
<L>With-in &thorn;e merris of Messedoyn &middot; &thorn;ar na man him knewe.</L>
<L N="212">Bot will &yogh;e herken hende &middot; now sall &yogh;e here</L>
<L>How he kide him in &thorn;e courete &middot; &amp; quayntid him with ladis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Secundus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syre, it be-tid on a tyme &middot; &thorn;e text me recordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e mode kynge of Messedone &middot; with mekill nounbre,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;at was sire Philip &thorn;e fers &middot; farne out of toune,</L>
<L>For to fe&yogh;t with his fais &middot; out of fere landis.</L>
<L>Quen he was boune oute of bur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; his bake turned,</L>
<L>As tite as Anec him amed &middot; out of his awyn kythe,</L>
<L N="220">He paste vp to &thorn;e Palais &middot; &amp; preualy entirs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t lend &thorn;are on loft &middot; &amp; luke on &thorn;e qwene.</L>
<L>Sone as him selfe was in &thorn;e sale &middot; &amp; sa&yogh;e hire with e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>He beheld Olympadas &middot; &thorn;at honourable lady;</L>
<L N="224">Hire bewte bitis in his brest &middot; &amp; his bodi thrillis,</L>
<L>And drifes thur&yogh;e his depe hert &middot; as he ware dart|wondid.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lede lawid in hire lofe &middot; as leme dose of gledis,</L>
<L>Put vp his hand to his hare &middot; &amp; heldid it bot littill.</L>
<L N="228">"Haile, modi qwene of Messidoyne" &middot; he maister-like said;</L>
<L>&THORN;are deyned him na daynte &middot; 'madame' hire to call,</L>
<L>Be-cause he knew him a kyng &middot; he carpid on &thorn;is wyse.</L>
<L>For if he come as A clerke &middot; with a croune schauyn,</L>
<L N="232">And di&yogh;t as a Doctour &middot; in drabland wedis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it all &thorn;e erth of Egipt &middot; had he bene aire ouire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an answars him &thorn;e qwene &middot; with full myld speche,</L>
<L>"Haile, maister," quod &thorn;at myld &middot; &amp; made him to sytt</L>
<L N="236">On a sege hire be-syde &middot; of silkyn clathis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar hire spakid with his speche &middot; &amp; spird of him wordis.</L>
<L>Quen he was sete in his sete &middot; &thorn;at semely qwene</L>
<L>Ai of Egipt erd &middot; enquirid if he were,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;o&yogh;t him like of &thorn;at lede &middot; be langage &amp; othire;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i scho wetis if he wald &middot; wete hire to say.<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"A! athel qwene," quod Anec &middot; "ai be &thorn;ou ioyed!</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou a wirschipfull worde &middot; has werpid &amp; spoken,</L>
<L N="244">A riall roune &thorn;ou me redis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. redis a redis; <I>the two latter words underlined</I>.</NOTE> &middot; a reson of blis,</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;ou mynnys of &thorn;at marche &middot; &amp; with &thorn;i mouth tellis.</L>
<L>For &thorn;are enhabetis in &thorn;at erd &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou are sayd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wisest wees in &thorn;is werd &middot; &thorn;e welken vndire.</L>
<L N="248">For &thorn;ai can swyth of a sweuyn &middot; all &thorn;e swepe tell,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ire it be sele or soro&yogh;e &middot; in a sete quile,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai can certifi &amp; se &middot; by sygnes of &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>Quat sall be-fall a-pon fold &middot; with-inen a fewe &yogh;erys.</L>
<L>Sum vndirstandis in a stounde &middot; &thorn;e steuen of &thorn;e briddis,</L>
<L N="253">To say &thorn;e by &thorn;ar sapience &middot; quat &thorn;ar sange menys;</L>
<L>Sum can &thorn;i consaile declare &middot; &thorn;ofe &thorn;ou it carpid neuire,</L>
<L>&THORN;e poyntis of all &thorn;i preuates &middot; pertly can schewe.</L>
<L N="256">Sum can &thorn;e brefe be-life &middot; &thorn;e birth of &thorn;ine childire,</L>
<L>Be it hee, be [it] scho &middot; haly &thorn;are werdes.</L>
<L>And if I say it my-selfe &middot; slik sotellte I haue,
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>Sa clere a witt &amp; sa clene &middot; my creatoure I lofe,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at all &thorn;e notis at I neuyn &middot; nobly I can,</L>
<L>As any prophet a-perte &middot; to proue &yogh;ow &thorn;e sothe."</L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;ire sawis had sayd &middot; he in his sege lened,</L>
<L>In stody still as a stane &middot; &amp; starid in hire face,</L>
<L N="264">Beheld haterly &thorn;at hend &middot; &thorn;at had his hert percid,</L>
<L>With depe desire of delite &middot; ay on &thorn;at dere waytis.</L>
<L>Sone as hire selfe it sawe &middot; at he hire sa behaldis,</L>
<L>&THORN;en scho talkis him to &middot; &amp; titely him fraynes:</L>
<L N="268">"Quare-on muse &yogh;e sa mekill, maister?" scho sayd;</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e behald me sa hogely &middot; quare-on is &yogh;our mynd?"</L>
<L>"My frely fode," quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "no&yogh;t bot &thorn;e werdes</L>
<L N="271">Of my gracious goddis &middot; &thorn;e grettest on erde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai haue tald me be-for &thorn;is tyme &middot; &thorn;at now I trew fynd,</L>
<L>How I suld<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. I suld I suld; <I>the two latter words underlined</I>.</NOTE> lenge in a land &middot; &amp; loke on a qwene."</L>
<L>&THORN;an out of his bosom he brayd &middot; a blesand table<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of Euour &amp; of othire &thorn;ingis &middot; odly fourmed,</L>
<L N="276">Of bras &amp; of brynt gold &middot; &amp; o[f] bri&yogh;t siluer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thre serclis sere &middot; in it selfe had.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e first compas I ken &middot; as me &thorn;e claus tellis,</L>
<L>Stude &thorn;e xij vndirstandings &middot; stoutly engrauen.</L>
<L N="280">In &thorn;is o&thorn;ir dra&yogh;t ware deuysid &middot; a dusan of bestis,</L>
<L>And semely sett was in &thorn;e thrid &middot; &thorn;e son &amp; &thorn;e mone.</L>
<L>Sethen he clekis out of a cas &middot; vij clere sternes</L>
<L>To tell him takens of &thorn;e tymes &middot; &amp; talis of our werdis;</L>
<L N="284">And vij stele-grauyn stanys &middot; &amp; stoute o&thorn;ire tway,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald for hurte or for harme &middot; any hathill kepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;us as he tuke furth his toylis &middot; &amp; his trammys<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. tranmys.</NOTE> schewis,</L>
<L>"If I sall lefe on &thorn;i lare" &middot; quod &thorn;e leue qwene,</L>
<L N="288">"Say me &thorn;e day &amp; &thorn;e same &yogh;ere &middot; &amp; &thorn;e selfe tyme</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e birth of &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; &thorn;at I best lufe."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answars Anec onane &middot; sayd, "is &thorn;ar o&yogh;t ellis</L>
<L>At &yogh;e wald, hend, of me here &middot; or at &yogh;oure hert willis?</L>
<L N="292">For any cas &thorn;at is to com<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. con.</NOTE> &middot; to knaw if &thorn;e likis,
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>I sall as namely &yogh;ow neuyn &middot; as it ware nowe done."</L>
<L>"&THORN;an will I," quod &thorn;e wale qwene &middot; "&yogh;e wete me to say,</L>
<L>Quat me &amp; Philip &middot; sall fall vs be-twene.</L>
<L N="296">For, bow he fra &thorn;e bataill &middot; bernys me tell,</L>
<L>&THORN;en will he wed ano&thorn;ire wife &middot; &amp; wayfe me for euer."</L>
<L>"Nay, no&yogh;t for ay," quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "&thorn;ar haue &thorn;ai fals spoken;</L>
<L>Neuer &thorn;e latter, or o&yogh;t lange &middot; sall lymp as &thorn;ou sayd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Line 300 precedes 1. 299 in the MS., but they are marked for transposition.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it I fynd, for all his fare &middot; fleme he sall &thorn;e to&thorn;ire,</L>
<L N="301">And wild &yogh;our self to will &middot; nyll he so will he."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was a-wondird of his wordis &middot; &thorn;e worthe lady,</L>
<L>Be-so&yogh;t sekirly &thorn;is sire &middot; if he safe vouchid,<MILESTONE N="6a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at scho my&yogh;t weterly wete &middot; &thorn;e will of all &thorn;ingis,</L>
<L N="305">Quatkyn poynt or plyte &middot; predestend hire were.</L>
<L>"Athill qwene," quod Anec &middot; "as I am enfourmed,</L>
<L>Ane of &thorn;e grettist of oure godis &middot; of grace &amp; of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="308">I fynd, or it be fere &middot; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to &thorn;e; <I>with</I> &thorn;e <I>underlined</I>.</NOTE> fleschely &thorn;e knaw,</L>
<L>And efter in all aduersites &middot; is amed &thorn;e to help."</L>
<L>&THORN;an sayd Olympadas &middot; "now, honourable maister,</L>
<L>I be-seke &thorn;e, my sire &middot; if &thorn;ou me say wald,</L>
<L N="312">Quatkyn fygour on fold &middot; or fourme at he beris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at demyd is or destaned &middot; &thorn;is dede for to worche."</L>
<L>"&THORN;at will I wele," quod &thorn;e wee &middot; "&amp; no&yogh;t a word le&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;is my&yogh;ty god at I me[ne] &middot; is of a medill age,</L>
<L N="316">No&yogh;t of &yogh;outh nor of eld &middot; nor &yogh;erris to many,</L>
<L>Bot euyn so be-twene twa &middot; &amp; to [mekyll] of nouthire.</L>
<L>How he is merkid &amp; made &middot; is mervaile to neuyn,</L>
<L>With&mdash;tachid in his for-top&mdash; &middot; twa tufe<NOTE PLACE="foot">haris <I>inserted here, but struck out</I>.</NOTE> hornes;</L>
<L N="320">A berd as a besom &middot; with thyn bred haris,</L>
<L>A mouthe as a mastif<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. mastis.</NOTE> hunde &middot; vn-metely to shaw.</L>
<L>Bot, dame, if he be &thorn;us di&yogh;t &middot; drede &thorn;e neuer &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e be buxsom &amp; bayne &middot; &amp; boune to his will.</L>
<L N="324">Be ny&yogh;ter-tale he sall &thorn;e ne&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;is note to begyn,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="11"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e be merryd neuer &thorn;e mare &middot; bot mete him in sweuyn."</L>
<L>"Now certayn, sire," sayd &thorn;e qwene &middot; "selly me thinke.</L>
<L>Bot may I se &thorn;is be sothe &middot; at &yogh;e me say here,</L>
<L N="328">No&yogh;t as a prophet ne a prest &middot; I prays sall &thorn;i selfe,</L>
<L>Bot rehers &thorn;e as hie&yogh;e gode &middot; &amp; hie &thorn;e for euire."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at rysis vp &thorn;e renke &middot; &amp; his rowme lefys,</L>
<L>La&yogh;t leue at &thorn;e qwene &middot; for a litill quile,</L>
<L N="332">Gase him doune be &thorn;e grecis &middot; a-gayn fra &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L>Furthe to make his maistryse &middot; &amp; mose in his arte.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;us passis he fra &thorn;e place &middot; to proue his sle&yogh;tis,<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Silis furth all him selfe &middot; &thorn;e cyte with-outen,</L>
<L N="336">Drafe in-to a depe dissert &middot; &amp; drewe vp herbis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chosest for inchantement &middot; at he chese couthe.</L>
<L>Quen he had gedird his grese &middot; &amp; grune &thorn;aim esundire,</L>
<L>For Iapis of his gemetry &middot; &thorn;e ious out he wrengis,</L>
<L N="340">Erne till exor&yogh;ise &middot; &amp; ethis euer elike,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it suld worthe as he wald &middot; &amp; on na way faile.</L>
<L>He clatird on coniurisons &middot; &amp; calid to him deuyls,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e incheson of his charme &middot; with &thorn;at &thorn;e chefe qwene</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;e same ny&yogh;t in hire slep &middot; suld se with hire e&yogh;en</L>
<L>Amon hire awyn god &middot; in hire armes ligge,</L>
<L>And dreme at he didd hire swa &middot; &amp; quen he done hadd,</L>
<L N="347">&THORN;an suld he say to hire-selfe &middot; sadly &thorn;ire wordis,</L>
<L>"Now has &thorn;ou, woman, I-wys &middot; with-in &thorn;i twa sydis</L>
<L>Consayued him at in all &thorn;i care &middot; &thorn;i cors sall defend."</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilk euyn ouer-&yogh;ede &middot; &amp; arly on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>As arly as &thorn;e riche qwene &middot; was resyn fra slepe,</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;an efter Anec<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Anes.</NOTE> on-ane &middot; scho al aboute sendis,</L>
<L>Takis him betwene &thorn;am twa &middot; tald him hire sweuyn.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a," quod he, "comly qwene &middot; I couthe, &amp; &thorn;ou wald</L>
<L>Preualy in &thorn;i palais &middot; lat me a place haue,</L>
<L N="356">Make &thorn;e to se &thorn;e same gode &middot; &amp; &thorn;i-selfe wakand,</L>
<L>Face to face all his fourme &middot; &amp; his effecte clene.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>&THORN;is grete god full of grace &middot; sall glide to &thorn;i chambre,</L>
<L>In a dredfull deuys &middot; a dragons fourme,</L>
<L N="360">And &thorn;an &thorn;e figour of a freke &middot; he sall take eftire,</L>
<L>And preualy in &thorn;at part &middot; a-pere &yogh;owe be-forne."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answars him &thorn;e swete quene &middot; &amp; sone him it grantis,</L>
<L>"Sire, chese &thorn;e a chambre &middot; quare &thorn;e chefe &thorn;inkis,</L>
<L>Now&thorn;ire myne awen ne na nothire &middot; god lat &thorn;e no&yogh;t spare,<MILESTONE N="7a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="365">Or any place at &yogh;ow plece &middot; my palas with-in.</L>
<L>For may &thorn;ou hald me &thorn;is hest &middot; as &thorn;ou here tellis,</L>
<L>And profe &thorn;us in my presens &middot; as a propire sothe,</L>
<L>&THORN;en sall I cherische &thorn;e with chere &middot; as &thorn;ou my child were,</L>
<L N="369">Loute &thorn;e louely &amp; loue &middot; all my lyfe days."</L>
<L>"Graunt mercy," quod &thorn;e grete clerke &middot; to &thorn;e gude lady,</L>
<L>Thankis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Thangis, <I>altered to</I> Thankis.</NOTE> hire full thraly &middot; &amp; &thorn;en forth wendis</L>
<L N="372">To loke &amp; layte him a loge &middot; quare he lenge my&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. my&yogh;tes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And buske him a bedsted &middot; quare him best likid.</L>
<L>Qwen it was metyn to &thorn;e merke &middot; &thorn;at men ware to ryst,</L>
<L>And folke was on &thorn;aire firste slepe &middot; &amp; it was furth euyns,</L>
<L N="376">&THORN;an Anec on ane &middot; his artis he fandis,</L>
<L>And changid by enchantmentis &middot; his chere all to-gedire.</L>
<L>&THORN;er worthid he by his wiche-craft &middot; in-to a wild dragon,</L>
<L>And to the ladi lere &middot; he lendid in haste,</L>
<L N="380">Fli&yogh;and in his fethire-hames &middot; &amp; ferly fast sletis,</L>
<L>And in a braide, or he blan &middot; he &thorn;e bed entris.</L>
<L>Quen he was<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he was he was, <I>but corrected</I>.</NOTE> laide be-lyfe &middot; his liknes he changis,</L>
<L>Worthis agayn to a wee &middot; fra a worme turnys.</L>
<L>&THORN;en kisses he kenely &thorn;e quene &middot; &amp; clappis in armes,</L>
<L N="385">Langis sare to &thorn;e layke &middot; &amp; on-loft worthis.</L>
<L>Quen he had wro&yogh;t all his will &middot; hire wame &thorn;en he touches,</L>
<L N="387">And with a renyst reryd &middot; &thorn;is reson he said,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is concepcion with kyngis &middot; sal be callid here-efter
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>A verra victor a-vansid &middot; with all &thorn;e vayne werde."</L>
<L>&THORN;us be-gylid he this gude wyfe &middot; &amp; makis hire to wene</L>
<L>It ware na gett of na gome &middot; bot of god ane.</L>
<L N="392">Qwen &thorn;e day-raw rase &middot; he rysis be-lyfe,</L>
<L>Lendis a-lande fra &thorn;e loft &middot; &amp; left hire with child.</L>
<L>Sone as hire bele gun bolne &middot; all hire blee changis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. g changis (<I>sic</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="395">So was scho ferd &amp; a-fri&yogh;t &middot; a ferly ware ellis.<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To be bonden with barne &middot; mekill bale to hire ne&yogh;ehis,</L>
<L>For it &amp; Philip hire fere &middot; o-ferrom was sybb.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Anec hire awyn clerke &middot; scho on-ane callis,</L>
<L>"Lo, maister, slike a myschefe!" &middot; &amp; maynly hire pleynes.</L>
<L N="400">"I dred &thorn;at I nere dee &middot; bot &yogh;e me deme sone</L>
<L>Quat me is beste of &thorn;is case &middot; if euer &thorn;e kyng turne."</L>
<L>"Be no&yogh;t a-bayste," quod &thorn;e berne &middot; "ne a-bleyd nothire,</L>
<L>&THORN;are sall na chanche &thorn;e chefe &middot; &thorn;e charge of a pese.</L>
<L N="404">For Amon oure athill gode &middot; sall all-way &thorn;e helpe,</L>
<L>And kepe &thorn;e full careles &middot; if any cas fallis."</L>
<L>&para; Quat dose now &thorn;is diuinour &middot; bot to desert wendis,</L>
<L>Airis on all him ane &middot; out of &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L N="408">&YOGH;ede him furthe eftirsons &middot; herbis to seche,</L>
<L>Reft &thorn;am<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. him, <I>copied from line above.</I></NOTE> vp be &thorn;e rotis &middot; &amp; radly &thorn;am stampis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iuse for his gemetry<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gremetry.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;at Iogloure takis,</L>
<L>A[nd] sythen<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cythen.</NOTE> a brid of &thorn;e see &middot; him seluyn him fangis,</L>
<L N="412">Clatirs to hyre coynte &thorn;ingis &middot; kenely enchantis,</L>
<L>And [with] &thorn;e wose of &thorn;e wede &middot; hire wengis anoyntis;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;is demerlayke he did &middot; bot be &thorn;e deuyllis craftis,</L>
<L>How he my&yogh;t compas &amp; kast &middot; &thorn;e kynge to begyle.</L>
<L N="416">He wro&yogh;t a wondirfull wile &middot; &amp; will &yogh;e now here</L>
<L>How he be-glouird &thorn;is gome &middot; &amp; gilid him in sweuyn?</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilk Philip &thorn;e fyrs &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e fi&yogh;t lenges,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same ny&yogh;t in his slepe &middot; he sa&yogh;e, as him tho&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="14"></L>
<L N="420">Amon his awen god &middot; in armes with his qwene,</L>
<L>And make with hire market &middot; as [he] a man were.</L>
<L>And quen he wro&yogh;t had his will &middot; &thorn;en witrely him metis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bowes to hire belechiste &middot; &amp; bigly it sewys,</L>
<L N="424">And sethen asselis it him selfe &middot; semely &amp; faire</L>
<L>With a rede golde rynge &middot; on &thorn;is aray grayuyn;</L>
<L>A lyons heuyd was on-loft &middot; louely coruyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bounde of a bri&yogh;t son &middot; &amp; a brande kene.<MILESTONE N="8a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="428">And &thorn;en he went furth his way &middot; sayd, "woman, &thorn;ou hauys</L>
<L>&THORN;i full defendoure on fold &middot; now frely consa[u]yd."</L>
<L>Als radly as &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; rase on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L N="431">Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e dawyng of day &middot; a diuinour he callis,</L>
<L>And as him dremyd ilke a dele &middot; &thorn;at doctour he tellis,</L>
<L>And fraynes him fast on &thorn;is fare &middot; how it be-fall suld.</L>
<L>"Phylip," quod &thorn;e phylysofyre &middot; "&thorn;i fere is with childe,</L>
<L>And with no gett of na gome &middot; bot of god selfe.</L>
<L N="436">And, gudman, [on] &thorn;e gold rynge &middot; &thorn;e thre grauen thyngis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. y thynges (<I>sic</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai ere &thorn;us mekill to mene &middot; as me my mynd tellis.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e lyon hede," quod &thorn;e lede &middot; "&thorn;en licken I, on first,</L>
<L N="439">&THORN;e birth &thorn;at scho bere sall &middot; als best it be-semys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chefe sall to a chiftan &middot; &amp; slike a chefe maister,</L>
<L>As to be halden heuydman<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. heuysdman.</NOTE> &middot; of all &thorn;e hale werde.</L>
<L>Now sall I clerily declare &middot; &thorn;e course on &thorn;e sonne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at sygnyfys &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">ma <I>inserted, but struck out.</I></NOTE> same man &middot; &thorn;at sett is, be wird,</L>
<L N="444">So many prouynce to pas &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e prowis of armys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sall hit with his hede &middot; in-to &thorn;e heghe est.</L>
<L>Now<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. W Now; <I>with</I> W <I>expuncted.</I></NOTE> of &thorn;is bytand brand &middot; berne, will &yogh;e here;</L>
<L N="447">And all is bot &thorn;is hathill man &middot; as I are sayd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sall sa fele men afray &middot; with fauchon in hande,</L>
<L>And out of nounbre to neuyn &middot; of nacions wynn."</L>
<L>&THORN;an foundis Philip to &thorn;e fy&yogh;t &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fild entres,
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>And sone in delingis of dyntis &middot; a dragon aperis,</L>
<L N="452">&THORN;at stre&yogh;t be-for him in &thorn;e stoure &middot; strikis doune his faas,</L>
<L>And all his enmys in &thorn;at erd &middot; he endid in a stounde.</L>
<L>When Phylyp with his faire folke &middot; had &thorn;e fild won,</L>
<L>&THORN;an metis he him to Messadone &middot; &thorn;ar metis him &thorn;e qwene,</L>
<L N="456">Kyssis comly hire king &middot; &amp; of his come ioys,</L>
<L>And how he fore scho him fraynes &middot; ferly &yogh;erne.</L>
<L>"Wele, graunt mercy," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "my god, I him loue;<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot how &thorn;at &yogh;e ga sa<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> ga sa.</NOTE> grete &middot; gud dame?" he sayd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has ragid," quod &thorn;e renge &middot; "with vnryd gestis;</L>
<L N="461">Now hafe I, lede, all to lange &middot; lengid fra hame."</L>
<L>&THORN;us to bre hire o bourde &middot; he breuys &thorn;ire wordis;</L>
<L>"To quam has &thorn;ou &thorn;e tane till &middot; tell m[e] &thorn;e sothe?</L>
<L N="464">Outhire mete has mendid &thorn;e full mekill &middot; as may I no&yogh;t trowe,</L>
<L>Or ane has stollen in my stede &middot; sen I was stad &thorn;are."</L>
<L>&THORN;us bayst he &thorn;e bri&yogh;t qwene &middot; &thorn;at all hire ble changid,</L>
<L>To skyre skarlet hewe &middot; skyftis hire face,</L>
<L>Hire chere at was chalke-quyte &middot; as any chaffe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> chasse.</NOTE> worthis;</L>
<L N="469">So was scho schamed of &thorn;e schont &middot; &thorn;at hire &thorn;e schalk made.</L>
<L>"Nay, quod &thorn;e comly kyng &middot; "cache vp &thorn;ine hert,</L>
<L>&THORN;ofe &thorn;ou haue forfet, na force &middot; so has fele othire.</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;ou has giltid, bot no&yogh;t gretly &middot; it greuys me &thorn;e les;</L>
<L>For god has geten &thorn;e &thorn;is gett &middot; a-gaynes &thorn;i will;</L>
<L>All &thorn;at was done &thorn;e bedene &middot; was me be dreme schewyd,</L>
<L>I sa&yogh;e it surely as my-selfe &middot; slepe in my tentis,</L>
<L N="476">And oure god all-to-gedire &middot; is ground of &thorn;e cause;</L>
<L>Of me worthis &thorn;e na wite &middot; ne of na wee ellis."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;en tyd it anes on a tym &middot; a lytill terme efter,</L>
<L N="479">&THORN;is dere kyng on a day &middot; on his dese syttis,</L>
<L>Had parreld him a proude feste &middot; of princes &amp; dukis,
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>With maisterlingis of Messadone &middot; &amp; many o&thorn;ire noble[s].</L>
<L>&THORN;us as he sat in his sete &middot; softly by his qwene,</L>
<L>In schene schemerand schroude &middot; all of schire stanes,</L>
<L N="484">He kest vp his contenance &middot; &amp; kny&yogh;tly he lokes,</L>
<L>And gladis gudly his gestis &middot; as his degre wald.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Anec[t]anabus on-ane &middot; in al&thorn;ire-mast ioy</L>
<L>Did on him his dragon-hame &middot; &amp; drafe thur&yogh;e &thorn;e sale,<MILESTONE N="9a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With slike a rowste &amp; rerid &middot; &thorn;e romance it wittnes,</L>
<L N="489">&THORN;at nere had bernes for &thorn;at bere &middot; bene bro&yogh;t out of witt.</L>
<L>He was sa hatter &amp; sa hoge &middot; quen he &thorn;e hall entird,</L>
<L>Lete sa lathely a late &middot; &amp; sa loude cried,</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;at all &thorn;e fest was a-ferd &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire folke bathe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chefe chaiare of &thorn;e qwene &middot; he chese him be-lyue,</L>
<L>And laide as hendly as a hunde &middot; his hede in hire arme,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;in kyssis he hire clene mouthe &middot; enclynes hire lawe,</L>
<L N="496">And braydis furth with a brym bere &middot; out at &thorn;e brade &yogh;atis.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd Philip to his fere &middot; &amp; all his fre gestis,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;one selfe dragon forsothe &middot; I sa&yogh;e with myne e&yogh;en;</L>
<L N="499">Quen I was stad in &thorn;e stoure &middot; he strenthid all myne oste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar &thorn;e floure in &thorn;e filde &middot; I fangid &thorn;ur&yogh;e him selfe."</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ire ferly &thorn;ar fell &middot; within fewe days,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was sett in his sale &middot; with septer in hand;</L>
<L>&THORN;en come &thorn;ar-in a litill brid &middot; in-to his arme flo&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="504">And &thorn;ar hurkils &amp; hydis &middot; as scho were hand-tame;</L>
<L>Fast scho flekirs about his fete &middot; &amp; fle&yogh;tirs aboute,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar it nestild in a noke &middot; as it a nest were,</L>
<L>Qwill scho had layd in his lape &middot; a litill tyne egg,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an scho fangis hire fli&yogh;t &middot; &amp; flo&yogh;e away swyth.</L>
<L N="509">&THORN;is egg, or &thorn;e kyng wyst &middot; to &thorn;e erth fallis,</L>
<L>Brak, &amp; so it wele burde &middot; &amp; brast all e-soundir;</L>
<L>&THORN;an wendis &thorn;ar-out a litill worm &middot; &amp; wald it eft enter,</L>
<L N="512">And or scho hit in hire hede &middot; a hard deth suffirs.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>&THORN;an was ser Philip of &thorn;at fare &middot; ferly mekill sturbid,</L>
<L>Callis to him a kid clerke &middot; declaris to him &thorn;is wonder,</L>
<L>Beso&yogh;t him quat it sygnified &middot; to tell him &thorn;e treuthe.<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="516">"&THORN;at graunt I gudly," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; &amp; &thorn;us-gate he spekis:</L>
<L>"Sire, &thorn;ere sall borne be a barne &middot; of &thorn;i blithe lady,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dri&yogh;tyn efter &thorn;i day &middot; has destaned to regne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quilke sall walke all &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; wyn it him selfe,</L>
<L N="520">And hent sall a full hetire deth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. derth; <I>see</I> l. 512.</NOTE> &middot; or he may hame couer."</L>
<L>&THORN;us he vndid him ilka dele<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ilka adele; <I>wrongly</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; him &thorn;e dome reched,</L>
<L>Said it was sett to be so &middot; he sa&yogh;e by his artis.</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ow likis of &thorn;is lare &middot; to lesten any forthire,</L>
<L N="524">Sone sall I tell &yogh;ow a text &middot; how it be-tid efter.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Cercius passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now it te&yogh;t &thorn;e tyme &middot; at trauald &thorn;at qwene,</L>
<L>Quen scho suld bryng furth &middot; hire birth to &thorn;e werd.</L>
<L>Scho bidis many hard brayde &middot; baret enduris,</L>
<L N="528">What of wandreth &amp; wa &middot; as wemen dose all.</L>
<L>Thik schouris hire thrat &middot; tholid mekill soro&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Many peralus pull &middot; grete payne suffirs,</L>
<L>Sa sare werkis hire &thorn;e wame &middot; &amp; slik vn-wyn dreis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all scho dredis hire dede &middot; &amp; doute for &thorn;e werst.</L>
<L N="533">&THORN;an efter Anectanabus &middot; scho on-ane clepis,</L>
<L>And he was boune at hire bode &middot; &amp; bowes to hire chambre,</L>
<L>Gais him vp at &thorn;e grece &middot; &amp; gretis him faire,</L>
<L N="536">Fand hire sett in a sege &middot; &amp; soro&yogh;e ay elike.</L>
<L>"A! Anec!" quod &thorn;e qwene &middot; "me ar&yogh;es of my-selfe;</L>
<L>I am all in aunter &middot; sa akis me &thorn;e wame,</L>
<L N="539">Of werke well ne I wede &middot; &amp; slike wa tholis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me ware dere to be dede &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> than.</NOTE> dure &thorn;us on lyfe."<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, wynnes &yogh;ow vp," quod &thorn;e we &middot; "&amp; walkis a littill,
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e aire nowe &amp; &thorn;e elementis &middot; ere evyn in &thorn;is tyme</L>
<L>So trauailid out of temperoure &middot; &amp; troubild of &thorn;at sone,</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;at makis &thorn;i grippis and &thorn;i gridis &middot; a grete dele &thorn;e kenere."</L>
<L>&THORN;an faris scho vp &amp; farkis furth &middot; a fute or tway,</L>
<L>And sone sesis all hire syte &middot; in a sete quyle.</L>
<L>"Now bow &thorn;e doune," quod &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; scho his bone fillis,</L>
<L N="548">And syttand so in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> hire sege &middot; was softly delyuerd.</L>
<L>Bot now is meruaill &middot; to me<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to me to me; <I>but corrected.</I></NOTE> of &thorn;is wondire,</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;is man fra his modire wambe &middot; on &thorn;e mold fell;</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e erd euyn ouer &middot; sa egirly schakis,</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;at teldis, templis, &amp; touris &middot; tomble on hepis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e li&yogh;t lemand late &middot; laschis fra &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>Thonere-thrastis ware thra &middot; thristid &thorn;e welkyn,</L>
<L>Cloudis clenely to-clefe &middot; clatird vn-faire,</L>
<L N="556">All blakenid a-boute &middot; &amp; boris &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>Wild wedirs vp werpe &middot; &amp; &thorn;e wynd ryse,</L>
<L>And all<NOTE PLACE="foot">a <I>in text; but</I> alle <I>in margin.</I></NOTE> flames &thorn;e flode &middot; as it fire were,</L>
<L>Nowe bri&yogh;t, nowe blaa &middot; nowe on blase efter,</L>
<L N="560">And &thorn;an ouer-qwelmys in a qwirre &middot; &amp; qwatis euer e-like.</L>
<L>&THORN;an slike a derknes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dreknes.</NOTE> &thorn;ar drafe &middot; &amp; demyd &thorn;e skewys,</L>
<L>As blesenand as bale-fyre &middot; &amp; blake as &thorn;e hell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was neuer bot as ny&yogh;t &middot; fra &thorn;e none tyme</L>
<L N="564">Till it to mydday was meten &middot; on &thorn;e morne efter.</L>
<L>Gife &thorn;is ware mervale to myn &middot; &yogh;et emang othire</L>
<L>&THORN;en rekils it vnruydly &middot; &amp; raynes doune stanys,</L>
<L>Fell fra &thorn;e fyrmament &middot; as a hand lyftyng,</L>
<L N="568">And some as hoge as &thorn;i hede &middot; fra &thorn;e heuyn fallis.<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sa ferd was Philip of &thorn;at fare &middot; &thorn;at his flesche trymblid,</L>
<L>For sere sygnes at he sa&yogh;e &middot; as selly ware ellis.</L>
<L>As wyde as all &thorn;e werd was &thorn;ur&yogh;e &middot; warnyng &thorn;ai hadd,
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="19"></L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at o; <I>but</I> o <I>is expuncted</I>.</NOTE> houre &thorn;at Olympadas &middot; was of hire son li&yogh;ter.</L>
<L>Than lendis him vp &thorn;e leue kyng &middot; his lady to vysite,</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e man to his make &middot; "I am in many tho&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is frute sall haue na fostring &middot; ne be fed nou&thorn;ire;</L>
<L N="576">I ges it be no&yogh;t of my gett &middot; bot of god fourmed;</L>
<L>Be many cause at I ken &middot; I kan no&yogh;t supose</L>
<L>It be consayued of my kynde &middot; ne come of my-selfe.</L>
<L>I sa&yogh;e so, in &thorn;e same tyme &middot; he seuyrd fra &thorn;i wambe,</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;e erd &amp; all &thorn;e elementis &middot; so egirly schontid.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. schoutis; <I>altered to</I> schoutid.</NOTE></L>
<L>And que&thorn;er &yogh;it, for any quat &middot; a quyle latt him kepe,</L>
<L>And norisch him as namely &middot; as he myne awyn warre,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it will &thorn;are make of him mynde &middot; &amp; myn it here-eftire</L>
<L N="584">Hathils, swilke a haly son &middot; I hade in my tyme.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er barne," quod &thorn;e berne &middot; "I of my blode haue,</L>
<L>Ane of my sede, I supose &middot; &amp; sibbire of &thorn;e twa,</L>
<L N="587">&THORN;at I wan on myne o&thorn;ire wyfe &middot; &thorn;at I wedd first.</L>
<L>Lat him as ayre, quen I am er&thorn;ed &middot; enherit my landis,</L>
<L>And stall we him in stede of &thorn;is &middot; to sti&yogh;till my rewme,</L>
<L>For he is borne of my blode &middot; &amp; a-bore nerre,</L>
<L>And fede we &thorn;is othire, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> folke &middot; quen we ere fay worthid,</L>
<L>May sitt &amp; carpe, slike a knaue &middot; &thorn;aire last kyng hade."</L>
<L N="593">&THORN;ai did all as he demed &middot; &amp; his domes plesed,</L>
<L>Cherest &thorn;ai &thorn;is &yogh;onge child &middot; &amp; chosely him kepid;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware as besy him a-boute &middot; birdis &amp; ladis,</L>
<L N="596">As he had bene &thorn;ar hi&yogh;e god &middot; for sa &thorn;ai hopid all,</L>
<L>&THORN;is barne, quen he borne was &middot; as me &thorn;e boke tellis,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t wele a-prefe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a pere, <I>altered to</I> a prefe.</NOTE> for his a-port &middot; to any prince oute.</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at he li&yogh;t off &middot; he like was to nane,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er of fetour ne of face &middot; to fadire ne to modyre;<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="601">&THORN;e fax on his faire hede &middot; was ferly to schawe,</L>
<L>Large lyons lockis &middot; &thorn;at lange ere &amp; scharpe;</L>
<L>With grete glesenand e&yogh;en &middot; grymly he lokis,</L>
<L N="604">&THORN;at ware as blyckenand bri&yogh;t &middot; as blesand sternes,
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it ware &thorn;ai sett vn-samen &middot; of serelypy hewys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tane, to breve at a blisch &middot; as blak as a cole,</L>
<L>As any &yogh;are &yogh;eten gold &middot; &yogh;alow was &thorn;e tothire.</L>
<L N="608">And he wald-e&yogh;ed was &middot; as &thorn;e writt schewys,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it it tellis me &thorn;is tale &middot; &thorn;e tethe in his hede</L>
<L>Was as bitand breme &middot; as any bare tuskis.</L>
<L>His steuyn stiffe was [&amp;] steryn &middot; &thorn;at stonayd many,</L>
<L N="612">And as a lyon he lete &middot; quen he loude romys.</L>
<L>His fell fygoure &amp; his fourme &middot; fully be-takend</L>
<L>&THORN;e prowis &amp; &thorn;e grete pryse &middot; &thorn;at he a-preuyd eftire,</L>
<L>His hardynes, his hyndelaike &middot; &amp; his hetter my&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;e wirschip &thorn;at he wan &middot; quen he wex eldire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sembled his syb men &middot; be sent of &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>To consaile of &thorn;is kyng son &middot; how &thorn;ai him call suld,</L>
<L>And so him neuyned was &thorn;e name &middot; of his next frendis</L>
<L N="620">Alexsandire &thorn;e athill &middot; be allirs a-corde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he lede furthe be-lyfe &middot; to lere at &thorn;e scole,</L>
<L>As sone as to &thorn;at sapient &middot; him-self was of elde,</L>
<L>On-ane vn-to Arystotill &middot; &thorn;at was his awen maister,</L>
<L>And one of &thorn;e coronest clerkis &middot; &thorn;at euer knew letter.</L>
<L N="625">&THORN;an was he bro&yogh;t to a benke &middot; a boke in his hand,</L>
<L>And faste by his enfourme &middot; was fettild his place;</L>
<L>For it come no&yogh;t a kyng son &middot; &yogh;e knaw wele, to sytt</L>
<L>Doune in margon &amp; molle &middot; emange othire schrewis.</L>
<L N="629">Sone wex he witter &amp; wyse &middot; &amp; wonder wele leres,</L>
<L>Sped him in a schort space &middot; to spell &amp; to rede,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;en to gramere he gase &middot; as &thorn;e gyse wald,</L>
<L N="632">And &thorn;at has he all hale &middot; in a hand-quyle.<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In foure or in fyfe &yogh;ere &middot; he ferre was in lare</L>
<L>&THORN;an othire at had bene &thorn;are &middot; seuynte wynter;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld passe him in &thorn;at plite &middot; vnpussible semed,</L>
<L>Bot at god will at gaa furth &middot; qua may agayn stande?</L>
<L N="637">In absens of Arystotill &middot; if any of his feris</L>
<L>Raged with him vnridly &middot; or rofe him with harme,</L>
<L>Him wald he kenely on &thorn;e croune &middot; knok with his tablis,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="640">&THORN;at al to-brest wald &thorn;e bordis &middot; &amp; &thorn;e blode folowe.</L>
<L>If any scolere in &thorn;e scole &middot; his skorne at him makis,</L>
<L>He skapis him full skathely &middot; bot if he skyp better.</L>
<L>&THORN;us with his feris he fa&yogh;t &middot; as I fynd wreten,</L>
<L N="644">As wele in letter &amp; in lare &middot; as any laike ellis.</L>
<L>&THORN;us skilfull lange he scolaid &middot; &amp; &thorn;e scole vsed,</L>
<L>Tille he was euyn of eld &middot; elleuyn wynter.</L>
<L>He had na pere in na place &middot; &thorn;at proued so his tyme,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e principalte of all &thorn;e pake &middot; he of a-prefe wynnys.</L>
<L N="649">And qwen it te&yogh;t to &thorn;e tyme &middot; of ten &yogh;ere of age,</L>
<L>&THORN;en was him kend of &thorn;e kynde &middot; &amp; craft of bataile,</L>
<L>Wele &amp; wi&yogh;tly in were &middot; to welden a spere,</L>
<L N="652">A[nd] preke on a proude stede &middot; proudly enarmed.</L>
<L>&THORN;at lare was him lefe to &middot; &amp; lerid in a qwile</L>
<L>Was &thorn;ar na lede to him like &middot; with-in a fewe &yogh;eris.</L>
<L>So cheualus a chiftan &middot; he cheuys in a stonde,</L>
<L N="656">&THORN;at in anters of armes &middot; all men he passes.</L>
<L>Quen Philip see him sa fers &middot; in his first elde,</L>
<L>His hert &amp; his hardynes &middot; hi&yogh;ely he lofed,</L>
<L>Comendid mekill his kny&yogh;t-hede &middot; &amp; him callid on a day</L>
<L>Be-twene &thorn;am selfe on a tyme &middot; &amp; talkis &thorn;ire wordis:</L>
<L N="661">"Alexander," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "I augirly prayse</L>
<L>&THORN;i wirschip, &thorn;i worthines &middot; &thorn;i wit &amp; &thorn;i strenth.</L>
<L>Es nane so teche of &thorn;i tyme &middot; to tryi now o lyfe.<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="664">How suld I, lede, for &thorn;i lofe &middot; bot lufe &thorn;e in hert?</L>
<L>Bot I am sary for sothe &middot; my son, at &thorn;i fourme</L>
<L>Is lickenand on na lym &middot; ne like to my selfe;</L>
<L>Oft storbis me &thorn;i statour &middot; &amp; stingis me &yogh;erne,</L>
<L N="668">&THORN;at &thorn;i personale proporcion &middot; sa party is to myne."</L>
<L>&THORN;is herd hire &thorn;e hend quene &middot; &amp; heterly scho dredis,</L>
<L>Sent efter Anec &middot; &amp; askis him be-lyue,</L>
<L>Be-knew him clene all &thorn;e case &middot; how &thorn;e kyng sayd,</L>
<L>And frayns him fast quat &thorn;e freke &middot; of hire fare thingis.</L>
<L>&THORN;en con he calke &amp; a-conte &middot; &amp; kest on his fyngirs,</L>
<L N="674">Lokis him vp to &thorn;e lifte &middot; &amp; &thorn;e lady swares:</L>
<L>"Be no&yogh;t a-fri&yogh;t," quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "ne a-frayd nou&thorn;ir,
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="22"></L>
<L N="676">It sall &thorn;e noy no&yogh;t a neg &middot; nane of his tho&yogh;tis."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he heuys vp [his] hede &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e heuyn lokis,</L>
<L>Hedis heterly on hi&yogh;e &middot; behelde on a sterne,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e quilke he hopid in his hert &middot; sumquat to knawe,</L>
<L>Quat euire he wald wete &middot; of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of w his; <I>but</I> w <I>is expuncted</I>.</NOTE> his will all-to-gedire.</L>
<L>Quod Alexander to &thorn;is athill &middot; as he his arte fandis,</L>
<L>"Quat is &thorn;e planet or &thorn;e poynt &middot; &yogh;e purpose to seme?</L>
<L N="683">Quat sterne is it at &yogh;e stody on &middot; quare stekis it in heuyn?</L>
<L>May &yogh;e o&yogh;t me in any maner &middot; to &thorn;at sterne schewe?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;at can I wele," quod &thorn;e clerke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; "ellis couthe I littill;</L>
<L>No&yogh;t bot sewe me, son &middot; quen &thorn;e son is to reste,</L>
<L>Quen it [is] dreuyn to &thorn;e derke &middot; &amp; &thorn;e day fynyst,</L>
<L N="688">And &thorn;ou sall sothely se &middot; &thorn;e same with &thorn;ine e&yogh;en."</L>
<L>"Is o&yogh;t &thorn;i werid to &thorn;e wissid?" &middot; quod &thorn;e wee &thorn;an;</L>
<L>"For &thorn;at I couet to ken &middot; if &thorn;ou me kythe wald."</L>
<L>"Sire, sothely of myne awen son<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; slayne mon I worth,</L>
<L N="692">So was me destaned to dye &middot; gane many winter."</L>
<L>As tyte as Anec[tanabus] &middot; &thorn;is aunter had tald,<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;en [he] treyned doune fra &thorn;e toure &middot; to tute in &thorn;e sternes.</L>
<L N="695">&THORN;an airis ser Alexander &middot; eftire his fadire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer he kyndild of his kynde &middot; kend he bot litill.</L>
<L>&THORN;us led he furthe his leue child &middot; late on ane euen,</L>
<L>Sylis softely him selfe &middot; &thorn;e cite with-outen,</L>
<L>Bo&yogh;es him vp to a brenke &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L N="700">To &thorn;e hi&yogh;t of &thorn;e depe dike &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e heuyn waytis.</L>
<L>"Alexander, athil son" &middot; quod Anec his syre,</L>
<L>"Loo! &yogh;onder behald ouer &thorn;i hede &middot; &amp; se my hatter werdis;</L>
<L N="703">&THORN;e euyll sterne of Ercules &middot; how egirly it soro&yogh;es,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e mode Marcure &middot; makis sa mekill ioy;</L>
<L>Loo! &yogh;onder &thorn;e gentill Iubiter &middot; how Iolyle he schynes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e domes of my destany &middot; drawis to me swythe.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>&THORN;ik &amp; &thorn;rathly am I thret &middot; &amp; thole mon I sone</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;e sla&yogh;ter of myne awen son &middot; as me was sett euer."</L>
<L>Vnethis werped he &thorn;at worde &middot; &thorn;e writt me recordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne Alexander as sone &middot; was at him be-hind,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e bake with slike a bire &middot; he bare with his handis,</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;at doune he drafe to &thorn;e depest &middot; of &thorn;e dike bothom,</L>
<L>Sayd, "lo! vnhappeiste vndire heuyn &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;us on hand takis</L>
<L>As be &thorn;e welken to wete &middot; quat suld come efter!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has feyned &thorn;e for wyse &middot; &amp; fals all-to-gedire,</L>
<L N="716">Wele semys slike a sacchell &middot; to sye&yogh;e &thorn;us of lyfe!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Anec, as him a&yogh;t &middot; wele augirly granys,</L>
<L>Dryues vp a dede voyce &middot; &amp; dymly he spekis,</L>
<L>"Wele was &thorn;is cas to me knawen &middot; &amp; kyd many wynter,</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;at I suld dee slike a dethe &middot; be dome of my werdis.</L>
<L>Sayd I &thorn;e no&yogh;t so &middot; my selfe here be-fore,</L>
<L N="722">I suld be slayn of my son as now sothe worthis?"
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000045.tif" N="23">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="678">Hedes heterly on heght &middot; beheld on a sterne,<MILESTONE N="1a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whilke he hopyd in hys hert &middot; somqwatt to knaw,</L>
<L>What euer he wilnet for to wete &middot; hys wille all to-geder.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd alexander to &thorn;is athell &middot; as he by hym stonndes,</L>
<L>"What is &thorn;e planett or &thorn;e poynt &middot; yhe purposse<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. proposse.</NOTE> to se?</L>
<L>Or what sterne at ye stody on &middot; where stekys it in heuen?</L>
<L N="684">May &yogh;e oght in any maner me &middot; to &thorn;at merke shewe?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;at can I wele," quod &thorn;is clerke &middot; "ellys couth I bott lytyll;</L>
<L>Noght bott shew<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sic; read</I> sew.</NOTE> me now, sone &middot; qwen &thorn;e son is at rist,</L>
<L>When it is dryven to &thorn;e dirk &middot; &amp; &thorn;e day fynyshyt,</L>
<L N="688">And &thorn;u sall sorely &thorn;e same &middot; see with &thorn;i eghen."</L>
<L>"Is oght &thorn;i werd to &thorn;e wist?" &middot; quod &thorn;e wy &thorn;an;</L>
<L>"For &thorn;at I Couett to ken &middot; if &thorn;u me kyth wold."</L>
<L>"Syr, sothly of myne awen son &middot; slayn mon I worth,</L>
<L N="692">So was [me] destinate to dy &middot; done mony wynter."</L>
<L>Als tyte as anectanabus &middot; &thorn;ees aunters had tald,</L>
<L>Than turned he doun from &thorn;e toure &middot; to tote on &thorn;e sternes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ayres sir alexander &middot; aftir hys fader,</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;at euer he come of hys kynde &middot; knew [he] full lityll.</L>
<L>&THORN;us lede he forth is leue sonn &middot; late on an euen,</L>
<L>Syland softly &thorn;aim selfe &middot; &thorn;e cyte with-owte,</L>
<L>Bownes &thorn;aim vp to a brenke &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellys,</L>
<L N="700">To &thorn;e hight of &thorn;e hye dyke &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e heuen watyn.</L>
<L>"Alexander, athell sonn" &middot; quod anec hys fader,</L>
<L>"Beyond be-hald ouer my hed &middot; &amp; see my hote werdez;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ilke sterne of ercules &middot; howe egerly it sorowez,</L>
<L N="704">And how &thorn;e mode of mercury &middot; makys so mekyll Ioy;</L>
<L>Lo! how gentyll Iubiter &middot; how ioyfully he shynes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Domes of my destany &middot; drawes vnto [me] swyth.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>Thik &amp; thraly am I thrett &middot; &amp; thole must I sone</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;e slauughter of my awne sonn &middot; als me was sett euer."</L>
<L>Vnneth warpyd he &thorn;is word &middot; &thorn;e writt me recordez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alexander als belyfe &middot; was at hym bylyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> byhynde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;e bak with suche a bir &middot; hym bare with hys handez,</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;at Doun he drafe into &thorn;e dyppest &middot; of &thorn;e dyke bothum;<MILESTONE N="1b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sayd: "lo! vnhappyest vndir heuen &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;us on hand takes</L>
<L>Als be welkyn to wete &middot; what worth sall her-aftir!</L>
<L>Hase fenyd &thorn;e for wyse &middot; &amp; fals all to-geder,</L>
<L N="716">Wele semys suche a sachell &middot; to sepe &thorn;us of lyfe!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Anec, als hym awght &middot; wele awgardly granes,</L>
<L>Dryvez vp a dede voyce &middot; &amp; dymly he spekes:</L>
<L>"Wele was &thorn;is to me knawyn &middot; &amp; kyd mony wynter,</L>
<L N="720">That I suld dey such a dede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &middot; by<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> dome of my werdis.</L>
<L>Sayd I &thorn;e noght so &middot; my self here beforne</L>
<L N="722">I suld be slayn of my sonn &middot; als now is soth worthen?"</L>
<L N="723*">"What, and am I," quod alexander &middot; "ane of &thorn;i childer?"</L>
<L N="724*">"&YOGH;ha, son! als glad I my god &middot; I gat &thorn;e my seluen."</L>
<L>Fro he had hym &thorn;is worde sayd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &middot; he wakens no more,</L>
<L>Bot gaue a gremly grane &middot; &amp; &thorn;e gast &yogh;heldez.</L>
<L>That o&thorn;er wy for hys werkez &middot; wepys eueryllyke,</L>
<L N="728*">So hard &amp; so hertly &middot; &thorn;at ne&yogh; hys hert brestes.</L>
<L>&THORN;us plenys &thorn;is prouud knyght &middot; &thorn;e pyte of hys fader,</L>
<L>Cares hym downe into &thorn;e cafe &middot; &thorn;ar as &thorn;e cors ligges,</L>
<L N="731*">Belife lyftes he on-lofte &middot; euen on hys shulders,</L>
<L>And beres hym forth vppon hys bake &middot; at &thorn;e brade &yogh;ates.</L>
<L>Sone sayd &thorn;e whene, when sho hym see &middot; with syland teres;</L>
<L>"What haue &yogh;e done, my dere sonn?" &middot; &amp; drowpys doun in swone.</L>
<L>"Dame, now is &thorn;ar none other to do &middot; bot deme it &thorn;i seluen,</L>
<L N="736*">For as &thorn;i foly was before &middot; so foloweth aftir."</L>
<L>Than makes &thorn;is man &amp; hys moder &middot; menskfully &amp; faire</L>
<L>Titely hys enterment &middot; as &thorn;ai &thorn;at tyme vsed.</L>
<L>&THORN;us shamesly of hys awne childe &middot; hym chevyd such end.</L>
<L N="740*">And her fynes a fytt &middot; &amp; fayr when vs likez.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="4" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000048.tif" N="26">
<HEAD><B>Quartus passus.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="28">

<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="30">

<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="32">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;of I &thorn;is wirschip &thorn;e wayfe &middot; as wald &thorn;ine astate,<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="724">Lat &thorn;ou &thorn;i hert neuer &thorn;e hi&yogh;ere &middot; hale in-to pride.</L>
<L>For it was wont," quod &thorn;e wee &middot; "as wyse men tellis,</L>
<L>Full hi&yogh;e &thorn;ingis ouer-heldis &middot; to held o&thorn;er-quile.</L>
<L>Slike as ere now bro&yogh;t a-bofe &middot; nowe &thorn;e bothum askis,</L>
<L>And slike at left<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Indistinct; see</I> 1. 814.</NOTE> ere on lawe &middot; ere lift to &thorn;e sternes."</L>
<L N="729">"Sa ma aydeus," quod &thorn;at o&thorn;ire man &middot; "&thorn;ou tellis me treuthe,</L>
<L>Son &thorn;is ensample of &thorn;i-selfe &middot; &thorn;ou sais me, I trowe.</L>
<L>Vn-behalde &thorn;e wele on ilk halfe &middot; &amp; haue a gud e&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="732">Les on &thorn;ine ane here-efterward &middot; &thorn;ine ossyngis li&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander all in ire &middot; angrile spekis:</L>
<L>"Hy &thorn;e hethen-ward, &thorn;ou hathill &middot; &amp; houe &thorn;ou na langire.</L>
<L>For na-&thorn;ing as a-nente me &middot; &thorn;ou has no&yogh;t to mell,</L>
<L N="736">Ne with &thorn;i domes me to dele &middot; dole vndire sonne."</L>
<L>Now<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Nowith; <I>by confusion with line above</I>.</NOTE> is ser Nicollas anoyed &middot; &amp; nettild with ire,</L>
<L>As wrath as [a] waspe &middot; &amp; wode of his mynde,</L>
<L N="739">Reviles he &thorn;is o&thorn;ire renke &middot; with vnrid speche:</L>
<L>"Behald," quod he, "hedirward &middot; &amp; herken how I say;</L>
<L>Now be &thorn;e hert &amp; &thorn;e hele &middot; of my hathill fadire,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e god," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "&thorn;at gafe me &thorn;e saule,</L>
<L>A[ls] sprent [of] my spittyng &middot; a specke on &thorn;i chere,</L>
<L N="744">&THORN;ou sall be di&yogh;t to &thorn;e deth &middot; &amp; drepid of my handis."
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>Quen he had spokin so, for spyte &middot; he spittis in his face,</L>
<L>Dispises him despetously &middot; dispersons him foule.</L>
<L>"Hent &thorn;e &thorn;are," quod &thorn;e hatill<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> &middot; "as &thorn;e to haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hame, <I>with first stroke of</I> m <I>subpuncted.</I></NOTE> semes,</L>
<L N="748">Cure, for &thorn;i kene carpe &middot; chache nowe a schame!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an went him furthe Alexander &middot; &amp; his ande takis,</L>
<L>Lete a-swage or he sware &middot; &thorn;e swelme of his angirs,</L>
<L N="751">Be-se&yogh;is him how he say wold &middot; or he his sa&yogh;e &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>And turnes him &thorn;en to &thorn;e tulke &middot; &amp; talkis &thorn;ire wordis:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou has no&yogh;tid me now &middot; Nicollas," he sayd,</L>
<L>I swere &thorn;e, be my syre saule &middot; &amp; by his selfe pite,<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And be &thorn;e worthe wombe &middot; of my wale modre</L>
<L N="756">&THORN;at I was geten in of gode &middot; &amp; graithely consayued,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seis me, lede, or o&yogh;t lange &middot; in &thorn;i lande armed,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ire recouyre me &thorn;i rewme &middot; or reche vp &thorn;e girdill."</L>
<L N="759">&THORN;an set &thorn;ai &thorn;am slike a day &middot; to semble &amp; to fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-to tuke vp &thorn;aire trouthis &middot; &amp; twyned esondre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to semble &amp; to fi&yogh;t, <I>struck through, with</I> &amp; twyned esondre <I>above.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en &yogh;ode him furthe &thorn;i[s] &yogh;ong man &middot; &yogh;apeli &amp; swythe</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e marche of Messedone &middot; &amp; manly a-semblis</L>
<L>Of saudiours &amp; sekir men &middot; a soume out of nounbre,</L>
<L N="764">&THORN;at was &thorn;e baldest &amp; &thorn;e best &middot; breueyd in armes.</L>
<L>He parrails him a proude ost &middot; of princes &amp; o&thorn;ire,</L>
<L>Farkis to ser Philip &middot; &amp; fangis his leue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an Bocifilas his blonke &middot; he bremely ascendis,</L>
<L>And bounes on with his bataill &middot; out at &thorn;e brade &yogh;atis.</L>
<L N="769">&THORN;e same day at was sett<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e sembling of bathe,</L>
<L>Aithire with a firs flote &middot; in &thorn;e fild metis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nounbre of ser Nicollas &middot; it noyes me to reken,</L>
<L N="772">And Alexander was ane oste &middot; of augird many.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai tuke vp &thorn;aire trompes &middot; a-pon &thorn;e twa sidis,</L>
<L>Braidis banars a-brade &middot; buskis to mete.</L>
<L>So kinlid &thorn;e clarons &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e cliffe rynges,
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="36"></L>
<L N="776">&THORN;e holtis &amp; &thorn;e haire heere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> haire wode.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; &thorn;e hillis scheuyn.</L>
<L>Ilk a hathill to hors &middot; hi&yogh;is him be-lyue,</L>
<L>Stridis into stele-bowe &middot; stertis apon loft,</L>
<L>Has a helme on his hede &middot; &amp; honge on his swyre</L>
<L N="780">A schene schondirhand schild &middot; &amp; a schaft hentis.</L>
<L>Quat of stamping of stedis &middot; &amp; stering of bernes,</L>
<L>All dymed &thorn;e dale &middot; &amp; &thorn;e dust ryses.</L>
<L>With slik a bront &amp; a brusche &middot; &thorn;e bataill a-sembild,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e erth &amp; all &thorn;e el[e]mentis &middot; at anes had wrestild.<MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="785">Now aithire stoure on &thorn;ar stedis &middot; strikis to-gedire,</L>
<L>Spurnes out spakly &middot; with speris in hand,</L>
<L>Brekis in-to blasons &middot; bordren<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> broden.</NOTE> shildis,</L>
<L N="788">Beris in-to bri&yogh;t stele &middot; bitand lances,</L>
<L>Sone in scheuerand schidis &middot; schaftis ere brosten,</L>
<L>Al to-spryngis in sprotis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> in sprotis.</NOTE> &middot; speris of syris,</L>
<L>Dryfuys doune duchepers &middot; &amp; doykis of &thorn;ar horses,</L>
<L N="792">Fellis fay to &thorn;e fold &middot; many fresch kny&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>Quat dose now &thorn;is Nichollas &middot; bot nymes him a spere,</L>
<L>Kest him on &thorn;is &yogh;ong kny&yogh;t &middot; to couire him a name;</L>
<L>And Alexander with anothire &middot; airis him agayne,</L>
<L N="796">Girdis grymly to-gedire &middot; greuosly metis.</L>
<L>Sa sare was &thorn;e semble &middot; &thorn;ire seggis be-twene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al to-wraiste &thorn;ai &thorn;ar wode &middot; &amp; werpis in-sondire,</L>
<L N="799">Al to-clatirs in-to cauels &middot; clene to &thorn;aire handis,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar left nou&thorn;ire in &thorn;ar hand &middot; &thorn;e lengthe of an ellyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;en littid &thorn;ai na langer &middot; bot laschid out swerdis,</L>
<L>Aithire a blesynand brand<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; brait out of schethe,</L>
<L>Hewis on hattirly &middot; had thurgh mailes,</L>
<L N="804">Many starand stanes &middot; strikis of &thorn;aire helmes.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Alexander in ane ire &middot; his arme vp-liftis,</L>
<L>Swythe swyngis out his swerde &middot; &amp; his swayfe feches.</L>
<L>&THORN;e noll of Nicollas &thorn;e kyng &middot; he fra &thorn;e nebb partis,</L>
<L N="808">&THORN;at doun he fell fra his fole &middot; &amp; fynyst for euir.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was him destand &thorn;at day &middot; as dri&yogh;ten had shapid,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>To hent him &thorn;e hi&yogh;ere hande &middot; of his athill fais.</L>
<L>&THORN;are slike wirschip he wan &middot; ware wonder to tell;</L>
<L N="812">Had of &thorn;at hi&yogh;e kyng &middot; &thorn;e hede fra &thorn;e shuldirs.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was him geuyn vp &thorn;e &yogh;erde &middot; &amp; &yogh;olden &thorn;e rewme,</L>
<L>And all at left was<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> was.</NOTE> o lyfe &middot; lordis &amp; othire,<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Come to &thorn;at conquerour &middot; &amp; on knese<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ken knese, <I>with</I> ken <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> fallis,</L>
<L N="816">And in his mercy &amp; meth &middot; mekely &thorn;aim put.</L>
<L>&THORN;is renke &amp; his rounsy &middot; &thorn;ai reche vp a croune,</L>
<L>As gome at has &thorn;e garland &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e gre wonn.</L>
<L>&THORN;us with &thorn;e floure in &thorn;e fild &middot; he fangid his enmy,</L>
<L N="820">And haldis on with hale here &middot; hame to his fadire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fyndis he Philip on his flett &middot; with a fest huge</L>
<L>Had wed him ano&thorn;er wyfe &middot; &amp; wayfid his quene;</L>
<L>Ane Cleopatras caled<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he caled; <I>but</I> he <I>is not wanted</I>.</NOTE> &middot; a grete kyngis do&yogh;ter,</L>
<L N="824">And [laft] had Olympadas &middot; &amp; openly for-saken.</L>
<L>"Fadire," quod &thorn;is fell kny&yogh;t &middot; quen he &thorn;is fest entirs,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e palme here of my first price &middot; I pray &thorn;e resayfe,</L>
<L>Forthe to &thorn;e weding or I winde &middot; of my wale modire,</L>
<L>And kaire me to a-no&thorn;ire kyng &middot; to couple hire to wyfe.</L>
<L N="829">For &thorn;e to felsen ne to folo&yogh;e &middot; fallis me na mare,</L>
<L>Ne here to duell with &thorn;i douce &middot; deynes me na langer,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou mas &thorn;e slike a mangery &middot; &amp; macchis changis,</L>
<L N="832">And I to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> consaile vn-callid &middot; I can no&yogh;t &thorn;ar-on."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ar carpis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. crapis.</NOTE> to &thorn;e kyng &middot; a kny&yogh;t at &thorn;e table,</L>
<L>Ane lesias, a lede &middot; &amp; on loude speches:</L>
<L>"Cleopatras a knafe child &middot; consayue sall &amp; bere,</L>
<L N="836">&THORN;at demed is eftir &thorn;i deth &middot; duly to regne."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander at &thorn;is kny&yogh;t &middot; angirs vnfaire,</L>
<L>Wynnes him vp a wardrere &middot; he walt in his handis,</L>
<L>So hard him hittis on &thorn;e hede &middot; his hernes out weltid,</L>
<L N="840">And sa he lost has &thorn;e lyfe &middot; for his le&thorn;er wordis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e wale kyng wrath &middot; as wonder ware ellis,</L>
<L>Braydis him vp fra &thorn;e borde &middot; &amp; a brand clekis,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>Airid toward Alexander &middot; &amp; ames him to strike.</L>
<L N="844">Bot &thorn;an him failis &thorn;e feete<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fete, <I>altered to</I> feete.</NOTE> &middot; or he first wenys,<MILESTONE N="15a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He stakirs, he stumbils &middot; &amp; stande he ne mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot ay fundirs &amp; fallis &middot; as he ferde ware.</L>
<L>&THORN;e faster forward him<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> he faris &middot; &thorn;e faster he snapirs;</L>
<L>Quat was &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e case &middot; &thorn;at knawis oure lorde.</L>
<L N="849">"Quat now," quod athill Alexander &middot; "quat<NOTE PLACE="foot">quod.</NOTE> ailis &thorn;e to fall?</L>
<L>Has &thorn;ou na force in &thorn;i fete &middot; ne fele of &thorn;i-selfe?</L>
<L>For a freke to be ferd &middot; or a-fraid outhire,</L>
<L N="852">And &thorn;ou &thorn;e gouernere of grece &middot; &thorn;at ware grete wondire!"</L>
<L>&THORN;en tittis he doune in &thorn;at tene &middot; &thorn;e tablis ilkane,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e hall be [&thorn;e] hare &middot; halis he &thorn;e bride,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e wee in his wreth &middot; wrekis his modire,</L>
<L>And Philip falne [was] sare seke &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e fest strubled.</L>
<L N="857">As sone as Alexander &middot; of angire he slakis,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> aslakes.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lendis o-loft to &thorn;e lede &middot; a litill days eftir,</L>
<L>Cairis vp with comfurth &middot; &thorn;e kyng for to vysite,</L>
<L N="860">He comes to &thorn;e curten &middot; &amp; carpis &thorn;is wordis:</L>
<L>"Philip," quod &thorn;is ilke freke &middot; &amp; forwith him standis,</L>
<L>"&THORN;of it vn-semely me sytt &middot; &thorn;e so for to call,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t as &thorn;i suget &amp; &thorn;i son &middot; my sawe I &thorn;e &yogh;eld,</L>
<L N="864">Bot as a felaw or a frynde &middot; fallis to a-nothire.</L>
<L>Sire, latt &thorn;i wreth a-wai wende &middot; &amp; with &thorn;i wyfe sa&yogh;till,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e los of Lesias &middot; litill &thorn;ou charge.</L>
<L N="867">I did bot my deuire &middot; to drepe him, me<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> thinke;</L>
<L>For it awe him no&yogh;t sa openly &middot; slike ossing to make.</L>
<L>And ser, vnworthely &thorn;ou wro&yogh;t &middot; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou wele knawis,</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;ou was boune with a brand &middot; my bodi to schende."</L>
<L>&THORN;en rewis &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; of vnride werkis,</L>
<L N="872">Blischis vp to &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; braste out at grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;en airis him on Alexander &middot; to his awen modire;
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>"Bees not a-glopened, madame &middot; ne greued at my fadire;</L>
<L>If all &yogh;e synned him be-syde &middot; as &yogh;our selfe knawis,</L>
<L N="876">&thorn;ar-of na we may &thorn;e wite &middot; it was godis will."<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at he fanges hire furthe &middot; to Philip hire ledis,</L>
<L>And he comly hire kist &middot; &amp; cordis with hire faire,</L>
<L>Anes with Olympadas &middot; &amp; &thorn;e tothire woydis,</L>
<L N="880">And lofes hire lely &middot; to his lyfes ende.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000049.tif" N="27">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The same &amp; &thorn;e selue tyme &middot; as says me &thorn;e text,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e cuntre of capadose &middot; come a kyd prince</L>
<L>To kyng philipp &thorn;e fers &middot; &amp; hym a fole bryngez;</L>
<L N="744*">A grett horse &amp; a hoge &middot; a hegh &amp; a wilde,</L>
<L>A store &amp; a styf stede &middot; stalwortly bondyn;</L>
<L>His choll chaltird &amp; chauelez &middot; in chynez of yren;<MILESTONE N="2a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In rapes fast &middot; for ryfyng of bernes;</L>
<L N="748*">For other mete &thorn;an manysflesche &middot; mouthed he neuer.</L>
<L>Busifolen to &thorn;is blonk &middot; was breued &thorn;e name.</L>
<L>He hed so ferdfull a face &middot; as ony fyre lokez;</L>
<L>Bere als a boles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Altered to</I> boyles <I>in later hand</I>.</NOTE> heued &middot; a bryn on hys shulderr,</L>
<L N="752*">And toton owt of hys top &middot; als tyndis of hornes.</L>
<L>The fayrnes of &thorn;is ilke fole &middot; when philip avysed,</L>
<L>&THORN;an says he to hys seruand &middot; to see to &thorn;is capyll,</L>
<L>And stighillys hym in som stede &middot; a stable by hym one,</L>
<L N="756*">With lang lates of yren &middot; &thorn;at he might lig in.</L>
<L>And all at wer dampned to &thorn;e deth &middot; &amp; demyd at &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sall be bro&yogh;t fra &thorn;e bare &middot; &thorn;is blonk into stable,</L>
<L N="759*">To wery at hys awne wille &middot; &amp; weyle<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wele, <I>corr. to</I> weyle.</NOTE> of &thorn;e fattest.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it philip of hys faire goddes &middot; hym fanges such a sware,</L>
<L>Yff ony berne wer so bald &middot; baron or other,</L>
<L>Or wy &thorn;at myght &thorn;is wilde best &middot; worth for to ryde,</L>
<L>Was dewly aftir hys day &middot; destinate to regne.</L>
<L N="764*">When alexander was of elde &middot; awght &yogh;eres &amp; foure,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he worthy &amp; wight &middot; &amp; wisely hed leryd</L>
<L>At arestotell all ouer &middot; &thorn;e artez all seuen,</L>
<L>And castor, ane o&thorn;er clerke &thorn;ar &middot; at wer hys kyd maisteres.</L>
<L N="768*">So carez he in &thorn;e castell-&yogh;arde &amp; commes on a day</L>
<L>By a wyndow als &thorn;is wild horse &middot; [was] warloked in bandez;
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>Lokes in at a lat &middot; sagh ly hym byforne</L>
<L>So mony menbres of men &middot; wer mervayle to tell.</L>
<L N="772*">&thorn;ar liggez lymmes of laddes &middot; leggez &amp; harmes,</L>
<L>Tharmes thrist owt of thees &middot; banes &amp; shuldres.</L>
<L>Som hanchyd of &thorn;e heued &middot; som &thorn;e handez etyn,</L>
<L>Som &thorn;ar riggez owt rytte &middot; &amp; som &thorn;ar ribbez rent.</L>
<L N="776*">Of &thorn;is wonder he hed &middot; &amp; so he wele burd.</L>
<L>And hardly hys awne hand &middot; in at a hole puttes,</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. And, <I>corr. to</I> He.</NOTE> layd owt a lang neke &middot; &amp; hys hand likkys;</L>
<L>Faire faldes hys fete &middot; &amp; falles<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. faldis, <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE> hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hys fete, <I>repeated, but struck out</I>.</NOTE> to &thorn;e erth,</L>
<L N="780*">Hendly haldes vp hys heued &middot; byheld in hys face,</L>
<L>On Alexander ay-whare &middot; euer elike wates.<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;en wist &thorn;e wy wele enogh &middot; hys wyll all-to-geder;</L>
<L>Brades vppe &thorn;e brade &yogh;ate &middot; &amp; &thorn;e barre entres,</L>
<L N="784*">On &thorn;e rige with hys right hande &middot; hym rodely strakez,</L>
<L>And he full frely &amp; faire &middot; hym faunys &amp; loutez.</L>
<L>Was neuer barslett in band &middot; more buxum to hys lord.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was &thorn;is blonke to &thorn;is bern &middot; for all his breme teches.</L>
<L N="788*">&THORN;us lowtes &thorn;is lede on low &middot; &amp; lowsys hys chynez,</L>
<L>Blyssis blythly hym abouute &middot; &amp; a bridyll fyndez;</L>
<L>Grathez on &thorn;is gay gere &middot; &amp; &thorn;en a gilt sadyll;</L>
<L>Ledes hym forth of &thorn;at loge &middot; &amp; &thorn;en of-lofte lepys.</L>
<L N="792*">Than strenys he hys streropes &middot; &amp; stre&yogh;t vp sittes;</L>
<L>Lad hym by &thorn;e loran &middot; &amp; hym &thorn;e lede wissez.</L>
<L>And he als rekyndly ran &middot; rolland hym vnder,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;e sadyll hed sewyd &middot; seuenten wynter.</L>
<L N="796*">Sone as philip &thorn;e ferse &middot; hym on &thorn;is fole metes,</L>
<L>"Son," he sayd, "now er &thorn;e sawes &middot; into &thorn;i seluen fyneshit,</L>
<L>Right as my graceux gode &middot; hase galet me before.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou must rewle all my realm &middot; qwen I am raght hyne."</L>
<L N="800*">Quod alexander als beliue &middot; "my awne athell fader,</L>
<L>I beseke &thorn;e my soueren &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou my sete dresse</L>
<L>In a chosyn chariott &middot; as a chefe maister,</L>
<L>With folawand me a fair flete &middot; of fele men of armes."
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>"&THORN;at graunt I gladly," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; with a gode wille,</L>
<L N="805*">"First of my faire foles &middot; fang &thorn;e a hundreth;</L>
<L>And syne sexty thowsand, my son &middot; &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at, <I>corr. to</I> &thorn;ou.</NOTE> &thorn;i seluen wale</L>
<L>Of shillynges &amp; of shire gold &middot; to shote in &thorn;i Cofyre;</L>
<L>Syne of my chefe chiftanes &middot; chese &thorn;e &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. the, <I>corr. to</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE> best,</L>
<L N="808*">&THORN;e most proved of my princez &middot; in poyntez of were;</L>
<L>Wyes ne no wale wede &middot; want shall &thorn;e no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>And held on with a hale here &middot; &thorn;ar hersound &thorn;ou worth."<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wroth.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thys barne hym buskes as he bede &middot; &amp; bade he no langre,</L>
<L N="812*">Bot grathes hym to &thorn;e gate &middot; with a gyn noble.</L>
<L>Forth with eufestyus he ferd &middot; a freke &thorn;at he loued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a fyne Philo[so]f[e]r &middot; a frend of hys awne.<MILESTONE N="3a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;itte takez he hym with-owte &thorn;e town &middot; twelf tried childer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hed Cosyn hym for chefe &middot; hys chevalry to lede;</L>
<L N="817*">And fair enformed &thorn;am of fight &middot; &amp; fetez of armez</L>
<L>For &yogh;apest in hys awne yoke &middot; &yogh;arly to drawe;</L>
<L>Fers felons with hym fangez &middot; &amp; florens enowe,</L>
<L N="820*">Full preciouse apparement &middot; hys person to cleth,</L>
<L>Comand kenely hys knyghtez &middot; to kepe to hys blonkez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> vnchaunce &thorn;aim achefe &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e chare &yogh;odez.</L>
<L>He prekys forth on hys play &middot; bot with a preuay men&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="824*">Chaterand with hys chiftanes &middot; in hys child gere.</L>
<L>To poliponenses hase he passed &middot; a prouince vnk[n]awyn,</L>
<L>And so was strykyn or he styntyd &middot; in-to &thorn;e strange realm.</L>
<L>The kyng of &thorn;att cuntree &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyth weldyd,</L>
<L N="828*">Which was callyd nicholas &middot; &amp; hym naytly metes,</L>
<L>Had rasyd vp a rode hoste &middot; &amp; heldyd hym ayaynez</L>
<L>With bald baratours on bent &middot; hym batell to &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>He flonge ow[t] on a fers fole &middot; far from hys hoste,</L>
<L N="832*">Ayres to sir alexander &middot; &amp; angrely franes:</L>
<L>"What is &thorn;i name, notesman &middot; neuen me &thorn;e sothe;</L>
<L>And whyne ert &thorn;ou &amp; who &middot; &amp; what makys &thorn;ou here?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e knyght, as he wele couth &middot; hym curtasly answers:</L>
<L N="836*">"Sir, kyng philip &thorn;e ferse &middot; my fader was haten,
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>And all &thorn;e marche of massydon &middot; he manours clene;</L>
<L>And I hys heyre alexander &middot; als elders me callen."</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er renishit r[e]nke &middot; hym rightes in &thorn;e sadyll,</L>
<L N="840*">Stranes owt hys sterops &middot; &amp; sternly lokez;</L>
<L>With a sembland as a hye sir &middot; settes owt &thorn;e brest,</L>
<L>Sayd: "who am I &thorn;at am here &middot; as &thorn;ou supposez?"</L>
<L>"Sir, &thorn;ou art a kyng of &thorn;is kyth &middot; I ken wele my-seluen,</L>
<L N="844*">Bott neuer &thorn;e latter in &thorn;is lede &middot; if &thorn;ou be lord here,</L>
<L N="723">&THORN;of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Of.</NOTE> I<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>follows after</I> I <I>in MS.</I></NOTE> &thorn;is worship &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e <I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> wafe &middot; as wald &thorn;ine astate,</L>
<L N="724">Lett &thorn;ou &thorn;i hert neuer &thorn;e hyer &middot; hale to &thorn;e pride.</L>
<L>For it is wont," quod &thorn;e wy &middot; "as wise men tellys,</L>
<L>The hyest thyng ra&thorn;est<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ra&thorn;eest.</NOTE> &middot; heldes o&thorn;er while.</L>
<L>Suche as now is broght a-bowue &middot; now &thorn;e bothom asken,</L>
<L>And sich als laft<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> last.</NOTE> now on loft<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so in</I> MS.; <I>read</I> laft er on lawe.</NOTE> &middot; er lyft to &thorn;e sternes."<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="729">"So madeus,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. madeus, <I>altered to</I> madyng, <I>in later ink.</I></NOTE> quod &thorn;is o&thorn;er man &middot; "&thorn;ou mellys me &thorn;e sothe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is ensampyll of &thorn;i-selfe &middot; &thorn;ou says me, I trowe.</L>
<L>Vmhede &thorn;e wele on ilke halfe &middot; &amp; haue a god Egen,</L>
<L N="732">Lest on &thorn;i-seluen ane o&thorn;er tyme &middot; &thorn;ine asking li&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;an alexander all in ire &middot; angirly spekes:</L>
<L>"Hy &thorn;e hyneward, &thorn;ou athell &middot; &amp; hofe here no langer.</L>
<L>For no&thorn;[i]ng als anense me &middot; &thorn;ou hase lityll to melle,</L>
<L N="736">Ne with me noght hase to do &middot; ne dele vnder &thorn;e sonn."</L>
<L>Now [is] sir Nicholas noyet &middot; &amp; netlett with ire,</L>
<L>Als wrath as a waspe &middot; &amp; wode owt of mynde,</L>
<L>Revylez he &thorn;is other renke &middot; with vnrode speche:</L>
<L N="740">"Byhald," he sayd, "hyderward &middot; &amp; here qwat I say;</L>
<L>Now by &thorn;e hert &amp; &thorn;e heale &middot; of my old fadir,</L>
<L>And be god," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "at gaue me &thorn;e saule,</L>
<L N="743">Als sprent of &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so in</I> MS.; <I>read</I> of my.</NOTE> spyttyng &middot; a speke of my<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> on &thorn;i.</NOTE> face,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall be di&yogh;t to the deth &middot; and drepyd of my handes."
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>When he had spokyn so, in spite &middot; he spittes at hys face,</L>
<L>Dispysys hym dyspytussly &middot; revylez hym foule.</L>
<L>"Hent &thorn;e &thorn;ar-to," quod &thorn;e athell &middot; "&thorn;at &thorn;e to haue semes,</L>
<L N="748">Cure, for &thorn;i kene carpyng &middot; cache now a shame!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an ayres hym forth alexander &middot; &amp; hys aynde takes,</L>
<L>To let swage or he sware &middot; &thorn;e swelme of hys angre,</L>
<L>Wysez hym how he say wald &middot; or he aunswer &yogh;heldes,</L>
<L>And turnyd hym &thorn;en to &thorn;is tulke &middot; &amp; talkez &thorn;ir wordez:</L>
<L N="753">"For &thorn;ou hase no&yogh;tyd me now &middot; nicholas," he sayd,</L>
<L>"I swere by my syre saule &middot; &amp; by hys seluen pyte,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;at worthi wombe &middot; of my wale moder</L>
<L N="756">&THORN;at I was gettyn in of god &middot; &amp; grathly consaued,</L>
<L>Thu sees me, lede, in &thorn;i land &middot; or oght lang cnarmed,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er recouer me &thorn;i realm &middot; or reche me vppe [&thorn;e] girdyll."</L>
<L>&THORN;an sett &thorn;ai &thorn;aim on suche a day &middot; to semble &amp; to fight,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-to takez vpp &thorn;ar trewthez &middot; &amp; twynnon in-sonder.</L>
<L N="761">&THORN;an &yogh;ode hym furth &thorn;is yong man &middot; &yogh;apely &amp; swithe</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e marche of masydon &middot; &amp; manly assembles</L>
<L>Of sowiours &amp; of syker men &middot; a some owt of nowmbre,</L>
<L N="764">&THORN;at wer &thorn;e baldest &amp; &thorn;e best &middot; breuet in armez.</L>
<L>He Apperels hym a prouud oste &middot; of princez &amp; o&thorn;er,<MILESTONE N="4a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ferkys to sire philip &middot; &amp; fonges hys leue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an bucifolon hys blonk &middot; he bremely assendes,</L>
<L N="768">And bownez on with hys batell &middot; in at &thorn;e brade &yogh;atez.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same day &thorn;at was set &middot; &thorn;e semblyng of bath,</L>
<L>Ather with a fers flete &middot; in &thorn;e felde metyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nowmbre of sir nicholas &middot; it neyt<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> me to rekyn,</L>
<L N="772">And alexander was ane ost &middot; of awgerly mony.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai tukkyn vp &thorn;air trompez &middot; vpon &thorn;e two sydez,</L>
<L>Bradez baners on brade &middot; buskes to mete.</L>
<L>So knellyd &thorn;e clarions &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e clyff rongen,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="37"></L>
<L N="776">That &thorn;e holtez of &thorn;e heer wode &middot; &amp; &thorn;e hillez sheuen.</L>
<L>Ilke athell to hys hors &middot; hyes hym belyue,</L>
<L>Striden to stele-bowe &middot; startyn vpon lofte,</L>
<L>Had helmes vpon hedes ful hey &middot; &amp; hynget vmby &thorn;ar shwyre</L>
<L N="780">A shemerand sheld &middot; &amp; &thorn;air shaftez hynten.</L>
<L>What of stampyng of stedes &middot; &amp; strippyng of baners,</L>
<L>All demmyd &thorn;e dale &middot; &amp; &thorn;e duste risez.</L>
<L>With suche a bront &amp; a broush &middot; &thorn;e batell assembled,</L>
<L N="784">As &thorn;e erth &amp; all &thorn;e elementes &middot; at anez had wrystyllyd.</L>
<L>Now ather stoure on &thorn;ar stedes &middot; striken to-gedir,</L>
<L>Sprenten owt spakly &middot; with speres in hand,</L>
<L>Brochen both basynettes &middot; &amp; brouden sheldez,</L>
<L N="788">Beres in-to bright stele &middot; bitand lancez,</L>
<L>Sone in-to sheuerand shidez &middot; shaftez to-bristen,</L>
<L>All to-sprongen into sprotes &middot; sperez of cipriss,</L>
<L>Dryvez downe docesperes &middot; and dukez of blonkez,</L>
<L N="792">Felles fey to &thorn;e fold &middot; many fers knyghtes.</L>
<L>What doys me now &thorn;is nicholas &middot; bott nymmez hym a sper,</L>
<L>Kest hym on &thorn;is yong knyght &middot; to gett hym a name;</L>
<L>And alexander with an o&thorn;er &middot; ayers hym ayayns,</L>
<L N="796">Ridyn grymly to-geder &middot; &amp; grysly metyn.</L>
<L>So [sar] was &thorn;e semble &middot; [&thorn;ir] Seges by-twene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all to-wrasted &thorn;ai [&thorn;ar] wod &middot; &amp; warpyd in-sonder,</L>
<L>All claters in clyftez &middot; clene to &thorn;air fistez,</L>
<L N="800">&THORN;ai lefte no&thorn;er in &thorn;aire [hand] &middot; &thorn;e lenth of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> ane Elne.<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an let &thorn;ai no langer &middot; bot laughtyn owt swerdes,</L>
<L>A&thorn;ir a brade blysnand brand &middot; brade forth of shethez,</L>
<L>Hewen on heterly &middot; hadon &thorn;orow malys,</L>
<L N="804">Fele starand stanes &middot; striken of &thorn;air helmes.</L>
<L>Than alexander in ire &middot; hys arme vpp lyftes,</L>
<L>Swith swynnges vp hys swerd &middot; &amp; hys swaffe faches.</L>
<L>The nole of nicholas &thorn;e kyng &middot; he fra [&thorn;e] nek partes,</L>
<L N="808">That doun he fel from hys fole &middot; fynyshit for euer.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was hym destinate &thorn;at day &middot; as dri&yogh;ten hym shapyd,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>To hynt hym &thorn;e ouerhand &middot; of hys athell foes.</L>
<L N="811">&thorn;ar suche a worship he wan &middot; war wonder to telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;an hed he of &thorn;e hye kyng &middot; &thorn;e heued from &thorn;e shulders.</L>
<L>Than &thorn;ai gave hym vp &thorn;e &yogh;erd &middot; &amp; yolden &thorn;e realme,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at left wer [o] liue &middot; lordez &amp; other,</L>
<L>Comes to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in MS.</I></NOTE> conquerour &middot; &amp; on knes fallen,</L>
<L N="816">And on hys mercy &amp; his might &middot; mekely &thorn;aim puttes.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;us reuerently &middot; &thorn;ai rechen hym a crowne,</L>
<L>Als gome &thorn;at hase &thorn;e garland &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e gree wonne.</L>
<L>&THORN;us with &thorn;e floure in &thorn;e feld &middot; fongez he is enmy,</L>
<L N="820">And heldes on with a hynde heyre &middot; home to his fader.</L>
<L>Then fyndes he philip with his flete &middot; at a feste hoge</L>
<L>Had weddit hym ane o&thorn;er wife &middot; &amp; waueschyd hys moder;</L>
<L>Ane cleopatras was callyd &middot; a grett kyngez doghter,</L>
<L N="824">And laft [had] olympades &middot; &amp; opynly forsaken.</L>
<L>"Fadre," quod &thorn;is fele child &middot; when he &thorn;e fest entred,</L>
<L>"The palme here of my first pride &middot; I pray &thorn;e resaue,</L>
<L>Forth to &thorn;e weddyng will I wende &middot; of my wale modre,</L>
<L>And caire me to ane o&thorn;er kyng &middot; to cowpyll hir to wyfe.</L>
<L N="829">For &thorn;e to filson ne to folow &middot; falles me no more,</L>
<L>Ne here to dwelle at &thorn;i devyse &middot; deynes me no langer,</L>
<L>Thou makes suche a mangery &middot; &amp; &thorn;i mache changes,</L>
<L N="832">And I to counsell vncallyd &middot; I can noght heron."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ar carpes to &thorn;e kyng &middot; A knyght at &thorn;e table,</L>
<L>Ane lesyas, a lede &middot; &amp; on lowde spekes:</L>
<L>"Cleopatras a knaffe child &middot; consaue sall &amp; bere,</L>
<L N="836">That destinate is aftir &thorn;i day &middot; dewly to regne."</L>
<L>&THORN;en Alexander at &thorn;is athell &middot; angers vnfaire,</L>
<L>Wynnes hym vp a wardrerd &middot; he weld in hys hande,<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So hard hym hitte on &thorn;e hede &middot; his hernes owte weltyn,</L>
<L N="840">And so he lost hase hys lyfe &middot; for his lether wordes.</L>
<L>Than [was] &thorn;e wale kyng wrath &middot; als wonder wer elles,</L>
<L>Brades vp fro &thorn;e burde &middot; &amp; a brande clekez,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Ayres toward alexander &middot; &amp; aymes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. aynes.</NOTE> hym to smyte.</L>
<L N="844">Bot he fayled &thorn;e fote &middot; or he first wenes,</L>
<L>He stakez, he stombles &middot; &thorn;at stand he ne might,</L>
<L>Bott ay he fonders &amp; falles &middot; as he ferd wer.</L>
<L>The ferer forthward [he fares] &middot; &thorn;e faster [he] snappers;</L>
<L N="848">What was &thorn;e cause of &thorn;is case &middot; &thorn;at knawys our Lord.</L>
<L>"What now," quod alexander &middot; "qwatt ayles &thorn;e to fale?</L>
<L>Hase &thorn;ou no forse ne no fete &middot; ne fele to &thorn;i seluen?</L>
<L>For on freke to be so ferd &middot; or afrayd o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="852">And &thorn;ou &thorn;e gubernare of grece &middot; &thorn;at is a grete wondre!"</L>
<L>Then tittis he doun in &thorn;at tene &middot; &thorn;e tables ilkon,</L>
<L>Owt of &thorn;e halle by &thorn;e hare &middot; hales he &thorn;e birde,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e wye in his wrath &middot; wrekes hys modre,</L>
<L N="856">And philip fallyn was seke &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e fest stroblet.</L>
<L>So als byliue als alexander &middot; on angre aslakes,</L>
<L>He lendes on-lofte to &thorn;e lord &middot; a lityll dayes aftir,</L>
<L>Cares hym with comforth &middot; &thorn;e kyng for to visitt,</L>
<L N="860">Comes hym to &thorn;e cortyns &middot; &amp; carpez &thorn;ees wordez:</L>
<L>"Philip," quod &thorn;is fele freke &middot; &amp; for-with hym standez,</L>
<L>"&THORN;of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Of.</NOTE> it vnsemely me sitt &middot; &thorn;e so for to calle,</L>
<L>Noght als a sogett ne &thorn;i sonne &middot; my saw I &thorn;e yeld,</L>
<L N="864">Bot als a felow or a frend &middot; falles to an-other.</L>
<L>Sir, lat &thorn;i wrethes all wende &middot; &amp; with &thorn;i wyfe saghtyll,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e losse of sir lysyas &middot; lityll &thorn;ou charge.</L>
<L N="867">I dyd bot my deuer &middot; to drepe hym, me thynke,</L>
<L>For it awght hym no&yogh;t so opynly &middot; sike ossynges to make.</L>
<L>And vnworthly &thorn;ou wroght &middot; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou wele knawys,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou was bowne with a brande &middot; my body to shende."</L>
<L>Then rewys hym &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; of hys vnrode werkez,</L>
<L N="872">Blisshes vpp to &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; bristes owt to wepe.</L>
<L>Than ayres hym on sir alexander &middot; to hys awne modre;
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>"Beys noght aglopned, gude Dame &middot; ne greued to my fadre,</L>
<L>Ak if &thorn;ou haue synned hym bysyde &middot; als &thorn;ou &thorn;i-seluen says,<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="876">&THORN;arfore no gome may &thorn;e gylt &middot; for it is goddes wille."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at fongez hir &thorn;is freke &middot; &amp; to philip ledes,</L>
<L>And he opynly hir kyssitt &middot; &amp; cordes with hir faire,</L>
<L>&THORN;us [he anes] with olimphades &middot; &amp; &thorn;is other woydez,</L>
<L N="880">And leues louely with hir &middot; all hys lyue days.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="5" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000064.tif" N="42">
<HEAD><B>&para; Quintus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone eftir in a seson &middot; as &thorn;e buke sais,</L>
<L>Come driuand fra Darius &middot; &thorn;e deyne Empereure,</L>
<L>Heraudis on he&yogh;e hors &middot; hendly a-rayed,</L>
<L N="884">To ser Philip &thorn;e fers &middot; to feche &thorn;ar trouage.</L>
<L>Litill kyngis &thorn;ar come &middot; as &thorn;e clause tellis,</L>
<L>Li&yogh;t doune at &thorn;e loge &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar blonkis leues,</L>
<L>Caires in-to &thorn;e curte &middot; to craue him &thorn;ar dettis,</L>
<L N="888">Touchis titly &thorn;ar tale &middot; &amp; tribute him askis.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, caires hame," quod Alexander &middot; "a-gayn to &yogh;our kithes,</L>
<L>And sais &yogh;our maister, he make &middot; na ma sandis;</L>
<L N="891">For sen Philip had a fresche son &middot; &thorn;at fast now encressis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bees no&yogh;t suffird, I supose &middot; nane slike him to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>For sais &yogh;our lord, &thorn;e lefe hen &middot; &thorn;at laide hir first egg,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. 'e&yogh;e', <I>corrected to</I> egg.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire bodi nowe with barante &middot; is barely consumed,</L>
<L>And is Darius so of his dett &middot; duly depryued;</L>
<L N="896">And be &thorn;is titill, him tellis &middot; na tribute him fallis."</L>
<L>&THORN;en merualid &thorn;am &thorn;e messangirs &middot; mekill of his speche,</L>
<L>His witt &amp; his wisdome &middot; wonderly praysed.</L>
<L N="899">Faire at ser Ph[ilip] &thorn;e fers &middot; fang &thorn;ai &thorn;ar leue,</L>
<L>And syne clene of all &thorn;e curte &middot; &amp; cairis to &thorn;ar landis.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e palais of &thorn;e proude kyng &middot; to persie &thorn;ai went,</L>
<L>Dose &thorn;am in to Darius &middot; &thorn;ar he on dese syttis,</L>
<L>And telles him how his trouage &middot; is tynt al-to-gedire,<MILESTONE N="16a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="44"></L>
<L N="904">As Alexander awyn mouth &middot; had &thorn;am all enfourmed.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;en messangirs to Messedoyne &middot; come in &thorn;e mene qwile</L>
<L>To Ph[ilip] &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; &amp; freschly him tald,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e erthe of Ermony &middot; Erles &amp; princes,</L>
<L N="908">&THORN;at suld be suget to him-selfe &middot; wald seke him with armes.</L>
<L>And Alexander belyfe &middot; as athil man suld,</L>
<L>Vndirfangid to fe&yogh;t &middot; for Ph[ilip] to wende,</L>
<L>Gedirs him a grete ost &middot; graithes him in plates,</L>
<L N="912">And aires toward Ermony &middot; &thorn;at erd to distroy.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was a man in Messadone &middot; in &thorn;e marche duellid,</L>
<L>A proued prince &amp; a proude &middot; Pausanna was hatten,</L>
<L>A big berne &amp; a bald &middot; in brenys to ryde,</L>
<L N="916">&THORN;e son of ane Cerastis &middot; as &thorn;e buke witnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;is freke all his franche &middot; of Ph[ilip] he haldis,</L>
<L>And was a suget to him-selfe &middot; &amp; serues him a&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an he depely many day &middot; disired to haue &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L>And lyes vmlapped with hire lufe &middot; many lange wynter.</L>
<L N="921">And by<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at cause to &thorn;e kyng &middot; he kest slik a hate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he desiris his deth &middot; &amp; di&yogh;tis [him] &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L N="923">All &thorn;e folke of his affinite &middot; he freschly a-semblis,</L>
<L>And sekis furth with a hoge some &middot; a-saile<NOTE PLACE="foot">h <I>inserted before</I> a-saile, <I>but subpuncted.</I></NOTE> him to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>Quen Ph[ilip] heris of &thorn;at fare &middot; gret ferly him thinke[s],</L>
<L>Ferkis furth with a fewe folk &middot; him in &thorn;e fild metis,</L>
<L>Seis &thorn;e multitude sa mekill &middot; of men at he bringes,</L>
<L N="928">Braidis on his blonke toward &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; &thorn;aim &thorn;e bak shewis.</L>
<L>&THORN;en schrikis schilli all &thorn;e schalkis &middot; &amp; schoutis him at anes,</L>
<L>And Pausanna &thorn;e prince &middot; a-pon a proude stede</L>
<L>Sprengis out with a spere &middot; &amp; spedis him eftir,</L>
<L N="932">And &thorn;urgh &thorn;e bac in-to &thorn;e brest &middot; him beris to &thorn;e erd;
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>All ware he wondirly wondid &middot; he wendis no&yogh;t be-lyfe.<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His men &amp; all &thorn;e Messadones &middot; full mavnly ware stourbed,</L>
<L>Quat of doloure &amp; dyn &middot; quen &thorn;ai him dede hopid.</L>
<L N="936">Pausanna &thorn;an for &thorn;e prowis &middot; slike a pride hentis,</L>
<L>Vnethes wist he for welth &middot; wirke quat he mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>He prekis in-to &thorn;e palais &middot; to pull out &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L N="939">Wenys to wild hire at will &middot; &amp; away lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;an comes Alexander in &thorn;at cas &middot; &thorn;e cronaclis tellis,</L>
<L>With a riall ost &middot; of many able princes,</L>
<L>Airand out<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> of Ermony &middot; &amp; had all &thorn;e erth won;</L>
<L>Sees slike a rottillyng in &thorn;e rewme &middot; &amp; ridis al &thorn;e faster.</L>
<L N="944">&THORN;an past vp &thorn;e proud quene &middot; in-to preue chambre,</L>
<L>Wayues out at wyndou &middot; &amp; waytis a-boute,</L>
<L>Sa&yogh;e be &thorn;e sygnes &amp; be sike &middot; as with hire son comys,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e alyens armes &middot; at he was all maister.</L>
<L N="948">With &thorn;at scho haldis out hire hede &middot; &amp; he&yogh;e to him callis,</L>
<L>"Quare is &thorn;i werdes, my wale son &middot; &thorn;ou wan of &thorn;i godis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou suld be victour &amp; venge &middot; &amp; vencust<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. vencustis.</NOTE> neuire?</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. haue hafe, <I>altered to</I> haue.</NOTE> any hert here &middot; help now &thorn;i modire."</L>
<L N="952">Sone as pausanna &thorn;e prince &middot; with-in &thorn;e palais heris</L>
<L>&THORN;e comyng of &thorn;e kene kny&yogh;t &middot; he caires him agaynes,</L>
<L>Presis out of &thorn;e palais &middot; with a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line.</I></NOTE> pake armed,</L>
<L>And metes him in &thorn;e myd-fild &middot; with a mekill nounbre.</L>
<L N="956">And Alexander be-lyue &middot; quen he on him waites,</L>
<L>He swyngis out with a swerd &middot; &amp; swappis him to dethe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e renkis, all the route &middot; reches vp &thorn;aire wapen</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;is kid conquirour &middot; &amp; cried eftir socure.</L>
<L N="960">&THORN;an was &thorn;ar ane in &thorn;e ost &middot; on Alexander callis,</L>
<L>Sayd, "Ph[ilip] &thorn;i fadire &middot; is in &thorn;e fild drepid."</L>
<L>And he halis furth on hede &middot; &amp; halfe-dede him fyndis,</L>
<L>Brusches doune by &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; bitterly wepis.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="48"></L>
<L N="964">"A! Alexander!" quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "now am I at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> ane ende;"<MILESTONE N="17a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A litill liftis vp his liddis &middot; &amp; lokis in his face;</L>
<L>"Bot &yogh;it it gladis me," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "to ga &thorn;us to deth,</L>
<L N="967">To se my slaare in my si&yogh;t &middot; be sa sone &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>A! wele be &thorn;e, my wale son" &middot; &amp; waged with his hede;</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou has baldly on my bane &middot; &amp; bremely me vengid."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he blo&thorn;irs in &thorn;e brest &middot; &amp; &thorn;e breth stoppis,</L>
<L>And in a spedfull space &middot; so &thorn;e sprete &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L N="972">And Alexander ay on-ane &middot; augirly he wepis,</L>
<L>And gretis for him as greuously &middot; as he him geten hade.</L>
<L>With barons &amp; bachelers &middot; him bro&yogh;t to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>And erdis him in his awen erd &middot; as Emperoure fallis.</L>
<L N="976">The day efter his deth &middot; drerely him wendis</L>
<L>Alexander his aire &middot; &amp; syttis in his trone,</L>
<L>A clene croune on his hede &middot; clustird with gemmes,</L>
<L>To se how him seme wald &middot; &thorn;e sete of his fadire.</L>
<L N="980">He seis doune in &thorn;e sete &middot; with septer in hande,</L>
<L>Makis a crie &thorn;at all &thorn;e curte &middot; kni&yogh;tis &amp; erles</L>
<L>Suld put &thorn;aim in-to presens &middot; his precep to here.</L>
<L N="983">And all comyn at a kall &middot; &amp; on kneis heldis;</L>
<L>&THORN;an blisches he to his baronage &middot; &amp; breues &thorn;ir wordis:</L>
<L>"Lo! maistirs of Messedone &middot; sa mi&yogh;ty men &amp; noble,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e Traces &amp; of Tessaloyne &middot; &amp; &yogh;e &thorn;e trewe Grekis,</L>
<L N="987">How likis &yogh;ow nowe &yogh;our lege lord? &middot; lokis on my fourme,</L>
<L>And letis all ferdschip at-flee &middot; &amp; fange vp &yogh;our hertis,</L>
<L>And aires for nane alyens &middot; quils Alexander lastis.</L>
<L>For with &thorn;e graunt of my god &middot; I gesse, or I dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all the Barbare blode &middot; sall bowe to my-selfe.</L>
<L N="992">&THORN;are is na region ne rewme &middot; ne renke vnder heuen,</L>
<L>Ne nouthire-quare na nacion &middot; bot it sall my name loute.</L>
<L>For we of grece sall haue &thorn;e gree &middot; with grace ay to wild,<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And anely be ouer &thorn;e werd &middot; honourd &amp; praysed.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="50"></L>
<L N="996">And quilk of all myne athill men &middot; &thorn;at any armes wantis,</L>
<L>Lat pas in-to my palais &middot; &amp; plates him delyuire,</L>
<L>And he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line</I>.</NOTE> at of his awen has &middot; harnas him swythe,</L>
<L>And make him boune ilka berne &middot; to bataill to ride."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answard him with [a] voice &middot; all his proud princes,</L>
<L N="1001">And Erles in his Empire &middot; &thorn;at ware in eld striken,</L>
<L>Hathils of hi&yogh;e age &middot; Auncient kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Barons &amp; bachelers &middot; &amp; bryssid ware in Armes:</L>
<L>"Sire, we hafe farne to &thorn;e fi&yogh;t &middot; &amp; bene in fild preued</L>
<L N="1005">With ser Ph[ilip] &yogh;our fadire &middot; mony fele wynter,</L>
<L>And now vs failis all oure force &middot; &amp; oure flesch waykis;</L>
<L>For be &thorn;e floure neuer sa fresche &middot; it fadis at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Sire, all &thorn;e &yogh;eris of oure &yogh;outhe &middot; es &yogh;are syne passid,</L>
<L>And we for-trauailid &amp; terid &middot; &thorn;at now oure topp-haris,</L>
<L N="1010">Al to heuy to be hildid &middot; in any here-wedis,</L>
<L>Or any angwische of armes &middot; any mare suffire.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i, lord, with &yogh;oure leue &middot; we lawe &yogh;ow be-sechis</L>
<L>We may no&yogh;t stand now in stede &middot; oure strenth is [to] febill.</L>
<L>Wale &yogh;ow o&thorn;er werriouris &middot; &thorn;at wi&yogh;t ere &amp; &yogh;onger,</L>
<L>Slike as ere stife in a stoure &middot; strakis to thole."</L>
<L N="1016">"Nay, be my croune," quod &thorn;e king &middot; "my couatyng is elder</L>
<L>&THORN;e sadnes of slike men &middot; &thorn;an swyftnes of childir;</L>
<L>For barnes in &thorn;ar bignes &middot; it baldis &thorn;am mekill,</L>
<L>Oft with vnprouednes in presse &middot; to pas out of lyfe;</L>
<L N="1020">For-thi ouer-si&yogh;t of alde men &middot; I anely me chese;</L>
<L>Be connynge &amp; be consaile &middot; &thorn;ai kyth ai &thorn;ar werkis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e sle&yogh;t of hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar, <I>altered to</I> hys.</NOTE> sapience &middot; &thorn;ai selcuthely prayse,</L>
<L>And clene a-cordis to his carpe &middot; kni&yogh;tis &amp; othire.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;en dose him furthe &thorn;is dere kyng &middot; a litill dais eftir,</L>
<L N="1025">Alexander with ane ost &middot; of many athill dukis,<MILESTONE N="18a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>Samed a vnsene somme &middot; to saile he begynnes</L>
<L>Ouer in-to ytaile &middot; &thorn;a yles to distruye.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e coste of Calodone &middot; he comes him ouer first,</L>
<L N="1029">And &thorn;ar a cite he asailes &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line</I>.</NOTE> in sege lengis.</L>
<L>Bot wees wi&yogh;tly with-in &middot; &thorn;e wallis ascendid,</L>
<L>Freschly fendid of &middot; &amp; fersly with-stude.</L>
<L N="1032">"&YOGH;e Calodoyns," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; he callis fra with|oute,</L>
<L>"Outhire macches &yogh;ow maynly &thorn;erto &middot; or namely dies,</L>
<L>And fi&yogh;tis fast with &yogh;our fais &middot; to &yogh;e fey worthe,</L>
<L>Or &yogh;efes &yogh;arely vp &thorn;e &yogh;erde &middot; &amp; &yogh;eld me &thorn;e cite."</L>
<L N="1036">So chaunses it &thorn;is chiftan &middot; or he a-cheued &thorn;ine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fele he brenes of &thorn;a bernes &middot; &amp; &thorn;e bur&yogh;e wynnes,</L>
<L>And caires so out of Calodone &middot; quen he it couerid had,</L>
<L N="1039">Ouer &thorn;e ythes in-to Italee &middot; &amp; &thorn;at Ile entirs.</L>
<L>&THORN;en ware &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;e.</NOTE> [redles of] rede &middot; all redd of his come,</L>
<L>Prays him all of &thorn;e pees &middot; &amp; presandis him faire,</L>
<L>Sexti thousand &thorn;ai him send &middot; of sekire besandis,</L>
<L>Of clere gold of &thorn;aire kist &middot; &amp; coruns a hundrethe.</L>
<L N="1044">&THORN;are tuke he tribute &thorn;at tyme &middot; &thorn;e titill recordis,</L>
<L>Out euyn in-to &thorn;e occident &middot; of all at &thorn;are duellid,</L>
<L>Of qwilke &thorn;e erde &amp; &thorn;e erthe &middot; Europe was callid,</L>
<L>And ames &thorn;an to Affrike &middot; &amp; all at esse leues.</L>
<L N="1048">&THORN;an ra&yogh;t he fra &thorn;a regions &middot; &amp; remowed his ost,</L>
<L>Cachis in-to ano&thorn;ire kythe &middot; &amp; crossis ouer &thorn;e stremes,</L>
<L>Aires in-to Affrike &middot; with many athill prince[s],</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er wing of &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; wynnes it be-lyfe,</L>
<L N="1052">&THORN;at syde sodanly &amp; sone &middot; &thorn;at ser he a-cheues.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar he fande bot fewe &middot; &thorn;at felly withstude,</L>
<L>Na ridars in &thorn;a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. na, <I>corrected to</I> &thorn;a.</NOTE> regions &middot; ne rebell bot littill;</L>
<L>He laches it &thorn;e li&yogh;tlyere &middot; as was &thorn;e les wonder.</L>
<L N="1056">&THORN;an kaires he fra &thorn;o contres &middot; &amp; kerue[s] ouer &thorn;e stremes,<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Furthe to Frantites he ferd &middot; slike a ferre Ile,
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>Seches &thorn;ar to a synagoge &middot; him-selfe &amp; his princes,</L>
<L N="1059">Amon &thorn;ar awen god &middot; at &thorn;ai honoure my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And so to &thorn;e temple as he ti&yogh;t &middot; with his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>At the end of the line</I>.</NOTE> tid Erles,</L>
<L>&THORN;an metis him myddis &thorn;e way &middot; was meruale to sene,</L>
<L>A hert with a huge hede &middot; &thorn;e hareest on erthe,</L>
<L>Was to be-hald as a harow &middot; for-helid ouer &thorn;e tyndis;</L>
<L N="1064">And &thorn;an comande him &thorn;e kyng &middot; kenely to schote,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ar was na man so nemyll &middot; &thorn;at him hit couthe.</L>
<L>"A! hilla, haile," quod Alexander &middot; &amp; him a narawe hent,</L>
<L>Dro&yogh;e, &amp; at &thorn;e first dra&yogh;te &middot; him dreped for euire.</L>
<L N="1068">Fra &thorn;ethen to &thorn;is ilk day &middot; &thorn;an is &thorn;at ilke place,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stede &thorn;ar &thorn;is stith man &middot; strikis &thorn;is hert,</L>
<L>Sagittarius forsoth &middot; men gafe it to name,</L>
<L>And will do for &thorn;at ilke werk &middot; ay qwen &thorn;e werd turnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;en aires him on ser Alexander &middot; till Amon temple,</L>
<L N="1073">Offirs to his awen gode &middot; &amp; honours him faire,</L>
<L>Geuys him garsons of gold &middot; &amp; of gud stanes,</L>
<L>And hald hestes him to hete &middot; him hettirly besekis.</L>
<L N="1076">&THORN;an passes he &thorn;ethen with his princes &middot; to sich a place wendis,</L>
<L>Capho Resey we rede &middot; &thorn;e romaunce it callis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-in fyndis him &thorn;e freke &middot; fyftene Burghes,</L>
<L>And glidand to &thorn;e grete see &middot; xij grym waters.</L>
<L N="1080">Of ilka bild, sais &thorn;e buke &middot; barred was &thorn;e &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>Stoken stifly with-out &middot; with staplis &amp; cheynes.</L>
<L>&THORN;are lengis him lefe &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>At the end of the line</I>.</NOTE> kynge &middot; &amp; logis all a neuen,</L>
<L>And sacrifyce &thorn;ar efsones<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> eftsones.</NOTE> &middot; to many sere godis.</L>
<L N="1084">&THORN;e same ni&yogh;t in his slepe &middot; Seraphis aperis,</L>
<L>Anothire of his grete godis &middot; in a grym fourme,<MILESTONE N="19a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Cled in a comly clathe &middot; of castans hewes,</L>
<L>And silis euyn to him-selfe &middot; &amp; said him &thorn;ir wordis:</L>
<L N="1088">"Alexander, athill kyng" &middot; &amp; asperly spekis,</L>
<L>Toward a mi&yogh;ti montayne &middot; him myntis with his fynger,
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>"May &thorn;ou o&yogh;t, lede, &thorn;e &yogh;onder lawe &middot; lyft on &thorn;i schulder,</L>
<L>And stire it oute of &thorn;e stede &middot; &amp; stable in a-nothire?"</L>
<L N="1092">"Nay, qua mi&yogh;t &thorn;at," quod &thorn;e man &middot; "for mede vndire heuen?"</L>
<L>"Sire, as &yogh;one &yogh;ondire hi&yogh;e hill &middot; sall ay hald his place,</L>
<L>So sall &thorn;i name fra now furth &middot; be mynned in mynde,</L>
<L>And ay to &thorn;e day of dome &middot; &thorn;i dedis be remenbrid."</L>
<L N="1096">&THORN;an Alexander belyue &middot; him askis a demaunde,</L>
<L>"I be-seche &thorn;e now, Syraphas &middot; if &thorn;ou me say wald<NOTE PLACE="foot">After l. 1097 the MS. has a half-line, viz. 'For any hathill vndire heuen.' This is really the former half of l. 1102 below, and is marked for omission in the MS. This accounts for the omission of l. 1098 in the numbering, which is made to agree with Stevenson's edition.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1099">&THORN;e prophecy, or &thorn;ou pas &middot; of all my playn werdis,</L>
<L>How me is destayned to dye &middot; &amp; quen my day fallis?"</L>
<L N="1101">"Sire, certayne," quod Seraphis &middot; "as to my-selfe thinkis,</L>
<L>For any hathill vnder heuen &middot; I hald for &thorn;e better,</L>
<L>Withouten wa<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to no&yogh;t at wete; <I>but either</I> to, <I>or</I> at, <I>must be omitted</I>.</NOTE> no&yogh;t at wete &middot; &thorn;e wathe of his ende</L>
<L N="1104">&THORN;en know<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> w <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e cas or it come &middot; &amp; ay in care lenge.</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les I sall &thorn;e neuen &middot; sen &thorn;ou me now prays,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sall sal.</NOTE> be drechid of a drinke &middot; a dra&yogh;te of vnsele,</L>
<L N="1107">And all &thorn;i &yogh;eris ere &yogh;eten &yogh;are &middot; &amp; &thorn;i &yogh;outhe fenyst,</L>
<L>Lange or &thorn;ou haue meten &thorn;e merke &middot; of &thorn;i mydill age.</L>
<L>Bot quen ne in quat time &middot; sal qwaite &thorn;e &thorn;is aunter,</L>
<L>Enquire me no&yogh;t &thorn;at question &middot; for I queth &thorn;e it neuer.</L>
<L>For outhire out of &thorn;e orient &middot; sall openly here-efter</L>
<L N="1112">Vndo &thorn;e dre&yogh;t of &thorn;i days &middot; &amp; &thorn;i ded tell."</L>
<L>&THORN;an waynest him &thorn;is vayne god &middot; &amp; voidis fra &thorn;e chambre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e modi kyng on &thorn;e morne &middot; all monand he ryses;</L>
<L>&THORN;e mast parti of his princes &middot; &amp; of his proud ost<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1116">Hastis &thorn;am in-to Ascoiloym &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar &thorn;ai him bydis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an callis he to him carpentaris &middot; &amp; comandis &thorn;aim swy&thorn;e
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>In mynde &amp; in memory of him &middot; to make a cite,</L>
<L>And neuens it his awen name &middot; &thorn;at neuer syne changid,</L>
<L N="1120">Bot Alexsander ay furth &middot; efter him-seluen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">callid <I>added in a later hand, at the end of the line.</I></NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000065.tif" N="43">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Sone aftir in a seson</B> &middot; als says me &thorn;e writtes,</L>
<L>Come dryvand from sir darius &middot; &thorn;e digne Emperour,</L>
<L>Harraldes on hye horsez &middot; hendly arayede,</L>
<L N="884">To sir philopp &thorn;e fers &middot; to fett &thorn;air truage.</L>
<L>Kengez &thorn;ar come &middot; als &thorn;e clause tellez,</L>
<L>Lightyd doun at &thorn;e loge &middot; laftyn &thorn;ar blonkes,</L>
<L>Cairen fourth in-to &thorn;e courte &middot; to crauen &thorn;air dett,</L>
<L N="888">Tochett titely &thorn;are tale &middot; &amp; tribute hym asked.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, ayres hame," quod alexander &middot; "agayn to your kythez,</L>
<L>And says your maister, to me &middot; he make no moo sondez;</L>
<L N="891">For seth philop had a fressh sonn &middot; &thorn;at fast now en|cresse[s],<NOTE PLACE="foot">The lines 890 and 891 are written after line 892 in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>That beys not sufferd, I suppose &middot; no suche to hym &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>And says your lord, &thorn;e leyue henne &middot; &thorn;at lade hir frist Egge,</L>
<L>Hir body now with baraynte &middot; is barely consumed,</L>
<L>And so is darius of hys dette &middot; dewly depriued;</L>
<L N="896">And be &thorn;is tale, hym telle &middot; no tribute hym falles."</L>
<L>Than mervalett &thorn;es messyngers &middot; mykyll of hys speche,</L>
<L>Hys witt &amp; hys wisdom &middot; &thorn;ai wonderly prasen.</L>
<L>Faire at philip &thorn;e fers &middot; &thorn;air leue &thorn;ai fangen,</L>
<L N="900">And syne clene from &thorn;e courte &middot; caires to &thorn;air landez.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e palass of &thorn;e prouude [king] &middot; to perse &thorn;ai wenden,</L>
<L>And dyd &thorn;aim to sir darius &middot; &thorn;are he on dese syttes,</L>
<L>And tald hym howe is truage &middot; is tyntt all-togedre,
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="45"></L>
<L N="904">Als alex[ander] awne mouth &middot; &thorn;aim all had enformed.</L>
<L>&THORN;an messyngers to masydon &middot; come in &thorn;e meyne qwyle,</L>
<L>To philopp &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; &amp; felly hym toldyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e erth of ermony &middot; Erelez<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The MS. has</I> &amp; baron <I>after</I> Erelez, <I>but crossed through and expuncted.</I></NOTE> &amp; princez,</L>
<L N="908">At suld be sogett to hym-seluen &middot; wald seke hym with armez.</L>
<L>And alexander als beliue &middot; als athell man suld,</L>
<L>Vnderfonged &thorn;ar &thorn;e feght &middot; for philip his fader,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="912">And ayers toward ermony &middot; &thorn;at erth to distroy.</L>
<L>Then was a man in massidon &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e marche dwellyd,<MILESTONE N="6a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A proved prince &amp; a proude &middot; pausana he heght,</L>
<L>A Bigg berne &amp; a bald &middot; in brenes to ryde,</L>
<L N="916">&THORN;e sonne of one sorastes &middot; als says me &thorn;e text.</L>
<L>This freke of all &thorn;e fraunches &middot; of kyng philop haldes,</L>
<L>And was sogett to hym-seluen &middot; &amp; seruage hym awght.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;ett depely mony day &middot; desirred he &thorn;e whene,</L>
<L N="920">And leued vnlappyd with hir loue &middot; mony lang wynter.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;at cause to &thorn;e kyng &middot; he kest suche a hate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he desired hys deyde &middot; &amp; dight hym &thorn;arfore.</L>
<L N="923">All &thorn;e folke of hys affinite &middot; he fresly assemblez,</L>
<L>And sekez owt with a hoge some &middot; a-sawte hym to yelde.</L>
<L>When philip herd of &thorn;is fare &middot; grett ferly he thynkez,</L>
<L>Ferkez forth with a few folke &middot; &amp; hym in feld metes,</L>
<L N="927">Seys &thorn;e multitude so much &middot; of men &thorn;at he brynges,</L>
<L>Brades toward &thorn;e burgh on hys blonk &middot; &amp; hys bak shewys.</L>
<L>&THORN;an scrikes shilly all &thorn;e shalkys<NOTE PLACE="foot">all &thorn;e <I>is repeated here, but expuncted in MS.</I></NOTE> &middot; &amp; shotes at onys,</L>
<L>And pausana &thorn;e prince &middot; vpon a prouude stede</L>
<L>Sprynges forth with a spere &middot; &amp; spedes hym after,</L>
<L N="932">And &thorn;orow &thorn;e bake in-to &thorn;e brest &middot; hym berez to &thorn;e erth.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="47"></L>
<L N="933*">He heldes doun in &thorn;e hey way &middot; &amp; halfe deyde liggez,</L>
<L N="933">And was so wonderly woundit &middot; he wenyd noght to leve.</L>
<L>Hys men &amp; all &thorn;e masidons &middot; full fowly wer stourblett,</L>
<L>What for doloure &amp; dyne &middot; when &thorn;ai hym dede hopen.</L>
<L N="936">Pausana for &thorn;ees prowes &middot; slike a pride hentes,</L>
<L>That vneth he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hy, <I>corrected to</I> he.</NOTE> wist for welth &middot; what he wirke might.</L>
<L>He prekes into &thorn;e palace &middot; to pull owt &thorn;e whene,</L>
<L>Wenes to wilde hir at will &middot; &amp; away lede.</L>
<L N="940">&THORN;an comes euen onon &middot; &thorn;e cronacles telles,</L>
<L>Alexander with ane oste &middot; of mony able princez,</L>
<L>Ayrand owt of Ermony &middot; hed all &thorn;e erth wonne;<NOTE PLACE="marg">2<SUP>a</SUP> victoria alexandri</NOTE></L>
<L>Herd suche a rastelyng in &thorn;e realm &middot; &amp; rydez &thorn;e faster.</L>
<L>Than passyd forth &thorn;e prouude whene &middot; into a prevay chamer,</L>
<L N="945">Wayfez vp a wyndow &middot; &amp; waytes &thorn;ar-owt,</L>
<L>Sees wele by signes &middot; at hir sonne come,</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e alyens armes &middot; &thorn;at he was all mayster.</L>
<L N="948">With &thorn;at she haldez forth hir heued &middot; &amp; hegh to hym calles:<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Whare er &thorn;i werdes, my wale sonn &middot; &thorn;ou wan of &thorn;i goddez,</L>
<L>Thu suld be victour to venge &middot; &amp; venkest neuer?</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou haue ony hert her &middot; help now &thorn;i moder."</L>
<L N="952">Sone as pausana in &thorn;e place &middot; &thorn;is tale herys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e commyng of &thorn;is kene knyght &middot; he carys hym ayayns,</L>
<L>Preses owt of &thorn;e palasse &middot; with a pake enarmed,</L>
<L>And metes hym in &thorn;e myd-feld &middot; with a much nowmbre.</L>
<L N="956">Bot alexander als belyfe &middot; as he on hym wates,</L>
<L>He swyngez owt a sharpe swerde &middot; &amp; hym to deth swappys;</L>
<L>And &thorn;en hys renkez all in rowte &middot; rechen vp &thorn;ar waypynnez</L>
<L N="959">Vnto &thorn;is kyd conquerour &middot; &amp; cryen aftir socour.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd &thorn;ar an with-in &thorn;e ost &middot; &amp; on alexander calles,</L>
<L>Sayd: "philip &thorn;i fader &middot; is in &thorn;e feld drepyd."</L>
<L>And he hyes &thorn;en fast forth &middot; &amp; halfe-deyde hym fyndez,</L>
<L>Brushys doun by &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; bitterly wepys.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="49"></L>
<L N="964">"Aa! alexander, sonn!" quod &thorn;is athell &middot; "[now] am I att on ende."</L>
<L>A lityll lyftes hys lendes &middot; &amp; lukes in hys face;</L>
<L>"Bot &yogh;ett me gladdes," quod &thorn;is gome &middot; "to byde &thorn;us on lyve,</L>
<L N="967">To see my slaer in my sight &middot; be so sone &yogh;holden.</L>
<L>A! wele be &thorn;ou, wale son" &middot; &amp; wagged with hys heued;</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou hase baldly on my bane &middot; &amp; bremely me venged."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he blothers in &thorn;e brest &middot; &amp; hys breth stoppys,</L>
<L>And in a spedfull space &middot; &thorn;e spirit he &yogh;eldez.</L>
<L N="972">Bott alexander euerelike &middot; awgerdly pleynez,</L>
<L>And grettes for hym als grefully &middot; as he hym gettyn hed.</L>
<L>With barons &amp; with bachelers &middot; he bare hym to &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L>And erdes hym in hys awne erth &middot; as emperour falles.</L>
<L N="976">The day after hys deth &middot; &thorn;en durely he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> him.</NOTE> wendes</L>
<L>Alexander hys ayre &middot; vppe in hys awne trone,</L>
<L>A clere croune on hys heued &middot; clustird with gemmys,</L>
<L>To se how he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> him.</NOTE> seme wald &middot; &thorn;e sete of hys fader.</L>
<L N="980">He sittes doun in &thorn;at sete &middot; with septour in hand,</L>
<L>Makes a cry &thorn;at all &thorn;e courte &middot; knyghtez &amp; Erelez</L>
<L>Suld come &amp; be present &middot; hys precept to here.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai come at hys calle &middot; &amp; on kneys heldit,</L>
<L N="984">&THORN;an blyssez he vnto hys bernes &middot; &amp; breues &thorn;es wordez:</L>
<L>"Lo! maisterlynges of massydon &middot; so myghty &amp; so noble,<MILESTONE N="7a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ye tracez of thessalon &middot; &amp; ye trew grekez,</L>
<L>How likez now you your leege lord? &middot; loke on my forme,</L>
<L>And lettes all ferdshipys<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. frendshipys.</NOTE> flee &middot; &amp; fongez vpp your hertes,</L>
<L N="989">And arghes for no aliens &middot; whilse alexander lefys.</L>
<L>For with &thorn;e graunt of my god &middot; I gesse, or I dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e barberon blode &middot; sall bow to my seluen.</L>
<L N="992">Thare is no region ne realm &middot; so riche vnder heuen,</L>
<L>Ne no&thorn;er-whare no nacion &middot; bot sall my name lowte.</L>
<L>For we of grece sal haue &thorn;e gre &middot; with grace ay to weld,</L>
<L>And only ouer all &thorn;e werld &middot; be honourd &amp; prassed.
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="51"></L>
<L N="996">And whilk of all my athell men &middot; any armour wantes,</L>
<L>Bot passe into my palasse &middot; &amp; plates hym delyver,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at of hys awne hase &middot; harnes hym swith,</L>
<L>And make hym bowne euerylke berne &middot; to batell to wend."</L>
<L>&THORN;en answerd hym with a voyce &middot; all hys prouude princez</L>
<L N="1001">And Ereles of hys Empire &middot; &thorn;at wer in elde stryken,</L>
<L>Hatels<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> of hegh age &middot; &amp; auancet knyghtez,</L>
<L>Barons &amp; bachelers &middot; &thorn;at bresyd wer in armys:</L>
<L>"Sir, we haue faren in-to feld<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> feld.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; ben in feld<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> feld.</NOTE> preuett</L>
<L N="1005">With sir philip your fader &middot; many fele wyntre,</L>
<L>And now vs falez all our force &middot; &amp; owr fleche wakens;</L>
<L>For be &thorn;e floure neuer so freshe &middot; it fades at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L N="1008">Sir, all &thorn;e &yogh;eres of owr youth &middot; bene &yogh;are syne passyd,</L>
<L>And we for-traveld &amp; for-tyred &middot; &thorn;at now owr topp horez,</L>
<L>All to hevy to be hold &middot; with ony here wedes,</L>
<L>Or ony awnterez of armes &middot; to any more suffre.</L>
<L N="1012">For-&thorn;i, lorde, with your leve &middot; we loughly besekes,</L>
<L>We may noght stande you in stede &middot; our strenthez er to feble.</L>
<L>Lat wale you other weriowrs &middot; &thorn;at wight er &amp; yonge,</L>
<L>Sike as styffe er in stowre &middot; strakez to dele."</L>
<L N="1016">"Nay, by my Corone," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "my covetyng is helder</L>
<L>The sadnesse of suche men &middot; &thorn;en swyftnes of childer;</L>
<L>For barnez in &thorn;air bignes &middot; &thorn;at beldez &thorn;aim to mekyll,</L>
<L>Oft with vnpro[ued]nes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. vnprones.</NOTE> in prese<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. prorese, <I>corrected to</I> prese.</NOTE> &middot; passen owt of liue;</L>
<L N="1020">For-&thorn;i ouersight of ald men<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. almen.</NOTE> &middot; I anely me chese;</L>
<L>By Connyng &amp; consell &middot; &thorn;ai kythen ay &thorn;ar Werkez."<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;e sleght of hys sapience &middot; &thorn;ai selcouthly prasen,</L>
<L>And clene acordes to hys carpyng &middot; knyghtez &amp; othre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. othree.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than dose hym furth &thorn;e derfe kyng &middot; a lityll days aftir,</L>
<L N="1025">Alexander with ane ost &middot; of mony athell dukez,
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>Sampnez ane vnsene some &middot; to sayle he begynnez</L>
<L>Oure in-to Itale &middot; &thorn;e ylez to distroy.</L>
<L N="1028">In-to &thorn;e cost of calydon &middot; he commez on first,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar a cyte assalez &middot; and in a sege lenges.</L>
<L>Bot wies wightly with-in &middot; &thorn;e wallez ascendyn,</L>
<L>Freshly defendyng of &middot; &amp; fersly with-stondyn.</L>
<L N="1032">"Yhe calodons," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; and [calles] from with|owte,</L>
<L>"Owther mache yow manly<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. maly, <I>corrected by later hand to</I> manly.</NOTE> &thorn;arto &middot; or maynly dyez,</L>
<L>And feght fast with &yogh;ouer faes &middot; to yhe faye worthen,</L>
<L>Or yevez &yogh;arely vp &thorn;e &yogh;erd &middot; and gefes me vp &thorn;e cite."</L>
<L N="1036">So chauncez it &thorn;at cheftan &middot; or he achevet &thorn;ine,</L>
<L>That fele he britens of &thorn;a bernez &middot; &amp; &thorn;e burgh wynnez.</L>
<L>&THORN;en carez owt of calidon &middot; when he it coueryd hadde,</L>
<L>Owre &thorn;e ylez of ytale &middot; &amp; &thorn;a ylez entrees.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai wer redles of-ragthe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.; <I>both</I> MSS. <I>corrupt</I>.</NOTE> &middot; of &thorn;is kengez commyng,</L>
<L N="1041">Prayed hym all for &thorn;e pease &middot; &amp; present hym faire,</L>
<L>Sexty thousand hym sendes &middot; of sekyr besandez,</L>
<L>Of clere gold of &thorn;air kystez &middot; and corownez a hundreth.</L>
<L N="1044">Thare tuke he tribute &thorn;at tyme &middot; as &thorn;e text recordez,</L>
<L>Owt onon into &thorn;e occident &middot; of all &thorn;at &thorn;ar dwellyd,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whilke &thorn;e erth &middot; of Ermony is callyd,</L>
<L>And amez hym toward aufrike &middot; &amp; all at ease leues.</L>
<L N="1048">Than raught he from &thorn;e regions &middot; &amp; rowmyd hys oste,</L>
<L>Cachez into an-other kyth &middot; &amp; crosez ouer &thorn;e stremez,</L>
<L>Ayrez hym into aufrik &middot; with mony athell princez,</L>
<L>An-other wynge of &thorn;e werld &middot; wynnes it belyue,</L>
<L N="1052">&THORN;at syde sodanly &amp; sone &middot; &thorn;at sire hym achevys.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar he fand bott few &middot; to fersly hym withstonde,</L>
<L>Ne ryders in &thorn;at regions &middot; ne rebellez bot lityll;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;aim laught all &thorn;e lighter &middot; as was les wondre.</L>
<L N="1056">&THORN;en cairez he fro &thorn;oes cuntrees &middot; &amp; kerues ouer &thorn;e stremes,</L>
<L>Forth to francides he fared &middot; suche a ferme yle,<MILESTONE N="8a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>Sekes &thorn;ar to a synagoge &middot; hym-selfe &amp; hys princez,</L>
<L>Amone &thorn;ar awne god &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ai adour mighten,</L>
<L>And so to hys tempyll to-teght &middot; all with hys tried Ereles.</L>
<L N="1061">Than met &thorn;aim in myd way &middot; was mervale to see,</L>
<L>Ane hert with a hoge heued &middot; &thorn;e aughfulest on erth,</L>
<L>Was to behald as a harrow &middot; foreheld ouer with tyndez;</L>
<L N="1064">And &thorn;an Comandez &thorn;aim &thorn;e kyng &middot; kenely to shote,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ar was no man so nemyll &middot; &thorn;at hym hit couth.</L>
<L>"A! euell hale!" quod alexander &middot; &amp; an arow hyntes,</L>
<L>Drogh, and at &thorn;e frist draught &middot; hym drepyd for euer.</L>
<L N="1068">Fro &thorn;ine &thorn;an vnto &thorn;is day &middot; &thorn;an is &thorn;at ilke place,</L>
<L>The stede &thorn;ar &thorn;is styffe man &middot; strikez &thorn;is hert,</L>
<L>Sagittarius for soth &middot; men seggen it to name,</L>
<L>And will do for &thorn;at ilke deyd &middot; ay to &thorn;e werld lastes.</L>
<L>Than ayrez hym on sir alexander &middot; to &thorn;e amonez temple,</L>
<L N="1073">Offers to hys awne god &middot; &amp; honours hym faire,</L>
<L>Gyffez hym garsons<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. garfons.</NOTE> of gold &middot; and other gude stanez,</L>
<L>And held hestez hym to hete &middot; heterly besekez.</L>
<L N="1076">Than passid he &thorn;ine with hys princez &middot; to siche a place wendes,</L>
<L>Chaipho rosey we rede &middot; &thorn;e romanys it telles;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arin fyndez &thorn;e freke &middot; fyftene burges,</L>
<L>And glydand to &thorn;e grett see &middot; twelfe gret waters.</L>
<L N="1080">Off ilke belde, says &thorn;e buke &middot; barred was &thorn;e &yogh;ates,</L>
<L>Stoken styfly withowte &middot; with barrez of yren.</L>
<L>Thare lengez &thorn;e leue kynge &middot; &amp; loges all an euen,</L>
<L>And sacrified &thorn;ar eft-sones &middot; to mony sere goddez.</L>
<L N="1084">The same nyght in hys slepe &middot; serapys appered,</L>
<L>An-other of hys grett goddez &middot; &amp; in a grymme forme,</L>
<L>Clede in a clath &middot; of castanez colour,</L>
<L>And syles euen to hym-selfe &middot; &amp; sayd hym &thorn;ees wordez:</L>
<L>"A! alexander, atell<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> kynge" &middot; and asperly spekys,</L>
<L N="1089">And toward a myghty mountane &middot; hym myntyd with hys fynger,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>"May &thorn;ou oght, lede, yond[e]r low &middot; lift on &thorn;i shulder,</L>
<L>And stere it owt of one stede &middot; &amp; stablet in ane other?"</L>
<L N="1092">"Nay, wha my&yogh;t &thorn;at," quod &thorn;e man, &middot; "for mede vnder heuen?"</L>
<L>"Sir, as yonder hye hille &middot; sall hald ay hys place,</L>
<L>So sall &thorn;i name owt of nowmbre &middot; be nomyn in-to mynde,<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And vnto &thorn;e day of dome &middot; &thorn;i dedes be remenbryd."</L>
<L N="1096">Than alexander als belyue &middot; hym askys a demande,</L>
<L>"I beseke &thorn;e, sir serapys &middot; yf &thorn;ou me say wald<NOTE PLACE="foot">Line 1098 is omitted in the numbering; see note on p. 56.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1099">&THORN;e prophecy or &thorn;ou passe &middot; of all my playne werdes,</L>
<L>How me is destanet to dye &middot; &amp; when my day fallez?"</L>
<L N="1101">"Sir, certanly," quod seraphys &middot; "als to my-seluen thynkez,</L>
<L>To ony athell vnder heuen &middot; I hald it for &thorn;e better,</L>
<L>With-owtyn wa no&yogh;t to witte &middot; &thorn;e wothe of hys ende</L>
<L N="1104">Ne knaw &thorn;e cause or it come &middot; &amp; ay in care lenge.</L>
<L>Bot neuer-&thorn;e-lesse I sall &thorn;e neven &middot; sen &thorn;ou me prayes,</L>
<L>Thu sall be drenchett with a drinke &middot; a draught of vnclene,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e yherez &thorn;ar &middot; in &thorn;i youth fynyshytt,</L>
<L>Lange or &thorn;ou metyn haue &thorn;e merke &middot; of &thorn;i medyll age.</L>
<L>Bott when ne in what age or tyme &middot; sall falle &thorn;is awentur,</L>
<L N="1110">Inquire me noght &thorn;is question &middot; I queth it &thorn;e neuer.</L>
<L>For other owt of &thorn;e orient &middot; sall openly hereafter</L>
<L N="1112">Vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So;</I> for Vndo.</NOTE> &thorn;e dro&yogh;t of &thorn;i days &middot; &amp; &thorn;i deth to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Better omitted</I>.</NOTE> telle."</L>
<L>&THORN;an vanyshit &thorn;is wayn god &middot; &amp; woydez from &thorn;e chawmbre.</L>
<L>The mody kyng on &thorn;e morne &middot; all murnand he risez,</L>
<L>&THORN;e moste party of hys princez &middot; &amp; of hys proude ostez</L>
<L N="1116">Bound to ascolon &middot; and &thorn;ar hym abydez.</L>
<L>Than callyd he to hys carpenters &middot; comand &thorn;aim swythe
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>In mynde &amp; memory of hym &middot; to make &thorn;ar a cite,</L>
<L>And after his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. myne; <I>wrongly</I>.</NOTE> awne name &middot; &thorn;at neuer syne chaungett,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. chaaungett.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1120">Alexander ay forth &middot; after hym-seluen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000080.tif" N="58">
<HEAD><B>&para; Sextus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now airis he furthe with his ost &middot; to Egist he thinkes;</L>
<L>And clene all &thorn;e contre &middot; quen &thorn;ai his come herd,</L>
<L>As he had bene a hi&yogh;e gode &middot; &thorn;ai &yogh;ode him a-gayn,</L>
<L N="1124">Resaued him with reuerence &middot; &amp; to &thorn;ar rewme lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere entirs him &thorn;at Emperoure &middot; &amp; in &thorn;at erd findis</L>
<L>Of Anec his awen sire &middot; ane ymage of sable,</L>
<L>A berne was of blake stane &middot; all &thorn;e body hewen</L>
<L>With conyschance of a kynge &middot; with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> coron &amp; septere.</L>
<L N="1129">&THORN;an askis of &thorn;am Alexander &middot; as he &thorn;ar-on lokis,</L>
<L>Quat maner of man apon mold &middot; it was made efter?</L>
<L>"Sire, Anectabus" &middot; quod all with a steuen,</L>
<L N="1132">"&THORN;at all &thorn;e erth of Egipte &middot; enerid vmquile."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e flammand flode &middot; fell in his e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at Anec," quod &thorn;is athil kyng &middot; "was myne awen fadire."</L>
<L>&THORN;an fallis he flat on &thorn;e fold &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fete kyssis;</L>
<L N="1136">On &thorn;e stane quare it stode &middot; stilly he mournes.</L>
<L>Syne in-to Sirie with his seggis &middot; he so&yogh;t at &thorn;e gaynest,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> as baratours bald &middot; him bigly with-standis,</L>
<L>Set on him sadly &middot; &amp; slo&yogh;e of his kni&yogh;tis;</L>
<L N="1140">Bot &yogh;et &yogh;arely are he &yogh;ode &middot; &thorn;ai &yogh;ald him &thorn;e regne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an drafe he sa to Damac &middot; with dukis &amp; princes,</L>
<L>And sone he sesyd all &thorn;at syde &middot; &amp; Sydoyne he takis,<MILESTONE N="20a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;en trussis him to Tyre &middot; &amp; &thorn;are his tentis settis</L>
<L N="1144">Be-syde &thorn;e cite with a some &middot; &amp; in a sege lengys.</L>
<L>&THORN;are he lies with his ledis &middot; lang or he foundes,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e bur&yogh;e with his bernes &middot; &amp; mekill bale suffirs.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>Quat of ane, quat of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> o&thorn;ire &middot; oft his oste pleynes,</L>
<L N="1148">For wele wist &thorn;ai &thorn;am nane &middot; to wyn to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>It was sa stiffe &amp; sa strang &middot; &amp; stalworthly wallid,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. And &thorn;ai; <I>but</I> &thorn;ai <I>is better omitted</I>.</NOTE> so hedously hi&yogh;e &middot; it was a huge wondire,</L>
<L>Tildid full of turestis &middot; &amp; toures of defence,</L>
<L N="1152">Batailid &amp; bretagid &middot; a-boute as a castell.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wawis of &thorn;e wild see &middot; apon &thorn;e wallis betis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pure populande hurle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> perle.</NOTE> &middot; passis it vmby,</L>
<L N="1155">It was enforced with sa fele &middot; fludis &amp; othire,</L>
<L>It semed neuer sege vnder son &middot; be saute it to wyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an etils him sir Alexander &middot; &amp; belyue makis</L>
<L>Be-side &thorn;e cite in &thorn;e See &middot; to sett vp a loge,</L>
<L>A hi&yogh;e tilde as a toure &middot; teldid on schippis,</L>
<L N="1160">&THORN;at mi&yogh;t na Naue for &thorn;at note &middot; ne&yogh;e to &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;is baistell had bild &middot; vp to &thorn;e bur&yogh;e wallis,</L>
<L>And ti&yogh;t him as tyme was &middot; &thorn;e toune to assaill,</L>
<L>Slik mischife in &thorn;e mene quile &middot; emang his men fallis,</L>
<L N="1164">For megire &amp; for meteles &middot; ware mervaile to here.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was Princes in poynt &middot; to perisch for euire,</L>
<L>Alle in doute to be dede &middot; dukis &amp; erlis,</L>
<L>In fere to be famyschist &middot; many fers kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="1168">For &thorn;ar is na wa in &thorn;e werd &middot; to &thorn;e wode hunger.</L>
<L>&THORN;an pleynis him &thorn;e proud kyng &middot; &thorn;e pete of his men,</L>
<L>And sendis out his sandis-men &middot; with selid lettirs,</L>
<L N="1171">To ierusalem to Iaudis &middot; at &thorn;e iewes teches,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e bischop in &thorn;at bur&yogh;e &middot; breuyd in &thorn;a dais;<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Him moneste as a maister &middot; him<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> maynly to send</L>
<L>Fresch folke for &thorn;e fi&yogh;t &middot; &amp; fode for his oste,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e trouage &thorn;are to him &middot; tittly to wayue,</L>
<L N="1176">&THORN;at he to Darius of dewe &middot; was dangird to paye.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it comand he &thorn;is clerke &middot; &thorn;e kyng in his writtes,</L>
<L>For any richas him redis &middot; rathere to thole</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayntenance of &thorn;e Messedoyns &amp; of &thorn;e meri Grekis,
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="62"></L>
<L N="1180">&THORN;an &thorn;aim<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;aiem.</NOTE> of Persy to pay &middot; or to plese authere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an takis &thorn;e bischop &thorn;e breue &middot; &amp; bu&yogh;es to a chambre,</L>
<L>Resayued it with reuerence &middot; &amp; redis it<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> ouire,</L>
<L>Gase him doun be degrece &middot; a-gayne to &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L N="1184">Swiftly to &thorn;e swiars &middot; &amp; &thorn;am his sware &yogh;eldis:</L>
<L>"Sirs, airis a-gayn to Alexander &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;<SUP>us</SUP>.</NOTE> him tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me was done many day &middot; depely to swere,</L>
<L>Neuer Persy to paire &middot; to pas with myne armes</L>
<L N="1188">In damaging of Darius &middot; durand his lyfe."</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e wale kyng wist &middot; he writhis him vnfaire,</L>
<L>"Now be &thorn;at god," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "&thorn;at gatt me on erthe,</L>
<L N="1191">I sall anes on &thorn;e iewis &middot; enioyne or I die,</L>
<L>Sall ken &thorn;am quas comandment &middot; to kepe at &thorn;am fall."</L>
<L>&YOGH;it for na torfar him tid &middot; Tyre wald he no&yogh;t leue,</L>
<L>Bot chese him out a chiftane &middot; &amp; charge[s] him belyue,</L>
<L>A mody man, ser Meliager &middot; a maister of his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hio.</NOTE> oste,</L>
<L N="1196">To fande him furth with a flote &middot; of fyue hundreth kni&yogh;tis;</L>
<L>A[nd] Ioynes him to Iosaphat &middot; his iournay to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to to; <I>with former</I> to <I>struck out.</I></NOTE> take,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e pastours &amp; &thorn;e playnes &middot; prestly to driue,</L>
<L>And bring in all &thorn;e bestaill &middot; barayn &amp; othire,</L>
<L N="1200">&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t se on any syde &middot; &thorn;e cite of Gadirs.</L>
<L>&THORN;an mouys he on, ser Meliager &middot; &thorn;is mi&yogh;tifull prince</L>
<L>With a soume of sekir men &middot; &amp; Sampson &thorn;am ledis,<MILESTONE N="21a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A renke at in &thorn;a regions &middot; had redyn oft sythis,</L>
<L>And knew &thorn;e costis &amp; &thorn;e kitthis &middot; clene all-to-gedire.</L>
<L N="1205">&THORN;us &yogh;ede &thorn;ai furthe egirly &middot; &amp; entirs &thorn;e vaile,</L>
<L>And slike a prai &thorn;am apreued &middot; as pyne were to reken,</L>
<L>Bryngis furthe, sayd &thorn;e boke &middot; bestis out of nounbre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. mounbre.</NOTE></L>
<L>And trottes on toward Tyre &middot; with taite at &thorn;aire hertis.</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;ai meten ware a myle &middot; &thorn;e meris with-outen,
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>&thorn;ar metis &thorn;aim with a mekill flote &middot; &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e playnes,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at was duke of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> droues &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e derfe hillis,</L>
<L N="1212">Ane Theosellus, a tulke &middot; &thorn;at tened &thorn;am vnfaire.</L>
<L>He girdis in with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted at the end of the line.</I></NOTE> a ging &middot; armed in plates,</L>
<L>Alto-bruntes oure bernes &middot; &amp; brathly woundid,</L>
<L>Fellis fele at a frusch &middot; fey to &thorn;e gronde,</L>
<L N="1216">And many renke at he roue &middot; rase neuer efter.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was ser Meliager moued &middot; &amp; maynly debatis,</L>
<L>Flingis out on a fole &middot; with a fell spere,</L>
<L>Gers many grete syre grane &middot; &amp; girdis &thorn;ur&yogh;e maillis,</L>
<L N="1220">And many bernes at a braide &middot; in his brath endis.</L>
<L>And Sampson on anothire side &middot; setis out belyue,</L>
<L>Bruschis furth on a blonk &middot; brymly he smytis,</L>
<L>Betis on with a brande &middot; broken was his lance,</L>
<L N="1224">Hewis doun of &thorn;a hirdis &middot; hurtis &thorn;am vn-faire.</L>
<L>Arystes, ane athill man &middot; ai elike fi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Spirris out with a spere &middot; &amp; spedis his mi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>And noyed of &thorn;are note-men &middot; at &thorn;e nete kepid,</L>
<L N="1228">And many bald, or he blan &middot; bro&yogh;t out o-lyue.</L>
<L>Caulus, anothire kni&yogh;t &middot; on a kene stede,</L>
<L>On Theosellus in twa &middot; his tymbre he brekis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he dryfes to &thorn;e duke &middot; as demys &thorn;e textis,</L>
<L N="1232">And with a swyng of a swerd &middot; swappis of hes hede.</L>
<L>When he was drepid &amp; dede &middot; at &thorn;e droues &yogh;emyd,<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e prekars of &thorn;e pastors &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e proude landis,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e folke of his affinite &middot; at fresch ware vn-wondid ,</L>
<L N="1236">&THORN;at outhire fote had or fole &middot; to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t foundid.</L>
<L>&THORN;us Meliager with his men &middot; &thorn;e menske has a-chevyd,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fairere of &thorn;ar faes &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fild wonn;</L>
<L>Raschis with rethere &middot; &amp; rydis bot a quyle,</L>
<L N="1240">&THORN;at ne ne&yogh;is &thorn;am a-nothire note &middot; as new as &thorn;e first.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was a maister of &thorn;e marches &middot; mi&yogh;tist of othire</L>
<L>Ane Beritinus, a berne &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Come girdand out of Gadirs &middot; out of &thorn;e grete cite,
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="66"></L>
<L N="1244">With &thorn;e selcuthest soume &middot; &thorn;at semblid was euire.</L>
<L>Slik a mynd vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to <I>added in margin</I>.</NOTE> me &middot; ware meruaill to reken,</L>
<L>Thretti thousand in thede &middot; of thra men of armes,</L>
<L>Slike as was buskest on blonkes &middot; in brenys &amp; platis,</L>
<L>And othire folawand on fote &middot; fele with-outen nounbre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e multitude was sa mekill &middot; as mynes vs &thorn;e writtis,</L>
<L>Of wees &amp; of wild horsis &middot; &amp; wapened prenys,</L>
<L>Sa stithe a steuyn in &thorn;e stoure &middot; of stedis &amp; ellis,</L>
<L N="1252">As it was semand to si&yogh;t &middot; as all &thorn;e soyle trymblid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ware &thorn;e Messedones amayd &middot; quen &thorn;a see<NOTE PLACE="foot">see <I>added in margin</I>.</NOTE> sa many;</L>
<L>Sire Meliager [was] in gret mynd &middot; a man out to sende</L>
<L N="1255">To ser Alexander belyue &middot; &thorn;aire allire maister,</L>
<L>To come &amp; help with his here &middot; or &thorn;ai to hande &yogh;ode.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was nane &thorn;at was glad &middot; &thorn;at message to gange,</L>
<L>Bot ilka lathire &amp; othire &middot; to leue &thorn;aire frynde,</L>
<L>Fest &thorn;ar forward in-fere &middot; &thorn;at fewe at &thorn;ai ware,</L>
<L N="1260">To do as dri&yogh;ten wald deme &middot; &amp; dyi all to-gedire;</L>
<L>To telle &thorn;aire torfere entyre &middot; it taryed me swythe.<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot so &thorn;e mode Meliager &middot; &amp; his men fe&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ser Beritinus &thorn;e bald &middot; &thorn;ai bretned to dethe,</L>
<L N="1264">And Sampson on &thorn;is side &middot; was slay &thorn;ar-agaynys.</L>
<L>&THORN;en mournes all &thorn;e Messedones &middot; &amp; maynten him &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>Makis &thorn;ar mane for &thorn;at man &middot; &amp; many othire noble,</L>
<L N="1267">For maistris &amp; mynistris &middot; menere &amp; grettir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was in morsels magged &middot; &amp; martrid a hundreth.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at left ware on lyfe &middot; bot a litill me&yogh;ne,</L>
<L>Ware als malstrid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic.</I></NOTE> &amp; mased &middot; &amp; matid of &thorn;aire strenthes,</L>
<L N="1271">Sa waike &amp; so wyndles &middot; &amp; wery for-fo&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai were will in &thorn;is werd &middot; qwat &thorn;ai worthe suld.</L>
<L>Sire Meliager &amp; othire maa &middot; mayned were sare,</L>
<L>All be-bled &amp; to-brissid &middot; &thorn;at ne&yogh;e &thorn;ar breth failes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai were sa feble &amp; sa faynt &middot; &amp; full of &thorn;aim-selfe,</L>
<L N="1276">&THORN;at all in fere was in fourme &middot; &thorn;e fild for to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires him forth Arestes &middot; was augrily wondid,</L>
<L>To Alexander onone &middot; &thorn;as auntirs him tellis,
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>&THORN;e morth of all &thorn;e Messedone[s] &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e many grekis,</L>
<L N="1280">Rekens him &thorn;ar resons &middot; &thorn;at reuthe was to here.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e semely kyng &middot; chacches his bernes,</L>
<L>Semblis him a huge soume &middot; &amp; fra &thorn;e sege wendis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e toure of Tire &amp; &thorn;e toune &middot; titly he leues,</L>
<L N="1284">And Ioynes him to Iosaphat &middot; full ioyles he rydes.</L>
<L>Ay he gretis as he gase &middot; for grefe of his kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Ay he pleynys as he passes &middot; &thorn;e pite of his erlis,</L>
<L>Ay he wepis as he wendis &middot; for his wale princes,</L>
<L N="1288">And soueraynly for Sampson &middot; he sorowis ay elike.</L>
<L>When he was tane fraward<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. toward <I>altered to</I> fraward.</NOTE> Tyre &middot; toward &thorn;e vaile,</L>
<L>&THORN;e werke at he wro&yogh;t had &middot; &thorn;at water whyt-in,<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he had sett in &thorn;e see &middot; &thorn;e cite with-out,</L>
<L N="1292">&thorn;ar-in he lefte had a lede &middot; &thorn;e loge for to kepe.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;an ser Balaan, a berne &middot; at in &thorn;e bur&yogh;e lengis,</L>
<L>Ane of &thorn;e terands of Tyre &middot; atyres him<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>here inserts</I> h, <I>but it is struck out</I>.</NOTE> belyue,</L>
<L N="1295">Buskes him in breneis &middot; with big men of armes,</L>
<L>With traumes &amp; with tribochetis &middot; &thorn;e tild to asaile.</L>
<L>He bekirs out at &thorn;e bild &middot; within &thorn;e bur&yogh;e-wallis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai without in &thorn;e werke &middot; wi&yogh;tly defendis,</L>
<L>Schot scharply betwene &middot; schomes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> schoures.</NOTE> of dartis;</L>
<L N="1300">Weris wondirly wele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; werpis out stanes.</L>
<L>Bot Balaa[n] in &thorn;e barmeken &middot; sa bitterly fi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>All to-combirs &thorn;am clene &middot; with cast of engynes.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e top of &thorn;e toure &middot; he tiltis in-to &thorn;e watir,</L>
<L N="1304">And all &thorn;e tulkis in &thorn;e tild &middot; he termens o lyue;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an in batis &amp; in bargis &middot; he bownes him swyth,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bothum of &thorn;e baistell &middot; he buskis him with-out,</L>
<L N="1307">Bretens doun all &thorn;e bild &middot; &amp; &thorn;e bernys quellis,</L>
<L>Drenches hire in &thorn;e hi&yogh;e see &middot; &amp; drawis hire on hepis.</L>
<L>Quen it was smeten in small &middot; with &thorn;e smert wa&yogh;es,</L>
<L>Ilka gobet his gate &middot; glidis fra othire.</L>
<L>&THORN;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;us was.</NOTE> &thorn;e strenth ilk stike<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. stilk stike; <I>but</I> stilk <I>is struck out</I>.</NOTE> &middot; was in a stounde wasted,
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>And Balaa[n] bowis in-to &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; barris to &thorn;e &yogh;atis.</L>
<L N="1313">Be &thorn;is oure kyng with his kni&yogh;t[is] &middot; is comen in-to &thorn;e vaile,</L>
<L>Alexander with ane ost &middot; his kni&yogh;tis to help,</L>
<L>Fyndis a fewe of his folke &middot; fe&yogh;tand &yogh;erne,</L>
<L N="1316">And ay a segge be him-selfe &middot; sett all a hundreth.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at Bucifalon his blonke &middot; he brased<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> a <I>is ill-formed</I>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e side,</L>
<L>Springis out with a spere &middot; spillis at &thorn;e gaynest,</L>
<L>Ridis euen &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e route &middot; &thorn;ar rankest &thorn;ai were,</L>
<L N="1320">Be rawe of &thorn;ar rabetis &middot; he ruschid to &thorn;e erthe,<MILESTONE N="23a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He strikis all fra &thorn;ar stedis &middot; stre&yogh;t him be-forne.</L>
<L>Was nane sa stiffe in &thorn;at stoure &middot; mi&yogh;t stand him agayn;</L>
<L>Quare althire-thickest was &thorn;e thrange &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;aim he rynnes,</L>
<L N="1324">And makis a wai wyde eno&yogh;e &middot; waynes to mete.</L>
<L>He laschis out a lange swerde &middot; quen his launce failes,</L>
<L>Threschis doun in a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> thrawe &middot; many threuyn dukis,</L>
<L>Stirs him sa in a stonde &middot; &amp; his stithe erlis</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;at &thorn;ar was [na] berne on bent &middot; bott bretened or &yogh;olden.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seggis on his awen side &middot; &thorn;at he slayn fyndis,</L>
<L>He mas to graue sum in grete &middot; &amp; sum in gray marble.</L>
<L>And &thorn;a &thorn;at laft ware o-lyue &middot; he lokis &thorn;ar woundis,</L>
<L N="1332">And faire fangis his folke &middot; &amp; fra &thorn;e fild wendis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bowes he to &thorn;e baistall &middot; &amp; brymly it semblis,</L>
<L>Gedirs of ilk glode &middot; grettir &amp; smallire,</L>
<L>And prekis furth with his pray &middot; &amp; passes fraward Gadirs,</L>
<L N="1336">And ti&yogh;t agayne toward Tyre &middot; to termen his sege.</L>
<L>Quen he was dreuyn ouer &thorn;e dales &middot; &amp; drewe to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he blisches to &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; sees his bild voidid,</L>
<L>Als bare as a bast &middot; his baistell a-way,</L>
<L N="1340">But outhire burde or bate &middot; bot &thorn;e brade wattir,
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>&THORN;an mournes all &thorn;e Messadones &middot; &amp; maynly was sturb[i]d.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> i <I>is illegible</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Alexander also &middot; was augrely greuyd,</L>
<L>So ware &thorn;ai troubild out of tone &middot; quen &thorn;ai &thorn;aire tild miste,</L>
<L N="1344">&THORN;at of &thorn;e taking of Tire &middot; trest &thorn;ai na langire.</L>
<L>And so him-selfe in his slepe &middot; &thorn;e same ni&yogh;t eftir,</L>
<L>Him tho&yogh;t he had in his hand &middot; &amp; held of a vyne</L>
<L N="1347">A growen grape of a grype &middot; a grete &amp; a rype,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quilke he flange<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> of, <I>but it is struck out</I>.</NOTE> on &thorn;e flore &middot; &amp; with his fete tredis.</L>
<L>And quen he broken had &thorn;e bery &middot; als &thorn;e berne semes,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar folowis out of fresche wyne &middot; feetles to mete;<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So largely &amp; so delauyly &middot; of licoure, him thinkis,</L>
<L N="1352">Of ane rasyn to ryn &middot; it was a ryfe wondire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng callis him a clerke &middot; kenely on &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> morne,</L>
<L>Als radly as he rase &middot; to reche him his sweuyn.</L>
<L>"Sire, bees a-dred neuir a dele" &middot; &thorn;e diuinour said,</L>
<L N="1356">"I vndire-take on my trouthe &middot; Tire is &thorn;ine awen;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e bery at &yogh;e brake sa &middot; is &thorn;e bur&yogh;e euen.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sall be sesid &thorn;e full sone &middot; &amp; to &thorn;i-selfe &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou sall eft all on ernest &middot; entire on &thorn;e wallis,</L>
<L N="1360">And foulire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> foule hire.</NOTE> vndir &thorn;i feete &middot; with-in a fewe days.</L>
<L>Now compas kenely &thorn;is kyng &middot; &amp; castis in his mynd</L>
<L>How he mi&yogh;t couir in any cas &middot; to come to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Deuynes depely on dais &middot; dropis many wiles,</L>
<L N="1364">If he cuthe seke any sle&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;at him serue wald;</L>
<L>And makis to sett in &thorn;e see<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> of, <I>but it is struck out</I>.</NOTE> &middot; ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e same place,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar as &thorn;e bild at he bi[l]did &middot; biggid wasse first,</L>
<L>To stable vp a grete strenthe &middot; all on store schipis,</L>
<L N="1368">Hugir be &thorn;e halfe dele &middot; &amp; hi&yogh;ere &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;ire;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he fiches &amp; firmes &middot; sa fast to &thorn;e wall,</L>
<L>So nere, vnethes at ane eld &middot; mi&yogh;t narowly betwene,</L>
<L N="1371">And band hire, as &thorn;e buke sais &middot; bigly to-gedire,
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at scho flisch no&thorn;er fayle<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. flay fayle; <I>but</I> flay <I>is struck out.</I></NOTE> &middot; fyue score aunkirs.</L>
<L>Quen he had ti&yogh;t vp &thorn;is tram &middot; &amp; &thorn;is tild rerid,</L>
<L>Hit had of bradnes abofe &middot; to breue out of mesure;</L>
<L>And to hede be a huge thing &middot; hi&yogh;ere it semed</L>
<L N="1376">&THORN;an was &thorn;e wallis, sais &thorn;e writt &middot; of &thorn;e wale touris.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander all his ane &middot; an-ane he ascendis,</L>
<L>Closid all in clere stele &middot; &amp; in clene plates,</L>
<L>And monestis ilk modire son &middot; maynly &amp; swyth,<MILESTONE N="24a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1380">&THORN;at all be bowne at a brayd &middot; &thorn;e bur&yogh;e to assaile.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e ost euyn ouir &middot; he openly comandis</L>
<L>To be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> radly all arayd &middot; &amp; redy to fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;ai sa&yogh;e &thorn;at him-selfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">selfe <I>added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e cite was entrid,</L>
<L N="1384">Wan vp wi&yogh;tly on &thorn;e wallis &middot; ilk wee him eftir.</L>
<L>Now tenelis vp taburs &middot; and all &thorn;e to&umacr;n rengis,</L>
<L>Steryn steuyn vp strake &middot; strakid &thorn;ar trumpis,</L>
<L>Blewe bemys of bras &middot; bernes assemblis,</L>
<L N="1388">Se&yogh;es to on ilk syde &middot; &amp; a saute &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are presis to with paues &middot; peple withouten;</L>
<L>Archars with arows &middot; of atter envemonde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Schotis vp scharply &middot; at shalkis on &thorn;e wallis,</L>
<L N="1392">Lasch at &thorn;am of loft &middot; many lede flo&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &yogh;apely a-&yogh;ayne &middot; &amp; &yogh;ildis &thorn;am swythe,</L>
<L>Bekire out of &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; bald men many,</L>
<L>Kenely &thorn;ai kast of &middot; with kastis of stanys,</L>
<L N="1396">Driues dartis at oure dukis &middot; dedly &thorn;am woundid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an passe vp oure princes &middot; prestly<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> er, <I>but it is struck out.</I></NOTE> enarmed,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e baistell a-bofe &middot; bremely ascendid,</L>
<L>Sum with lances on-loft &middot; &amp; with lange swerdis,</L>
<L N="1400">With ax &amp; with alblaster &middot; &amp; alkens wapen.</L>
<L>Alexander ai elike &middot; augrily fe&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Now a schaft, now a schild &middot; nowe a scheue hentis,</L>
<L>Now a sparth, now a spere &middot; &amp; sped so his mi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="1404">&THORN;at it ware tere any tonge &middot; to of his turnes rekyn.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai with-in on &thorn;e wall &middot; worthili with-stude,</L>
<L>Fersly defend of &middot; &amp; fellid of his kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="1407">Thristis ouir thikefald &middot; many threuyn berne[s],</L>
<L>And doun bakward &thorn;am bare &middot; in-to &thorn;e brad wattir.<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at oure wees without &middot; writhis &thorn;am vnfare,</L>
<L>Went wode of &thorn;aire witt &middot; &amp; wrekis &thorn;am swyth;</L>
<L>For na wounde ne na wathe &middot; wand &thorn;ai na langir,</L>
<L N="1412">Bot all wirkis him &thorn;e wa &middot; &amp; wrake at he cuthe.</L>
<L>Sum braidis to &thorn;ar bowis &middot; bremely &thorn;ai schut,</L>
<L>Quethirs out quarels &middot; quikly be-twene;</L>
<L>Strykis vp of &thorn;e stoure &middot; stanes of engynes,</L>
<L N="1416">&THORN;at &thorn;e bretage a-boue &middot; brast all in soundire,</L>
<L>Girdis ouir garettis &middot; with gomes to &thorn;e erthe,</L>
<L>Tilt torettis doun &middot; toures on hepis,</L>
<L>Spedely with sprygaldis &middot; spilt &thorn;aire braynes,</L>
<L N="1420">Many mi&yogh;tfull man &middot; marris on &thorn;e wallis.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e kirnells ware kast &middot; &amp; kutt doun before,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at &thorn;e baistell &amp; &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; ware bathe elike hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And all oure werke without &thorn;e wallis &middot; weterly semed,</L>
<L N="1424">&THORN;e sidis of &thorn;e cite &middot; to se to o fernes,</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander belyf<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bely, <I>altered to</I> belyf <I>in later hand.</I></NOTE> &middot; on &thorn;am all entris,</L>
<L>Bruschis in with a brand &middot; on bernes a hundreth,</L>
<L>Thrang thur&yogh;e a thousand &middot; &thorn;are thikest &thorn;ai were,</L>
<L N="1428">Wynnes worthly ouer &thorn;e wallis &middot; with-in to &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first modire son he mett &middot; o&thorn;ire man outhire,</L>
<L>Was Balaan &thorn;e bald berne &middot; as &thorn;e boke tellis,</L>
<L N="1431">And him he settis on a saute &middot; &amp; slo&yogh;e him belyue,</L>
<L>And werpid him out ouir &thorn;e wall &middot; in-to &thorn;e wild streme.</L>
<L>Sone as oure athils be-hind &middot; sa&yogh;e &thorn;ar he entred,</L>
<L>His men &amp; all &thorn;e Messedones &middot; maynly ascendis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai of Grece gredely &middot; girdis vp eftire,</L>
<L N="1436">Thringis vp on a thraw &middot; thousandis many.</L>
<L>Sum stepis vp on sties &middot; to &thorn;e stane wallis,<MILESTONE N="25a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On ilka staffe of a staire<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> staire.</NOTE> &middot; stike wald a cluster;
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="78"></L>
<L N="1439">And qua sa leddirs had nane &middot; as &thorn;e lyne tellis,</L>
<L>Wald gett &thorn;am hald with &thorn;ar hend &middot; &amp; on-loft clyme.</L>
<L>Sa fre&yogh;t ware &thorn;ar othire &middot; &thorn;at fe&yogh;tis within,</L>
<L>For Balaan &thorn;ar bald duke &middot; &thorn;at bro&yogh;t was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> of lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all failis &thorn;am &thorn;e force &middot; &amp; so ferd worthe,</L>
<L N="1444">&THORN;at nothire with stafe ne with stane &middot; withstand &thorn;ai na langir.</L>
<L>Sire Alexander with his athils &middot; &amp; his awen sle&yogh;tis</L>
<L>&THORN;e toune of Tire &thorn;us he tuke &middot; &amp; othire twa bur&yogh;es,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e quilke &thorn;e siriens of &thorn;is sire &middot; so many soro&yogh;es had,</L>
<L>As wald bot tary all oure tale &middot; &thorn;aire tourment to reken.</L>
<L N="1449">Sone as &thorn;is cite was sesid &middot; &amp; slayne vp &amp; &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>&THORN;en ridis furth &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; &amp; remowed his ost,</L>
<L>Gais him furth to Gasa &middot; a-nothire grete cite,</L>
<L N="1452">And &thorn;at he settis on a saute &middot; &amp; sesis it be-lyue;</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;is Gasa was geten &middot; he graythis him swyth,</L>
<L>And Ioynes him toward Ierusalem &middot; &thorn;e iewis to distroy;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> kis; <I>but it is struck out.</I></NOTE> kepis of &thorn;is carpe &middot; to knaw any ferre,</L>
<L N="1456">Sone sall I neuen &yogh;ow &thorn;e note &middot; &thorn;at is next eftir.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000081.tif" N="59">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Now ayers he forth</B> with hys Ereles, &middot; to egip he wendes;</L>
<L>And clene all &thorn;e cuntree &middot; when &thorn;ai hys comyng harde,</L>
<L>Als he hed ben a hegh god &middot; &thorn;ai halden hym agayns,</L>
<L>Resaved hym with reuerence &middot; &amp; to &thorn;air realm ledyn.</L>
<L>Thare entrez hym &thorn;e Emperour &middot; and in &thorn;at erth fyndez</L>
<L>Of anec hys awne syre &middot; ane ymage of sabyll,</L>
<L N="1127">A berne was of blak stane &middot; all &thorn;e body euen</L>
<L>With conyshaunce of kyngez &middot; coron and septur in hand.</L>
<L>Than askys he &thorn;aim alexander &middot; als he &thorn;ar-on wates,</L>
<L>What maner of man vpon mold &middot; &thorn;at was merkyd after?</L>
<L>"Sir, anec," quod all men &middot; with a sterne steven,</L>
<L N="1132">"That &thorn;e erth of egipt &middot; enhered some tyme."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e femand flode &middot; flasshed in hys eghen,<MILESTONE N="9a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"That anec," quod &thorn;is athell kyng &middot; "my awne fadre was."</L>
<L>&THORN;an fallez he flatt on &thorn;e fold &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fote kyssez</L>
<L N="1136">Of &thorn;at stane &thorn;at stode &middot; &amp; stylly murnez.</L>
<L>Syne into surry with hys seggez &middot; he soght &thorn;e ganest,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai as baratours bald &middot; hym bigly withstandyn,</L>
<L>Set vppon hym sadly &middot; &amp; slew of hys knyghtez;</L>
<L N="1140">Bot &yogh;arle or he &yogh;ode &middot; &thorn;ai &yogh;olde hym vp &thorn;e realm.</L>
<L>Than draue he so to Damask &middot; with dokez &amp; princez,</L>
<L>And sone he sesys all &thorn;at syde &middot; and sy[do]ne he takez,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en he trussys hym to tyre &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar hys tentes settes</L>
<L N="1144">Besyde &thorn;e site with a somme &middot; &amp; in a sege lengez.</L>
<L>&THORN;air he lay with hys ledes &middot; lange or he fondytt,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e burgh with hys bernes &middot; &amp; muche bale suffred.
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>What of o &thorn;ing, whatt of o&thorn;ir &middot; ofte hys oste plenys,</L>
<L N="1148">For wele trowde &thorn;ai &thorn;an &middot; none to wynne to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>It was so stiffe &amp; so strang &middot; &amp; so stalworthly wroght,</L>
<L>And so hydusly hye &middot; &thorn;at was A grett wondre,</L>
<L>Tyldet full of torrettes &middot; &amp; towrez of defencez,</L>
<L N="1152">Bateld &amp; britagett &middot; abowt as a castell.</L>
<L>The wawes of &thorn;e wilde see &middot; vpon &thorn;e walle betyn,</L>
<L>The pure populand perle &middot; passyd it vmbe,</L>
<L N="1155">It was enforsed so wele &middot; with flodez &amp; other,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar semed neuer sege vnder &thorn;e son &middot; by sawte it to wynne.</L>
<L>Than etellez hym sir alexander &middot; &amp; als belyue makes</L>
<L>Besyde &thorn;e cite in &thorn;e see &middot; to sett vp a loge,</L>
<L>A hye tylde as a towre &middot; tyldet of shippes,</L>
<L N="1160">&THORN;at might no navy for &thorn;at note &middot; negh to &thorn;e haven.</L>
<L>When he &thorn;is bastell had byggyd &middot; nere &thorn;e burgh walles,</L>
<L>And tight hym as tyme was &middot; &thorn;e burgh to assaylle,</L>
<L>Such mischefe in &thorn;e meynne tyme &middot; vppon &thorn;e men fallez,</L>
<L N="1164">For meger &amp; for metelesse &middot; wer mervell to telle.</L>
<L>Thare wer princez in plite &middot; to perische for euer,</L>
<L>All in dowte to [be] dede &middot; dukez &amp; Ereles,</L>
<L>In fere to be famyshyd &middot; mony ferce knyghtez,</L>
<L N="1168">For &thorn;ar is [na] wa in werld &middot; to &thorn;e wod hunger.</L>
<L>Than rewys hym &thorn;e prouude kyng &middot; &thorn;e pyte of hys men,</L>
<L>And sendys forth sendesmen &middot; with selett lettres,<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To Ierusalem to Iawdez &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes teches,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1172">&THORN;at of &thorn;at burgh was byshop &middot; brevyd in &thorn;o dayes;</L>
<L>He monyshytt hym as a minister &middot; hym manly to sende</L>
<L>Fresh folk for &thorn;e fight &middot; &amp; fode for &thorn;e folke,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;air truage &middot; tyte to hym wayfe,</L>
<L N="1176">That he to Darius of dew &middot; was dangert to pay.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it command he &thorn;is clerke &middot; &thorn;e kyng in hys writtez,</L>
<L>For any richez he redes &middot; rather to chese</L>
<L>The mayntenaunce of massidons &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e mony grekez,
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="63"></L>
<L N="1180">&THORN;en &thorn;aim of perse to pay &middot; or to please owder.</L>
<L>Than takez &thorn;e Bishop &thorn;e breue &middot; &amp; to chawmbre bownes,</L>
<L>Ressaves it with reuerence &middot; &amp; redes it ouer,</L>
<L>Gase hym downe be degrece &middot; ayayn to &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L N="1184">Swythly to &thorn;e swyers &middot; &amp; &thorn;aim &thorn;e sware &yogh;eldez:</L>
<L>"Sirres, ayres agayn to alexander &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us hym tellys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>That me was done mony day &middot; deply to swere,</L>
<L>Neuer perse to pare &middot; ne passe with none armez</L>
<L N="1188">In damagyng of darius &middot; endurand hys lyue."</L>
<L>When &thorn;e wale kyng wist &middot; he wex wode wroth,</L>
<L>"Now by god," quod &thorn;e grome &middot; "&thorn;at gatt me on erth,</L>
<L>I sall seche Iewres on &thorn;e Iewes &middot; enys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>read</I> enioine.</NOTE> or I dye,</L>
<L N="1192">Sall kenne whoys commaundement &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;aim to kepe fallez.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it for no torfer &thorn;at he tyde &middot; tyre wald he noght leue,</L>
<L>Bot chesez hym owt a chiftane &middot; &amp; chargez hym belyue,</L>
<L>A mody man, sir meliager, &middot; a maister of hys oste,</L>
<L>To founde forth with a flete &middot; of fyfe hundreth knyghtez;</L>
<L N="1197">And iniones hym to Iosaphatt &middot; hys Iornay to make,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e pastours &amp; &thorn;e playnes &middot; prestly to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. de.</NOTE> dryve,</L>
<L>Bot bring in all &thorn;es bestes &middot; baren &amp; other,</L>
<L N="1200">&THORN;at he might see in ony syde &middot; &thorn;e cite of Gaders.</L>
<L>Than mefes on sire Meliager &middot; &thorn;is mightfull prince</L>
<L>Wyth a soume of syker men &middot; &amp; sampson &thorn;aim ledes,</L>
<L>A renke &thorn;at in &thorn;a regions &middot; had rydyn oft sythez,</L>
<L N="1204">And knew &thorn;e costez &amp; &thorn;e kythez &middot; clene all-to-geder.</L>
<L>&THORN;us hyed &thorn;ai forth egerly &middot; &amp; entird &thorn;e wale,</L>
<L>And suche a pray &thorn;aim preved &middot; als pyne wer to reken,</L>
<L>Bringez forth, als says &thorn;e buk &middot; bestes owt of nowmbre,<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1208">And trottes on toward tyre &middot; with ioy at &thorn;air hertes.</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;ai metyn hed a myle &middot; &thorn;e mers with-out,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. were out.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>&thorn;ar metes &thorn;aime a miche folke &middot; &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e playnes,</L>
<L>The duke of &thorn;e drafes &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e derfe fellys,</L>
<L N="1212">One teosellus a tulke &middot; &thorn;at tenyd &thorn;aim vnfaire.</L>
<L>He girdes in with a gyn &middot; grathed in playthes,</L>
<L>All to-brountes &thorn;es bernes &middot; &amp; wykydly &thorn;aim woundes,</L>
<L>Felles mony fey at a frush &middot; fast to &thorn;e grunde,</L>
<L N="1216">And mony renke &thorn;at he ouer-rade &middot; rase neuer aftir.</L>
<L>Than was sir meliager amoved &middot; &amp; manly debates,</L>
<L>Flyngez forth on a fole &middot; with a fele spere,</L>
<L N="1219">And beres mony grett syre &middot; &thorn;orow thike males,</L>
<L>All fell bernes at [a] brayde &middot; whilse his breth lastez.</L>
<L>And sampson on ane other syde &middot; settez on belyue,</L>
<L>Brushes forth on a blonke &middot; brathly he smytez,</L>
<L>Betes on with a brande &middot; for brokyn was hys launce,</L>
<L N="1224">Hewes doun on &thorn;e herdez &middot; &amp; hurtez &thorn;aim vnfaire.</L>
<L>Then arestes, an athell man &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Better omitted.</I></NOTE> ay clike feghtez,</L>
<L>Sparres forth with a spere &middot; &amp; spedes hys mightez,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1228">Mony bald or he blan &middot; broght owt of lyfe.</L>
<L>Than Caulus, an other knyght &middot; on a ked stede,</L>
<L>On thoosellus in twa &middot; hys tembre he brekys;</L>
<L>And &thorn;en he dryffes to &thorn;e duke &middot; als tellys me &thorn;e texte,</L>
<L>Bot with a swyng of a swerde &middot; swappez of hys heued.</L>
<L>When he was drepyd &thorn;us &amp; dede &middot; &amp; &thorn;e drawes &yogh;emyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prekers of &thorn;e pasturs &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e prouud Landez,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e folk of hys affinite &middot; &thorn;at frehsse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic.</I></NOTE> wer vnwoundet,</L>
<L N="1236">&THORN;at other fote hed or fole &middot; to &thorn;e fly&yogh;t foundez.</L>
<L>Thus meliager with hys men &middot; &thorn;e menske &thorn;ar acheuett,</L>
<L>Fellyd &thorn;e feirare<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. feirhare.</NOTE> of &thorn;ar foes &middot; and &thorn;e feld wonnez<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> wonn.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And rachen with &thorn;air route &middot; &amp; ryden bott a while,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ar neghyd &thorn;aim ane o&thorn;er note &middot; als new as before;</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was a maister of &thorn;e marche &middot; &thorn;e myghtiest of other.</L>
<L N="1242">One beritinus, a berne &middot; als &thorn;e buke telles,</L>
<L>Come girdand furth of gaders &middot; owt of &thorn;e grete cyte,
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="67"></L>
<L N="1244">With &thorn;e selcouutest soume &middot; &thorn;at semblyd was euer,</L>
<L>With a mynd to me &middot; wer mervell to rekyn,<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A threti thouusand in thede &middot; of thro men of armes,</L>
<L>Suche as wer on blonnkes &middot; in brenys &amp; platez,</L>
<L N="1248">And other folowand on fote &middot; fele owt of nowmbre.</L>
<L>The multitude was so much &middot; as menys vs &thorn;e writtez,</L>
<L>Of wyes &amp; of wild horse &middot; &amp; of wapenned bernes,</L>
<L>So styf a steuen in &thorn;e stoure &middot; of stedes &amp; enmys,</L>
<L N="1252">As it was semand [to si&yogh;t] &middot; as &thorn;e son tremblyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;en wer &thorn;e masydons ameved &middot; when &thorn;ai so mony seen;</L>
<L>Sir meliager was in grete mynd &middot; a man owt to send</L>
<L N="1255">To alexander als belyue &middot; &thorn;aire aller maister,</L>
<L>To Come to help with hys heir &middot; or &thorn;ai to hand rydyn.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ar was nane &thorn;at was made &middot; &thorn;e message to fannge,</L>
<L>Bot ilke lede elike loth &middot; to leven &thorn;air frendes,</L>
<L>And festned &thorn;air forwardez in-fere &middot; &thorn;e few &thorn;at &thorn;ar wer,</L>
<L N="1260">To do as drighten wald deme &middot; &amp; dye all to-geder;</L>
<L>To tell &thorn;air torfer in tere &middot; it wald tary me to lang.</L>
<L>Bot so &thorn;e mody meliager &middot; &amp; hys men foghten,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Sir bertinus &thorn;e bald &middot; &thorn;ai brityned to dede,</L>
<L N="1264">And sampson was of hys syde &middot; slayn &thorn;ar-agayns.</L>
<L>&THORN;en murned all &thorn;e masydons &middot; &amp; meynyd hym swyth,</L>
<L>Made grett mone for &thorn;is man &middot; &amp; mony o&thorn;er noble,</L>
<L N="1267">For maisters &amp; ministers &middot; meyner &amp; gretter,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wer in morsellys made &middot; &amp; martyred by hundrethis.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at left wer on-lyue &middot; bot a lytell meynhe,</L>
<L>Wer also maistrett &amp; masyd &middot; &amp; mated of &thorn;air strennthes,</L>
<L>So wake &amp; so wyndles &middot; &amp; wery for-fouughten,</L>
<L N="1272">&THORN;at &thorn;ai wer wille in &thorn;e werld &middot; qwat &thorn;ai worth suld.</L>
<L>Sir meliager &amp; o&thorn;er mo &middot; mayned wer sare,</L>
<L>All to-bled &amp; to-brysed &middot; &thorn;at nere &thorn;air breth fayled,</L>
<L>Thai wer so feble and so faynte &middot; and full of &thorn;aim-seluen,</L>
<L N="1276">&THORN;at all in fere &amp; in forme &middot; &thorn;e feld for to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>Than ayres hym forth aristes &middot; was augerdly woundett,</L>
<L>To alexander anone &middot; &thorn;ees aunters hym telles,
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>The morte of all &thorn;e masydons &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e mony grekez,</L>
<L N="1280">Rekens hym &thorn;e resons &middot; &thorn;at reuth was to here.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e comle kynge &middot; chakez hys bernes,</L>
<L><B>Semblett Hym A Hoge soume &middot; &amp; fro &thorn;e seige wendys,</B><MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The toure of tyre &amp; &thorn;e towne &middot; titely he levys,</L>
<L N="1284">And ioynes hym to Iosaphatt &middot; full ioyles to ryde.</L>
<L>Ay he gretes as he goys &middot; &thorn;e grefe of hys knyghtez,</L>
<L>Ay he plenys as he passez &middot; &thorn;e pite of hys Ereles,</L>
<L>Ay he wepys as he wendes &middot; for hys wale princes,</L>
<L N="1288">And souerandly for sampson &middot; he sorows euerilyke.</L>
<L>When he was turnyd froward tyre &middot; toward &thorn;e wale,</L>
<L>The werk at he wroght had &middot; &thorn;e water within,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hed sett in &thorn;e see &middot; &thorn;e cite withowte,</L>
<L N="1292">Thare-in he left hed a lityll<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> lede.</NOTE> &middot; [&thorn;e] loge for to kepe.</L>
<L>Bott &thorn;en sir balaan, a berne &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e burgh lenged,</L>
<L>One of &thorn;e tiraundez of tire &middot; atired hym belyue,</L>
<L>Buskes hym in brenes &middot; with big men of armes,</L>
<L N="1296">With trawynns &amp; trebgetes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. trelgetes.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e towre to assaylle.</L>
<L>He bekers owt at &thorn;e beld &middot; ouer &thorn;e brade walle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai within<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. withowt within.</NOTE> &thorn;e werk &middot; wightly defenden,</L>
<L>Shoton sharply bytwene &middot; swappyn owt dartez;</L>
<L N="1300">Weres wondrely wele &middot; warpyn owt stanes.</L>
<L>Bot balaan in &thorn;e britage &middot; so bitterly feghtez,</L>
<L>All to-combers &thorn;aim clene &middot; with cast of engynes.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e toppe of &thorn;e toure &middot; he typys in &thorn;e water,</L>
<L N="1304">And all &thorn;e tulkez in &thorn;e teld &middot; he termys &thorn;e lyve;</L>
<L>Than in bargez &amp; in botez &middot; he bownes hym swyth,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bothom of &thorn;e bastell &middot; he buskez hym withowte,</L>
<L>Bretens downe all &thorn;e belde &middot; &amp; &thorn;e bernes whelles,</L>
<L N="1308">Drenches hir in &thorn;e depe &middot; &amp; drawes hir on hepys.</L>
<L>When it was smytyn so in small &middot; within &thorn;e smert wawes,</L>
<L>Ilke gobett fro o&thorn;er &middot; glydes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gydes, <I>corr. to</I> glydes.</NOTE> fast &thorn;air way.</L>
<L>Thus &thorn;is strenth ilke steke &middot; in a stound wastyd,
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="71"></L>
<L N="1312">And balaan bownes to &thorn;e burgh &middot; &amp; barres &thorn;e &yogh;atez.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at owr kyng with hys knyghtez &middot; was comen to &thorn;e wale,</L>
<L>Alex[ander] with an hoste &middot; hys athell to help,</L>
<L>Fyndes a few of hys folke &middot; feghtyng full &yogh;arne,</L>
<L N="1316">And a sege by hym-self &middot; sett to a hundreth.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at bucifelon hys blonke &middot; he brochys in &thorn;e sydez,</L>
<L>Spryngez forth with a spere &middot; spyllez at &thorn;e ganest,</L>
<L>Rides euen &thorn;orow &thorn;e route &middot; &thorn;are rankest &thorn;ai were,<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1320">The rawes of &thorn;air arayes &middot; he rushes to &thorn;e erth,</L>
<L>He strikez all &thorn;air stedes &middot; streght downe hym before,</L>
<L>Was none so styffe in &thorn;e stoure &middot; to stand hym ayayns;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar all &thorn;e thikest wer of thrange &middot; thrugh &thorn;aim he rynnes,</L>
<L N="1324">And makez a way wyde enogh &middot; waynez for to mete.</L>
<L>He lashes owt a lang swerde &middot; when hys launce wantes,</L>
<L>Thristez downe in a thraw &middot; mony thryme dokes,</L>
<L>Stirrez hym so in a stound &middot; he and hys styff ereles,</L>
<L N="1328">&THORN;at &thorn;ar ne was bern on &thorn;e bent &middot; bot bryttynett or &yogh;olden.</L>
<L>The segges of hys awne syde &middot; all at he slayn fyndez,</L>
<L>He makes to grave, some in grete &middot; some in gray marbyll.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at left wer on lyue &middot; he leches &thorn;air woundez,</L>
<L N="1332">And fair fangez he hys folke &middot; &amp; fro &thorn;e feld turnes.<NOTE PLACE="marg">3<SUP>a</SUP> victoria alexandri.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Then prekes forth with hys pray &middot; &thorn;us before gaders,</L>
<L N="1336">And turnes agayn toward tyre &middot; to terme hys seige.</L>
<L>When he was dreven ouer &thorn;e dales &middot; &amp; drew to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he blyshys to &thorn;e burgh &middot; &amp; seys hys beylde woydett,</L>
<L>Also bare as ony baste &middot; hys bastell away,</L>
<L N="1340">Bout ony buske or borde &middot; bot &thorn;e brode water.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>Than murnes all &thorn;e masidons &middot; &amp; felly wer trublett,</L>
<L>And alexander was also &middot; awgerdly grevyde,</L>
<L>So wer &thorn;ai turblett of &thorn;e towne &middot; qwen &thorn;ai &thorn;ar tild myssyd,</L>
<L N="1344">That of &thorn;e takyng of tire &middot; tristed &thorn;ai no lenger.</L>
<L>And so hym-selfe in hys slepe &middot; &thorn;e same nyght after,</L>
<L>Hym toght<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic in</I> MS.</NOTE> he had in hys hand &middot; a held of a wyne,</L>
<L N="1347">A growen grope of a gripe &middot; a grett &amp; a rype,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilke he flonge of &thorn;e floure &middot; &amp; with hys fete tredes;</L>
<L>And when he brokyn hed &thorn;e bery &middot; als &thorn;e bern semys,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar flowe owt of fresh wynne &middot; flodez enowe;</L>
<L>So largly &amp; so delavy &middot; of liquor hym thynkez,</L>
<L N="1352">Of ane raysyn to ryn &middot; &thorn;at was a gret wondre.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynge callez a clerke &middot; kenely on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>Als radly as euer he rose &middot; to rachen hym hys swevyn.</L>
<L>"Sir, beys dred neuer a dele" &middot; &thorn;e devinour hym sayde,</L>
<L N="1356">"I vndertake it on my trewth &middot; tyre is &thorn;i nawne;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e bery &thorn;at &thorn;ou brake &middot; &thorn;at is &thorn;e burgh euen,</L>
<L>That shal be sesyd &thorn;e ful sone &middot; &amp; to &thorn;i-seluen &yogh;olden,<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou sall eft in ernest &middot; enter &thorn;e walles,</L>
<L N="1360">And fell hir vnder fote &middot; within a few days."</L>
<L>Now Compas kenely &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; castes in hys mynd</L>
<L>How he couth in ony case &middot; come to &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L>Devynez deply on days &middot; dropes mony willes,</L>
<L N="1364">If he couht seke ony sleght &middot; &thorn;at hym serue wald;</L>
<L>And makes to sett in &thorn;e see &middot; right in &thorn;e same place,</L>
<L>&THORN;air as &thorn;e tild &thorn;at he bild &middot; bigget was frist,</L>
<L>To stabill vp a strenth &middot; all of store schippes,</L>
<L N="1368">Hoger by &thorn;e halfe dele &middot; &amp; hyer &thorn;en &thorn;at o&thorn;er;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he feghys &amp; fermes &middot; so fast to &thorn;e wall,</L>
<L>So negh &thorn;at vnneth a nedyll &middot; myght narowly bytwene,</L>
<L>And band hir, as &thorn;e boke says &middot; bigly to-geder,
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="75"></L>
<L N="1372">Lest sho flechett or faylett &middot; with fyfe score ankers.</L>
<L>When he hed tight vp &thorn;is trame &middot; &amp; &thorn;is teld reryd,</L>
<L>It hed of bradnes aboue &middot; to breue owt of mesour;</L>
<L>And to hede by hoge &thorn;ing &middot; hegher it semyd</L>
<L>Than was [&thorn;e walles], as &thorn;e writte says &middot; of &thorn;e wale tourez.</L>
<L N="1377">&THORN;an alexander all [his ane] &middot; a-none he ascendez,</L>
<L>Closed all in clere stele &middot; &amp; in clene platez,</L>
<L>And monyshit iche moderson &middot; manly &amp; swythe,</L>
<L N="1380">&THORN;at all be bowne at a brade &middot; &thorn;e burght to asayle.</L>
<L>All &thorn;e hoste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Better</I> oste.</NOTE> euen ouer &middot; opynly he comandes</L>
<L>&YOGH;arly all to be arraed &middot; and redy to fight;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at &thorn;ai see &thorn;at hym-selfe &middot; &thorn;e cite was entird,</L>
<L N="1384">Wynnen vpp vppo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e walle &middot; ilke wy hym after.</L>
<L>Now tynkyll vp taburnes &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e towne ringes,</L>
<L>Sterne stevyn vpon stroke &middot; straked trompettes,</L>
<L>Blew bemes of brace &middot; bernes assembled,</L>
<L N="1388">Sought to on ilk syde &middot; &amp; a saute &yogh;eldyn,</L>
<L>To prese to with paves &middot; a peple withowte;</L>
<L>Archers with arowes &middot; of atter enuenmonyd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> enuenomyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Shoton vp sharply &middot; at salkez on &thorn;e wallez,</L>
<L N="1392">Lashe at &thorn;aim on-lofte &middot; in mony lowd showte,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &yogh;opely ayayn &middot; &yogh;eldyn &thorn;aim swythe,</L>
<L>Bekeryng forth of &thorn;e burgh &middot; bald men many,<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Kenely &thorn;ai kepe &middot; with castyng of stanes,</L>
<L N="1396">Dryves dartez at owr dukez &middot; deply &thorn;aim wounden.</L>
<L>Than passyd vp of princez &middot; pristly enarmed,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e bastell abowne &middot; bremely ascenden,</L>
<L>Some with launcez on-lofte &middot; &amp; some with long swerdez,</L>
<L N="1400">With ax &amp; with awblester &middot; &amp; alken wapens.</L>
<L>And alexander ay elik &middot; awgerdly feghtez,</L>
<L>Now a shafte, now a shelde, &middot; now a swerde hentez,</L>
<L>Now a sparth, now a spere &middot; &amp; sped so hys mightez,</L>
<L N="1404">&THORN;at it wald tere ony tong &middot; hys tournays to reken.
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai within on &thorn;e wall &middot; wightly withstondyn,</L>
<L>Derfley defenden of &middot; &amp; fellez of hys bernes,</L>
<L>Thraste ouer thikefald &middot; mony thrifen knyghtez,</L>
<L N="1408">And doun bakeward &thorn;ai bare &middot; into &thorn;e brade water.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at oure wyes withowte &middot; wrathen &thorn;aim vnfaire,</L>
<L>Went ne wode owt of &thorn;ar witte &middot; &amp; wrekes &thorn;aim swyth;</L>
<L>For no wa ne no wound &middot; waned &thorn;ai no langer,</L>
<L N="1412">Bot all wirkyd &thorn;aim wa &middot; &amp; wrake at &thorn;ai couth.</L>
<L>Som braden to &thorn;air bowes &middot; &amp; bremely shotyn,</L>
<L>Whirres owt quarels &middot; whikly betwene;</L>
<L>Strike vp of &thorn;e stoure &middot; stanes &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; <I>written above the line; read</I> of.</NOTE> engynes,</L>
<L N="1416">&THORN;at &thorn;e britage abofe &middot; brast all in sonder,</L>
<L>Girdes ouer garrates &middot; with gomes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cunes; <I>wrongly</I>.</NOTE> to &thorn;e erth,</L>
<L>Typed torrettes doune &middot; towres on hepes,</L>
<L>Spedely with springaltez &middot; spilten &thorn;air bernes,</L>
<L N="1420">Many mightyfull man &middot; merred on &thorn;e walles.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e kernels wer kest &middot; &amp; cut<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. owt.</NOTE> doun before,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at &thorn;e bastell &amp; &thorn;e burgh &middot; was bath elike hye,</L>
<L>And all owre &thorn;e werke withowt &middot; witterly semyd,</L>
<L N="1424">The sydes of &thorn;e cite &middot; to se to on fernesse,</L>
<L>Than alexander als belyue &middot; on &thorn;aim all entres,</L>
<L>Brushes in with a brannde &middot; on bernes an hundreth,</L>
<L>Thrang &thorn;orow a thousand &middot; &thorn;ar as &thorn;ai thikest wer,</L>
<L N="1428">Wynnes wightly ouer &thorn;e wall &middot; within to &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>The frist moderson &thorn;at he mett &middot; or other man other,<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Was balaan &thorn;e bald berne &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellez,</L>
<L>And hym he settes on a sawte &middot; &amp; slogh hym belyfe,</L>
<L>And wappyd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> warpyd.</NOTE> hym ouer &thorn;e walles &middot; in-to &thorn;e wild stremes.</L>
<L N="1433">When &thorn;air hatels byhynde &middot; saw &thorn;ar heued entre,</L>
<L>Hys men &amp; all &thorn;e masydons &middot; manly ascenden,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai of grece gredely &middot; girdes vp after,</L>
<L N="1436">Thronge vp on a thraw &middot; thousandez mony.</L>
<L>Some spettyn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> steppyn.</NOTE> vp on styes &middot; to &thorn;e stane walles,</L>
<L>On ilke staffe on a stare &middot; steke wald a clostre;
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>And who so ledderys couth lache &middot; as &thorn;e line wittnes,</L>
<L>Wald gett &thorn;air hald with &thorn;air hand &middot; &amp; on-lofte wynne.</L>
<L N="1441">So fri&yogh;t wer &thorn;ase other folke &middot; &thorn;at foghten within,</L>
<L>Fro<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> For.</NOTE> balaan &thorn;air bald duke &middot; &thorn;at broght was of liue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all failez &thorn;aim &thorn;e force &middot; &amp; so ferd worthen,</L>
<L N="1444">&THORN;at nowder with staffe ne with stane &middot; withstode &thorn;ai no langer.</L>
<L>Sir alexander with &thorn;oes athellys &middot; &amp; with hys awne sleghtez</L>
<L>The toure of tire &thorn;us he tuke &middot; and other ij burghez,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whilke &thorn;e sariens of &thorn;is syre &middot; so many sorowys haddyn;</L>
<L N="1448">All wald bot tary owr tale &middot; &thorn;aire turment to reken.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Obsid[et] le tyre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone als &thorn;is cite was sesyd &middot; slayne vp &amp; &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>&THORN;an rides forth &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; &amp; removes &thorn;e hoste,</L>
<L>Gase forth to gaza &middot; ane othre grete cite,</L>
<L N="1452">And he settes on a sawte &middot; and seses it beliue;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;is gaza was gettyn &middot; he grathes hym swyth,</L>
<L>And ioynes hym toward Ierusalem &middot; &thorn;e Iewez to distroy;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;at kepys of &thorn;is carpyng &middot; to here any ferrer,</L>
<L>Sone sall I neuen &thorn;ou &thorn;e note &middot; &thorn;at now is next after.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000100.tif" N="78">
<HEAD><B>Septimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Als hastily as &thorn;ai herd of &middot; in &thorn;e haly cite,</L>
<L>And bodword to &thorn;e bischop &middot; bro&yogh;t of his come,</L>
<L N="1459">For Alexander a&yogh;e &middot; almast he euen deis,</L>
<L>For he had nite him a nerand &middot; no&yogh;t bot o new time.</L>
<L>And now him &thorn;inke in his &thorn;o&yogh;t &middot; him thurt no&yogh;t haue carid</L>
<L>In all his mast mystir &middot; nad he &thorn;at man faylid,</L>
<L>When he for socure to &thorn;e cite &middot; sent him his lettir;<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1464">And he soyned him be his sorement &middot; &thorn;at sare him for|thinkis.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>"For me had leuer," quod &thorn;e lede &middot; "be lethirely for|sworn</L>
<L>On as many halidoms &middot; as opens<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. open; <I>altered to</I> opens <I>in later hand</I>.</NOTE> &amp; speris,</L>
<L N="1467">&THORN;an anys haue greuyd &thorn;at gome &middot; or warned him his erand!</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer I warned him his will &middot; wa is me &thorn;at stonde!"</L>
<L>&THORN;us was Iaudes of ioy &middot; &amp; iolite depryued;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e iewis of ierusalem &middot; he Ioyntly a-sembles.</L>
<L>He said, "Alexander is at hand &middot; &amp; will vs all cumbre,</L>
<L N="1472">And we ere dredles vndone &middot; bot dri&yogh;ten vs help."</L>
<L>&THORN;an bedis &thorn;e bischop all &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; barnes &amp; othire,</L>
<L>Athils of all age &middot; eldire &amp; &yogh;ongire,</L>
<L>Comandis to ilka creatour &middot; to crie &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e stretis,</L>
<L N="1476">To thre dais on a thrawe &middot; be threpild to-gedire,</L>
<L>Ilk a frek &amp; ilka fante &middot; to fast &amp; to pray,</L>
<L>To ocupy &thorn;ar oures &amp; orisons &middot; &amp; offire in &thorn;ar temple,</L>
<L>And call vp with a clene voice &middot; to &thorn;e kyng of heuyn,</L>
<L N="1480">To kepe &thorn;am, at &thorn;is conquiroure &middot; encumbrid &thorn;aim neuir.</L>
<L>Now se&yogh;en &thorn;ai to &thorn;ar Sinagogis &middot; all &thorn;e cite ouire,</L>
<L>Ilka bodi &thorn;ar bedis &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e bur&yogh;e lengis,</L>
<L>Putt &thorn;am to prayris &middot; &amp; penaunce enduris,</L>
<L N="1484">&THORN;e vengance of &thorn;is victoure &middot; to voide if &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&yogh;t eftir &thorn;e note &middot; as<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp;.</NOTE> tellis me &thorn;e writtis,</L>
<L>Quen all &thorn;e cite was on-slepe &middot; &amp; sacrifis endid,</L>
<L>In ane abite of &thorn;e aire &middot; ane Aungell aperis</L>
<L N="1488">To Iaudas of ierusalem &middot; &amp; him with ioy gretis:</L>
<L>"I bringe &thorn;e bodword of blis &middot; ser bischop," he said,</L>
<L>"With salutis of solas &middot; I am sent fra &thorn;e trone,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e maister of man &middot; &thorn;e mi&yogh;tfull fadere,</L>
<L N="1492">&THORN;at bedis &thorn;e no&yogh;t be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> a-baist &middot; he has &thorn;i bone herd;</L>
<L>And I amonest &thorn;e to-morne &middot; as I am enIoyned,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou as radly as &thorn;ou rise &middot; aray all &thorn;e cite,<MILESTONE N="26a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e stretis &amp; in all stedis &middot; stoutly &amp; faire,
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="82"></L>
<L N="1496">&THORN;at it be onest all ouire &middot; &amp; open vp &thorn;e &yogh;atis.</L>
<L>Lett &thorn;an &thorn;e pupill ilka poll &middot; apareld be clene,</L>
<L>And al manere of men &middot; in mylk-quyte clathis.</L>
<L>And pas, &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;i prelatis &middot; &amp; prestis of &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L N="1500">Raueste all on a raw &middot; as &yogh;oure rewill askis.</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;is conquirour comes &middot; caire him agaynes;</L>
<L>For he mon ride &thorn;us &amp; regne &middot; ouire all &thorn;e ronde werde</L>
<L>Be lordschip in ilka lede &middot; in-to his laste days,</L>
<L N="1504">And &thorn;en be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he.</NOTE> di&yogh;t to &thorn;e deth &middot; of dri&yogh;tins ire."</L>
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;e derke ouire-drafe &middot; &amp; &thorn;e day springis,</L>
<L>Oure bischop bounes him of bed &middot; &amp; buskis on his wedis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en iogis all &thorn;e iewis &middot; &amp; generall callis,</L>
<L N="1508">A-vaies &thorn;aim his vision &middot; how &thorn;e voice bedis;</L>
<L>&THORN;an consals him &thorn;e clergy &middot; clene all-to-gedire,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cite asentis &middot; sarazens &amp; o&thorn;ir,</L>
<L>To buwne furth with all &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; buske &thorn;am belyue,</L>
<L N="1512">As him was said in his slepe &middot; &thorn;is souerayn to mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;an rynnes he furth in a rase &middot; &amp; arais all &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Braidis ouire with bawdkyns &middot; all &thorn;e brade stretis,</L>
<L N="1515">With tars &amp; with tafeta &middot; &thorn;ar he trede sulde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e erth to slike ane Emperoure &middot; ware ouire feble.</L>
<L>He plyes ouire &thorn;e pauement &middot; with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added above the line.</I></NOTE> pallen webis,</L>
<L>Mas on hi&yogh;t ouire his hede &middot; for hete of &thorn;e sone,</L>
<L N="1519">Sylours of sendale &middot; to sele ouire &thorn;e gatis,</L>
<L>And sammes &thorn;aim on aithire side &middot; with silken rapis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en he caggis vp on cordis &middot; as curteyns it were,</L>
<L>Euen as &thorn;e esyngis &yogh;ede &middot; ouire be &thorn;e costes,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e wawis with-oute &middot; in webis of ynde,</L>
<L N="1524">Of bri&yogh;t blasand blewe &middot; browden with sternes.<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;us atired he &thorn;e toune &middot; &amp; titely &thorn;ar-eftir</L>
<L>On ilka way wid open &middot; werped he &thorn;e &yogh;atis;</L>
<L>And qua so lukis fra with-out &middot; &amp; with-in haldis,</L>
<L N="1528">It semyd as &thorn;e cite to se &middot; ane of &thorn;e seuyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. seuyns; <I>with final</I> s <I>expuncted.</I></NOTE> heuyns.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Now passis furth &thorn;is prelate &middot; with prestis of &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L>Reueschid him rially &middot; &amp; &thorn;at in riche wedis,</L>
<L>With erst &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> an.</NOTE> abite vndire all &middot; as I am in-fourmede,</L>
<L N="1532">Fulle of bridis &amp; of bestis &middot; of bise &amp; of purpre;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was garnest full gay &middot; with golden skirtis,</L>
<L>Store starand stanes &middot; strekilland all ouire,</L>
<L>Saudid full of safirs &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire sere gemmes,</L>
<L N="1536">And poudird with perry &middot; was perrour &amp; othire.</L>
<L>And sithen he castis on a Cape &middot; of kastand hewes,</L>
<L>With riche rabies of gold &middot; railed bi &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> hemmes,</L>
<L>A vestoure to vise on &middot; of violet floures,</L>
<L N="1540">Wro&yogh;t full of wodwose &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er wild bestis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;an him hi&yogh;tild his hede &middot; &amp; had on a Mitre,</L>
<L>Was forgid all of fyne gold &middot; &amp; fret full of perrils,</L>
<L>Sti&yogh;t staffull of stanes &middot; &thorn;at stra&yogh;t out bemes,</L>
<L N="1544">As it ware shemerand shaftis &middot; of &thorn;e shire son.</L>
<L>Doctours &amp; diuinours &middot; &amp; othire dere maistris,</L>
<L>Iustis of iewry &middot; &amp; iogis of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Ware tired all in tonacles &middot; of tarrayn webbis;</L>
<L N="1548">&THORN;ai were bret-full of bees &middot; all &thorn;e body ouire,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er clientis &amp; clerkis &middot; as to &thorn;e kirke fallis,</L>
<L>Ware all samen of a soyte &middot; in surples of raynes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at slike a si&yogh;t, I supose &middot; was neuer sene eftire,</L>
<L N="1552">So parailed a procession &middot; a person a-gaynes.</L>
<L>Now bowis furth &thorn;e bischop &middot; at &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>With prestis &amp; with prelatis &middot; a pake out of nombre;<MILESTONE N="27a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cite in sorte &middot; felowis him eftir,</L>
<L N="1556">Quirris furth all in quite &middot; of qualite as aungels;</L>
<L>Maistirs, marchands, &amp; Maire &middot; mynistris &amp; othire,</L>
<L>Worthi wedous &amp; wenchis &middot; &amp; wyues of &thorn;e cite;</L>
<L>Be ilka barne in &thorn;e burgh &middot; as bla&yogh;t ere &thorn;aire wedis</L>
<L N="1560">As any snyppand snawe &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e snape li&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar passis &thorn;e procession &middot; a piple be-forne,</L>
<L>Of childire all in chalk<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. shalk.</NOTE> quyte &middot; chosen out a hundreth,</L>
<L>With bellis &amp; with baners &middot; &amp; blasand torchis,
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="86"></L>
<L N="1564">Instrumentis &amp; ymagis &middot; with-in of &thorn;e Mynstire;</L>
<L>Sum with sensours &amp; so[m] &middot; with silueryn cheynes,</L>
<L>Quare-of &thorn;e reke aromatike &middot; rase to &thorn;e welken;</L>
<L>Sum with of &thorn;e saynt-ware &middot; many sere thingis,</L>
<L N="1568">With tablis &amp; topoures &middot; &amp; tretice of &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>Sum bolstirs of burnet &middot; en-brouden with perill,</L>
<L>Bare before &thorn;e bischop &middot; his buke on to lig;</L>
<L>Sum candilstickis of clere gold &middot; &amp; of clene siluer,</L>
<L N="1572">With releckis full rially &middot; &thorn;e richest on &thorn;e auutere.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seyis all &thorn;e semle &middot; &thorn;e cite with-oute,</L>
<L>Vn-to a stonen stede &middot; stre&yogh;t on &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L>Scopulus, by sum skill &middot; &thorn;e scripture it callis,</L>
<L N="1576">And &thorn;are &thorn;e come of &thorn;e kynge &middot; &thorn;is couent abidis.</L>
<L>Sone Alexander with ane ost &middot; of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> many athille dukis,</L>
<L>Come prekand toward &thorn;e place &middot; with princes &amp; erlis,</L>
<L>Sees slike a multitude of men &middot; in milke-quite clathis,</L>
<L N="1580">And ilk seg in a soyte &middot; at selly him thinkis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fyndis he in &thorn;is o&thorn;ire flote &middot; fanons and stolis,</L>
<L>Practisirs &amp; prematis &middot; &amp; prestis of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L N="1583">Of dialiticus &amp; decre &middot; doctours of aythir,</L>
<L>Bathe chambirlayn &amp; chaplayne &middot; in chalk-quite wedis.</L>
<L>And as he waytis in a wra &middot; &thorn;an was he ware sone<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e maister of &thorn;at meneyhe &middot; in-myddis &thorn;e puple,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e bald bischop &middot; a-bofe alle &thorn;[e]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;.</NOTE> iewis,</L>
<L N="1588">Was gra&thorn;id in a garment &middot; of gold &amp; of pu[r]pree.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he heues vp his e&yogh;e &middot; be-haldis on his myter,</L>
<L>Be-fore he sa&yogh;e of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here</I> forgid <I>is inserted, but is underlined.</I></NOTE> fyne gold &middot; forgid a plate,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-in grauen &thorn;e grettest &middot; of all gods names,</L>
<L N="1592">&THORN;is title, Tetragramaton &middot; for so &thorn;e text tellis.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at comandis &thorn;e kyng &middot; his kny&yogh;tis ouire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> euire.</NOTE> ilkane,</L>
<L>Bathe beron &amp; bachelere &middot; &amp; bald men of armes,</L>
<L>Na nere &thorn;at place to aproche &middot; a payn of &thorn;ar lyuys,</L>
<L N="1596">Bot all to hald &thorn;am be-hynd &middot; heraud &amp; othire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an airis he furth all him ane &middot; to &thorn;is athill mene&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Bowis him doun of his blonke &middot; &thorn;e bischop be-forne,</L>
<L>And kneland on &thorn;e cald erth &middot; he knockis on his brest,</L>
<L N="1600">And reuerencez &thorn;is haly name &middot; at he seis wreten.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e iewis of ierusalem &middot; Iustis &amp; othire,</L>
<L>Lordis &amp; ladis &middot; &amp; be &thorn;e litill childere,</L>
<L>Enclynes &thorn;am to &thorn;e conquirour &middot; &amp; him on<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> kneis gretis,</L>
<L N="1604">Kest vp a kene crie &middot; &amp; carpis &thorn;ir wordis.</L>
<L>"Ay mo&yogh;t he lefe, ay mo&yogh;t he lefe" &middot; quod ilka man twyse,</L>
<L>"Alexander, &thorn;e athill aire &middot; vndire &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>Ay mo&yogh;t he lefe, ay mo&yogh;t he lefe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here the</I> MS. <I>wrongly inserts</I> quod.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e lege Emperoure,</L>
<L N="1608">&THORN;e wildire of all &thorn;e werde &middot; &amp; worthist on erthe,</L>
<L>Ay mo&yogh;t he lef, ay mo&yogh;t he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> leue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE>" &middot; quod loude all at anys,</L>
<L>"Ouircomere clene of ilka coste &middot; &amp; ouircomyn neuir,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gretest &amp; &thorn;e gloriosest &middot; &thorn;at euir god formed,</L>
<L N="1612">Erle or Emperoure &middot; &amp; any erdly prince."</L>
<L>&THORN;are was comen with him kyngis &middot; as &thorn;e clause tellis,</L>
<L>Seneiours out of Sireland<NOTE PLACE="foot">land <I>is above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &middot; was to him-selfe &yogh;olden,</L>
<L N="1615">And &thorn;ai meruailed &thorn;am mekill &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai it herd so be-heryd &middot; &amp; held it in wondire.<MILESTONE N="28a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an Permeon, a proude kni&yogh;t &middot; a prince of his oste,</L>
<L>Aires to sir Alexander &middot; &amp; askis at him swythe,</L>
<L N="1619">Syn him adoured all men &middot; eldire &amp; &yogh;ongir,</L>
<L>Qui he obeschid so lawe &amp; bende &middot; &thorn;e bischop of iewis?</L>
<L>"Nay," quod &thorn;e comly kynge &middot; &amp; &thorn;e kny&yogh;t swaris,</L>
<L>"Nouthire haylsid I him &middot; ne hildid him nouthire,</L>
<L N="1623">Bot it was gode at I grete &middot; &thorn;e gouernoure of all,</L>
<L>Of quam in &thorn;e abite &amp; &thorn;e armes &middot; he was all clethid.</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e marche of Messedone &middot; me mynes on a tyme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at slike a segg in my slepe &middot; me sodanly aperid,</L>
<L>Euyn in slike a similitude &middot; &amp; &thorn;is same wedis,</L>
<L N="1628">For all &thorn;e werd as &thorn;is wee &middot; wendis now atired.
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>And &thorn;en I mused<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> d <I>is above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> in my mynde &middot; how at I my&yogh;t wyn</L>
<L>Anothire anell of &thorn;e erth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. werd erth; <I>but</I> werd <I>is struck out</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;at Aysy we call it,</L>
<L>And me thret to be thra<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> to be thra; <I>partly underlined</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; for na &thorn;ing turne,</L>
<L N="1632">Bot tire me titely &thorn;arto &middot; &amp; tristly to wende.</L>
<L>And syne sa&yogh;e I na segg &middot; &thorn;at sa was arayd;</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>And sekirly yone semys &middot; &thorn;e same to se<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;e in same to to w; <I>altered to</I> &thorn;e same to se.</NOTE> to within,</L>
<L N="1635">&THORN;e same gode at I in my slepe &middot; sa&yogh;e in my days;</L>
<L>And now I hope me, &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; of &thorn;e haly fadire,</L>
<L>Of quam &thorn;e hered haly name &middot; is &yogh;ondire on hi&yogh;e wreten,</L>
<L>To do with Darius or I dyi &middot; how so me dere thinke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pride of all &thorn;e Persens &middot; purely distroy.</L>
<L N="1640">And &yogh;it I sothely supose &middot; quat so my sale hopis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sall fall apon fold &middot; slik fyaunce I haue</L>
<L>In &thorn;e grace of grete god &middot; at gyes all &thorn;e sternes,</L>
<L N="1643">&THORN;at it sall be in my will &middot; &amp; on na way faile."</L>
<L>Now tas &thorn;e bischop &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e bur&yogh;e wendis,<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With sange &amp; solempnite &middot; him to &thorn;e cite ledis,</L>
<L>He was resayued, as I rede &middot; with reuerence &amp; Ioye,</L>
<L N="1647">As he ware duke of ilk douth &middot; &amp; dreuyn doun fra heuen.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gas he furth with his gingis &middot; to godis awen temple,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of sir Salamon &thorn;e sage &middot; sett was &amp; foundid,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he lythis of &thorn;are lare &middot; as &thorn;e law wald;</L>
<L>He offird in &thorn;at oratori &middot; &amp; honourd oure lorde.</L>
<L N="1652">And Iaudas of ierusalem &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e iewis eftir</L>
<L>Bringis out a brade buke &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e berne reches,</L>
<L>Was plant full of prophasys &middot; playnely all ouire,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e doctrine of Daniell &middot; &amp; of his dere sawis.</L>
<L N="1656">&THORN;e lord<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> lokis on &thorn;e lyne &middot; &amp; on a lefe fyndis</L>
<L>How &thorn;e gomes out of grece &middot; suld with &thorn;aire grete mi&yogh;tis
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>&THORN;e pupill out of Persye &middot; purely distroy;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he hopis sall be he &middot; &amp; hertly he ioyes.</L>
<L N="1660">&THORN;an partis he to &thorn;a prelatis &middot; many proude giftis,</L>
<L>Was nane sa pore in &thorn;at place &middot; bot he his purse fillis,</L>
<L>Geues &thorn;am garsons of gold &middot; &amp; of gud stanes,</L>
<L>Rife riches eno&yogh;e &middot; robies &amp; perles,</L>
<L N="1664">Besands to &thorn;e bischop &middot; he bed out of nounbre,</L>
<L>Reches him of rede gold &middot; ransons many,</L>
<L>Tas him to his tresory &middot; talent him to shewe,</L>
<L>Bad him wale quat he wald &middot; &amp; wild him &thorn;e to&thorn;ir.</L>
<L N="1668">&YOGH;it bedis he him, &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis:</L>
<L>"Sire, quat &thorn;ou will in &thorn;is werd &middot; to wild &amp; to haue,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t bot aske it at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. at it.</NOTE> Alexander &middot; quat &thorn;ou will apon reson,</L>
<L>And I sall grant, or I ga &middot; with a gud will."</L>
<L N="1672">&THORN;an bowis doun &thorn;e bischop &middot; &amp; him a bone askis,</L>
<L>"Sire, &thorn;is I depely disire &middot; durst I it neuyn,<MILESTONE N="29a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at it be leuefull vs oure lare &middot; &amp; oure law vse,</L>
<L>As oure fadirs has folowid &middot; forwith &thorn;is tyme;</L>
<L N="1676">As of &yogh;oure grete gudnes &middot; at &yogh;e grant wald</L>
<L>To lat vs sitt be safe &middot; bot for &thorn;is seuyn wyntir,</L>
<L>But tribute or trouag &middot; quils &thorn;e terme lastis,</L>
<L>&THORN;an were we halden all &thorn;e hepe &middot; to hi&yogh;e &thorn;e for euir.</L>
<L N="1680">And &yogh;it I will, be &yogh;oure leue &middot; a worde &amp; na mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e men of Medi &middot; man, be &yogh;oure leue,</L>
<L>Lang all in oure lawe &middot; lely to-gedire,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai of Babilon bathe &middot; &amp; bede I na nothire."</L>
<L N="1684">Quod Alexander belyue &middot; "all &thorn;is I graunt,</L>
<L>And els any othire thing &middot; aske &amp; be serued."</L>
<L>"Nay, now na mare," quod &thorn;e man &middot; &amp; mekly him thankid,</L>
<L>"Bot ay &thorn;i lordschip &amp; &thorn;i loue &middot; quils my lyfe dures."</L>
<L N="1688">Now kastis &thorn;is conquirour &middot; to caire fra &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>And mas to bide in &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; a berne of his awyn,</L>
<L>A messagere to myn &middot; on quat men of him said,
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>Ane Ardromacius, a gome &middot; as<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e buke tellis.</L>
<L N="1692">&THORN;an bowis to &thorn;e bischop &middot; his benyson to fang,</L>
<L>Takis lufly his leue &middot; &amp; lendis on forthere.</L>
<L>To Sere cites &thorn;ar be-syde &middot; he so&yogh;t with his hostis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai frendly &amp; faire &middot; frely resayued him.</L>
<L N="1696">&THORN;an of &thorn;e Siriens summe &middot; in &thorn;e same tyme</L>
<L>Folow fra &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; as fals men suld,</L>
<L>Did &thorn;am to sir Darius &middot; &amp; depely &thorn;am playnt,</L>
<L N="1699">Quat erroure of &thorn;is Emperoure &middot; &amp; euill &thorn;ai suffird.</L>
<L>And he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;am faire vndir-fong &middot; &amp; fraynes &thorn;am &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>Askis &thorn;am of sir Alexander &middot; all at he cuthe,<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bathe of his statoure &amp; his strenth &middot; if he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> if he.</NOTE> ware store ben,</L>
<L>His qualite, his quantite &middot; he quirys all-to-gedire;</L>
<L N="1704">And &thorn;ai in parchement him payntid &middot; his person him shewid,</L>
<L>Ane amla&yogh;e, ane asaleny &middot; ane ape of all othire,</L>
<L>A wirling, a wayryngle &middot; a wawil-e&yogh;id shrewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cait[if]este creatour &middot; &thorn;at cried was euire.</L>
<L N="1708">And &thorn;an, as he lenes &middot; &amp; lokis on his fourme,</L>
<L>His litillaike &amp; his licknes &middot; he laythly dispiced,</L>
<L>And thre thingis of his thede &middot; he &thorn;o&yogh;t him sa feble,</L>
<L>He dressis to him in dedeyne &middot; &amp; in dispite sendis:</L>
<L N="1712">First a ball, says &thorn;e buke &middot; &thorn;e barne with to play,</L>
<L>A herne-pan es of a berne &middot; of brend gold yeuen,</L>
<L>For hottre &amp; for hething &middot; a Hatt made of twyggis;</L>
<L>Sayd &thorn;at was benere him to bere &middot; &thorn;an a bri&yogh;t helme.</L>
<L N="1716">Slike presandis out of Persy &middot; he to &thorn;e prince sendis,</L>
<L>His brefe with a brade sele &middot; &amp; biddis hum<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> him.</NOTE> ga swythe.</L>
<L>And qua sa will has to wete &middot; howe it worthis eftir,</L>
<L>Now sall I neuen vs here next &middot; &thorn;e note of his lettir.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000101.tif" N="79">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1457"><B>Als hastely as &thorn;ai herd of &middot; in haly cite,</B></L>
<L><B>And Bodword</B> to &thorn;e bischop &middot; was broght of hys come,</L>
<L N="1459">For alexander aw &middot; almost he dyes,</L>
<L>And for he hed nekyd hym with nay &middot; in a new tyme.</L>
<L>And now he &thorn;enkez in his thought &middot; he turht<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thurt.</NOTE> noght haue cared</L>
<L>In all hys maste mister &middot; made he hym faylez,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> nad he &thorn;e man fayled.</NOTE></L>
<L>When he for socour to &thorn;e cite &middot; send hym hys lettre;</L>
<L N="1464">And he soned hym by &thorn;is case &middot; &thorn;at nowe hym for|thynkez.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>"For me hed leuer," quod &thorn;e lede &middot; "bene letherly forsworne<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On all &thorn;e halydoms &middot; as opyn are to nevyn,</L>
<L N="1467">Than onys haue greved &thorn;is gome &middot; or groched with hys erand!</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer I warned hym hys wille &middot; wa is me bestound!"</L>
<L>Thus was Iaudes of ioy &middot; &amp; iolyte depreuett;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e Iewes of Ierusalem &middot; he iontly assemblez.</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Said.</NOTE>, "alexander is at hand &middot; &amp; wille vs all combred,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> combre.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1472">And we er vtterly vndone &middot; bot dryghten vs shelde."</L>
<L>Than biddez &thorn;e bischop all &thorn;e burgh &middot; bernes &amp; o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Athelles of all age &middot; bath elder &amp; yonger,</L>
<L>Comand iche creature &middot; &amp; cryed &thorn;orow &thorn;e stretes,</L>
<L N="1476">Till thre days on a thraw &middot; wer threpelytt to-geder,</L>
<L>And ilke freke &amp; euery faunt &middot; to fast &amp; to pray,</L>
<L>To occupy in &thorn;air orisons &middot; &amp; offers<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> offer.</NOTE> in &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L>And calle vp with kene cry &middot; vnto &thorn;e kyng of heuen,</L>
<L N="1480">And kepe &thorn;aim with &thorn;is conquerour &middot; he comber &thorn;aim neuer.</L>
<L>Thai soght to &thorn;air sinagoge &middot; all &thorn;e cite ouer;</L>
<L>Iche body to &thorn;air bedes &middot; at in &thorn;e burgh lendes</L>
<L>Putten &thorn;aim to prayers &middot; &amp; pennance indurett,</L>
<L N="1484">&THORN;e vengance of &thorn;is victor &middot; to voyde if &thorn;ai might.</L>
<L>The thred nyght after &thorn;is note &middot; as neuen me &thorn;e text,</L>
<L>When all &thorn;e cite was slepe &middot; &amp; sacrifese endytt,<NOTE PLACE="marg">apparieio angeli episcopo Ieromo|solitano.</NOTE></L>
<L>In ane habett of &thorn;e ayre &middot; an angell apperes</L>
<L N="1488">To Iaudes of Ierusalem &middot; and hym with ioy gretes:</L>
<L>"I brynge &thorn;e bodworde of [blis] &middot; sir bischop," he sayd,</L>
<L>"With salutez of solace &middot; am send fro &thorn;e trone,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e hye maister of mageste &middot; &amp; &thorn;at mightfull fadre,</L>
<L>A byddes &thorn;e noght be abaysed &middot; he hase &thorn;i bone herd;</L>
<L N="1493">And I amonesh &thorn;e to-morne &middot; als me was amoved,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou als radly as &thorn;ou ryses &middot; aray all &thorn;i cite,</L>
<L>The stretes &amp; all stedes &middot; stoutly &amp; faire,
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="83"></L>
<L N="1496">&THORN;at it be honest all ouer &middot; &amp; opyn vp &thorn;e &yogh;ates.</L>
<L>Lett &thorn;en &thorn;i peple euerilke polle &middot; aparaeld<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. aparaerld; <I>see l.</I> 1552.</NOTE> be clene,</L>
<L>And all maner of men &middot; in milke-whitte clathez.</L>
<L>Bott passe, &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;i pristez &middot; &amp; prelatez of &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L N="1500">Reuest all on rawe &middot; as your rewle askez.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;is conquerour comez &middot; carez hym agayns;<MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he must ryde &amp; reyne &middot; ouer all &thorn;e brede of &thorn;e werlde,</L>
<L>And be Lord of ilke lede &middot; vnto hys last dayes,</L>
<L N="1504">And &thorn;en be dight vnto &thorn;e deth &middot; of drightenez ayre."</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e dyrke ouer-drafe &middot; &amp; &thorn;e day springez,</L>
<L>Oure Bishop bownes hym of bede &middot; &amp; buskes hys wedes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en &thorn;at Iew of all Iewes &middot; in generall he clepys,</L>
<L N="1508">Says &thorn;aim hys vision &middot; &amp; as &thorn;e voyce biddes;</L>
<L>Than councellys hym &thorn;e Clerge &middot; clene all-to-geder,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cety be assent &middot; sariauntez &amp; other,</L>
<L>To bowne hym forth with all &thorn;e burgh &middot; &amp; buske hym beliue,</L>
<L>As hym was sayd in hys slepe &middot; &thorn;is souerand to mete.</L>
<L N="1513">Than rynnes forth in a rese &middot; arayes all &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L>Spredes ouer with bawdkens &middot; all &thorn;e brode stretes,</L>
<L>With riche clothez of taffata &middot; qwer he trede suld,</L>
<L N="1516">For &thorn;e erth to siche ane emperour &middot; wer all to feble.</L>
<L>He plyes ouer &thorn;e payment &middot; pallen webbes,</L>
<L>Makez on hight ouer &thorn;e heued &middot; for het<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> t <I>is written above the line</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e son,</L>
<L N="1519">Silours of sendale &middot; to syle ouer &thorn;e gatez,</L>
<L>And sampnez &thorn;aime on a&thorn;er [side] &middot; with sylkyn rapez,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an he cachez vp on cordez &middot; als curtaynez it were.</L>
<L>Euen als &thorn;e esynges &yogh;ode &middot; ouer be &thorn;e costez,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e wallez withowte &middot; in webbez of Inde,</L>
<L N="1524">Of bright blysnand blew &middot; browden with sternes.</L>
<L>Thus attyred he &thorn;is toune &middot; &amp; titely &thorn;ar-after</L>
<L>Of ilke way wide hopyn &middot; warpyd he &thorn;e &yogh;atez;</L>
<L>Att who so wates fro withowte &middot; &amp; within hedes,</L>
<L N="1528">It semyd as to se to &middot; on of &thorn;e seuen heuens.
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>Now passes &thorn;is prelate &middot; with prestez of &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L>Reuest fully rially &middot; &amp; with ryche wedes,</L>
<L>First ane habett vnder all &middot; as I am enformed.</L>
<L N="1532">Full of birdes &amp; of bestes &middot; of byse &amp; of purpurre;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was garneshed full gay &middot; with gold skirtez,</L>
<L>Store starand stanes &middot; strenklett all ouer,</L>
<L>Sawdett with saphirez &middot; and o&thorn;er sere gemmys,</L>
<L N="1536">And pouuderet vith perre &middot; was purer &thorn;ar<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> &thorn;an.</NOTE> o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Bot syne he kest on a Cape &middot; of castans hewe,</L>
<L>With riche rybans of gold &middot; raythely &thorn;e hem,</L>
<L>A vesture of vyce &middot; of vyolet flourez,<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1540">Wroght full [of] wodwose &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er wylde bestes;</L>
<L>And &thorn;en he heghtlet on hys heued &middot; a hoge fair myter,</L>
<L>Was forgett all [of] fyne gold &middot; &amp; frett full of perlez,</L>
<L>Stight staffull of stanes &middot; &thorn;at straughten owt bemes,</L>
<L N="1544">Als it wer shemerand shaftez &middot; shott fro &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>Doctours &amp; deuynours &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er dere maistres,</L>
<L>Iustes of Iewry &middot; &amp; Iewes of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Wer tyrett all in tonacles &middot; of tartaren webbys;</L>
<L N="1548">And &thorn;ai wer brightfull of bleez &middot; all &thorn;e body ouer,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er clerkez &amp; colettes &middot; at to &thorn;e kirke longen,</L>
<L>Wer all sampnen in a sott &middot; with surples of reynes,</L>
<L>That suche a sight, I suppose &middot; was neuer sene aftir,</L>
<L N="1552">So paraeld a procession &middot; ane person agayns.</L>
<L>Now bownes furth &thorn;e bischop &middot; at &thorn;e brode &yogh;ates,</L>
<L>With pristes &amp; with prelatez &middot; a pake owt of nowmbre;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e cite of sorte &middot; sylez hym after,</L>
<L N="1556">Whirrez forth all in white &middot; of qualite of angels;</L>
<L>Marchaundez, maister mair &middot; mynister and o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Worthy wedous and wifes &middot; &amp; whenches of &thorn;e cite;</L>
<L>Be ilke a barne in &thorn;e burgh &middot; all blaught is hys wedes</L>
<L N="1560">Als any snappand snaw &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e snape lightes.</L>
<L>Than passys &thorn;e procession &middot; a peple beforne,</L>
<L>Of childer all in chalke white &middot; chosyn a hundreth,</L>
<L>With bellys &amp; with banners<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. barners.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; blesand torchez,
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="87"></L>
<L N="1564">Instrumentes &amp; ymagez &middot; within of &thorn;e temple;</L>
<L>Som with censours &amp; som<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. so, <I>alt. to</I> set; <I>but read</I> s&omacr; = som.</NOTE> &middot; with syluer chynes,</L>
<L>Whar-of &thorn;e reke of aromatyke &middot; rase to &thorn;e welken;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sanctuary &middot; mony sere &thorn;ingez,</L>
<L N="1568">With tabels &amp; tapers &middot; &amp; tretes of &thorn;e law;</L>
<L>Som bolsters of burnett &middot; enbrowden with perle,</L>
<L>Borne byfore &thorn;e bishop &middot; hys boke on to lig;</L>
<L>Som candelstyke of clene gold &middot; &amp; of good syluer,</L>
<L N="1572">With relikkez fully rially &middot; &thorn;e richest of &thorn;e werld.</L>
<L>Thus se&yogh;es all &thorn;is semble &middot; &thorn;e cite withowte,</L>
<L>Vnto a stonon stede &middot; stre&yogh;t on &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L>Scopulus, be some skely &middot; &thorn;e scriptur it calles,</L>
<L N="1576">And &thorn;ar &thorn;e come of &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;is Couent abydez.</L>
<L>Sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Some.</NOTE> Alexander with an hoste &middot; of many athell dukez,<MILESTONE N="15a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Come prekand to &thorn;e palace &middot; with princez &amp; Erelez,</L>
<L>Saugh suche a multitude of men &middot; [in] mylke-white wedes,</L>
<L N="1580">And ilke a sege in a sote &middot; &thorn;at selly hym thynkez.</L>
<L>Than fyndez he in a nother flete &middot; of fanons &amp; stoles,</L>
<L>Practyf men in prevatez &middot; &amp; prestez of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Of Dialeticus and decre &middot; doctours of ather,</L>
<L>Bath chamerlayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. chamernlayn.</NOTE> &amp; chapelayn &middot; in chalke-white wedes.</L>
<L N="1585">And als he wates in a wray &middot; &thorn;en was he war sone</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e maister of &thorn;at meyn&yogh;e &middot; in-myddez of &thorn;e peple,</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e bald bischop &middot; abowne all &thorn;e Iewes,</L>
<L N="1588">Was grathed in a garment &middot; of gold &amp; of siluer.</L>
<L>Than he heldes vp on hegh &middot; beheld on hys myter,</L>
<L>Before he se of fyne gold &middot; forgett a playte,</L>
<L>An &thorn;ar-on grauen on &thorn;e grethest &middot; of all godez namez,</L>
<L N="1592">This title, tetragramaton &middot; for so &thorn;e text wittnesse.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at Comand &thorn;e kynge &middot; hys knyghtez all,</L>
<L>Bath barouns &amp; bachelers &middot; bald men of armez,</L>
<L>No nere &thorn;e place [to aproche] &middot; vpon payn of &thorn;air lyfez,</L>
<L N="1596">Bot all to hald &thorn;aim byhynde &middot; &thorn;e lesse &amp; &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Than ayres he forth all hym one &middot; to &thorn;is athell meyn&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>Bowes hym downe of hys blonke &middot; &thorn;e bischopp before,</L>
<L>Kneland on<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of.</NOTE> &thorn;e cald erth &middot; &amp; knokez on hys briste,</L>
<L>And hersouns &thorn;at haly name &middot; &thorn;at he byheld written.</L>
<L N="1601">&THORN;an all &thorn;e Iewes of Ierusalem &middot; Iustice &amp; o&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Processio versus alex|andrum apud Ierusalem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lordez &amp; lades &middot; be &thorn;e lityll sottez,</L>
<L>Inclines &thorn;aim to &thorn;is conquerour &middot; &amp; hym on knees gretes,</L>
<L N="1604">Kest vp a kene crye &middot; &amp; carpyd &thorn;ees wordes:</L>
<L>"Ay mott he leue, ay mot he leue" &middot; quod ilke a lede twyse,</L>
<L N="1606">"Alexander, &thorn;e athelfullest &middot; hayr vnder heven,</L>
<L>Ay mot he leue, ay mott he leue &middot; &thorn;is lege Emperour,</L>
<L>The welder of all &thorn;e werld &middot; &amp; worthiest vnder wylde,</L>
<L>Ay mott he leue," quod &thorn;e Land &middot; [loude all] at anes,</L>
<L>"Ouercommer clene of ilke coste &middot; &amp; ouercommyn neuer,</L>
<L>The grettest &amp; &thorn;e gloriest &middot; &thorn;at euer god formed,</L>
<L N="1612">Erell or ony Emperour &middot; or erthlich prince!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an Wer &thorn;air common whit hym kyngez &middot; als &thorn;e clause telles,<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Senyours owt of Surry &middot; wer to hym-selue &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai amervale &thorn;aime mekyll &middot; as menys me &thorn;e writtes,</L>
<L N="1616">When &thorn;ai saw hym so heret &middot; &amp; heldyn it a wondre.</L>
<L>Than Permeon, a proude kny&yogh;t &middot; a prince of hys hoste,</L>
<L>Ayres to sir alexander &middot; and askys hym swith,</L>
<L>Sen hym adouret all men &middot; alder &amp; yonger,</L>
<L>Why he obeyd &amp; bowed so &middot; to &thorn;e bischop of Iewes?</L>
<L N="1621">"Nay," quod &thorn;e comly kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. knyge.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; &thorn;e kny&yogh;t swerez,</L>
<L>"No&thorn;er haylsed I hym &middot; ne heldit hym no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Bod it was god at I gret &middot; &thorn;e gouernour of all,</L>
<L>Of whome in &thorn;e habett &amp; &thorn;e armez &middot; he was all clethyd.</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e marche of masydon &middot; me menys on a tyme,</L>
<L N="1626">Suche a segh in my slepe &middot; me sodenly appered,</L>
<L>Euen in suche a sembland &middot; &amp; in &thorn;e same wedes,</L>
<L N="1628">For all &thorn;is werld as &thorn;is wy &middot; wendes now attyred.
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>And &thorn;an 1 musyd in my mynde &middot; how &thorn;at I might wynne,</L>
<L>Ane o&thorn;er angle of &thorn;e erth &middot; &thorn;at asy we calle,</L>
<L>And he me thrett to be tra<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thra.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; for no thyng turne,</L>
<L N="1632">Bot tyre me titely &thorn;arto &middot; &amp; tristly to wend.</L>
<L N="1633">And syne saw I no segh &middot; &thorn;at so was atired;</L>
<L N="1633*">And he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> I; <I>twice</I>.</NOTE> hoppyd &thorn;e helder &thorn;at &thorn;is was he &middot; at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> I; <I>twice</I>.</NOTE> saw &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="1634">For sekerly he semys so &middot; to se withowte,</L>
<L>The<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Thame.</NOTE> same god &thorn;at in my slepe &middot; I sawe in &thorn;o days;</L>
<L N="1636">And now I hope, &thorn;orow help &middot; of &thorn;e hye fadre,</L>
<L>On whom &thorn;e holy name is &yogh;ond &middot; on hye written,</L>
<L>To do with Darius, or I dye &middot; how I some dere thynke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pride of all &thorn;e persens &middot; purely distroy.</L>
<L N="1640">Bot &yogh;itte I sothly suppose &middot; qwat so my saule &thorn;inkez,</L>
<L>That sall be-falle vppon falde &middot; slyke fiance I haue</L>
<L>In &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e grett god &middot; &thorn;at gydez all sternes,</L>
<L>That it sall in my will be &middot; &amp; in no ways faille."</L>
<L N="1644">Now takys &thorn;is Bishop &thorn;e berne &middot; &amp; to burgh ledes,</L>
<L>With sange &amp; solempnite &middot; with hym to cite wendes,</L>
<L>He was resaued, as I rede &middot; with reuerence &amp; Ioy,</L>
<L>As he wer duke of iche dochre &middot; &amp; drevyn owt of heuen.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gays he forth with hys gyng &middot; to goddes awne temple,<MILESTONE N="16a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1649">That of sir salamon &thorn;e sage &middot; sett was &amp; fondyn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar he lightez of &thorn;ar lare &middot; &amp;, als &thorn;e lawe wald,</L>
<L>He offers in &thorn;at oratory &middot; &amp; honours owr Lorde.</L>
<L N="1652">And Iaudes of Ierusalem &middot; &thorn;e Iewes fadir,</L>
<L>Bringes forth a brade buke &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e berne reches,</L>
<L>Was plantyd full of prophecyes &middot; playnly all ouer,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e doctryne of daniell &middot; &amp; of hys dere sawes.</L>
<L N="1656">The lede lokys on a lefe &middot; &amp; in a lyne fyndes<NOTE PLACE="marg">prophecia</NOTE></L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e gomez owt of grece &middot; suld with &thorn;air grett mightez
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>The peple owt of perse &middot; purely distroy;</L>
<L>And [&thorn;at] he hopys suld be he &middot; &amp; heterly he ioyes.</L>
<L N="1660">Than he partes to &thorn;e prelates &middot; mony prouude gyftes,</L>
<L>Was non so pure in &thorn;e place &middot; bot he hys purse fillez,</L>
<L>Gyfez &thorn;aim garisons of gold &middot; &amp; of god stanez,</L>
<L>Riche giftez enogh &middot; bath rubies &amp; perelez,</L>
<L>Besaundez to &thorn;e bischopp &middot; he badde owt of nowmbre,</L>
<L N="1665">Rechez hym of rede gold &middot; raunsons mony,</L>
<L>Takez hym to hys tresory &middot; talentes hym shewys,</L>
<L>Bade hym wale qwat he walde &middot; &amp; wyld hym &thorn;aes o&thorn;er.</L>
<L N="1668">&YOGH;it biddez hym &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; als &thorn;e boke tellez:</L>
<L>"Sir, qwat &thorn;ou will in &thorn;is werld &middot; to weld or to haue,</L>
<L>No&yogh;t bot aske at alexander &middot; any thyng of reson,</L>
<L>And I sall graunte, or I gay &middot; with a goode wille."</L>
<L>Than bowes downe our bischop &middot; &amp; hym a bone askez,</L>
<L N="1673">"Sir, &thorn;is I depely desirre &middot; durst I it neuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e wald latte vs oure lare &middot; &amp; owre lawez vse,</L>
<L>Als owr faders hase foloued &middot; forewith &thorn;is tyme;</L>
<L N="1676">And of your grett goodnesse &middot; if &yogh;e &thorn;is graunte wald</L>
<L>To latt vs sitte &amp; be safe &middot; bot for &thorn;is seuen wynter,</L>
<L>Withowte tribute or truage &middot; whils &thorn;e terme lastes,</L>
<L>&THORN;en wer we halden all &thorn;e hepe &middot; to pray for you for euer.</L>
<L N="1680">And &yogh;itt I wille, be your leue &middot; a worde &amp; no more,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e men of mede &middot; may, be your leue,</L>
<L>Lenge all in your<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> our.</NOTE> lawe &middot; lely to-geder,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai of babilon bath &middot; &thorn;an bid I none othre."</L>
<L N="1684">Quod alexander als belyue &middot; "all &thorn;is I graunt,</L>
<L>And ellys ony o&thorn;er thyng &middot; aske &amp; be serued."<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Nay, nowe no more," quod &thorn;is man &middot; &amp; mekely hym thankez,</L>
<L>"Bot your lordship and youre loue &middot; whille my lyve lastes."</L>
<L N="1688">Now kyst hym &thorn;is conquerour &middot; to care fro &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>And made to byde in &thorn;e burgh &middot; a berne of hir awne,</L>
<L>A messynger to meyn on &middot; qwat men of hym sayd,
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Ane.</NOTE> andromacius, a man &middot; as I am enformed.</L>
<L N="1692">&THORN;an bowys he to &thorn;e Bishop &middot; hys benyson to fange,</L>
<L>Keches lufly hys leue &middot; &amp; lendez on ferther.</L>
<L>To setez &thorn;ar bysyde &middot; he soght with hys hostez,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai frendly &amp; faire &middot; &amp; frely resaued hym.</L>
<L N="1696">Bot &thorn;en of surriens a soume &middot; in &thorn;e same tyme</L>
<L>Flowen from &thorn;is fell kyng &middot; as fals men suldyn,</L>
<L>Did &thorn;aim to sir Darius &middot; &amp; depely &thorn;aim plenyd,</L>
<L>What errour of &thorn;is emperour &middot; &amp; ille &thorn;at &thorn;ai suffred.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;aim faire vnderfangez &middot; &amp; franez &thorn;aim &yogh;arne,</L>
<L N="1701">Askez &thorn;aim of sir alexander &middot; all &thorn;at he couth,</L>
<L>Bath of hys stature &amp; hys strenth &middot; if he wer sture-baned,</L>
<L>Hys qualite, hys quantite &middot; enquirez all-to-gedyr;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai in perchemyn depayntyd &middot; hys person hym sweyd,</L>
<L N="1705">Ane amlaugh, ane aslyn &middot; ane ape of all other,</L>
<L>A wirlyng, a warlow &middot; a waugle-eghed shrewe,</L>
<L>The catyfest creatur &middot; &thorn;at credylytt was euer.</L>
<L>And &thorn;en &thorn;e Lord, as he lenytt &middot; &amp; lokett on hys forme,</L>
<L N="1709">Hys litilayke &amp; hys liknes &middot; he loudly dispysez,</L>
<L>And thro<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thre.</NOTE> thyngez of hys thede &middot; hym thoght so feble,</L>
<L>He dressyd to hym in dysdene &middot; &amp; dispite sendes:</L>
<L>Frist to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to <I>above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e barne, says &thorn;e buke &middot; a balle with to play,</L>
<L N="1713">A brayn-pan of a berne &middot; of brent gold &thorn;en,</L>
<L>For hocour &amp; for hethyng &middot; a hat made of wiggez<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> twiggez.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Sayd, &thorn;at was bener hym to bring &middot; &thorn;en a bright helme.</L>
<L>Suche presandez owt of perse &middot; he to &thorn;e prince wayfez,</L>
<L N="1717">Hys brefe with a brade seale &middot; &amp; byddes &thorn;aim go swithe.</L>
<L>And who sa wete wald &middot; how it worthed aftir,</L>
<L>Now sall I neuen vs on next &middot; &thorn;e note of hys lettre.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="8" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000118.tif" N="96">
<HEAD><B>Octauus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sire dere Darius on dese &middot; &thorn;e digne Emperoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng without comparrison &middot; of kyngis all othire,</L>
<L>Of all lordis &thorn;e lord &middot; &thorn;at leues in erthe,</L>
<L N="1723">Predicessour of princes &middot; &amp; peree<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> pere.</NOTE> to &thorn;e sonn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e souerayne sire of my soyle &middot; &thorn;at sittis in my trone,</L>
<L>In fang with my faire godis &middot; &thorn;at I affie maste,</L>
<L>To Alexander, &thorn;at of all &middot; so augrily him letes,</L>
<L>Oure subiet &amp; oure seruand &middot; &thorn;us we oure-selfe write.<MILESTONE N="30a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For it is wayued vs to wete &middot; &thorn;at wickidly &thorn;ou haues,</L>
<L N="1729">&THORN;ur&yogh;e enmyte &amp; enuy &middot; elacion of pride,</L>
<L>Be vanyte &amp; vayne glori &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;i wayns kindlis,</L>
<L>Puruayd &thorn;e pletours &middot; oure partis to ride.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has samed, as men he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin: better omitted</I>.</NOTE> sais &middot; a selly nounbre</L>
<L N="1733">Of wrichis &amp; wirlingis &middot; out of &thorn;e west endis,</L>
<L>Of laddis &amp; of losengers &middot; &amp; of litill theuys,</L>
<L>Slike sary soro&yogh;is as &thorn;i-selfe &middot; to seke vs agaynes,</L>
<L>And wenes to wild all &thorn;i will &middot; &amp; &thorn;at worthis ful late,</L>
<L N="1737">&THORN;e prouynce &amp; principalte &middot; of Persye la graunt.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou ert fere al to faynt &middot; oure force to ministere;</L>
<L>&THORN;of &thorn;ou had gedird all &thorn;e gomes &middot; &thorn;at euire god fourmed,</L>
<L>So, man, riued is oure rewme &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou may re&yogh;t lycken</L>
<L>&THORN;e store strenthe of oure stoure &middot; to sternes of &thorn;e heuen.</L>
<L>And slike a nekard as &thorn;i-selfe &middot; a no&yogh;t of all othire,</L>
<L>Is bot a madding to mell &middot; with mare &thorn;an him-seluen.</L>
<L N="1744">Forthi is bettir vnbynd &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e brathe leue,</L>
<L>And feyne all with fairnes &middot; &amp; fayne at &thorn;ou may.</L>
<L>For mare menseke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So; for</I> menske.</NOTE> is a man &middot; to meke him be tyme,</L>
<L>&THORN;an eftir made to be meke &middot; malegreue his chekis.</L>
<L N="1748">For all &thorn;e gracious godis &middot; &amp; gudnes on erthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sanys sete &amp; soile &middot; &amp; sustaynes &thorn;e erth,</L>
<L>Prayses ay &thorn;e Persyns &middot; passing all othire,
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="98"></L>
<L N="1751">And for &thorn;e oddiste of ilka ost &middot; honoures oure name.</L>
<L>And slike a dwinyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dwinnyg.</NOTE> a dwa&yogh;e &middot; &amp; a dwer&yogh;e as &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>A grub, a grege out of grace &middot; ane erd-growyn sorowe,</L>
<L>Will couet &yogh;it as a king &middot; with caytefes to lyte,</L>
<L>To couir at combrid all &thorn;e kyngis &middot; vndire &thorn;e cape of heuen!</L>
<L N="1756">Ri&yogh;t as a flaw of fell snawe &middot; ware fallyn of a ryft,</L>
<L>Of a wysti wonn waghe &middot; with &thorn;e wynd blawen,<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So with a flote of Fresons &middot; folowand &thorn;i helis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sekis fraward Sichim &middot; &thorn;i-selfe wrothir-haile,</L>
<L N="1760">And leuys as a lorell &middot; &thorn;us oure lande to entire,</L>
<L>And maa &thorn;i lepis &amp; &thorn;i laikis &middot; &amp; quat &thorn;e liste ellis,</L>
<L>As ratons or ru&yogh;e myse &middot; in a rowme chambre,</L>
<L>Aboute in beddis or in bernys &middot; &thorn;are baddis ere nane.</L>
<L N="1764">Bot I haue wilily waited &middot; &thorn;i wiles &amp; &thorn;i castis,</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;ou hopis all-&thorn;ir hiest &middot; to haue all &thorn;ar will,</L>
<L>I sall &thorn;e sett on a saute &middot; &amp; sla &thorn;e [with] my handis.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1767">For-&thorn;i for pompe or for pride &middot; &thorn;i purpose a-vise,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Turne &thorn;e, trechoure, be-time &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou na treson haue,</L>
<L>And drawe a-gayn to &thorn;i den &middot; vndire &thorn;i dam wyngis.</L>
<L>Se quat I send to &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;i, <I>altered to</I> &thorn;e.</NOTE> son &middot; &thorn;i-selfe with to laike,</L>
<L N="1771">A hatt &amp; a hand-ball &middot; &amp; a herne-panne;</L>
<L>Slike presandis to play with &middot; as pertines to babbis.</L>
<L>For ai a child mot him chese &middot; to childire geris;</L>
<L>For mestire &amp; miserie &middot; vnneth may &thorn;ou forthe</L>
<L>&THORN;ine awen caitefe cors &middot; to clethe &amp; to fede,</L>
<L N="1776">And supposis as a sott &middot; to sese oure landis,</L>
<L>And outhire darius to drepe &middot; or dryfe fra his kythis!</L>
<L>Bot by &thorn;e grace &amp; &thorn;e gude &middot; &thorn;at god gaue my fadire,</L>
<L>So riued is &thorn;e rede gold &middot; oure regions with-in,</L>
<L N="1780">&THORN;at qua sa had it on a hepe &middot; haly to-gedire,
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>It wald vs let, as I leue &middot; &thorn;e li&yogh;t of &thorn;e son!</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i bid I &thorn;e badrich &middot; on bathe twa &thorn;ine e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e plegg &amp; &thorn;e payn &middot; &amp; perill as folowis,</L>
<L N="1784">All &thorn;i vanyte to voide &middot; &amp; &thorn;i vayne pride,</L>
<L>And mew agayn to Messedone &middot; or any mare fall.</L>
<L>For be &thorn;e saule of my sire &middot; bot if &thorn;ou sone turne,</L>
<L>We sall &thorn;e send sike a soume &middot; of segis en-armed,</L>
<L N="1788">No&yogh;t as Philips fant &middot; salle fare with &thorn;i-selfe,<MILESTONE N="31a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot as a prince of proued theues &middot; pyne &thorn;e to dede."</L>
<L>Als sone as his sandismen &middot; to &thorn;is sire come,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai present him &thorn;e playntis &middot; &thorn;e pistill him rechis,</L>
<L N="1792">And Alexander belyue &middot; be-fore all his princes,</L>
<L>To all his ost euyn on &middot; he openly declaris.</L>
<L>And quen his kni&yogh;tis of &thorn;is clause &middot; &thorn;e carpe vndirstode,</L>
<L>&THORN;en ware &thorn;ai frekly a-frayd &middot; of &thorn;e fell sa&yogh;es;</L>
<L N="1796">And as sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> him s; <I>but it is struck out</I>.</NOTE> as him-selfe sa&yogh;e &middot; his seggis amoued,</L>
<L>In bilding of his bachelers &middot; he breuys &thorn;ire wordis:</L>
<L>"Quat now? my worthi werriouris &middot; sa wi&yogh;t &amp; sa noble,</L>
<L>Mi bernes &amp; my baratours &middot; &thorn;e best vndire heuen;</L>
<L N="1800">Lettis neuire it bro&yogh;t be on brade &middot; for vpbraide of schame,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e doute for &thorn;e indityngs &middot; of Darius pistils.</L>
<L>I sett &yogh;owe ane ensample &middot; &yogh;e se it all daye,</L>
<L>In thorps &amp; in many thede &middot; &thorn;ar &yogh;e &thorn;ur&yogh;e ride,</L>
<L N="1804">At ilka cote a kene curre &middot; as he &thorn;e chache wald;</L>
<L>Bot as bremely as he baies<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> e <I>is above the line</I>.</NOTE> &middot; he bitis neuir &thorn;e fastir.</L>
<L>Bot in sum, I suppose wele &middot; &thorn;at sothe is &thorn;e lettir,</L>
<L>&THORN;are as he tellis quyche a tunne &middot; of tresoure he hauys.</L>
<L N="1808">For-&thorn;i vs buse to be bigg &middot; &amp; bataill him &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete garisons of gold &middot; sall gedire vp oure hertis."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at comands &thorn;e kyng &middot; his kny&yogh;tis be-lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e donesmen &thorn;at fra Darius come &middot; with &thorn;e derfe lettir,</L>
<L N="1812">&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld titly &thorn;am take &middot; &amp; by &thorn;e to&yogh;e throtis,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;aire souerayne sake &middot; &thorn;am send to &thorn;e galawis.
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;a messangers a-maied &middot; as mervale ware ellis,</L>
<L N="1815">With kene carefull crie &middot; &thorn;is conquirour &thorn;ai said:</L>
<L>"Allas! quat lake lyse in vs lord &middot; if it be &yogh;oure will,</L>
<L>&THORN;us causeles for oure kynge &middot; encumbird to worthe?"</L>
<L>"The sa&yogh;es of &yogh;our souerayn" &middot; said &thorn;e kynge &thorn;en,</L>
<L>"Nedis me to slike notis &middot; as I had neuer etlid,<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1820">&THORN;at has &yogh;ow sent to my-selfe &middot; no&yogh;t sa as him a&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Loo 'litill thefe' in ilka lyne &middot; his lettir me callis."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a," quod &thorn;ai, "comly kyng" &middot; &amp; on knes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. keies, <I>altered to</I> knes.</NOTE> fallis,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ase ditis endited to &yogh;owe &middot; sir Darius him-seluyn,</L>
<L N="1824">For he knew no&yogh;t of &yogh;our kni&yogh;thede &middot; ne of &yogh;our kid strenth;</L>
<L>Ne wist no&yogh;t of &yogh;our worthenes &middot; &amp; wrate all &thorn;e baldire.</L>
<L>Bot wald &yogh;e grant vs to gaa &middot; &amp; gefe vs &yogh;our lefe,</L>
<L>&THORN;en suld we bremely &yogh;our bill &middot; to &thorn;e berne shewe."</L>
<L N="1828">&THORN;en lete &thorn;e lord &thorn;am allane &middot; &amp; went till his fest,</L>
<L>Takis &thorn;am with him to his tent &middot; &amp; &thorn;am at ese makis.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;ai in his sale &middot; were sett at &thorn;e table,</L>
<L>"Sire Alexander, athill kyng" &middot; quod all with a steuyn,</L>
<L N="1832">"Comands with vs to caire &middot; kni&yogh;tis a thousand,</L>
<L>And we sall surely oure sire &middot; &thorn;e send in &thorn;aire handis."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, make we blis," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "blithe mote &yogh;e worthe,</L>
<L>For as for takynge of &yogh;our lord &middot; sall na lede wynde."</L>
<L N="1836">To Darius ano&thorn;ir day &middot; enditis he a pistill,</L>
<L>A crest clenly inclosid &middot; &thorn;at consayued &thorn;is wordis.</L>
<L>Alexander, &thorn;e aire &middot; &amp; eldest childe bathe</L>
<L>Of kyng Philip &thorn;e fers &middot; &thorn;e fendere of grece,</L>
<L N="1840">And als of Olimpades &middot; &thorn;at honurable lady,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, Darius, on dese &middot; &thorn;us dite I my lettir.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou prince of all &thorn;e Persyns &middot; &thorn;at peres to &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e conquirour of ilka cost &middot; callid of &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L N="1844">With all &thorn;i gracious godis &middot; graithid in &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L>All &thorn;us I send to &yogh;owe I my<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> sawe &middot; vndir my sele wreten.</L>
<L>Sire, if we se with a suth &middot; surely me thinke,
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>Oure facultes, oure faire fees &middot; oure fermes &amp; our landis,</L>
<L N="1848">We may no&yogh;t chalang &thorn;am ne clayme &middot; ne call &thorn;aim oure awen,</L>
<L>Bot all I deme it as det &middot; &amp; to a day borowid.<MILESTONE N="32a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For sen we riden on &thorn;e rime &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e ringe seten</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e qwele of Fortoun, &thorn;e quene &middot; &thorn;at swiftly changis,</L>
<L N="1852">Ofte pas we in pouert &middot; fra plente of gudis,</L>
<L>Fra mirthe in-to mournyng &middot; fra mournyng in-to Ioye.</L>
<L>For now vs wantis in a qwirre &middot; as &thorn;e quele turnes;</L>
<L>Quen we suppose in oure sele &middot; to sit al&thorn;ir heist,</L>
<L N="1856">&THORN;an fondis furth dame Fortoun &middot; to &thorn;e flode-&yogh;atis,</L>
<L>Dra&yogh;es vp &thorn;e damme-borde &middot; &amp; drenchis vs euire.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i a we &thorn;at has wit &middot; &thorn;ofe he wele suffir,</L>
<L N="1859">So sadly in soueraynete &middot; he set neuire his hope</L>
<L>For pride of na pro[s]perite &middot; ne prise at him folewis,</L>
<L>To olle ay on his vndireling &middot; for ouer-laike a quyle.</L>
<L>For any sele vndire son &middot; a sott I him hald,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay has deyne &amp; dispite &middot; at dedis of litill,</L>
<L N="1864">Sen oft &thorn;e hauenlest here &middot; is houen to &thorn;e sternes,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at graithist is of gudis &middot; gird all to poudire.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i a depe dishonoure &middot; &yogh;e do to &yogh;oure name,</L>
<L>Ane emperoure &thorn;at on erth &middot; is euyn to &yogh;oure-selfe,</L>
<L N="1868">To me sa litill &amp; sa lawe &middot; slike lettirs to sende,</L>
<L>And presand out of Persy &middot; bot for a pure hethyng.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou enherestis all &thorn;is erth &middot; &amp; euens to &thorn;e son,</L>
<L>And callis &thorn;e kyng of ilka kithe &middot; vndir &thorn;e cape of heuen,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto sittis, as &thorn;ou sais &middot; in sege as ane Aungell,</L>
<L N="1873">To-gedire with &thorn;i grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> with grete.</NOTE> gods &middot; and on a gilt trone.</L>
<L>Bot syn gostid godesses &amp; gods &middot; ere graythid neuir to dye,</L>
<L>Bot ai sall last furth elike &middot; on-lyue ouire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> euire.</NOTE> mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai naue no will to my notis &middot; ne wilnyng to haue,</L>
<L N="1877">No dole ne no daliance &middot; of dedely bernes.</L>
<L>Bot I knaw I am coruptible &middot; &amp; caire &yogh;ow agaynes,</L>
<L>Als with a dedly duke &middot; to do my bataill;
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Bot &thorn;ou &thorn;of; <I>but</I> &thorn;ou <I>is underlined</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ou &thorn;e victor a-vaile &middot; na vaunte sall arise,</L>
<L>Ne lose, bot as a litill thefe &middot; &yogh;ow limpid to encumbre.</L>
<L>Bot chance it me, &thorn;at am a childe &middot; &thorn;e cheuer to worthe,<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at be geuyn me &thorn;e gree &middot; grete glorie is myn awen.</L>
<L N="1884">For &thorn;an sall spring vp &thorn;e speche &middot; &amp; sprede out<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin</I>.</NOTE> of mynd,</L>
<L>How I haue conquired a kyng &middot; &thorn;e kidest of &thorn;e werd.</L>
<L>Bot a tale &yogh;e me tald &middot; I trow be na faile,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ryfenes of &thorn;e rede gold &middot; &yogh;our region with-in,</L>
<L N="1888">Quilke plente is in Persy &middot; of perell &amp; of ellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e somme of siluer &amp; of siche &middot; &amp; of sere stanes,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with oure wittes has &thorn;ou wele &middot; &amp; oure will sharpid,</L>
<L N="1891">And blid with &thorn;i besands &middot; &thorn;e bataille to &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>Made vs corageous &amp; kene &middot; &yogh;oure clere gold to wyn,</L>
<L>And put a-way oure pouert &middot; &yogh;e plede vs to hald.</L>
<L N="1894">Bot as touchand &thorn;e trufils &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e to me sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e herne-pan, &thorn;e hand-ball &middot; &thorn;e hatt made of twiggis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are has &thorn;ou prophesid apert &middot; &amp; playnely vs schewid,</L>
<L N="1897">And faire affirmed vs before &middot; &thorn;at sall fall eftir.</L>
<L>For by &thorn;e ball, sir, I breue &middot; all &thorn;e brode werd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erthe at to myne enpire &middot; enterely bees &yogh;olden.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e hat, &thorn;at is holewe &middot; be-for &thorn;e heued bowed,</L>
<L N="1901">I constru &thorn;at ilka kyng &middot; sall clyne to my-selfe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an hope I by &thorn;e hernepan &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e hede couirs,</L>
<L>Ouir-comers<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Ouir-comer.</NOTE> to be callid &middot; &amp; ouire-comen neuire.</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou, &thorn;e grettest vndir god &middot; graithis me trouage,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;is dignites be-dene &middot; &thorn;at I diuined haue."</L>
<L>&THORN;is brefe bedis &thorn;aim him bere &middot; &amp; besands &thorn;am rechis;</L>
<L>And eftir armes all his ost &middot; &amp; airis on eftir forthire.</L>
<L N="1908">Sire Darius for &thorn;e ditis &middot; nere died he for angire,</L>
<L>To twa of &thorn;e derrest of his dukis &middot; ditis he &thorn;is pistill:</L>
<L>"I, &thorn;e corounnest kyng &middot; of kyngis all othire,</L>
<L N="1911">To &thorn;e, sir primus, a prince &middot; of Persye &thorn;e grettest,<MILESTONE N="33a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And als to ser Antagoyne &middot; myn awen athill dukis,
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>&THORN;e soueraynest of my seniourie &middot; my saroparis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> satroparis; <I>see</I> l. 1937.</NOTE> hatten,</L>
<L>Se here I send &yogh;ow my seele &middot; with salutis of ioye.</L>
<L>Fra Alexander &thorn;e kyng &middot; as I am in-fourmed,</L>
<L N="1916">Is entrid with oure enmys &middot; an endles nounbre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Anglies of Asie &middot; &amp; has &thorn;am all stroyed,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i of life &amp; o lym &middot; my lege men I charge</L>
<L>To prestli &yogh;ow apparaill &middot; &amp; pas &thorn;am agaynes,</L>
<L N="1920">With all &thorn;e hathils &amp; &thorn;e heris &middot; &amp; &thorn;e hi&yogh;e maistris</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e may semble in &thorn;e sidis &middot; saudiours &amp; othire.</L>
<L>&THORN;en chese &yogh;ow furth my chiftanes &middot; &amp; me &thorn;e child take,</L>
<L>Laches me &thorn;is losengere &middot; &amp; ledis me him hedire,</L>
<L N="1924">&THORN;at I may him skelp with a skorge &middot; &amp; &thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;en &thorn;e; <I>but</I> &thorn;e <I>is struck out</I>.</NOTE> of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin</I>.</NOTE> skire porpure</L>
<L>A side slauyn him sewe &middot; &amp; send him to his modire;</L>
<L>For now he proches for pride &middot; &amp; propurly he wedis,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i him bose to be bett &middot; as a barne fallis.</L>
<L N="1928">For it<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> a&yogh;e no&yogh;t slik ane Asald &middot; nane abletus to off werres,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e bowlis as a brode &middot; or with a ball playe."</L>
<L>&THORN;ire princes, sone as &thorn;e pistill &middot; was put &thorn;am in hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;an part &thorn;ai &thorn;e proud sele &middot; &thorn;e printe &thorn;ai adhoured,</L>
<L N="1932">Vn-lappis li&yogh;tly &thorn;e lefe &middot; &amp; &thorn;e line redes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us-gate agynward &middot; &thorn;ai graithid him anothire.</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e kiddest kyng to a-count &middot; of kyngis all othire,</L>
<L>Sire Dari, with &thorn;i dere godis &middot; drised on &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L N="1936">Gouernoure of ilk a gome &middot; &amp; god all &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;i satrapairs, &thorn;i seniours &middot; with seruage obeschen:</L>
<L>Sire, wetis it wele, &yogh;oure worthines &middot; &amp; wenys it na langire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is child, with his chiftans &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e charge vs to take,</L>
<L N="1940">Has reden all oure regions &middot; &amp; raymed oure landis,</L>
<L>Departid all oure prouynce &middot; &amp; purely it wastid.<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And we &thorn;an lift vp a lite &middot; &amp; lent him a-gayne,</L>
<L N="1943">Ferd furth with a flote &middot; &amp; him in &thorn;e fyld metis;
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Bot sone we bed him &thorn;e bake &middot; &amp; besely<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp; hi besely.</NOTE> we shapid</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e handis vn-hewyn &middot; of oure hatill<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> hathill.</NOTE> fais.</L>
<L>And now haly all &thorn;e hepe &middot; at &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> &yogh;oure help callis,</L>
<L>Vn-to &yogh;oure mekill maieste &middot; we mekely beseke,</L>
<L N="1948">&THORN;at vs <I>&yogh;our</I> lege &amp; &yogh;oure lele men &middot; it likid &yogh;ow to forthire,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;an oure wirschip at-wynde &middot; &amp; wastid be &thorn;e regme."</L>
<L>As radly as &thorn;e riche kyng &middot; had red ouir &thorn;is pistill,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at mevis in A<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> Messangere &middot; &amp; maynly him tellis,</L>
<L N="1952">&THORN;at Alexander was at hand &middot; &amp; had his ost loygid</L>
<L>A-pon &thorn;e streme of Struma<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> u <I>is above the line.</I></NOTE> &middot; &thorn;at strekis &thorn;ur&yogh;e his landis.</L>
<L>Sire Darius for &thorn;a ditis &middot; was depely a-greuyd,</L>
<L>Callis him his consail &middot; a clause he him enditis,</L>
<L N="1956">Mas a brefe at a braide &middot; &amp; it in brathe sendis,</L>
<L>To Alexander as be-lyue &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us him gretes.</L>
<L>&para; "I, sir Dari, &thorn;e deyne &middot; &amp; derfe Emperoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of kyngis I am callid &middot; &amp; conquirour bathe,</L>
<L N="1960">Of all lordis &thorn;e lord &middot; a-lose<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> alosed.</NOTE> &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>And ane of &thorn;e souerayne sires &middot; vndir &thorn;e vij sternes,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, my seruand, I send &middot; &amp; suthely &thorn;ou knawes,</L>
<L>And wete &thorn;ou wele &thorn;ur&yogh;e all &thorn;e werde &middot; is wirschip oure name.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. namo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1964">For all &thorn;e gracious gods &middot; at &thorn;e ground visitis,</L>
<L>All ere done me to doute &middot; ducsses<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So</I> (<I>or</I> ducsses) <I>in</I> MS.</NOTE> &amp; othire.</L>
<L>How burde &thorn;e &thorn;an be sa bald &middot; for blod in &thorn;i heued,</L>
<L N="1967">To moue &thorn;us ouir &thorn;e mountey[n]s &middot; &amp; ouir &thorn;e many watirs</L>
<L>With slike a soumme ouir &thorn;e see &middot; a saute vs to &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>Or any maistrie to make &middot; my maieste a-gayne?</L>
<L>For wella<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> wide ware &thorn;e wele &middot; wete &thorn;ou na nothire,<MILESTONE N="34a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1971">Bathe &thorn;i glorie &amp; &thorn;i grace &middot; &thorn;i gladnes in erthe,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou &thorn;e marches of Messedoyne &middot; mayntene &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>And gouerne bot &thorn;ine awen gronde &middot; agaynes oure<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inserted in the margin.</I></NOTE> will.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i ware bettir vnbynde &middot; or &thorn;ou bale suffire,</L>
<L>Remowe agayne to &thorn;i rewme &middot; &amp; rew of &thorn;i werkis.</L>
<L>For certayne, nyf my seniourie &middot; ne I my-selfe nouthire,</L>
<L N="1977">All &thorn;e werd my&yogh;t a wedowe &middot; wele &thorn;an be callid.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i turne &thorn;e be-time &middot; or any tene worthe,</L>
<L>Or at &thorn;e hate of my hert &middot; a-pon &thorn;i hede kindill.</L>
<L>Lend agayn to &thorn;i lande &middot; nowe quen &thorn;ou leue hauys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I mete &thorn;e in my malicoly &middot; my meth be to littill.</L>
<L N="1982">For-&thorn;i to ken &thorn;e to knaw &middot; my kyndnes here-eftir,</L>
<L>Bath my grace &amp; my glori &middot; &amp; my grete strenthe,</L>
<L>Loo here a gloue full of graynes &middot; I graythe &thorn;e to take,</L>
<L N="1985">Of &thorn;e chesses of a chesboll &middot; chosen for &thorn;e nanys.</L>
<L>For may &thorn;ou sowme me &thorn;ire sedis &middot; surely &thorn;ou trowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;t a-count all oure kni&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; oure kyd ostis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou truches &thorn;aim to tell &middot; &thorn;en tidis &thorn;e na no&thorn;ir,</L>
<L>Bot move a-gayn to Messedone &middot; &amp; meve<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. me, <I>altered to</I> meve.</NOTE> &thorn;e na forthire.</L>
<L N="1990">Fyne, fole, of &thorn;i fare &middot; &amp; fange to &thorn;i kythis;</L>
<L>For &thorn;is sede I &thorn;e send &middot; vnsowmyd bees neuire.</L>
<L>So ere we of all folke &middot; folke to be nombrid,</L>
<L N="1993">Or any wee to a-counte &middot; vndire &thorn;e clere sternys."</L>
<L>Now aires furth his athill men &middot; to Alexander wendis,</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e streme of struma &middot; stre&yogh;t with &thorn;a lettirs,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;am redis in a rese &middot; &amp; reches to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e sedis,</L>
<L N="1997">Tastis &thorn;am vndire his tuthe &middot; &amp; talkis &thorn;ir wordis:<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Here I se," quod &thorn;is sire &middot; "be &thorn;ire ilke cornes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pupill out of Persy &middot; ere passandly many,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. meke many; <I>but</I> meke <I>is struck out</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2000">Bot &thorn;am semes to be softe &middot; as &thorn;ir sedis prouys;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i how fele be all &thorn;e flote &middot; it forces bot littill."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is was men of Messedone &middot; fra his modire comen,</L>
<L>And said &thorn;at semely was seke &middot; &amp; semed to die;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;e waest of &thorn;e werd &middot; wald worth hire to visite,</L>
<L N="2005">Bot &yogh;it to Dary, or he went &middot; he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. his, <I>altered to</I> he.</NOTE> di&yogh;t &thorn;us a lettir.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000119.tif" N="97">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1720"><B>Syr Dere Darius on dese &middot; &thorn;e digne Emperour,</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola darij.</NOTE></L>
<L><B>The</B> kyng withowt comparison &middot; of kyngez all o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Of al lordes &thorn;e Lord &middot; &thorn;at leues in erthe,<MILESTONE N="17a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Predecessour of princez &middot; &amp; peir to &thorn;e Son,</L>
<L>The souerane syre of my sole &middot; &thorn;at sittis in myne trone,</L>
<L N="1725">In fange with my faire god &middot; &thorn;at I affye maste,</L>
<L>To Alexander, &thorn;at of all &middot; so augerdly hym letes,</L>
<L>Oure seget &amp; our siruant<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. souerent siruant; <I>the former word expuncted.</I></NOTE> &middot; &thorn;us our-selfe writtez.</L>
<L N="1728">For it is wayfed vs to wete &middot; &thorn;ou haues wikedly,</L>
<L>Thrugh enmyte &amp; enuye &middot; Elacion of pride,</L>
<L>Be vanyte &amp; vaynglory &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;i vaynes kyndeles,</L>
<L>Purvayd &thorn;e pletours &middot; oure partez to ryde.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hase sampned, als men sayn &middot; a sellich nowmbre</L>
<L N="1733">Off wrechez &amp; of wyrlyngez &middot; out of &thorn;e west ende,</L>
<L>Off laddez &amp; of losyngers &middot; &amp; of lityll thefez,</L>
<L>Siche sary sorowez as &thorn;i-self &middot; to seke vs agayns,</L>
<L>And wenys to weld at &thorn;i wille &middot; &thorn;at worthez full late,</L>
<L N="1737">The prouince &amp; &thorn;e principalite &middot; of perse le graunt.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou ert fere all to faynte &middot; oure force to withstonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Of.</NOTE> &thorn;ou hade gederit<NOTE PLACE="foot">it <I>written above the line.</I></NOTE> all &thorn;e gomez &middot; &thorn;at euer god formede,</L>
<L>So, man, ryfe is owr reme &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou may wele lekyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e sture strenth of owr stoure &middot; to &thorn;e sternez of heuen;</L>
<L>And sike a neker als &thorn;i selfe &middot; ane noght of all o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Is bot<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bod.</NOTE> a maddyng to mell &middot; with mare &thorn;en &thorn;i-selue.</L>
<L N="1744">For-&thorn;i is better vnbende &middot; &amp; of &thorn;i brathe leue,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>For mare menske is a man &middot; to meke hym be tyme,</L>
<L>Than after made to be meke &middot; mawgre hys chekys.</L>
<L N="1748">For all &thorn;e graciouse goddes &middot; &amp; goddesse on erth,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1750">Praysez ay &thorn;e persens &middot; passyng all o&thorn;er,
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And for &thorn;e oddest of ilke one oste &middot; honours owr name.</L>
<L N="1752">And slyke a dwynyng &middot; a drawgh of &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L>A grob, a grig out of grece &middot; ane erth-growen sorow,</L>
<L>Wyll couett &yogh;itte as a kyng &middot; with catyffez litell,</L>
<L>To couer &amp; to combre all &thorn;e kyngez &middot; vnder &thorn;e Cape of heuen!</L>
<L N="1756">Right as a flaw of fell snaw &middot; fallen wer fro &thorn;e drifte,</L>
<L>Of a wistus wondyn wagh &middot; with &thorn;e wynd blayn,</L>
<L>So with a flote of fresons &middot; folowand thi heles,</L>
<L>Thu sekys fraward sychim &middot; &thorn;i-selue with euell haille,</L>
<L N="1760">And Leues as a losell &middot; owr land for to entre,<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And make &thorn;i lepys &amp; &thorn;i lakez &middot; &amp; qwat &thorn;ou list ellys,</L>
<L>As ratons or ronke myce &middot; in a rowme chaumbre,</L>
<L>About on beddes or in bernez &middot; &thorn;ar baddez er nane.</L>
<L N="1764">Bott I haue willyly wayted &middot; &thorn;i wilez &amp; &thorn;i castez,</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ou hopys all-&thorn;ir eldest &middot; to haue at &thorn;ou likez,</L>
<L N="1766">I sall &thorn;e sett on a sawte &middot; &amp; slaye &thorn;e with my handez,</L>
<L N="1766*">And so sall, fole, for &thorn;i folez &middot; be fenyshit on dawes.</L>
<L N="1767">For &thorn;i pompe &amp; &thorn;i pride &middot; &thorn;i purpasse avyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to avyse; <I>but</I> to <I>is better omitted.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1767*">For yf &thorn;ou shote ouer-sheet &middot; &thorn;ou shendes &thorn;i flayne.</L>
<L N="1768">Turne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. To me <I>wrongly.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e, trechour, be tyme &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou no treson hable,</L>
<L>And [drawe] agayn to &thorn;i den &middot; vnder &thorn;i dame wengez.</L>
<L>Se qwat I sende &thorn;e, son &middot; &thorn;i-selfe with to layke,</L>
<L>A hatt here &amp; a hand-balle &middot; &amp; a herne-panne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. payne, <I>corrected to</I> panne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1772">Slike presantes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. presandez presantes.</NOTE> to play with &middot; as pertenys &thorn;e to haue.</L>
<L>For ay a childe most hym chose &middot; vnto childer gammez;</L>
<L>For mister &amp; for michefe &middot; vneth may &thorn;ou forth</L>
<L>&THORN;ine awne catef cors &middot; to cloth &amp; to fede,</L>
<L N="1776">And &yogh;it supposes as A sott &middot; to sesyn owr Landez,</L>
<L>And Darius to drepe &middot; &amp; dryve owt of hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">lys, <I>corrected to</I> hys.</NOTE> kythes!</L>
<L>Bot be &thorn;e grace &amp; &thorn;e goode &middot; &thorn;at god gafe my fader,</L>
<L>So ryfe is &thorn;e rede gold &middot; oure regions within,</L>
<L N="1780">At who so had it on a hepe &middot; holy to-gedre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to gredre.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>It wald hym lett, as I leue &middot; &thorn;e light of &thorn;e Son!</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i bid I &thorn;e badly &middot; vppon payn of &thorn;i eghen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. eughen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And on &thorn;e plight &amp; payn &middot; &amp; perle &thorn;at folows,</L>
<L N="1784">All &thorn;i vanyte to voyde &middot; &amp; &thorn;i vayn pryde,</L>
<L>And mefe ayayn to masydon &middot; or ony mare falle.</L>
<L>For, be &thorn;e sawle of my sire &middot; bot yf &thorn;ou sone turne,</L>
<L N="1787">I sall send &thorn;e suche a sume &middot; of segges enarmed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noght as philip faunt &middot; &thorn;ou sall fare with &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L>Bot as a prince reproued &middot; sall be pynyd to dede."</L>
<L>Als sone as euer hys sondesmen &middot; to &thorn;is syre commyn,</L>
<L>Thai present hym playnly &middot; &amp; &thorn;at pistill hym rechys,</L>
<L N="1792">And alexander als byliue &middot; before hys atell<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> princez,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e host euen ouer &middot; it opynly declares.<MILESTONE N="18a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And when &thorn;e knyghtez &middot; of &thorn;is clause vnderstonde,</L>
<L>Than wer &thorn;ai felly<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fellyd.</NOTE> affrayed &middot; of hys fell sawes;</L>
<L N="1796">And als sone as hym-selfe se &middot; hys seges ameyved,</L>
<L>In beldyng of hys bachelers &middot; he breues &thorn;ees wordes:</L>
<L>"What now? my worthy weryours &middot; so wight &amp; so noble,</L>
<L>My bernes &amp; my barotours &middot; &thorn;e best vnder heuen;</L>
<L N="1800">Lett neuer it be broght on brade &middot; for vmbrayd of shame,</L>
<L>Yhe dout for &thorn;e dityng &middot; of darius pistell.</L>
<L>I sett you an ensaumple &middot; ye se it euerilke day,</L>
<L>In thorpus &amp; in mony thede &middot; &thorn;are ye &thorn;orow ryden,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dyden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1804">. . . . .</L>
<L>For yf he bremely bays &middot; he bitez neuer helder.</L>
<L>Bot in some way, I suppose wele &middot; &thorn;at soght is hys lettre,</L>
<L>&THORN;air as he tellez which tunne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. tyme.</NOTE> &middot; of tresour he hase.</L>
<L N="1808">For-&thorn;i vs [bus] to be big &middot; &amp; batele hym &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete garison of gold &middot; sall geder vp owr hertes."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at commandez &thorn;e kyng &middot; hys knyghtez belyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are Domesmen &thorn;at from darius come &middot; with &thorn;e derfe lettrez,</L>
<L N="1812">&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld titely &thorn;aim take &middot; &amp; be to&yogh;e nekez,</L>
<L>For &thorn;air souerend sake &middot; &thorn;aim send to &thorn;e galouse.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>&THORN;en wer &thorn;ees messyngers amaced &middot; as mervell wer ellez,</L>
<L>With carfull chere &middot; to &thorn;e conquerour &thorn;ai saydyn:</L>
<L N="1816">"Alas! what lake lyes in vs &middot; lord, be your lefe,</L>
<L>Thus causles for owr kyng &middot; encombred to worthe?"</L>
<L>"The sawez of your soueren" &middot; sayd &thorn;e kyng &thorn;en,</L>
<L>"Nedes me now to seche notes &middot; as I neuer attelytt,</L>
<L N="1820">That he hase sent to my-seluen &middot; noght as he awght;</L>
<L>Lo! 'lityll thefe' in iche line &middot; hys lettre me calles."</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>"&THORN;is doyngez sir darius &middot; indited you hym-seluen,</L>
<L N="1824">For he knew noght your knyghthode &middot; ne your kyd strenthez;</L>
<L>Ne wist noght of yowr worthiness &middot; &amp; wrote all &thorn;e balder.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e wald graunt vs to go &middot; &amp; gyfe vs owr lyfez,</L>
<L>Than suld we bremely your blysse &middot; vnto &thorn;e berne shewe."</L>
<L>&THORN;an lete &thorn;e Lord &thorn;aim alon &middot; &amp; lathys &thorn;aim to hys feste,</L>
<L>Takes &thorn;aim with hym to hys tent &middot; &amp; makez &thorn;aim at ease.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;ees sandesmen in sale &middot; wer sett at &thorn;e table,<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Sir alexander, atell kyng" &middot; quod all with a stevyn,</L>
<L N="1832">"Comand with vs to care &middot; knyghtez a thowsand,</L>
<L>And we sall surely owr syre &middot; you send in &thorn;air handez."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, make &yogh;e blysse," quod &thorn;e kynge &middot; "blyth mote &yogh;e worthe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lachynge of your Lorde &middot; sall noght a lede weynde."</L>
<L N="1836">Bot to Darius on &thorn;at o&thorn;er day &middot; indited he a pistell,</L>
<L>A lettre clenly enclosyt &middot; &thorn;at consaued &thorn;ees wordes.</L>
<L><B>"I, alexander, ayr &middot; &amp; eldeste childe bothe</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of kyng philip &thorn;e ferse &middot; &thorn;e fender of grece,</L>
<L N="1840">And als of olimphades &middot; &thorn;at honorable ladye,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, sir Darius, on dese &middot; &thorn;us dite I my lettre.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou prince of all persens &middot; &thorn;at apperys to &thorn;e son,</L>
<L>The conquerour of ilke coste &middot; callyd of &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L N="1844">With all &thorn;i graciouse goddes &middot; grathed in &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L>All &thorn;us I send &thorn;ow to say &middot; vnder my sealle wrytten.</L>
<L>Sir, yf we se &thorn;e sothe &middot; surely me thynke,
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>Our facultez or faire feys &middot; owr fermez &amp; owre goldes,</L>
<L N="1848">We may noght chalynge &thorn;aim ne clame &middot; ne calle &thorn;aim our awne,</L>
<L>Bot all I deme as dett &middot; vnto a day borowed.</L>
<L>For yff we ryde on &thorn;i reme &middot; &amp; on &thorn;i renke settyn</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e whele of forton &amp; &thorn;e whene &middot; &thorn;at whistely chaungez,</L>
<L N="1852">Of[t] passe we in-to pouerte &middot; fro plente of godez,</L>
<L>Fro mirthe into murnyng &middot; fro murnyng into Ioy.</L>
<L>For now vs vantes in a whirre &middot; as &thorn;e whele chaungez;</L>
<L>When we supposye in howre-selfe &middot; to sitte all-&thorn;ar heldest,</L>
<L N="1856">&THORN;en fonndez doun dame forton &middot; to &thorn;e flode-&yogh;ates,</L>
<L>Drawez vp &thorn;e dame-borde &middot; &amp; drenchez vs for euer.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i a wye &thorn;at hase witte &middot; of &thorn;e whele sofre,</L>
<L>So<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. So doys he so sodandly; <I>of which</I> doys he <I>is subpuncted</I>.</NOTE> sodandly in hys souerente &middot; to sett neron<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.; <I>for</I> neuer on.</NOTE> hys hope</L>
<L N="1860">For pride of no prosperite &middot; ne prise at hym folowez,</L>
<L>To olle ay on hys vnderlinges &middot; for ouerlayke a while.</L>
<L>For ony ceyle vnder heven &middot; a sot I hym halde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay hase dene &amp; dispyte &middot; of dedes of lityll,</L>
<L N="1864">Syon oft &thorn;e haslokst her &middot; is heuen to &thorn;e sternes,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;, <I>with</I> ht <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> grethest was of goddez &middot; gird all to-geder.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i a depe disHonor &middot; yhe do to your Name,<MILESTONE N="19a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ane Emperour &thorn;at on &thorn;is erth &middot; is euen to your-seluen,</L>
<L N="1868">To me so lityll &amp; so lawe &middot; such lettres to wayfe,</L>
<L>And presentes owt of perse &middot; bot for a pure hethinge.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou inheretes all &thorn;is werld &middot; &amp; euens vnto &thorn;e sun,</L>
<L>And calles &thorn;e kyng of ilke kyth &middot; vnder &thorn;e cape of heuen,</L>
<L N="1872">And &thorn;arto sittes as &thorn;ou says &middot; in sege as an angell,</L>
<L>To-gedre with &thorn;i grett goddez &middot; on a gilt trone.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1876">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>I knaw I am corruptible &middot; &amp; caire &thorn;ow agayns,</L>
<L>Als a dedlich duk &middot; to do my batell;
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="107"></L>
<L N="1880">Bot if &thorn;ou &thorn;e victour availe &middot; no vaunt sall &thorn;ar rise,</L>
<L>No lose, bot of a lityll thef &middot; enlympyd you to combre.</L>
<L>Bot chaunce it me, &thorn;at I am childe &middot; &thorn;e cheuer to worth,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at if be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be, <I>written above the line</I>.</NOTE> gefyn me &thorn;e gre &middot; grete glory is my awne.</L>
<L N="1884">For &thorn;an sall springe vp &thorn;e speche &middot; &amp; sprede owt of mynde,</L>
<L>How at I haue Conquired a king &middot; &thorn;e kyddest of &thorn;e werld.</L>
<L>Bot one tale &yogh;e me tald &middot; I trowe be no fable,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e refuse of rede gold &middot; your regions within,</L>
<L N="1888">Which plente is in perse &middot; of perle &amp; of ellys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e some of siluer &amp; of siche &middot; &amp; of sere stones,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar-with owr willes er replete &middot; &amp; our wittes sharped,</L>
<L>And baldit vs with &thorn;i besaundez &middot; &thorn;e batell to byd,</L>
<L N="1892">Made vs coragiouse &amp; kene &middot; &thorn;i clere gold to wynne,</L>
<L>And put away our pouerte &middot; yhe pledyn vs to hald.</L>
<L>Bot as tochand &thorn;e trufels &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e to me send,</L>
<L>&THORN;e herne-payn, &thorn;e hand-balle &middot; &thorn;e hat made of twygges,</L>
<L>&THORN;air hase &thorn;ou prophecied apert &middot; &amp; playnly vs schewed,</L>
<L N="1897">And fair enformed vs before &middot; &thorn;at falle sall after.</L>
<L>For be &thorn;e bale, sir, I breue &middot; all &thorn;e brode werld,</L>
<L N="1899">The erth &thorn;at to myne empire &middot; entirely is &yogh;holden.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e hatte, &thorn;at is holys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> holow.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; before &thorn;e heued<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. heuend; <I>but see l.</I> 1902.</NOTE> bo&yogh;et,</L>
<L>I Constrew &thorn;at iche kyng &middot; sall incline to my-seluen.</L>
<L>&THORN;an hope I, be &thorn;e harnepanne &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e heued Couers,</L>
<L>Ouercommer to be callyd &middot; &amp; ouercomyn neuer.</L>
<L N="1904">Now &thorn;e gretest vnder god &middot; gyfes me truage,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;ar dignitez be-dene &middot; &thorn;at deuised I Haue."</L>
<L>THys brefe he biddez &thorn;aim Bere &middot; &amp; besaundes &thorn;aim reches;<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And aftyr armes hys oste &middot; &amp; ayres on forther.</L>
<L N="1908">Sir darius for &thorn;is detes &middot; nere dyes for sorow,</L>
<L>And to two &thorn;e derrest of hys dukes &middot; ditez he &thorn;is pistell:</L>
<L>"I, Coroundest kyng &middot; of kyngez all o&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e, sir Priamus, a prince &middot; of &thorn;e gretest perse,</L>
<L N="1912">And also to &thorn;e, sir antigon &middot; myne awne athell dukes,
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>The soueranest of my senory &middot; my satrapers halden,</L>
<L>Se here I send &thorn;ou my sealle &middot; with salutes of Ioy.</L>
<L>For alexander the kynge &middot; as I am informed,</L>
<L N="1916">Is entred with owr enmys &middot; ane endles nowmbre,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e anglez of asy &middot; &amp; hase &thorn;aim all stroyde,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i on life &amp; on lymez &middot; my legemen I charge</L>
<L>To pristly &thorn;ou apperale &middot; &amp; passe hym agayns,</L>
<L N="1920">With all &thorn;e hatellys &amp; &thorn;e herez &middot; &amp; &thorn;e hye maisters</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e may assemble on &thorn;ai sydez &middot; saugeours &amp; o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Chesse &thorn;ou forth chiftanez &middot; &amp; me &thorn;is childe takes,</L>
<L>Laches me &thorn;is losynger &middot; &amp; ledes me hym heder,</L>
<L N="1924">And [I] sall hym skelp with a scourge &middot; &amp; &thorn;en in skyre purpure</L>
<L>A syde slauyn hym insew &middot; &amp; send hym hys modre;</L>
<L>For now he prokes for pride &middot; &amp; p[ro]prely wodez,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i he must be bett &middot; as a barne falles.</L>
<L N="1928">Bot it aught noght suche brolle &middot; in none armez of werez,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e bulez as a brode &middot; or with a bale to play."</L>
<L>&THORN;ire princez, when &thorn;is pistell &middot; was putt &thorn;aim in hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai departyd &thorn;e prowde sealle &middot; &thorn;e printe &thorn;ai honour,</L>
<L N="1932">And vnlappyd lightly &thorn;e leffe &middot; &amp; &thorn;e lines redyn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us agaynward &middot; &thorn;[a]i grathed hym one o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e kyng to acount<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. acoaunt. <I>The MS. has a tag to the final letter of</I> acoaunt.</NOTE> &middot; of all kyngez on erth,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Dary with &thorn;i dere goddez &middot; dressyd in trone,</L>
<L N="1936">Gouernour<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Geuernour.</NOTE> of ilke grome &middot; &amp; god all &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L>&THORN;i satrapers, &thorn;i senyowrs &middot; with seruyce obidiens:</L>
<L>Sir, wetes it your worthynes &middot; &amp; wenys no langer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is childe with hys chiftanys &middot; &yogh;e charge vs to take,</L>
<L N="1940">He hase riden all your regions &middot; &amp; raymet owr landez,</L>
<L>Desperset all our prouince &middot; &amp; purely distroyde.</L>
<L>And we &thorn;en liften vp a lite &middot; &amp; rydyn hym ayayns,</L>
<L N="1943">Ferd forth with a folke &middot; &amp; hym in &thorn;e feld metyn;<MILESTONE N="20a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="111"></L>
<L N="1944">Bot sone wer bidden &thorn;aim &thorn;e bake &middot; &amp; besely echapyn</L>
<L>Owt of handez to &thorn;e swerde &middot; mony of owr athelles.</L>
<L>And we now haly all &thorn;e hepe &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e your helpe callyn,</L>
<L>Vnto your mykle mageste &middot; we mekely besekyn,</L>
<L N="1948">&THORN;at vs your lege &amp; your lele men &middot; it liked &yogh;ou to forther,</L>
<L>For owr worship is weynd &middot; &amp; wasted is owr remes."</L>
<L>And als radely as &thorn;e ryche kyng &middot; had red ouer &thorn;e pistell,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at mefys in a messynger &middot; &amp; manyly hym tellys,</L>
<L N="1952">&THORN;at alexander was at hand &middot; &amp; hed an hoste loget</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e streme of streuma &middot; &thorn;at straughit &thorn;orow &thorn;e land.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sir dary for &thorn;oe dedes &middot; was deply agrevyd,</L>
<L>Callys hys counsell &middot; a clause he inditez,</L>
<L N="1956">Makez a breue in a brayde &middot; &amp; in a breth sendes,</L>
<L>To alexander als belyue &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us hym gretes.</L>
<L><B>"I, Sir Dary &thorn;e digne &middot; &amp; derfe Emperour,</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola darij.</NOTE></L>
<L>The king of kyngez am called &middot; &amp; conquerour bath,</L>
<L N="1960">Of all Lordes Lord &middot; lowsed &thorn;orow &thorn;e werld,</L>
<L>And one of &thorn;e souerenest syres &middot; vndir &thorn;e seuen sternes,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, my siruand, I send &middot; &amp; sothly I knaw,</L>
<L>And wete &thorn;ou wele all &thorn;e werld &middot; worshippys my name.</L>
<L N="1964">For all &thorn;e gracieux goddez &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e ground viseten,</L>
<L>All er vndir my obedience &middot; dredles I telle.</L>
<L>How durst &thorn;ou be so bald &middot; for blode in &thorn;i heued,</L>
<L>To mefe &thorn;us ouer &thorn;ees montannez &middot; &amp; &thorn;es mony waters</L>
<L N="1968">With syke a soume for to seke &middot; a sawt vs to &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>Or ony maistre to make &middot; my mageste ayayns?</L>
<L>For wele wyde wer &thorn;i wele &middot; wete &thorn;ou none other,</L>
<L N="1971">Both &thorn;i glory &amp; grace &middot; &thorn;i gladnesse in erth,</L>
<L>Might &thorn;ou &thorn;e marche of masidon &middot; mayntene &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L>And gouern &thorn;ine awen grund &middot; agayns owr wyll.
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i it wer better vnbenden &middot; or &thorn;ou bale suffre,</L>
<L>Remefe agayn to &thorn;i realm &middot; or &thorn;ou sall it rewe.</L>
<L N="1976">For certan, yf my senory &middot; &amp; my-selue ne wer,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e werld might albido<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> a wido.</NOTE> &middot; wele &thorn;en be called.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i turne &thorn;e be-tyme &middot; or ony tene worth,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e hate of my hert &middot; on &thorn;i heued kyndle.</L>
<L N="1980">Lend Agayn to &thorn;i Land &middot; Will I Leue gefe &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou mete with my malicoly &middot; &thorn;i might be to lityll.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i to ken &thorn;e to knawe &middot; my kyngdome her-after,</L>
<L>Both my glory &amp; my grace &middot; &amp; my grete strenth,</L>
<L N="1984">Lo, her a glofe full of granes &middot; I grath &thorn;e to rekyn,</L>
<L>Off &thorn;e chefest of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. oft.</NOTE> chessebollez &middot; chosyn for &thorn;e nonest.</L>
<L>For and &thorn;ou may soume &thorn;ees sedes &middot; seurly &thorn;ou leue,</L>
<L>Thu may acount<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. acoaunt; <I>see l.</I> 1993.</NOTE> all owr knyghtez &middot; &amp; owr kyd ostez;</L>
<L>And yf &thorn;ou thynkes &thorn;aim to tell &middot; &thorn;en tydez &thorn;e none o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="1989">To mefe agayn to masidon &middot; &amp; mell &thorn;e no forther.</L>
<L>Fyne, fole, of &thorn;i fare &middot; and fange to &thorn;i kythes;</L>
<L>For as &thorn;is sede &thorn;at I send &middot; vnsoumed is euer,</L>
<L N="1992">So ben we of all<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I> ben we of all fo, <I>crossed through</I>.</NOTE> frekes &middot; &amp; folkez vnnowmyrd,</L>
<L>Or ony weght to acount &middot; vnder &thorn;e clere welkyn."</L>
<L>Now ayres forth &thorn;ees messyngers &middot; &amp; to alexander wendyn,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e streme of struma &middot; streght with &thorn;is lettres,</L>
<L N="1996">And &thorn;aim redes on a rase he &middot; &amp; rechez to &thorn;e sedes,</L>
<L>Castes &thorn;aim vnder his tothe &middot; &amp; talkys &thorn;ees wordes:</L>
<L>"Here I see," quod &thorn;is sire &middot; "be &thorn;ir selue cornes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e peple out of perse &middot; er passandly mony,</L>
<L N="2000">Bot &thorn;aim semys to be softe &middot; as &thorn;ees sedis preuez;</L>
<L>And &thorn;en how fele be all &thorn;e flote &middot; it forcez bot lityll."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at was men of masidon &middot; fro hys moder commyn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at semely was seke &middot; &amp; semyd to die;</L>
<L N="2004">And he &thorn;e woest of &thorn;e werld &middot; wald for hir to visytt,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it to Darius or he di&yogh;t &middot; he ditez suche a pistyll.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="9" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000136.tif" N="114">
<HEAD><B>Nonus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alexsaundere &thorn;e athill &middot; aire oute [of] grece,</L>
<L>&THORN;e son of Ph[ilip] &thorn;e fers &middot; &amp; of his faire lady,</L>
<L N="2008">Honoured Olimpadas &middot; &thorn;e oddest vndire heuyn,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, ser Dari, on &thorn;i dese &middot; &thorn;is dities I write.</L>
<L>For I am sent, be &thorn;e sure &middot; many sere letters,</L>
<L>And namly now on newe time &middot; fra myne awen kith,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e marche of Messadone &middot; &thorn;at mekill me greues,</L>
<L N="2013">All o&thorn;er wais to wirke &middot; &amp; my will likis.</L>
<L>Bot I warne &thorn;e, or I wynd &middot; &amp; will at &thorn;ou knaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for na drede I with-draw &middot; ne doute of &thorn;i pride,</L>
<L N="2016">For baisting of &thorn;i bobance &middot; ne of &thorn;i breme wordis,</L>
<L>Bot for to se &thorn;at is seke &middot; my semely modire.</L>
<L>Bot wete &thorn;ou wele &thorn;is, I-wis &middot; with-in a wale time,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at I fraist haue &thorn;at faire &middot; of my fayre lady,</L>
<L N="2020">I sall &thorn;e seke with a sowme &middot; of seggis enarmed,</L>
<L>Ane ost to noy &thorn;us to neuyn &middot; all of new kny&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e sake of &thorn;i sede &middot; &thorn;ou sent with &thorn;i lettre,</L>
<L>Loo, here a purse full of pepire &middot; my powere to ken,<MILESTONE N="35a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2024">To se &thorn;i-selfe a similitude &middot; how all &thorn;i soft grayns</L>
<L>Sall vndire-put be all &thorn;e pake &middot; vn-to &thorn;ir peper-cornes."</L>
<L>&THORN;is pistill to Persyns &middot; he with his pepir takis,</L>
<L N="2027">Partis prestly &thorn;am to &middot; many proude gittis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai haue la&yogh;t &thorn;am &thorn;ar leue &middot; &amp; &thorn;e lettir fangis,</L>
<L>And passis on to Persy &middot; &thorn;e princes to schewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander belyue &middot; with his athill dukis,</L>
<L N="2031">Rais him radly to ride &middot; &amp; remowis his ost;</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e streme of struma he stre&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; still mournes,</L>
<L>And mevis him toward Messedone &middot; his modir to visit.</L>
<L>He aires &thorn;ur&yogh;e Arabie &middot; &amp; armed &thorn;ar he findis</L>
<L>A duke of Darys &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;at drafe him agayne,</L>
<L N="2036">A pere out of Persy &middot; &amp; prince of his ost,</L>
<L>A maister man in &thorn;a marches &middot; Amont was hatten.</L>
<L>He girdis him with a ging &middot; &thorn;e grekis he asailes.
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>With Alexander all day &middot; asperly fe&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="2040">Marres of &thorn;e Messedons &middot; mi&yogh;tfull kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Dingis doun of &thorn;e dukis &middot; deris &thorn;am vn-faire,</L>
<L>Fra morne to &thorn;e mirke ni&yogh;t &middot; maynly &thorn;a cocken,</L>
<L N="2043">Se&yogh;es doun on aythire side &middot; segis out of nounbre.</L>
<L>Begynnys sone in &thorn;e gray day &middot; as any gleme springis,</L>
<L>And so to sett of &thorn;e son &middot; sesid &thorn;ai neuire.</L>
<L>&THORN;us thre dais out a thraw &middot; &thorn;ai threp ay elike;</L>
<L N="2047">So lange, sais me &thorn;e lyne &middot; lastid &thorn;e bataill,</L>
<L>Sike scoures were of blude &middot; of schondirhed bernes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at foles ferd in &thorn;e flosches &middot; to &thorn;e fetelakis;</L>
<L>Sa store &amp; stithe was &thorn;e stoure &middot; &thorn;e story me tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for soro&yogh;e of &thorn;e si&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of the; of <I>being added in the margin, but smeared out</I>.</NOTE> son<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> on &thorn;e heuen<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2052">Kest away his clerete &middot; &amp; his clippis suffirs,</L>
<L>For bale to blische on &thorn;e blode &middot; at on &thorn;e bent flo&yogh;es.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at oure gomes out of grece &middot; gedirs vp &thorn;ar hertis,</L>
<L>Fey fallis in &thorn;e fild &middot; fele of &thorn;ire othire,</L>
<L N="2056">&THORN;e pouwere of Persy &middot; in partis many</L>
<L>Se&yogh;es sidlings doun &middot; slayn of &thorn;aire blonkis.</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;e duke of ser Darys &middot; &thorn;a dedis be-haldis,</L>
<L N="2059">Amonta &thorn;e mi&yogh;tfull &middot; his men &thorn;an he fangis,</L>
<L>And vneth limpid him &thorn;e lee &middot; &thorn;e lyne me recordis,</L>
<L>Fra his faes with a fewe &middot; &thorn;e filde to de-voide.</L>
<L>And slike a pas, sais &thorn;e prose &middot; to Persy he ridis,</L>
<L N="2063">&THORN;at &yogh;it &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> selfe sandismen &middot; he in &thorn;e sale fyndis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra &thorn;e streme of struma &middot; were apon stedis wysid</L>
<L>Fra Alexander &amp; his ost &middot; with his athill pistill.</L>
<L>And &yogh;it ser dary on his dese &middot; &thorn;a dities a-visis,</L>
<L>Held &thorn;e lettir in his loue &middot; &amp; at &thorn;e ledis fraynes,</L>
<L N="2068">Quat he said of &thorn;e sedis &middot; &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> him-selfe sent.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai swiftly him sward &middot; &amp; swyth &thorn;us him tellis:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e kyng him ka&yogh;t," quod &thorn;e kni&yogh;tis "&amp; on &thorn;e cornes bitis,</L>
<L>And wele he geses be &thorn;e graynes &middot; &yogh;oure gomes ere fele,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="118"></L>
<L N="2072">Bot a thing, he said, he sa&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;at solast him maste,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware bot soft, he suposed &middot; for so &thorn;e sede proued."</L>
<L>&THORN;an pullis him vp &thorn;e proude kyng &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e pepire tastis,</L>
<L>Said, as it tuke him by &thorn;e tonge &middot; "his tulkis ere fewe,</L>
<L N="2076">Bot, be his kni&yogh;tis as kene &middot; as me &thorn;is cornes shewis,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e werd war to waike &middot; his wrothe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to wrohe, <I>altered to</I> wrothe to <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> to with-stand."<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hbith stand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e mody man Amonta &middot; &thorn;an melis &thorn;ir wordis,</L>
<L N="2079">"&YOGH;is, he ledis bot a lite &middot; lord, with &yogh;oure lefe;<MILESTONE N="36a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> bot fewe at him folo&yogh;es &middot; bot fe&yogh;tand bernes,</L>
<L>Bot mare fersere in feld &middot; fell neuire of modire.</L>
<L>For I my-selfe with a sowme &middot; set &thorn;aim agayns,</L>
<L>With of &thorn;e Persyns proude &middot; a pake out of nounbre,</L>
<L N="2084">Felire &thorn;an his folke &middot; be full fyue thousand,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it vs fell all to ferre &middot; &thorn;e fayntir to worthe;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai haue hedid of oure hathils &middot; &amp; a hepe woundid,</L>
<L>Fey falne to &thorn;e fold &middot; many fers erlis,</L>
<L N="2088">Bet doun oure bachelers &middot; my banir to-rased,</L>
<L>And a selly somme &middot; slayne of my kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>Quethire days<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> thre &thorn;ur&yogh;e-out &middot; thraly we fo&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>Derfe dintis &amp; dre&yogh;e &middot; delt &amp; taken,</L>
<L N="2092">And &yogh;it &thorn;e lawest at &thorn;e last &middot; vs limpid to bee,</L>
<L>And vnethis sauyd I my-selfe &middot; vn-slayn of &thorn;ar handis.</L>
<L>Bot treuly, ser," quod &thorn;e duke &middot; "gret tresore me thinke</L>
<L>At Alexander &thorn;e athill &middot; for of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Of <I>added above the line, indistinctly written; it is hardly wanted</I>.</NOTE> all ware he maister,</L>
<L N="2096">A-vanced with &thorn;e victore &middot; &amp; vengid on bis faes,</L>
<L>Was neuire &thorn;e he&yogh;are of a hawe &middot; his hert full of pride.</L>
<L>For mekely ilka modire son &middot; his awen men &amp; othire,</L>
<L>Als wele &thorn;e pure Persens &middot; as &thorn;e grete grekis,</L>
<L N="2100">All &thorn;e douth at was dede &middot; be-dene he comands</L>
<L>To gedire &thorn;am vp ilka gome &middot; &amp; &thorn;am in grauys ligg."</L>
<L>Now Alexander &amp; his ost &middot; armed on ridis,</L>
<L>And sone Cecile he &middot; with his seggis entrid,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="120"></L>
<L N="2104">&thorn;ar sere citis of &thorn;a sidis &middot; to him-selfe sweren,</L>
<L>And saudiours him to sewe &middot; seuyntene thousand.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ede he ouire in-to ane Ile &middot; Yssanna was hatten,<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at was &yogh;apely him &yogh;euyn &middot; &amp; &yogh;olden be-lyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;an vp he clame to a cliffe &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e cloudis semed,</L>
<L N="2109">&THORN;e Tor<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Top, <I>altered to</I> Tor.</NOTE> of Tare to taken &middot; &thorn;e tretis it callis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand he tildid on &thorn;e top &middot; &amp; tild<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. do tild; <I>with</I> do <I>underlined</I>.</NOTE> vp a cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e proud<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. perroude.</NOTE> toun of Persopole &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e place he ne&yogh;es.</L>
<L N="2112">&THORN;are sa&yogh;e he selcuthis sere &middot; as &thorn;e buke sais,</L>
<L>&THORN;e muses of musike &amp; &thorn;e merke &middot; how it was made first.</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires he in-to Asie &middot; &amp; ai as he fonndis,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e citis of &thorn;a sidis &middot; he sesis &thorn;am clene,</L>
<L N="2116">So fares he furth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he furth he; <I>with second</I> he <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> to Frigie &middot; a-no&thorn;ire faire Ile,</L>
<L>And ane &thorn;ar of his ald gods &middot; he honourd in a temple.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ferd he furth to a Flum &middot; was fyue cubetis brad,</L>
<L>Scamandra &thorn;e slire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> skire.</NOTE> flode &middot; &thorn;e scriptour it callis.</L>
<L N="2120">"Now happy be &yogh;ee," quod &thorn;e hathill &middot; "all in hert beris</L>
<L>&THORN;e honouris of &thorn;at odd clerke &middot; Homore &thorn;e grete."</L>
<L>"Mekill dere," quod ane Doctoneus &middot; "of &yogh;ow I deme sall,</L>
<L>And he of &thorn;e takyng of Troi &middot; tald all his lyue."</L>
<L N="2124">"Nay, I wald more worth," quod &thorn;e [wee] &middot; "a wyse man disc[i]ple,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e honour &thorn;at Acheles &middot; a&yogh;t all his time."</L>
<L>&THORN;an moves he him to Messedone &middot; with his mony princes,</L>
<L>Amendid of hire malidy &middot; his modire he fyndis,</L>
<L N="2128">A litill dais with hire lengis &middot; &amp; of hire lyfe ioyes,</L>
<L>And graythes him &thorn;an with his gere &middot; &amp; a-gayn fondis.</L>
<L>He passes on to-ward Persy &middot; &amp; pi&yogh;t doun his tentis</L>
<L>Besyd a bur&yogh;e at &thorn;e buke &middot; Abandra men<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> callis.</L>
<L N="2132">&THORN;ai fall on freschly &middot; &thorn;e folke of &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>And barris bremely at a bur&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;e foure brad &yogh;atis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an takis &thorn;e kyng his kni&yogh;tis &middot; vmlapis &thorn;e wallis,<MILESTONE N="37a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>Settis vp-on a saute &middot; on sidis eno&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="2136">Bot, for &thorn;e cite was vnsure &middot; &thorn;e seggis within</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t no&yogh;t &thorn;e braidis a-bide &middot; of bernes enarmed.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cries all to &thorn;e kyng &middot; "ser conquirour," &thorn;ai said:</L>
<L>"Ne steke we no&yogh;t oure stiff &yogh;atis &middot; &yogh;our strenthe to defend,</L>
<L N="2140">Bot for dred of ser Dary &middot; &thorn;e derfe Emperoure,</L>
<L>Lest, had we haldit to &yogh;our heste &middot; he had vs eft wastid."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, werpis &thorn;am vp," quod &thorn;e wee &middot; "&amp; wyde open settis,</L>
<L>If at &yogh;e shap &yogh;ow to shount &middot; vnschent of oure handis.</L>
<L>For quen I done haue with Dary &middot; &amp; my dede fenyschid,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall I tell &yogh;ow my tale &middot; how it sall tide eftir."</L>
<L>So baiste &thorn;am &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; with his breme wordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai vn&yogh;arked him &thorn;e &yogh;atis &middot; &amp; &yogh;ald him &thorn;e keys.</L>
<L N="2148">&THORN;e bur&yogh;e &thorn;us of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> abrandra &middot; he with his men takis,</L>
<L>To take &amp; leue quat him list &middot; &amp; lendis on forthire.</L>
<L>&THORN;en wyndis he to A wath toun &middot; was Wyothy hatten,</L>
<L>And come so to Caldipol &middot; ano&thorn;er kid cite,</L>
<L N="2152">So to the watir of wintir &middot; as it &thorn;e writte callis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are nere was fey for defaute &middot; enfamyschist his ost,</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tis kest vp a crie &middot; &amp; kenely &thorn;am menes:</L>
<L N="2155">"Loo, oure foles ere in fere &middot; fodeles to dye;"</L>
<L>&THORN;ai pleyne more &thorn;e pouirte &middot; &amp; &thorn;e pite of &thorn;ar horsis</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e soro&yogh;e of &thorn;am-selfe &middot; by &thorn;e seuynt parte.</L>
<L>"Quat ailes &yogh;ow?" quod Alexander &middot; to his athill dukis,</L>
<L>"Mi barons &amp; my baratorus &middot; &thorn;e biggest in erth,</L>
<L N="2160">&THORN;at has &thorn;e angwisch of armes &middot; ay to now suffird;</L>
<L>Quethire euire &yogh;oure hertis, I hope &middot; for horsys abatis?</L>
<L>May vs no&yogh;t limp, if any life &middot; lenge in oure<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Miswritten</I> oire <I>in</I> MS.</NOTE> brestis,</L>
<L>To couer be cas at a cleke &middot; courseris a thousand?<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2164">And vs demed be &thorn;e dome &middot; to die of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>&THORN;an standis in stede no&yogh;t of a stra &middot; all &thorn;e store stedis.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I rede," quod &thorn;e renke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kenke.</NOTE> &middot; "we ride on forthire,
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>And pas to sum othire place &middot; &thorn;are plente is in,</L>
<L N="2168">&THORN;at we may fange at &thorn;e full &middot; &thorn;e fude at vs wantis."</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;an prekis he furth with his princes &middot; to slike a playn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ap layn.</NOTE> wendis,</L>
<L>Luctus it hi&yogh;t, &thorn;e letterure &middot; &amp; &thorn;e line &thorn;us it callis;</L>
<L>&THORN;are his forrayouris fand &middot; &thorn;e fulth of vitaill,</L>
<L N="2172">Bathe to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> berne &amp; to blonk &middot; bide quen him likid.</L>
<L>When he was full &thorn;are &amp; fedd &middot; he flittis with his ost,</L>
<L>To Tergarontes he te&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;are ti&yogh;t was a mynstre;</L>
<L>He pi&yogh;t doun his pauilion &middot; &amp; passis to &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L N="2176">Sire Appoline to adoure &middot; &amp; othire ald goddis,</L>
<L>To offire in &thorn;at oritorie &middot; with honour he wyndis,</L>
<L>And sum of &thorn;am<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>After</I> at, to <I>is wrongly added above the line.</I></NOTE> spire &middot; how he spede suld.</L>
<L>Bot sone ane &yogh;acora him said &middot; a semely summe,</L>
<L N="2180">&THORN;an was nan honour of answaringis &middot; bot on a-no&thorn;ere bide.</L>
<L>&THORN;an dose him furth &thorn;e dere king &middot; &amp;, on &thorn;e day eftire,</L>
<L>He se&yogh;is to &thorn;e Synagog &middot; &amp; sacrif[is]e makis,</L>
<L N="2183">And Appoline als beliue &middot; him aykewordly swaris,</L>
<L>'Sire Ercules &thorn;e Emperoure' &middot; he euire in ane callis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander all in ire &middot; angrily spekis:</L>
<L>"Now fynd I wele," quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "&thorn;at fals ere &thorn;i wordis,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou neuyns me a new name &middot; at I neuire hi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou a god," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "&thorn;at is grete ioye!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an sekis he furth with a somme &middot; &amp; to A cite wyndis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e toun Thebea &middot; &thorn;e tretis it callis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he biddis all &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;at foure bald kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L N="2192">Suld be lett with him lend &middot; &amp; lenge in his weris.</L>
<L>&THORN;en tened &thorn;e Thebees folke &middot; &amp; tynd to &thorn;e &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>And to with-stand his strenthe &middot; ste&yogh;id to &thorn;e wallis,<MILESTONE N="38a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2195">Bad him bow on be-lyue &middot; &amp; bide &thorn;are na laingire;</L>
<L>For if he did, withouten dome &middot; &thorn;e deth &thorn;ai him hi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fangis him vp &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; a fuyll feyned la&yogh;tir,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>Said, "&yogh;e of Tebet ere tried &middot; &thorn;e tethiest on erth,</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e seggis vnder son &middot; &thorn;at citi&yogh;ens hatt;</L>
<L N="2200">Mast hi&yogh;e &yogh;e ere hersid &middot; &amp; herid of &yogh;oure strenthe.</L>
<L>And nowe sa &yogh;ape men as &yogh;e &middot; &thorn;e &yogh;atis hase stoken,</L>
<L>And me &amp; &thorn;e pruddest of my princes &middot; proferne vs werre;</L>
<L N="2203">And at &yogh;e so will, I-wis &middot; wondire me thinke,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us wald neuer at &yogh;e wro&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e wirscip of armes.</L>
<L>It contraries kni&yogh;thede &middot; &yogh;e knaw wele &yogh;our-selfe,</L>
<L>To any wi&yogh;t werriours &middot; in wallis &thorn;am to close.</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at kid is &amp; kene &middot; &amp; couettis a name,</L>
<L N="2208">Will fe&yogh;t fersely in fild &middot; his famen agayns."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander be-liue &middot; all a-boute &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Makis foure thousand &middot; with flanes &amp; bowis,</L>
<L>Biddis &thorn;am to bend vp &middot; brathly with arowis</L>
<L N="2212">To wonde &thorn;e wees with-in &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e wallis houys.</L>
<L>And twa thousand be tale &middot; he titely comaundis,</L>
<L>Of wele buskid bernns &middot; in brenys &amp; platis,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e sidis of &thorn;e cite &middot; &thorn;at sechus had biggid,</L>
<L N="2216">And Amphion, an athill kempe &middot; onane to distruy.</L>
<L>A full thousand he fangid &middot; to fire &thorn;e foure &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>And thre thousand of thra men &middot; to thraw with engynes.</L>
<L N="2219">Him-selfe of slingis &amp; slike &middot; a-semblis a me[n]&yogh;e,</L>
<L>To heede &amp; help of his hyne &middot; if any harme lympid.</L>
<L>Now ere his seggis all sett &middot; &amp; &thorn;e saute ne&yogh;is,</L>
<L>Were wakens be-twene &middot; werbild in trompis;</L>
<L>Oure pepill with payns &middot; pressis to without,</L>
<L N="2224">Halis vp hemp cordis &middot; hurled out arowis;</L>
<L>Othire athils of armes &middot; Albastis bendis,<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quirys out quarrels &middot; quappid thur&yogh;e mayles.</L>
<L>Sum with gunnes of &thorn;e grekis &middot; girdis vp stanes,</L>
<L N="2228">To tene &thorn;e Tebis folke &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e touris fe&yogh;tis;</L>
<L>Sum braide ouir &thorn;e barrers &middot; in blasand wede,</L>
<L>And faire fest on a fire &middot; all &thorn;e foure &yogh;atis;
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="128"></L>
<L N="2231">All &thorn;e bur&yogh;e at a braide &middot; was on a bale kyndild,</L>
<L>And &thorn;a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a&thorn;a, <I>with first</I> a <I>underlined.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at sounde ware vnslayn &middot; als sottes &thorn;am &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an with-out in oure ost &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>A Sire, at Sicistrus &middot; was callid be name,</L>
<L>A meri man, a Messangere &middot; &thorn;at maynly was ioyd</L>
<L N="2236">To se &thorn;e cite be sa sone &middot; sindid to brandis.</L>
<L>Anothre hathill vndire hand &middot; &thorn;at Hismon was<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. was was; <I>the second</I> was <I>underlined.</I></NOTE> callid,</L>
<L>Ane a maistre of musike &middot; <SUP>3</SUP>a man of &thorn;e cite,<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 <I>Substituted in</I> MS. <I>for</I> "&amp; in his art wepis;" <I>see next line.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="2239">Aires to ser Alexander &middot; &amp; in his hert wepis,</L>
<L>As qua sai, "prince, of oure place &middot; sum pete &thorn;ou haue."</L>
<L>&THORN;an lokis &thorn;e lord to &thorn;e lede &middot; said, "lettrid berne,</L>
<L>Quare-to feynys &thorn;ou &thorn;is fare &middot; for-with myne e&yogh;en?"</L>
<L>"Sire conquirour," quod &thorn;e clerke &middot; "&yogh;oure corage to bend,</L>
<L N="2244">And in ridding of oure riche toun &middot; &yogh;our reuth for to call."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e wale kyng wrath &middot; &amp; wi&yogh;tly comaundis</L>
<L>To bete in-to &thorn;e bare erth &middot; all &thorn;e bur&yogh;e-walles;</L>
<L>And quen all kynd was on colis &middot; &amp; kast apon hepis,</L>
<L>&THORN;an airis he on with his ost &middot; mare honour to wynn.</L>
<L N="2249">A Ientill man full ioyles &middot; iournais him eftir,</L>
<L>Folo&yogh;es &thorn;are fare &middot; ai on fote as &thorn;ai ride,</L>
<L>A sege at of &thorn;e same toun &middot; sire was &amp; maistre,</L>
<L N="2252">Ane callid was Cletomacus &middot; to crie eftir socure,</L>
<L>His ledis at left ware o-lyue &middot; a lite of &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;an askid at sire Appoline &middot; al<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written above the line.</I></NOTE> with a steuen,</L>
<L>"If euire it worthe sall to wee &middot; quen &thorn;e werd stand,</L>
<L>Oure bu[r]&yogh;e agayn for to bigg &middot; &thorn;at bretted is to no&yogh;t?"</L>
<L N="2257">&THORN;an gales &thorn;aire god &middot; a-gayn &amp; &thorn;us spekis:<MILESTONE N="39a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;e tulke &thorn;at tilld <I>&yogh;our</I> toun &middot; sall tield vp &amp; rere,</L>
<L>Sall thre times haue &thorn;e thra &middot; of sum threuyn gome</L>
<L>Of were ore of wristilling &middot; for &thorn;us has wirid shapen.</L>
<L>And quen &thorn;at wirschip is won &middot; within a wale time,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall he sett vp him-selfe &middot; &thorn;e cite as be-forne."
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>&THORN;us answars &thorn;am &thorn;aire ald gode &middot; &amp; osses on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="2264">And &thorn;ai als fayne, all &thorn;e flote &middot; as fowell of &thorn;e day.</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires on ser Alexander &middot; with his athill princes,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e castell of Corynthi &middot; he comes with his ost,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e Pers of &thorn;a partese &middot; to play on &thorn;e toures,</L>
<L N="2268">As all &thorn;e sires of &thorn;a sidis &middot; him-selfe had required.</L>
<L>&THORN;e multitude ware sa miche &middot; of men for to reken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are was sembild &amp; sett &middot; &thorn;at si&yogh;t to be-hald.</L>
<L>Quod Alexander bilyue &middot; to all at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;are stode,</L>
<L N="2272">"Quat gome sall &thorn;is gammen &middot; begin apon first?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an comes forth Cletomacus &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e kyng swaris,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tulke out of Thebie &middot; I tald &yogh;ow be-forne,</L>
<L N="2275">"If it &yogh;oure mekill maieste &middot; mi&yogh;t any thinge plese,</L>
<L>I wald to wacken &yogh;oure welth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. welah, <I>altered to</I> welth.</NOTE> &middot; now wirstill a turne."</L>
<L>&THORN;an mas &thorn;e prince him a place &middot; &amp; prestly him matches,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. maches, <I>altered to</I> matches.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he him girdes to &thorn;e grounde &middot; &amp; &thorn;e gree wynnes.</L>
<L>"Now faithly," quod &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; "fall &thorn;e so thrise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall be crouned, or I caire &middot; for kiddest of &thorn;e gamen."</L>
<L N="2281">&THORN;an &yogh;ede he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he to; <I>with</I> to <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> eftsones to &middot; &amp; his euen kastis,</L>
<L>Thringis to &thorn;e thrid time &middot; &amp; &thorn;e thra wynnys.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an comandis him &thorn;e kyng &middot; a coroune on hede,</L>
<L N="2284">As for &thorn;e prise of &thorn;e play &middot; putfull of stanes;</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad him beddels belyue: &middot; 'breue vs &thorn;i name.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. name name; <I>the first struck out</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sirres, by my sothe," quod &thorn;e segge &middot; "Sitiles I hi&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Qwi so, my worthe werstillare?" &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng said,<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2288">"How tidis it &thorn;e &amp; tou[n]les &middot; &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;i ton; ton <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> toname is callid?"</L>
<L>"Mi louely lorde," quod &thorn;e lede &middot; &amp; law him declines,</L>
<L>"Be-for &yogh;e come slike a kyng &middot; &amp; &thorn;e croune werrid,</L>
<L>I had a cite<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a h a cite; <I>with</I> a h <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> my-selfe &middot; &amp; segges I-nowe;</L>
<L N="2292">And sethen &yogh;e a&yogh;t &thorn;is enpire &middot; I am it all priued."</L>
<L>&THORN;an trowid trewly &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;at Theby he menyd,</L>
<L>And beddels &amp; bailyfs &middot; he bad on brad crie,
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>Be-fore his pupill apert &middot; &thorn;e powere him grauntis</L>
<L N="2296">To sett his cite vp agayn &middot; &amp; of him-selfe halden.</L>
<L>&THORN;an passis he to a proude toun &middot; Platea was hatten,</L>
<L>&THORN;are was sti&yogh;tild ane Strasageras &middot; &thorn;at was a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> stiffe prince,</L>
<L>Duse him in with his dukis &middot; to Dyanaas temple,</L>
<L N="2300">And fand a pure prophetas &middot; aparaild in vailes.</L>
<L>And scho, as sone as scho him sa&yogh;e &middot; said him &thorn;ir wordis:</L>
<L>"Welcom we, at all &thorn;e werd &middot; sall wyn with &thorn;i handis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund day before &thorn;e son &middot; he at &thorn;e cite wildid,</L>
<L N="2304">In-to &thorn;e temple he turned &middot; tythandis to herken;</L>
<L>"Quat ware &thorn;i will, ser, to wete?" &middot; &thorn;e woman frayned;</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou lesis all &thorn;i lordschip &middot; within a lite dais."</L>
<L>"Quat, &amp; has &thorn;ou ossed to Alexander &middot; &thorn;is ayndain wirdes,</L>
<L N="2308">And me &thorn;us ill? vn-ably &middot; &thorn;ine abet &thorn;ou weris."</L>
<L>"Nay, tene &yogh;ow no&yogh;t, for treuly &middot; &thorn;us tide bose it nede."</L>
<L>And so it worthid, for in a wrath &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng swyth</L>
<L>Him of his principalete priued &middot; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e prince fondis</L>
<L N="2312">Onane to Athenas &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e athill playntes;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai said, soure suld him sowe &middot; bot he &thorn;e cite &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>And Alexander with his ostes &middot; aires on forthire,</L>
<L>Ateynes him to-ward &thorn;e termes &middot; &amp; of &thorn;ar tene heres,</L>
<L>And slike a word he &thorn;aim wayues &middot; be writ fra him-self.</L>
<L>And qua so will has to wete &middot; how it worthid eftir,<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2318">Here sall I tell &thorn;am at loues &middot; to here forthire.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000137.tif" N="115">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>"I, alexander, eldest &middot; ayr out of grece,</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e son of Philip &thorn;e fers &middot; &amp; of hys faire lady,</L>
<L N="2008">Honored olimphades &middot; &thorn;e oddest vnder heuen,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, sir darius, on &thorn;i dese &middot; &thorn;is ditez I write.</L>
<L>For I am send, be &thorn;e sure &middot; mony sere lettres,</L>
<L>And nomely now on new tyme &middot; fro my awne kithes,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="2013">All o&thorn;er-wyse to wirke &middot; &thorn;en my wille liked.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is I werne, or I wende &middot; &amp; will at &thorn;ou knaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for no drede I withdraw &middot; &thorn;e dow of &thorn;i pryde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. proyde, or peryde (like per in piper, l. 2023); <I>read</I> pryde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2016">For basyng ne for bobas &middot; ne for breme wordes,</L>
<L>Bot for to Se &thorn;at is Seke &middot; my awne Semelych Modre.<MILESTONE N="21a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot wete &thorn;ou wele &thorn;is, I-wisse &middot; in a wale tyme,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at I fraysted haue &thorn;e fare &middot; of my faire lady,</L>
<L N="2020">I sall &thorn;e seche with a soume &middot; of seggez enarmed,</L>
<L>One oste to ney vs to newyn &middot; &amp; all of new knyghtez.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e sake of &thorn;i sede &middot; &thorn;ou send with &thorn;i writte,</L>
<L>Lo, here a purse full of piper &middot; my power to ken,</L>
<L N="2024">To se &thorn;i-selfe a similitude &middot; how all &thorn;ees softe granes</L>
<L>So vnder-put [be] all &thorn;e pake &middot; of &thorn;is pete cornez."</L>
<L>Thys pistyll to &thorn;e persens &middot; he with &thorn;is peper takys,</L>
<L>Partes pristly to &thorn;aim &middot; mony proude gyftez,</L>
<L N="2028">And &thorn;ai haue laughten &thorn;air leue &middot; &amp; &thorn;e lettrez fangett,</L>
<L>And passyd vnto perse &middot; &thorn;e prince it to shewe.</L>
<L>Then alexander &middot; with hys atell Dukez,</L>
<L>Rachez hym radly to ride &middot; &amp; remevez hys ostez,</L>
<L N="2032">Fro &thorn;e streme of struma &middot; he moved &amp; stilly murnez,</L>
<L>And mefez on toward masydon &middot; hys moder to viset.</L>
<L>He ayers toward araby &middot; &amp; armyd &thorn;ar he fyndez</L>
<L>A duke of Darius &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;at drafe hym agayns,</L>
<L N="2036">A Pere owt of perse &middot; &amp; prince of hys hoste,</L>
<L>A maister man of &thorn;e marche &middot; amonta was callyd.</L>
<L>He girdez in with a gyn &middot; &thorn;e grekes assaylez,
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>And with alexander all &thorn;e day &middot; asperly feghtez,</L>
<L N="2040">Marres of &thorn;e masidons &middot; mightfull knyghtez,</L>
<L>Dynges downe of &thorn;e dukez &middot; deres &thorn;aim vnfaire,</L>
<L>Fro morne vnto mirke nyght &middot; manly &thorn;ai feghtyn,</L>
<L>Slew downe on ather syde &middot; seges owt of nowmbre.</L>
<L N="2044">Began in &thorn;e gray day &middot; when &thorn;e gleme spronge,</L>
<L>And so to &thorn;e sett of &thorn;e son &middot; sessyd &thorn;ai neuer.</L>
<L>&thorn;us iij dayes in a thraw &middot; &thorn;ai threpyd euerelike;</L>
<L>So lang, says &thorn;e line &middot; lastyd &thorn;e batell,</L>
<L N="2048">Slyke showrez of shire blode &middot; of shenderet bernes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folez faired in flosshez &middot; to &thorn;e fete-lakez;</L>
<L>So sture &amp; styff was &thorn;e stoure &middot; &thorn;e story me telles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for sorow of &thorn;at fight &middot; &thorn;e son of heuen</L>
<L N="2052">Lost hase is clarite &middot; &amp; hys clepys sufers,</L>
<L><B>For bale to Blissh on blod &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e bent flowes.</B><MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at owr gomes owt of grece &middot; gerdyn vp &thorn;air hertes,</L>
<L>And fellyd fele in &thorn;e feld &middot; feyle of &thorn;is o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="2056">&THORN;e power owt of perse &middot; in parteez mony</L>
<L>Sweyd sleghtly downe &middot; slayn of &thorn;air blonkes.</L>
<L>And when sir Darius duke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ye duke; <I>but</I> ye <I>is subpuncted</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;is dedes bihaldyn,</L>
<L>Amonta &thorn;e mightfull &middot; hys men &thorn;en he fannges,</L>
<L N="2060">And vneth limpyd hym &thorn;e lyfe &middot; &thorn;e line me recordes,</L>
<L>And fro hys faes with A few folke &middot; &thorn;e feld he deuodes.</L>
<L>And suche a passe, &thorn;en says &thorn;e prose &middot; to perse he rydez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;it &thorn;e some sendesman &middot; he in &thorn;e sale fyndez,</L>
<L N="2064">At fro &thorn;e streme of strema &middot; was on stedes wysett</L>
<L>Fro alexander &amp; hys hoste &middot; with hys athell pistyll.</L>
<L>And &yogh;itt sir darius on &thorn;e dese &middot; on &thorn;is dytes awysez,</L>
<L>Held &thorn;is lettre in hys loue &middot; &amp; at &thorn;e ledes franes,</L>
<L N="2068">What he sayd of &thorn;aes sedes &middot; &thorn;at he &thorn;aim send hed.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ai hym, <I>but</I> hym <I>is subpuncted</I>.</NOTE> swyftly hym sware &middot; &amp; sothly hym tald:</L>
<L>"The kyng &thorn;aim kacht,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. katht.</NOTE> quod &thorn;e knyghtes &middot; "&amp; on &thorn;e kirnels bote,</L>
<L>And wele he gessed be &thorn;e granes &middot; your gomes er softe,
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="119"></L>
<L N="2072">Bot on<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ony, <I>corrected to</I> on.</NOTE> thynge, he sayd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he sayd <I>repeated; but once expuncted</I>.</NOTE> he sawgh &middot; &thorn;at solast hym mekyll,</L>
<L>Thai wer bot softe, he supposyd &middot; for so &thorn;e sede preved."</L>
<L>&THORN;en pullys hym vp &thorn;e prouude gome<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e peper tastez,</L>
<L>Sayd, als it toke hym be &thorn;e tong &middot; "hys tulkes wer fell,</L>
<L>For, be hys knyghtez als kene &middot; as me &thorn;e corne shewys,</L>
<L N="2077">All &thorn;e werld is to wake &middot; hys wrothe to wit-stande."</L>
<L>The worthy man amonta &middot; &thorn;an mellys &thorn;ir wordes,</L>
<L>Sayd, "he ledes bot a lityll &middot; lord, be your lefe;</L>
<L N="2080">Thai er bot few at hym folows &middot; of feghtand bernes,</L>
<L>Bot more forcer on a feld &middot; felle neuer of moder.</L>
<L>For I my-selfe with a soume &middot; set hym agayns,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e persens prouude &middot; a pake out of nowmbre,</L>
<L N="2084">Mo &thorn;en hys awne meyn&yogh;e &middot; be full fyue thousand,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Victoria con|tra amontam ducem darij.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;it vs fell all be fere &middot; &thorn;e faynter to worth;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> haue.</NOTE> hedit of owr athellys &middot; &amp; a [hepe] woundett,</L>
<L>And fey fallyn in &thorn;e feld &middot; mony ferce Erelez,</L>
<L N="2088">Betyn Done owr Bachelers &middot; my Barons all distroyd,<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And a selly soume of my knyghte[s] &middot; in &thorn;e feld slayne.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er thre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> r <I>is above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> days out-&thorn;orow &middot; thraly we feyten,</L>
<L>Drafe dyntes derfe &middot; deltyn &amp; token,</L>
<L N="2092">And &yogh;it &thorn;e lawest at &thorn;e last &middot; vs limpyd to be,</L>
<L>Bot vnneth saued I my-selue &middot; vnslayne of &thorn;air handes.</L>
<L>Bot trewly, sir," quod &thorn;e duke &middot; "grete tresour me thynke</L>
<L>At alexander &thorn;e athell &middot; for all was he maister,</L>
<L N="2096">Auancyd with wictory &middot; &amp; vengyd on hys enmys,</L>
<L>Was neuer &thorn;e helder of a haw &middot; [his] hert full of pride.</L>
<L>For mekely ilke moderson &middot; hys awne men &amp; othre,</L>
<L>Als wele &thorn;e pure persens &middot; as &thorn;e prouude grekez,</L>
<L N="2100">All &thorn;e doghty be-dene &middot; &thorn;at was dede he Commandez</L>
<L>To geder &thorn;aim vp ilke grome &middot; &amp; &thorn;aim in graue bring."</L>
<L>Now alexander &amp; hys oste &middot; armyd on he rydez,</L>
<L N="2103">And sone into cesyll &middot; he with hys segez enters,
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>Thare sere citez of &thorn;ai sydez &middot; to hym-selfe was &yogh;oldyn,</L>
<L>And saugeours hym to sewe &middot; seuentene thousand.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ode he ouer into an Ile &middot; Yssanna was haten,</L>
<L N="2107">And &thorn;at was &yogh;apely hym &yogh;efen &middot; &amp; yolden belyfe.</L>
<L>Than vp he clam to a clyffe &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e clowdez semyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e towre of taure to token &middot; &thorn;e tretes it calles;</L>
<L>&thorn;ar fand he tembret on &thorn;e top &middot; &amp; tyldit vp a cyte,</L>
<L>The proud towne of persipoll &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e place goys.</L>
<L N="2112">&thorn;ar saw he selcouthez sere &middot; as sayn me &thorn;e writtes,</L>
<L>The musys of musik &amp; &thorn;ar merke &middot; how it was made frist.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ayrez he into asy &middot; &amp; ay as he fonndez,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e citez of &thorn;o sydez &middot; he sesez &thorn;am ilkon,</L>
<L N="2116">So fares he forth to frige &middot; an-other fair yle,</L>
<L>And one of hys olde goddes &middot; honours in a temple.</L>
<L>&THORN;en faryd he forth to a flume &middot; fyue cubettes of brede,</L>
<L N="2119">Scamandra &thorn;e skyr flode &middot; &thorn;e scripture it neues.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Then mefes home to masidon &middot; with hys mony princez,</L>
<L>And mendyd of hir maledy &middot; [his] moder he fyndez,</L>
<L N="2128">A lite dayes with hir he lenges &middot; &amp; of hir lyve ioys,</L>
<L><B>And grathes</B> hym &thorn;an with hys gynge &middot; &amp; agayn fonndez.<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He passed on toward perse &middot; &amp; pyth doun hys tentes</L>
<L>Besyde a burgh &thorn;at &thorn;e buke &middot; bandara calles.</L>
<L N="2132">&THORN;en fell to &thorn;aim freshly &middot; &thorn;e folke of &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>And barred bremely at a brush &middot; &thorn;e foure brod &yogh;ates.</L>
<L>Then caches &thorn;e kyng hys knyghtez &middot; vmbelappes &thorn;e wallez,
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And settes vp a sawte &middot; to &thorn;e towne sydes;</L>
<L N="2136">But for &thorn;e cite was vnsure &middot; &thorn;e segez within</L>
<L>Might noght &thorn;e barettes abyde &middot; of seggez enarmed.</L>
<L>&THORN;en callyd &thorn;ai to &thorn;e kyng &middot; "sir Conquerour," &amp; sayd:</L>
<L>"We steke noght our &yogh;ates &middot; your strenth to defende,</L>
<L N="2140">Bot for &thorn;e drede of sir dary &middot; &thorn;e derfe Emperour,</L>
<L>Lest, hed we heldit to your hest &middot; he hed vs eft wastyd."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, warpez &thorn;aim vp," quod &thorn;e wye<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wyez.</NOTE> &middot; "&amp; wyde opyn settes,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>For when I done haue with Darius &middot; &amp; my dede fenyshyd,</L>
<L N="2145">Than sall I tell you my tale &middot; how it sall tyde after."</L>
<L>So babyst &thorn;aim &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; with hys breme wordez,</L>
<L>That &thorn;ai vn&yogh;arked hym &thorn;e yatez &middot; &amp; yeld hym &thorn;e kees.</L>
<L N="2148">Thus &thorn;e burght of bandra &middot; he with hys bernes takes,</L>
<L>To lache &amp; lefe qwat hym lyst &middot; &amp; lendez on for&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;an wendes he to a wale towne &middot; was worthyly haldyn,</L>
<L>And Come so to cadypolez &middot; ane o&thorn;er kyd cite,</L>
<L N="2152">So to &thorn;e water of wynter &middot; als it &thorn;e writte calles.</L>
<L>Thare negh was fey for defaute &middot; enfamyshyd hys oste,</L>
<L>Knyghtez kest vp a cry &middot; &amp; kenely &thorn;aim meane;</L>
<L>Sayd: "lo, oure folez bene in fere &middot; for fodeles to dye;"</L>
<L N="2156">Plenys more &thorn;e perty &middot; &amp; pety of &thorn;air blonkez</L>
<L>&THORN;an of &thorn;e sorow of &thorn;aim selfe &middot; be &thorn;e seuent dele.</L>
<L>"What aylez you nowe?" quod alexander &middot; to hys athell Dukez,</L>
<L>"My barons &amp; my baratours &middot; biggest on erth,</L>
<L N="2160">That hase &thorn;e angers of armes &middot; ay to now sofferd;</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er euer your hertes &middot; for horse-fleshez abaytez?</L>
<L>May we noght lympe, if ony lyfe &middot; leng in our brestes,</L>
<L>To couer be case at a cleke &middot; coursours a thouusand?</L>
<L N="2164">And yf vs demyd be &thorn;e dome &middot; to dye all at ones,</L>
<L>&THORN;an standes in stede noght of A stra &middot; all our styffe stedes.</L>
<L><B>For-&thorn;i</B><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> i <I>above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> I rede," quod &thorn;e renke &middot; "<B>We</B> rydyn on <B>For&thorn;er,</B><MILESTONE N="23a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>And passe we to som o&thorn;er place &middot; where plente is in,</L>
<L N="2168">Thare we may fang at &thorn;e full &middot; &thorn;e fode at vs wantes,</L>
<L N="2168*">And bath our folk &amp; owr folez &middot; fyll &thorn;aire wambes."</L>
<L>Then prekys he forth with hys princez &middot; to suche a place wendes,</L>
<L>Luctus it &thorn;e lettre &middot; &amp; &thorn;e line calles;</L>
<L>Thare as hys saugeours hase fondyn &middot; &thorn;e fulth of &thorn;e vitale,</L>
<L N="2172">Bath to bern &amp; to blonke &middot; byde whils he liked.</L>
<L>When he was fulle &thorn;ar &amp; fed &middot; he flittes hys ostez,</L>
<L>To tergarontes he ti&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;ar telde was a mynster;</L>
<L>Py&yogh;t doun hys pauvilons &middot; &amp; passyd to &thorn;e temple,</L>
<L N="2176">Sir appolyn to adoure &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er alde goddez,</L>
<L>To offre in &thorn;at oratory &middot; with honour in he wendes,</L>
<L>And of som sperete to spire &middot; how he spede suld.</L>
<L N="2179">Bott on &yogh;acora hym sayd &middot; a semlych Nonn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ar was none o&thorn;er answer &middot; bot ane o&thorn;er day to abyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an drafe hym for[th] &thorn;e dere kyng &middot; &amp;, on &thorn;e day after,</L>
<L>He soght into &thorn;e sinagoge &middot; &amp; sacrifice makez,</L>
<L>And appolyne als belyue &middot; hym aukwardly answers,</L>
<L N="2184">'Sir ercules &thorn;is emperour' &middot; hym euer onon clepys.</L>
<L>Than alexander all in ire &middot; angerly spekys:</L>
<L>"Now fynde I wele," quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "&thorn;at false er &thorn;i wordes,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou nevens a new name &middot; &thorn;at I neuer hight;</L>
<L N="2188">And &thorn;ou a god," quod &thorn;e gome &middot; "&thorn;at is grete Ioy!"</L>
<L>Then sekys he forth with a soume &middot; &amp; to a cyte wendes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ilke towne hight tebea &middot; &thorn;e tretez so it calles,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar he biddez all &thorn;e burgh &middot; &thorn;at foure bald knyghtez</L>
<L N="2192">Suld be lett with hym wende &middot; &amp; in hys werys lenge.</L>
<L>&THORN;en tenyd &thorn;e tebe folke &middot; &amp; tit to &thorn;e &yogh;atez,</L>
<L>And withstode his strenth &middot; &amp; strode to &thorn;e walles,</L>
<L N="2195">Bad hym buske on belyue &middot; &amp; abyde &thorn;ar no langer;</L>
<L>For if he dyd, withowtyn dowte &middot; &thorn;e dede &thorn;ai hight hym.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fangez vp &thorn;e fele kyng &middot; a ful fenyd laughter,
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>Sayd, "&yogh;e of tebe er triest &middot; &amp; thethiest on erth,</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;e seges vnder sun &middot; &thorn;at citesyns er called;</L>
<L N="2200">Most heyly ye be auancett &middot; &amp; hight in hert.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Catchword</I>&mdash;in hert; <I>wrongly</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L><B>And</B> now so &yogh;ope men as &yogh;e &middot; &yogh;ates <B>Hase</B> stoken,<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Me &amp; my proudest of my princez &middot; &yogh;e do profre were;</L>
<L N="2203">And &thorn;at &yogh;e so will, I-wys &middot; wondre me thynke,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us wald neuer &thorn;at &yogh;e wroght &middot; worschip of armes.</L>
<L>It contrarys knyghthod &middot; ye knawe wele your-seluen,</L>
<L>To any wight wereour &middot; in walles hym to close.</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at kyd is &amp; kene &middot; &amp; couates hym a name,</L>
<L N="2208">Will fersly feght in &thorn;e feld &middot; hys faymen ayayns."</L>
<L>And alexander als belyfe &middot; all vmbe &thorn;e cyte,</L>
<L>Mase iiij Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thousand, <I>which is intended by this contraction for</I> Lat. <I>mille</I>.</NOTE> to fonde &middot; with flanes &amp; bowes,</L>
<L>Byddes &thorn;ame to bend vp &middot; &amp; brathly with arowez</L>
<L N="2212">To wound &thorn;e wyes within &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e wallez hoved.</L>
<L>And two thouusand be tale &middot; he tytely Commandez,</L>
<L>Of wele busked bernes &middot; in brenes &amp; in plates,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e sydes of &thorn;e cite &middot; &thorn;at sichus had bigged,</L>
<L N="2216">And amphion, &thorn;e athell kemp &middot; anone to distroye.</L>
<L>And iiij Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thousand, <I>which is intended by this contraction for</I> Lat. <I>mille</I>.</NOTE> he fonge &middot; to fyre &thorn;e iiij &yogh;ates,</L>
<L>Bot thre Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> thousand, <I>which is intended by this contraction for</I> Lat. <I>mille</I>.</NOTE> of thra men &middot; to thraw with engynez.</L>
<L>Hym-self with slengers &amp; slyke &middot; he somned<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> soumed.</NOTE> a men&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="2220">To heyd &amp; to help hys hynes &middot; if any harme limpyd.</L>
<L>Now er is seges all sett &middot; &amp; &thorn;e saute neghed,</L>
<L>Were wakned be-twene &middot; werblet trompez;</L>
<L>Our peple with pavyce &middot; presen to withowt,</L>
<L N="2224">Halez vp hemp cordez &middot; hurlett owt arows;</L>
<L>O&thorn;er athells of armes &middot; alblastrez benden,</L>
<L>Whirres owt qwarels &middot; wappyd thrugh males.</L>
<L>Som with gunnez of &thorn;e grekys &middot; gyrdyn vp stones,</L>
<L N="2228">To tene &thorn;e tebet folke &middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e toure fighten;</L>
<L>Som bradyn oure &thorn;e barres &middot; in blysnand wedes,</L>
<L>And faire fest on a fyre &middot; all &thorn;e foure &yogh;ates;
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e burgh at a brayde &middot; was on a blasse kyndlett,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at sunde wer vnslayne &middot; as seges &thorn;aim &yogh;olden.</L>
<L N="2233">Than was withowt in &thorn;e ost &middot; als &thorn;e buke tellys,</L>
<L>A syre, &thorn;at sicistreus<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> sicisterus.</NOTE> &middot; was seget to name,</L>
<L>A mery man, a messyngere &middot; &thorn;at manly <B>was</B> Ioynet<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Ioyed.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="24a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2236">To see &thorn;e cite be so sone &middot; shendit to brandes.</L>
<L>Ane-o&thorn;er athell vnder hand &middot; &thorn;at Hisman was callyd,</L>
<L>One maister of musike &middot; a man of &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L N="2239">Ayrez hym to Alexander &middot; &amp; in hys hert wepys,</L>
<L>Als wha sa, "Prince, of your place &middot; som pite &yogh;e haue."</L>
<L>Then lokys &thorn;e lord to &thorn;e led &middot; sayd, "lettred berne,</L>
<L>Whare to fenys &thorn;ou &thorn;is fare &middot; for-with my eghen I see?"</L>
<L>"Sir Conquerour," quod &thorn;is clerk &middot; "your<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. pore.</NOTE> corage to bynde,</L>
<L N="2244">And in riddyng of our riche towne &middot; your reuth for to calle."</L>
<L>Than was &thorn;e wale kyng wroght &middot; &amp; wittily Commandes</L>
<L>To bete into &thorn;e bare erth &middot; all &thorn;e burgh walles;</L>
<L>And when all kyndlett was on colez &middot; &amp; castyn vppon hepys,</L>
<L N="2248">Than ayrez he on with hys ost &middot; more worship to wyn.</L>
<L>A gentilman full ioyles &middot; &thorn;en iornays hym after,</L>
<L>Folows &thorn;e folke ay on fote &middot; as &thorn;e faire ryden,</L>
<L>A sege of &thorn;e same cite &middot; &thorn;at syre was &amp; maister,</L>
<L N="2252">That callyd was clytomacus &middot; to cry after socour,</L>
<L>Hys ledes &thorn;at left wer on-lyue &middot; a lyte of &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>Then askyd &thorn;ai at sir Apolyn &middot; all with a stevyn,</L>
<L N="2255">"Yf it worth sall to wy &middot; whil &thorn;e world standes,</L>
<L>Oure burgh ayayn to be beld &middot; &thorn;at brytynd is to noght?"</L>
<L>Than galez &thorn;ar god &thorn;aim ayayn &middot; &amp; &thorn;us-gates he spekes:</L>
<L>"The tulke &thorn;at teld mon your town &middot; sall teld vp &amp; rerre,</L>
<L>Sall thre tymez haue &thorn;e tro &middot; of some kynne gamez</L>
<L N="2260">Off were or of wristylyng &middot; for so hase werdez shapyn.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at worship is won &middot; within a wale tyme,</L>
<L>Than sall he sett vp [him] selfe &middot; &thorn;e cite als beforne."
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>Thus answers &thorn;aim &thorn;is old god &middot; &amp; ossus on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="2264">And &thorn;ai als fayne, all &thorn;e flote &middot; als foule is on morne.</L>
<L>Than Ayrez hym on sir Alexander &middot; with hys athell Princez,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e castell of corinthy &middot; he commys with hys ostez,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e peres of &thorn;ai partez &middot; to play on &thorn;e towrez,</L>
<L N="2268">Als all &thorn;e syres of &thorn;at sydez &middot; hem-selfe hed required.</L>
<L><B>The</B> multitude Wher to muche &middot; <B>oF</B> men for to reken,<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That wer &thorn;ar semblyd &amp; set &middot; &thorn;at feght to be-hold.</L>
<L>Quod alexander als belyue &middot; to all &thorn;at &thorn;ar stodyn:</L>
<L N="2272">"What gome sall &thorn;is gamen &middot; begyn vpon first?"</L>
<L>Then commes furth Clytomacus &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e kyng sweres,</L>
<L>The tulke owt of tebe &middot; I tald you beforne;</L>
<L>"If it your mekyll mageste &middot; might any thyng please,</L>
<L N="2276">I wald to wakyn oure welth &middot; now wrastyll a turne."</L>
<L>&THORN;en makes &thorn;e prince hym a place &middot; &amp; prestly hym maches,</L>
<L>And he hym grydes to &thorn;e grund &middot; &amp; &thorn;e gre wynnez.</L>
<L>"Now fathfully, quod &thorn;e feyle kyng &middot; "&thorn;us fall &thorn;ou thrisse,</L>
<L>Thu sall be crownyd, or I go &middot; for kyddest of gamme."</L>
<L N="2281">&THORN;en &yogh;ode he eftsons to &middot; &amp; hys euen castes,</L>
<L>Thrynges to &thorn;e thryd tyme &middot; &amp; &thorn;e thro wynnes.</L>
<L>And &thorn;en Commandes &thorn;e kyng &middot; a croune on heued,</L>
<L N="2284">Als for &thorn;e fee of &thorn;e play &middot; pi&yogh;t-full of stanes;</L>
<L>Then byde hym bedels belyfe: &middot; 'breue vs &thorn;i name.'</L>
<L>"Sirs, be my soght," quod &thorn;e seghe &middot; "siteles<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. e. city-less; <I>so also</I> town-less <I>in line</I> 2288.</NOTE> I hyght."</L>
<L>"Whi so, my worthy wristiller?" &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng sayd,</L>
<L N="2288">"How tydes it &thorn;e at tounles &middot; &thorn;i to-name is called?"</L>
<L>"My louely Lord," quod &thorn;e lede &middot; &amp; law he declynes,</L>
<L>"Before &yogh;e Come suche &middot; &amp; &thorn;e crowne wered,</L>
<L>I hed a cyte my-self &middot; &amp; seges enowe;</L>
<L N="2292">And syne &yogh;e aught &thorn;is empyre &middot; &amp; I am depriued."</L>
<L>Then trowyd trewly &thorn;e kyng &middot; at tebet he neuynd,</L>
<L>And Bedels &amp; bail&yogh;ais &middot; he bad a-none crye,
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>Before hys peple so pert &middot; &amp; hym &thorn;e power grauntez</L>
<L N="2296">To set hys cite vp agayn &middot; &amp; of hym-self hald.</L>
<L>&THORN;an passys he to a prouud toun &middot; platea was haten,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was sti&yogh;let one strasagera &middot; &thorn;at was a styffe Prince,</L>
<L>Dose hym in with hys Dukes &middot; to Dicnas<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Dianas.</NOTE> temple,</L>
<L N="2300">And fand a pure prophett &middot; apparelt in wales.</L>
<L>And als sone as sho hym see &middot; sho sayd &thorn;ees wordes:</L>
<L>"Welcom, wye, &thorn;at &thorn;e werld &middot; sall wynne with &thorn;i handes."</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund day before &thorn;e sun &middot; he &thorn;at cite weLdit,<MILESTONE N="25a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2304">To &thorn;e temple he tight &middot; tithanndez to herken.</L>
<L>"What is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &thorn;i will," quod [the] woman, "sir, to witt &middot; &amp; how &thorn;ou me franes;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou lossez all &thorn;i Lordschips &middot; within a lityll dayes."</L>
<L>"What &amp; hase &thorn;u ossed to alexander &middot; &thorn;us aydom wordes,</L>
<L N="2308">And me &thorn;us? vnably &middot; &thorn;in&emacr; habet &thorn;ou werys."</L>
<L>"Nay, tene &thorn;e noght, for trewly &middot; &thorn;us tyde bus it nedes."</L>
<L>And so it worthed, for in a wrath &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng swyth</L>
<L>Hym of hys principalite depriues &middot; &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;e Prince fondes</L>
<L N="2312">Anone vnto athens &amp; on &middot; of &thorn;e athell Planettes;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.; <I>but corruptly.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai sayd, saire suld he sike &middot; bot he &thorn;e cite &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>And alexander with hys ost &middot; &thorn;en ayres on fer&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="2315">Attellys hym toward &thorn;e terme &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e tene heres,</L>
<L>And such a word he &thorn;aim wayffez &middot; be writte fro hym-seluen.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="10" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000154.tif" N="132">
<HEAD><B>Decimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I Alexander, &thorn;e aire &middot; &amp; eldest childe hatten</L>
<L>Of kyng Philip &thorn;e fers &middot; &thorn;at fest am in grece,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e quene Olimpades &middot; &thorn;e oddest vnder heuen,</L>
<L N="2322">To all &yogh;ow of Athenes &middot; &thorn;us etill I my sa&yogh;es.</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at my fadere was fey &middot; &amp; farne out o lyue,</L>
<L>And I was sett in his sege &middot; with septour to regne,</L>
<L>Sethen went I with my werriours &middot; in-to &thorn;e west endes,
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>And ay with-out any armes &middot; &thorn;aim all at anys &yogh;olden,</L>
<L>All Europe to myn enpire &middot; enterely &thorn;aim geuyn,</L>
<L N="2328">Euyn to &thorn;e Occiane &middot; out of ald Rome.</L>
<L>Qua &thorn;at vs rekinly resayues &middot; na riddour &thorn;ai tholid,</L>
<L>And all at othire wais wro&yogh;t &middot; we wast &thorn;am for euire.</L>
<L>And now fra &thorn;e marche of Messedone &middot; I meued opon late</L>
<L>&THORN;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e anglis here of Afle &middot; with myne athill dukis,</L>
<L N="2333">And so &thorn;e Thebies &thorn;am ti&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e toun to defende,</L>
<L>And I &thorn;ar pompe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ponpe.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;aire pride &middot; to poudire declined.</L>
<L>To &yogh;ow now write I on &thorn;is wise &middot; &thorn;at, wald &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> me send</L>
<L N="2336">Ten fyne Philisofours<NOTE PLACE="foot">so <I>is written above the line</I>.</NOTE> &middot; to fand with my wittes,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure bur&yogh;es ne &yogh;our bri&yogh;t bees &middot; bidd I &thorn;an nothire,</L>
<L>Bot at &yogh;e knaw me for kyng &middot; &amp; call me &yogh;our lord.</L>
<L>For &amp; &yogh;e nyk now to myn empire &middot; &yogh;our nekis for<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> to bowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bos &yogh;ow bigger<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. biggis.</NOTE> to be &middot; &thorn;en all my bald princes,</L>
<L>Or laite anothire ladis-man &middot; a-losed mare of strenth</L>
<L>&THORN;an I my-selfe or my seggis &middot; be &thorn;e seuent dele."</L>
<L N="2343">&THORN;ire athils of Atenes &middot; &thorn;ir augard clerkis<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an reuerenst &thorn;ai &thorn;e riche seele &middot; &amp; red ouer &thorn;e pistill,</L>
<L>Syne kest vp a crie &middot; with a kene voice at anys,</L>
<L>Sum in comending of his carpe &middot; &amp; on clene it spitid.</L>
<L>A Filisphire &thorn;an on first &middot; before &thorn;e folke risis,</L>
<L N="2348">Ane Eschilus in erde &middot; &amp; ernstly he spekis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e douth &amp; all diuinours &middot; be-dene he comaundis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld corde be na cas &middot; vn-to &thorn;e kingis hestis.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at all samen on a sopp &middot; semblis &thorn;e pupill,</L>
<L N="2352">A doctour, ane Domystyne &middot; &thorn;ai derely beseke</L>
<L>To consaile &thorn;aim als in &thorn;e cause &middot; &amp; ken &thorn;am &thorn;e best.</L>
<L>And he rekinly rase &middot; &amp; rekyns &thorn;ire wordis:</L>
<L>"I be-seke &yogh;ow now, my citi&yogh;ens &middot; if &thorn;at &yogh;e safe vouche,</L>
<L N="2356">Bot sobirly a sete quile &middot; my sa&yogh;es for to here.</L>
<L>Sirs, if &yogh;e fele &yogh;ow so fers &middot; his force to with-stand,</L>
<L>Aires agaynes him with armes &middot; admitts no&yogh;t his sa&yogh;es.</L>
<L>And if<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> fy, <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;e fynde &yogh;e be to faynt &middot; fulfillis his will,
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="136"></L>
<L N="2360">Vn-to his mekill maieste &middot; mekely &yogh;ow bowe.</L>
<L>For Sexes in sum time &middot; surmountid all kyngis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it li&yogh;t he law at &thorn;e last &middot; for all his lethire prid.</L>
<L>Bot Alexander with his armee &middot; in alkin rewmys</L>
<L N="2364">Has happend &yogh;it ai hedire-to &middot; &thorn;e herre of his faes;</L>
<L>Vnnombirable ere &thorn;e notis &middot; to neuen of his weres,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it betid neuir &thorn;e time &middot; &thorn;at euire tuke he schame.</L>
<L N="2367">Ware no&yogh;t &thorn;e tulkis out of Tire &middot; &thorn;e tidiest on erth,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kiddest kni&yogh;tis to a-count &middot; vnder &thorn;e cape of heuen,</L>
<L>Quat bathe for corage &amp; kene &middot; &amp; connyng in armes?</L>
<L>Loke quare it profet &thorn;am a peese &middot; all &thorn;aire proud strenth.</L>
<L>Was no&yogh;t &thorn;e Thebes &thorn;ar-to &middot; &thorn;e threyest<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. theyest; <I>with a third</I> e <I>above</I> y.</NOTE> of othire,<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2372">&THORN;e worthiest wees of &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; of witt clerest,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at &thorn;aire cites ware sett &middot; &thorn;e sotelest of weres?</L>
<L>Quat seruyd all &thorn;ai sapient &middot; or sle&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sele&yogh;t; <I>altered to</I> sle&yogh;t.</NOTE> of batall?</L>
<L>Of Poliponenses &thorn;e pupill &middot; with &thorn;is prince fo&yogh;ten,</L>
<L N="2376">And &thorn;at &thorn;am lethirly con like &middot; by &thorn;e lattir ende,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;aire kythe &middot; was killid doun &amp; heded,</L>
<L>His renkis raymed all &thorn;e route &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e rewme &yogh;olden.</L>
<L N="2379">Wate &yogh;e no&yogh;t wele &thorn;ur&yogh;e all &thorn;e werd &middot; how wirdis with him cheues?</L>
<L>Hase he no&yogh;t cites butt saute &middot; sesyd out of nounbre?</L>
<L>And for Strasagirs &thorn;e strang &middot; he of his strenth priued,</L>
<L N="2382">&YOGH;e meue al &thorn;us malicoly &middot; his maieste a-gayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;are do &yogh;e no&yogh;t &yogh;our deuire &middot; &thorn;at dare I wele proue,</L>
<L>It was &thorn;e gilt all of &thorn;e gome &middot; &amp; no&yogh;t of &thorn;e gud lord.</L>
<L>Ne had he trispast him to &middot; I take it on my trouthe,</L>
<L>Had neuire his cite ne his soile &middot; be sesid fra him nouthire.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e auaunt ser Alexander &middot; is all &thorn;e werd famyd</L>
<L N="2388">For ane of &thorn;e curtast kyng &middot; &thorn;at euir croune werid,</L>
<L>And wete &yogh;e wele at slik a we &middot; at is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> wyse halden,</L>
<L>He wald neuire suprise &middot; no sege vndir heuen."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at all of Atenenys &middot; &thorn;is aunceant maistir,
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="138"></L>
<L N="2392">And clene all &thorn;e clergy &middot; comensure &amp; othire,</L>
<L>&THORN;is diuinour Domestyne &middot; bedene &thorn;ai comendid,</L>
<L>A-cordis &thorn;aim to his consaile &middot; &amp; kendly it prased.</L>
<L>&THORN;an amed &thorn;ai to ser Alexander &middot; onane for to send</L>
<L N="2396">A croune all of clere gold &middot; clustrid with gemmes,</L>
<L>Of fyfty ponde with &thorn;e payse &middot; as &thorn;e prose<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. prorose.</NOTE> tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;is tresoure tire &thorn;ai him to &middot; &amp; tribute him hetes.</L>
<L>Now ere &thorn;e sandismen<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sandisment.</NOTE> &middot; sett on &thorn;aire horsis,<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2400">A Ientill man &thorn;at Iowell &middot; enioyned was to kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was full sekirly &amp; soft &middot; all in silke falden;</L>
<L>Bot clerkis to &thorn;e conquirour &middot; caired with &thorn;aim many.</L>
<L>&THORN;an movis furth &thorn;e messagere &middot; of mylis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. mylid, <I>altered to</I> mylis.</NOTE> bot fewe,</L>
<L N="2404">&THORN;at &thorn;ai nere li&yogh;t as belyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bely, <I>altered to</I> belyue.</NOTE> &middot; at &thorn;e kyngis tentis,</L>
<L>Knelid doun befor &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; him &thorn;e croune rechid,</L>
<L>And &yogh;erely tribute him to geue &middot; &yogh;apely him hetis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an takis &thorn;e gudman &thorn;e gifte &middot; &amp; gretly &thorn;am &thorn;ankis,</L>
<L N="2408">And vndirstandis in a stound &middot; how it stude clene,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e eging of Eschilus &middot; &thorn;at ertid his feris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai with-sitt suld his sa&yogh;es &middot; &amp; serue no&yogh;t his pistill.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dities of Domestiane &middot; so did he bathe,</L>
<L N="2412">&THORN;at comaundid &amp; his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> comandmentis &middot; to kepe in all wyse,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it neuire-&thorn;e-lattir to &thorn;a ledis &middot; a lettir he fourmed,</L>
<L>In presidine with his awen<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. awent, <I>altered to</I> awen.</NOTE> prince &middot; reportand &thorn;a wordis:</L>
<L>&para; "I, kyng Philip son &thorn;e fers &middot; &amp; his faire ladis,</L>
<L N="2416">Honoured Olimpades &middot; &thorn;at I obesche maste,</L>
<L>I kepe neuire king to be callid &middot; ne cache me &thorn;at name,</L>
<L>Till all &thorn;e barbarine blude &middot; a-bowe to &thorn;e grekis.</L>
<L N="2419">I etill neuir Athenes &middot; with armes for to entre,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;ow to question enquere &middot; &amp; qwete with my wittis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. handis, <I>altered to</I> wittis.</NOTE></L>
<L>I purpose ay out of repreue &middot; &yogh;oure persons to leue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e &thorn;e contrari clene &middot; &yogh;oure concience it opence.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Bot quilk as first of &yogh;ow foundis &middot; a fote vs agayne,</L>
<L N="2424">Sall neuir deuoide my dedeyne &middot; ne my derfe ire.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e at wickid ere within &middot; ay wickidly &yogh;e thinke;</L>
<L>For as &thorn;e grayne is in &thorn;e grape &middot; growis &thorn;e frutis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Tebies tulkid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; perhaps for</I> tukkid.</NOTE> vs with tene &middot; a-tired &thorn;am in armes,<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it rad for all &thorn;aire rebelte &middot; resayued &thorn;ai &thorn;aire medis.</L>
<L>And for Strasagera &thorn;e stoute &middot; &yogh;e stithli me blamed,</L>
<L N="2430">&THORN;are as he gilt me agayns &middot; &amp; I him gradid haue,</L>
<L>I wrate to &yogh;ow at me to wayue &middot; be ten wyse clerkis;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e kest out comaundmentis &middot; &yogh;e knew no&yogh;t my strenth.</L>
<L N="2433">I mi&yogh;t a-coupe of &thorn;at cause &middot; if I it kythe wald;</L>
<L>Bot I for-geue &yogh;ow all &thorn;e gilt &middot; &amp; greues me na mare.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i bees glad now, all &thorn;e gingis &middot; &yogh;e sall na gref haue,</L>
<L N="2436">&THORN;e diuinour<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. duinour.</NOTE> domestyne &middot; for &yogh;e his domes held."</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;ai consayued had &thorn;e clause &middot; &amp; construed &thorn;e lettir,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware &thorn;e meriest modirsons &middot; on morne mi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> ryse.</L>
<L>&para; Now fonndis furth &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; &amp; flittis with his ostes,</L>
<L N="2440">Lendis him to Lacedoyne &middot; a litill fra &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>With-out &thorn;e bur&yogh;e on a banke &middot; he bildis his tentis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are him-selfe with a somme &middot; in a sege le[n]gis.</L>
<L N="2443">&THORN;e ledis out of Lacedone &middot; belyue &thorn;am asemble,</L>
<L>Said, "bow we neuir to his bode &middot; for bale apon erth,</L>
<L>Ne lat vs neuir be sa lethire &middot; at we like worthe</L>
<L>To &thorn;am of Ateynes &middot; it is oure opyn schame;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai ware baist of his bost &middot; bredid for no&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="2448">Bot be we kni&yogh;tly &amp; kene &middot; oure corage to schew."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai &yogh;arkid to &thorn;e &yogh;atis &middot; &amp; &yogh;ode to &thorn;e wallis,</L>
<L>Sum in Iopons, sum in Iesserantis &middot; sum Ioyned all in platis.</L>
<L>A grayne of &thorn;e grete see &middot; &thorn;aim aboute glidis;</L>
<L N="2452">For-&thorn;i buskis &thorn;am &thorn;e burgh &middot; a bataill with-out,</L>
<L>Preses furth at posternes &middot; in-to &thorn;e porte wyndis,</L>
<L>Schalkis scott in-to shipis &middot; all in shire mailes;</L>
<L>Archars with arows &middot; with attrid barbis,
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="142"></L>
<L N="2456">Gais &thorn;am in-to galays &middot; &amp; grathis &thorn;am be-forne.<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bowes bernes in-to bargis &middot; with basinettis on heued,</L>
<L>Sparrethis spetous to spend &middot; &amp; speris in handis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai crosse ouir toward &thorn;e kyng &middot; as kyndmen suld,</L>
<L N="2460">With as feyle on &thorn;e flode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; as fo&yogh;ten with-in.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord him lokis on &thorn;e ledis &middot; &amp; a litill smyles,</L>
<L>And sent twa vndir his seele &middot; &thorn;ir sa&yogh;es in a pistill.</L>
<L>&para; "I, Philip son &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; as I first sayd,</L>
<L N="2464">And als of Olimpades &middot; I anely &yogh;ow rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e end of &yogh;oure eldirs &middot; enterely &yogh;e be-hald,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be <I>added in margin.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And roomes no&yogh;t at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e ray[n]bowe &middot; &thorn;at reche &yogh;e ne may,</L>
<L N="2467">And &thorn;e powere of &thorn;e Persens &middot; so truly &yogh;e traist.</L>
<L>Lat se now, getis &yogh;ow a name &middot; &amp; naytis &yogh;our stre[n]the;</L>
<L>Bot bowis first fra &yogh;our bargis &middot; &amp; blythly &thorn;aim wayfe,</L>
<L>For, fest I all on a fire &middot; &thorn;e foly is &yogh;oure awen."</L>
<L N="2471">Ledis out of Lacedone &middot; quen &thorn;ai &thorn;e lettir redd,</L>
<L>Were drery, bot for all &thorn;e dole &middot; &thorn;a di&yogh;t &thorn;aim to fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng &amp; his kni&yogh;tis &middot; vm-clappis &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Settis all &thorn;e gailis on gledis &middot; &amp; girdis doun &thorn;e wallis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e citi&yogh;ens &amp; seriantis &middot; at vne-slayne ware</L>
<L N="2476">Bowis &thorn;am to &thorn;is baratour &middot; bodis &amp; lyuys.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e knaw wele," quod &thorn;e conquirour &middot; "my comyng was esye;</L>
<L>Bot for &yogh;e fangid me no&yogh;t faire &middot; fired is &yogh;our schippis,</L>
<L N="2479">&YOGH;our bur&yogh;e is bretind &amp; &yogh;our bernes &middot; I bed &yogh;ow my-selfe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e suld no&yogh;t stody ne stem &middot; &thorn;e sternes for to handill.</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at steppis on a stee &middot; quen &thorn;e staues failis,</L>
<L>&THORN;an fautis him festing to his fete &middot; &amp; fall him be-houes;</L>
<L>So, ri&yogh;t as Sexis was slayn &middot; sum time with &yogh;our eldirs,</L>
<L>So ettild &yogh;e ser Alexander &middot; bot &thorn;are &yogh;oure ame failes."<MILESTONE N="43a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;is sa&yogh;e had &thorn;am said &middot; &thorn;e cite he &thorn;am grauntid,</L>
<L>Fondis furth with his folke &middot; &thorn;ar fraunches &thorn;am leues.
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>&THORN;is souerayn with his seggis &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e Sycile<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Sytile.</NOTE> he wyndis,</L>
<L N="2488">&THORN;o&yogh;t to ride &amp; to rayme &middot; &thorn;e regions of barbres.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was ser Darius dred &middot; &amp; sembled derf ostis,</L>
<L>His kni&yogh;tis, his consaill &middot; &amp; carpis &thorn;ire wordis,</L>
<L>Said:"lo! my seris, now may se &middot; &yogh;our-selfe with &yogh;our e&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="2492">How Alexander in his armes &middot; all-way encreses,</L>
<L>In valour &amp; in victori &middot; &amp; vertues so noble;</L>
<L>&THORN;are as I thret him as a thefe &middot; thedis to dispoyle,</L>
<L N="2495">Now werrays he full worthily &middot; as wi&yogh;t man suld,</L>
<L>Constreynes with his contenance &middot; kni&yogh;tis to him bow.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare I spek him dispite &middot; &amp; in my speche hindire,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hi&yogh;ere I here him enhansed &middot; &amp; hersude his name.</L>
<L>A ball &amp; a hernepan &middot; I to &thorn;e barne sent,</L>
<L N="2500">For burde &amp; for bobance &middot; &thorn;e bab with to play.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at I countid bot a knaue &middot; may now be cald maistir;</L>
<L>For quare he fondis on fold &middot; dame fortune him folo&yogh;e[s].</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i <I>added in the margin.</I></NOTE> vs haue bos in hert &middot; &thorn;e hele of oure pupill,</L>
<L N="2504">And for na pompe ne na pride &middot; his person dispice,</L>
<L>For his lose, for all his litillaike &middot; is loued &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e werd.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mare I myn oure maieste &middot; &thorn;e mare it abatis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grace of &thorn;e grete god<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; I ges, will him help,</L>
<L N="2508">Of prise &thorn;e hi&yogh;e prouynce &middot; vn-to &thorn;is prince leues.</L>
<L>Quen we hope althire-hi&yogh;est &middot; to hery him with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> armes,</L>
<L>&THORN;an am I redd all oure rewme &middot; be reft vs for euire."</L>
<L>Sone as ser Dary till his dukis &middot; deuysid had &thorn;ir wordis,<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2512">&THORN;an answars him ane Oriathire &middot; ane of his awen brethire,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou has &thorn;is gome out of grece &middot; so gretly e[n]hansid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we Elanda suld leue &middot; &amp; he &thorn;is landis entre.</L>
<L>Bot wald &yogh;our maieste &thorn;e maners &middot; of &thorn;is man sewe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mi&yogh;t &yogh;oure rewme haue in ryst &middot; &amp; othire rewmes wyn.
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="2517">For Alexander all-ways &middot; or any of his erles,</L>
<L>Naytis him-selfe in ilke nede &middot; &amp; so his name rysis."</L>
<L>"Quat sall I take of him my temes &middot; tittire &thorn;an he myne?"</L>
<L>"Sire, on my perell," quod a prince &middot; "he passes all othire;</L>
<L N="2521">&THORN;e wee wirkis all be witt &middot; he worthis &thorn;e bettir;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i of &thorn;e lion, as I leue &middot; la&yogh;t is his birthe."</L>
<L>"Quat knawis &thorn;ou &thorn;at?" quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;e kni&yogh;t swaris:</L>
<L N="2524">"Sire, I was sent on a sand &middot; my-sell on a time,</L>
<L>To Philip his fadere &middot; to feche oure trouage;</L>
<L>&THORN;are had I si&yogh;t of &thorn;e segg &middot; his sapient I herde.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i plese it to &yogh;our person &middot; &yogh;oure princes a-sembles,</L>
<L N="2528">Of Mede of Mesopotane &middot; &thorn;e men of Itaile,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pupill of Appolomados &middot; &thorn;e panthis folke,</L>
<L>And ma &thorn;at houes to &yogh;our hest &middot; a hundreth &amp; fifti.</L>
<L>Lat vs gedire &thorn;us oure gomes &middot; oure gods will vs help;</L>
<L>And quen he sesse vs sike a sowme &middot; sare will he drede.</L>
<L N="2533">&YOGH;a, bot a wolfe, quod a wee &middot; will were many flokkis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. flolkis, i. e. flokkis.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e grekis &middot; ouire-gos &thorn;e barbers."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is ser Ph[ilip] son &thorn;e fers &middot; of fe&yogh;tand folk</L>
<L>Had semblid ane vnsene sowme &middot; as &thorn;e buke sais,</L>
<L>Twa C. Mille in thede &middot; all<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin</I>.</NOTE> of threuen kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L N="2538">Ridis furth in aray &middot; removis his tentis;</L>
<L N="2538*">. . . . .</L>
<L>Vn-to a watere he wendis &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L N="2540">&THORN;at with &thorn;a marchesmen &middot; Mocian was hatten;</L>
<L>It was clerire &thorn;an cristall &middot; &amp; cole as a chill;<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-in couet oure kyng &middot; his cors for to bathe.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;an wan of his wede &middot; &amp; weschid him all ouire,</L>
<L N="2544">Quare-&thorn;ur&yogh;e he hent slike a harme &middot; at hatirly him greued.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chele eftir chaufing &middot; enchafis so his hernes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was fallen in a feuire &middot; or he first wend.
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>&THORN;an mourned all &thorn;e Messedons &middot; as meruaill ware ellis.</L>
<L N="2548">&THORN;ai sa&yogh;e him so to be seke &middot; said ilkane to othire:</L>
<L>"Be &thorn;is disese to ser Darie &middot; &amp; his dukis knawen,</L>
<L>He sall vs sett on a-saute &middot; &amp; surely en[c]ounbre."</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai were sary &amp; so &middot; na selly me thingke,</L>
<L N="2552">For ay &thorn;e hele of &thorn;e hede &middot; helpis all &thorn;e menbris.</L>
<L>&THORN;an callis to him &thorn;e conquirour &middot; a clerke of his awen,</L>
<L>Ane Philip, his fesisiane &middot; his fare to behald;</L>
<L>Of al manere of medcyne &middot; man &thorn;at maste couthe,</L>
<L N="2556">A &yogh;onge berdles barne &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Said: "lat li&yogh;tly my lord &middot; for in a litill stonde</L>
<L>My-self with a serop &middot; sall saue &yogh;ow be-lyue."</L>
<L>&THORN;an permeon &thorn;e proude &middot; a prince of his ost,</L>
<L N="2560">&THORN;at held &thorn;e erth of Ermonye &middot; &amp; enmyte hadd</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;is clerke of &thorn;e kyngis &middot; &amp; be no cause els</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e lede was loued &middot; &amp; with &thorn;e lord chereschest;</L>
<L>&THORN;an ames he to ser Alexander &middot; on ane slike a pistill:</L>
<L N="2564">"Kepis &yogh;ow," quod he, "conquirour &middot; &amp; caches no&yogh;t his drenke;</L>
<L>For Darius eftir his deth &middot; his do&yogh;ter has him hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ow to sla be som sle&yogh;t &middot; to sese him his landis."</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;e berne no&yogh;t a bene &middot; baist of his wordis,</L>
<L N="2568">He asurid him so sadly &middot; &thorn;e serep he takis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e licor in his awen looue &middot; &thorn;e lettir in &thorn;e tothire,</L>
<L>And in-to Phili[pi]s face &middot; fast<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. face face fast.</NOTE> he behaldis.<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2571">He bad him dred neuire a dele &middot; &amp; it drink swyth,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;e pistill of &thorn;e prince &middot; he put him in hand.</L>
<L>&THORN;e leche lokid ouire &thorn;e lynes &middot; "my lording," he said,</L>
<L>"I am no&yogh;t gilty of &thorn;is gile &middot; be all &thorn;e grete gods!"</L>
<L>As fast was he fysche-hale &middot; &amp; Philip he callis,</L>
<L N="2576">Halsis him full hertly &middot; &amp; of his hele thankis,</L>
<L>Said, "wele knew &thorn;ou my kynd &middot; lufe &thorn;i concience,</L>
<L>First suposid I of &thorn;i serop &middot; syne sesid &thorn;e &thorn;e lettir.</L>
<L>"Mi louely lord, be &yogh;our leue &middot; lattes him a-pere,</L>
<L N="2580">&THORN;e tulk at sike a trayne &middot; has touchid to my-selfe."
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>&THORN;an eftir ser Permes his prince &middot; prestly he sendis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;e trechoure was tane &middot; &amp; for his trayne hedid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an mouys he furth with his men &middot; &amp; Medy he wynnys</L>
<L N="2584">Enterly to his empire &middot; &amp; Ermonye &thorn;e mare.</L>
<L>Till a dissert &thorn;an he drafe &middot; was dry &amp; na watere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ur&yogh;e Adriac till Eufraten &middot; &amp; ames &thorn;are his tentis,</L>
<L>And mas a brig ouire &thorn;e bourne &middot; of Barges<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Bargos.</NOTE> with cheynes;</L>
<L N="2588">Comandis his kni&yogh;tis ouire to caire &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar &thorn;ai vncachid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cachid, <I>with</I> vn <I>above</I>.</NOTE> hertis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sa&yogh;e &thorn;e streme so stife &middot; it stonaid &thorn;am all,</L>
<L>For ferd &thorn;e festing suld faile &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai in &thorn;e flode droune.</L>
<L N="2591">&THORN;an mas he laddis ouire to lend &middot; &amp; lokars of bestis,</L>
<L>And monestis &thorn;am ilk modire-son &middot; him maynly to tell.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was his baratours a-baist &middot; &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;e berne writhis,</L>
<L>Fandis him first on be-fore &middot; &amp; all folo&yogh;es eftir.</L>
<L>&THORN;an passid &thorn;are out of Paradese &middot; twa proude Flummes,</L>
<L N="2596">&THORN;ur&yogh;e Medy &amp; Messopotane &middot; &thorn;ai move, as I fynd,</L>
<L>And so to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> Babilon &thorn;ai bowe &middot; ane is &thorn;e bourne of Tygre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tothire is Eufrates full euen &middot; &amp; rynnes so to Sylus.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cutis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. tutis.</NOTE> &thorn;e kyng in to &thorn;e cablis &middot; &amp; to his kni&yogh;tis sais:<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2600">"Lo! &thorn;of vs fall now to flee &middot; we may na ferryre wend;</L>
<L>&THORN;are I rede," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "oure bakis neuir to turne,</L>
<L>And if we did, with-outen dome &middot; to die all at anes;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at folowid has ai &thorn;e floure &middot; &amp; he at fled neuire.</L>
<L N="2604">Bees li&yogh;t &amp; laches &yogh;ow a lose &middot; it is a lord gamen.</L>
<L>For I make a-vow at Messedone &middot; we sall na mare see,</L>
<L>Till all &thorn;e barbres vs bow &middot; &thorn;an may we blith turne."
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000155.tif" N="133">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I alexander, ayre &middot; &amp; heldest child both</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2320">Off kyng philip &thorn;e fers &middot; &thorn;at fessit am in grece,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e whene olimphades &middot; &thorn;e oddest vnder hevyn,</L>
<L>To all you of atthenys &middot; &thorn;us atthill I my sawes.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at my fader was fey &middot; &amp; fallyn out of lyve,</L>
<L N="2324">And I was sett in hys sege &middot; with septour in hand,</L>
<L>Syne went I with my weryours &middot; in-to &thorn;e west ende,
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai withowtyn armys &middot; &thorn;aim all at onys &yogh;eldyn,</L>
<L N="2327">All europe to my empyre &middot; enterly &thorn;ai geven.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at rekenly vs resaued &middot; no raddour tholett,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at other-wyse wroght &middot; we wastyd for euer.</L>
<L>And now fro &thorn;e marche of massydon &middot; I mefed on late</L>
<L N="2332">Torow &thorn;e anglez of asy &middot; with myne athell Dukez,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e tebes &thorn;aim ty&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e toun to defende,</L>
<L>That I &thorn;air pompe &amp; &thorn;air pride &middot; to powder haue declined.</L>
<L>And now writte I on &thorn;is wise &middot; &thorn;at, wold &yogh;e me send</L>
<L N="2336">Ten<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Then.</NOTE> fyne philosophirs &middot; to fond with my wittez,</L>
<L>Your burghes ne your bryght bees &middot; bidde I none o&thorn;er,</L>
<L><B>Bot</B> &thorn;at &yogh;e knaw me for your kyng &middot; &amp; calle me your Lord.<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For nyk yhe to myne empyre &middot; your nekkys for to bowe,</L>
<L N="2340">&THORN;an bus you bigger to be &middot; &thorn;an all my bald Princes,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er lates ane o&thorn;er lodesman &middot; alosed more of strenth</L>
<L>Then I my-self &amp; my seges &middot; be &thorn;e seuynt dele."</L>
<L>&THORN;oes athels of athens &middot; &thorn;es awgerd Clerkez</L>
<L>&THORN;en reuerenst &thorn;ai &thorn;e riche seale &middot; &amp; red ouer &thorn;e pistell,</L>
<L N="2345">Syne kestyn vp a clene voyce &middot; &amp; cried all at onys,</L>
<L>Some in Commendyng of hys carpyng &middot; &amp; som in dyspysyng.</L>
<L>Than A philisofre<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. philipofre.</NOTE> on &thorn;e frist &middot; before &thorn;at folke ryses,</L>
<L N="2348">Ane Esculus in &thorn;at erde &middot; &amp; egirly spekes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;e.</NOTE> Doughty &amp; all Dyuynours &middot; be-dene he Commandez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld acord be no case &middot; to &thorn;e kyngez heste.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at al sampnes in a sopp &middot; assempbles &thorn;e peple,</L>
<L N="2352">A Doctour, ane Domestyn &middot; &thorn;ai derly besekyn</L>
<L>To Counsell &thorn;aim in &thorn;at cause &middot; &amp; ken &thorn;aim &thorn;e best.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;an rakenly rose &middot; &amp; rekens &thorn;ees wordes:</L>
<L>"I Beseke you now, my citesyns &middot; if &thorn;at &yogh;e saue woche,</L>
<L N="2356">Bot soberly a sete qwyle &middot; my sawys for to herkyn."</L>
<L>And sayd, "if &yogh;e feyle you so ferce &middot; hys force to withstond,</L>
<L>Ayres ayayns hym with armes &middot; admittes noght hys sawes.</L>
<L>And if yhe fynd &yogh;e faynt &middot; fulfyll &thorn;an hys wylle,
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="137"></L>
<L N="2360">Vnto his mekyll mageste &middot; mekely you bowes.</L>
<L>For sexes in som tyme &middot; sirmountyd all kyngez,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it li&yogh;t he lawe at &thorn;e last &middot; for all hys lethir pride.</L>
<L>Bot alexander with hys armes &middot; in alkyn realmes</L>
<L>Hase happynd ay &yogh;it hyder &middot; to &thorn;e hyer of hys foes;</L>
<L N="2365">Vnnowmerable er &thorn;e notez &middot; to nevyn of &thorn;e weres,</L>
<L>And &yogh;itt betyd neuer &thorn;e tyme &middot; &thorn;at euer toke he shame.</L>
<L>Wer noght &thorn;e tulkez of tire &middot; &thorn;e triest of &thorn;e werld,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyddest knyghtez to acount &middot; vnder &thorn;e cope of heuen,</L>
<L>What bath<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>MS. has</I> &thorn;e <I>after</I> bath, <I>but it is struck out</I>.</NOTE> of corage &amp; kene &middot; &amp; connyng of armez?</L>
<L>Loke quar it profett &thorn;am a pese &middot; all &thorn;air proude strenth.</L>
<L>Wer noght &thorn;e tebettes &thorn;arto &middot; &thorn;e tithiest of o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="2372">The worthiest wyes of &thorn;e werld &middot; &amp; of witte clerest,<MILESTONE N="26a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>What seruyd &yogh;itte all &thorn;ar sapience &middot; &amp; sleghtes of were?</L>
<L>Of poliponenses &thorn;e peple &middot; with &thorn;is prince feghten,</L>
<L N="2376">And &thorn;at &thorn;aim lederly con like &middot; &yogh;it at &thorn;e latter ende,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;e kyth &middot; was kyllyd downe &amp; heued,</L>
<L>Hys renkes raymet all &thorn;e route &middot; &amp; hys realme &yogh;olden.</L>
<L N="2379">Wayte &yogh;e noght wele &thorn;orow all &thorn;e werld &middot; how all thyng with hym goys?</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>And for strasagera &thorn;e strang &middot; he of hys strenth priues,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it &yogh;e make you malicoly &middot; hys mageste ayayns.</L>
<L>&THORN;arto yhe do not your Diuour<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Dinuour.</NOTE> &middot; I dar it wele prefe,</L>
<L N="2384">It was &thorn;e gilt of gome &middot; not of &thorn;e gode Lord.</L>
<L>For had he noght trasped hym vnto &middot; I take on my saule,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e graunt of &thorn;e sir alexander &middot; is all &thorn;e werld famed</L>
<L>For one of &thorn;e curtasest kyng &middot; &thorn;at euer crowne weryd,</L>
<L>And wete &yogh;e wele &thorn;at suche a wye &middot; &thorn;at is so wyse haldyn,</L>
<L N="2390">He wald neuer sussprise &middot; no sege vnder heven."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at all &thorn;ise athenez &middot; &amp; &thorn;a auancet maisters,
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="139"></L>
<L N="2392">And Clene all &thorn;e clerge &middot; commensour &amp; o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Thys Diuinour domestyn &middot; by-dene &thorn;ai commendyn,</L>
<L>Acorde &thorn;aim to hys counsell &middot; &amp; kenly it prasen.</L>
<L>Then ameyd &thorn;aim to sir alexander &middot; anone for to send</L>
<L N="2396">A Crowne all of clene gold &middot; clustred with gemmys,</L>
<L>Of fifty pound was &thorn;e passe &middot; as &thorn;e prose tellys,</L>
<L>Thys tresour tire &thorn;ai hym to &middot; &amp; tribute hym highten.</L>
<L>Now er &thorn;e sandesmen in sute &middot; sett on &thorn;ar blonkez,</L>
<L N="2400">A gentilman &thorn;at Iowell &middot; inioneyd was to kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was full sarkenly &amp; full soft &middot; all in sylke falden;</L>
<L>Bot clerkes to &thorn;e conquerour &middot; cayred with &thorn;aim none.</L>
<L>Then meffyd forth &thorn;e messyngers &middot; myles bot a few,</L>
<L N="2404">And li&yogh;t all belyue &middot; at &thorn;e lordes tentes,</L>
<L>Knele downe before &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; hym &thorn;e crowne raughten,</L>
<L>And &yogh;erly tribute hym to gyf &middot; &yogh;apely hym highten.</L>
<L>Than tase &thorn;e godman &thorn;air giftez &middot; &amp; gretly &thorn;aim thankes,</L>
<L N="2408">And vnderstondes in a stound &middot; how it stode clene,</L>
<L><B>And</B> of &thorn;e eggyng of EscuLus &middot; &thorn;at ertyd hys foes,<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To withsitte hys sawe &middot; &amp; serue noght hys pistyll.</L>
<L>The dytes of domestyn &middot; &amp; so dyd of both,</L>
<L N="2412">&THORN;at Counsellyd hys Commaundment &middot; to kepe on all wyse.</L>
<L>Yit neuer-&thorn;e-leter to &thorn;o ledes &middot; a letter he enformed,</L>
<L>In presydence hys Awne prince &middot; reportand &thorn;es wordes:</L>
<L><B>"I, kyng Philipp son &thorn;e ferce &middot; &amp; hys fayre ladys,</B></L>
<L N="2416">Honourd olymphades &middot; &thorn;at I obey most,</L>
<L>I kepe neuer kyng to be called &middot; ne cache me &thorn;at name,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Better</I> Til.</NOTE> all &thorn;e barberon blude &middot; bowe to &thorn;e grekys.</L>
<L N="2419">I attellyd neuer athens &middot; with armes to entre,</L>
<L>Bot you questions to enquire &middot; to wete with my writtes.</L>
<L>And purposed ay out of reproue &middot; your persens to leue,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e &thorn;e contrary clene &middot; in your conscience doys shew.
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>Bot whilke of yow as foundes frist &middot; on fote vs agayns,</L>
<L N="2424">Sall neuer voyde my dysdane &middot; ne my derfe Ire.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e at thynkys wykkydly &middot; &amp; wyrkys agayns;</L>
<L>For as &thorn;e grane is of &thorn;e grase &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar growez &thorn;e frute.</L>
<L>The tebettes tulkyd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Perhaps for</I> tukkyd.</NOTE> vs with tene &middot; atyred &thorn;aim in armys,</L>
<L N="2428">&YOGH;itt for all &thorn;air riallte &middot; resaued &thorn;ai &thorn;air mede.</L>
<L>And for strasagera &thorn;e stout &middot; &yogh;e styfly me blame,</L>
<L>Thar as he giltyd me ayayns &middot; I hym gradit haue,</L>
<L>I wrate to you me to wafe &middot; ten wise clerkez;</L>
<L>Yhe kest out Commandmentes &middot; &amp; knew noght my strenth.</L>
<L N="2433">I might a-coup you of &thorn;at cause &middot; &amp; I it kyth wald;</L>
<L>Bot I forgyfe you all &thorn;e gilt &middot; &amp; grefez me no more.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i beys glade now, all &thorn;e pake &middot; &yogh;e sall no grefe sofre,</L>
<L N="2436">The Diuynour Domestyn &middot; for &yogh;e hys domes halden."</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;ai consaued hed &thorn;e clause &middot; &amp; construed &thorn;e pistyll,</L>
<L>Thai wer &thorn;e meriest modersons &middot; &thorn;at might on morne rise.</L>
<L>Now fonndes he furth &thorn;e fele kyng &middot; &amp; flittes hys ostez,</L>
<L N="2440">. . . . .</L>
<L>Without &thorn;e burgh on a bank &middot; beldit he hys tentez,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar hym-self with a soume &middot; in a sege lenges.</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. To &thorn;e.</NOTE> ledes out of lacydon &middot; belyfe &thorn;aim assembled,</L>
<L>Sayd: "bow we neuer to hys body &middot; for bale vppon erthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. erthd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2445">Ne lett vs neuer be so lethir &middot; &thorn;at we leke worthen<MILESTONE N="27a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;ise out [of] athens &middot; for it wer opyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. orpyn.</NOTE> shame;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai wer basyt for hys beste &middot; &amp; ferd for noght;</L>
<L N="2448">Bot be we knyghtly &amp; kene &middot; oure corage to shew."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai &yogh;arken to &yogh;ates &middot; &amp; &yogh;oden to &thorn;e walles,</L>
<L>Some in Iompons &amp; in Iesserauntez &middot; som Ioned in platez.</L>
<L>A grayne of &thorn;e grete see &middot; glad &thorn;aim all vmbe;</L>
<L N="2452">For-&thorn;i buskys &thorn;aime &thorn;e burgesse &middot; a batale withowt,</L>
<L>Pressen forth at posternes &middot; vnto a place wenden,</L>
<L>Shalkez shotten into shippez &middot; all in shire malys,</L>
<L>Arches with arows &middot; with atterd barbes,
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="143"></L>
<L N="2456">Gone &thorn;aim into galays &middot; &amp; grathen &thorn;aim &thorn;arforne.</L>
<L>Bowyn bernes into bargez &middot; with Basynettes on heued,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. heuend.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sparthys spitous to spend &middot; &amp; speres in handes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai crossyn ouer toward &thorn;e kyng &middot; als kene men shulden,</L>
<L N="2460">With als fele on &thorn;e flode &middot; as foughten within.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord hym lokez on &thorn;e ledes &middot; &amp; a lityll Smylez,</L>
<L>And Send &thorn;aim vnder hys sealle &middot; &thorn;is saughez in a pistyll.</L>
<L>"Myself, philipp &thorn;e fell kyngez [son] &middot; as I first sayd,<NOTE PLACE="marg">epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2464">&amp; als of olimphades &middot; I only you rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e ende of your elders &middot; enterly &yogh;e holden,</L>
<L>And rooues<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> roones.</NOTE> noght at &thorn;e rayne-bowe &middot; &thorn;at reche &yogh;e ne may,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e power of persyens &middot; so purely &yogh;e trasten.</L>
<L>Lettes se, nemmys yow a name &middot; &amp; naytes your strenthe;</L>
<L>Bot bowes first fra your bargez &middot; &amp; blythly &thorn;am woydez,</L>
<L>For fest I al in a fyre &middot; &thorn;e foly is your awne."</L>
<L N="2471">The ledes owt of lacidon &middot; when &thorn;ai &thorn;e lettres herd,</L>
<L>War drery, bot [for] all &thorn;e dole &middot; &thorn;ai dight &thorn;aim to fight.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng &amp; hys knyghtes &middot; vmbelappes &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Sett all &thorn;e Galays on gledes &middot; brynt doun &thorn;e wallez;</L>
<L>The cetyners &amp; &thorn;e sergeantes &middot; all &thorn;at vnslayne weryn</L>
<L N="2476">Bowes &thorn;an to &thorn;e baratour &middot; both bodes &amp; lyfez.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e knowe wele," quod &thorn;e conquerour &middot; "my Commyng was full easy;<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot for<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> &yogh;e fonge me not fair &middot; nowe fyryd er your shippez,</L>
<L>Your borgh es bryttynyd &amp; your berne[s] &middot; I byd you my|seluen,</L>
<L N="2480">&YOGH;e suld nott study ne stem &middot; &thorn;e sternes to byholde.</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at steppys on a stegh &middot; when &thorn;e stoure faylez,</L>
<L>&THORN;en fallys hym &thorn;e festyng of hys fete &middot; &amp; falle hym byhofys;</L>
<L>So ryght as sixes was slayne &middot; some tyme with your aldours,</L>
<L>Als ettled &yogh;e Sir A[lexander]. &middot; bot &thorn;ar your kast faylyd."</L>
<L>When he &thorn;is sagh hed &thorn;aim sayd &middot; &thorn;e Cyte he &thorn;am grauntyd,</L>
<L>Fondes forth with hys folke &middot; &thorn;air franchez &thorn;aim lefys.
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>Thys souerayne with hys seneours &middot; throghe secyll he wendes,</L>
<L N="2488">thoght to ryde &amp; to rame &middot; &thorn;e regions of Barbers.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was sir darius a-drede &middot; &amp; derfly &thorn;an sembles</L>
<L>Hys knyghtes &amp; hys Counsell &middot; &amp; carped &thorn;es wordes,</L>
<L>Sayd: "sirys, nowe may &yogh;e se &middot; your-self with your eey,</L>
<L N="2492">How A[lexander] in hys armys &middot; alway encreses,</L>
<L>In valour &amp; victory &middot; &amp; vertus so noble;</L>
<L>&thorn;ar as I thratt [him] as a thefe &middot; thedes to dispoyle,</L>
<L>Nowe warreys he full worthily<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. worthtly.</NOTE> &middot; als wi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. with.</NOTE> man suld,</L>
<L>Constraynes with hys contenance &middot; knyghtes to bowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e more I speke hym dispite &middot; &amp; in my speche endered,</L>
<L>The heyar I here hym enhaunsyd &middot; &amp; hersud hys name.</L>
<L>A ball &amp; a brayne-pan &middot; I to &thorn;e berne send,</L>
<L N="2500">For burde &amp; for bobance &middot; &thorn;e bab with to play.</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;at I Counte bot a knaffe &middot; may now be callyd [maister];</L>
<L>For whar he ffoundez apon fold &middot; dame fortoune hym sewes,</L>
<L N="2503">For-thi vs hafe buse in hert &middot; &thorn;e heyle of our peple,</L>
<L>And for no pompe ne no pryde &middot; hys person to dispyse,</L>
<L>For hys loyse, ffor all hys hattellayke &middot; is losyt &thorn;orow &thorn;e werld.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e more I meng our maieste &middot; &thorn;e more it debates,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Catchword</I>&mdash;&thorn;e grace.</NOTE></L>
<L>The grace of &thorn;e grete god &middot; I gesse, wele hym helpes,<MILESTONE N="28a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2508">Of pris &thorn;e hegh provynce &middot; vnto &thorn;is prince lefys.</L>
<L>When we hope all &thorn;e heldest &middot; to herye hym with armes,</L>
<L>&THORN;en am I raddest all our realme &middot; be raymed from vs first."</L>
<L>Sone as sir Dary to hys dukez &middot; devysed hase &thorn;ees wordez,</L>
<L N="2512">&THORN;en answers hym oryather &middot; on of hys awne brether,</L>
<L>"Now hase &thorn;is gome oute of grece &middot; so gretly enhaunsed,</L>
<L>And we &thorn;e lande shuld leve &middot; &amp; he &thorn;e landes entre.</L>
<L N="2515">Bot wald &yogh;our maieste &thorn;e maners &middot; of &thorn;is man sewe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e myght your realme haue in rist &middot; &amp; other landes wynne.
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="147"></L>
<L N="2517">For A[lexander] always &middot; or ony of hys bernes,</L>
<L>Nates hym-self in ony nede &middot; &amp; so hys name rysys."</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>"Sir, on my perell," quod a prince &middot; "he passes all o&thorn;er;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wee wyrches all with witte &middot; &amp; worthes ay &thorn;e better;</L>
<L N="2522">For-&thorn;i of &thorn;e lyon, as I lefe &middot; laght he hys byrth."</L>
<L>"What knawez &thorn;ou &thorn;at?" quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;e knyght answers:</L>
<L N="2524">"Sir, I was send on a sond &middot; my-self on a tyme,</L>
<L>To philip hys fader &middot; to feche hys trowage;</L>
<L>&thorn;ar hed I syght of &thorn;e segge &middot; hys sapiens I herd.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i ples it yowur person &middot; &yogh;our princes assembles,</L>
<L N="2528">Off medy &amp; of mesopothany &middot; &thorn;e men of ytalle,</L>
<L>The peple of appolomados &middot; &thorn;e peranthez folkez,</L>
<L>And mo &thorn;en hewen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; read</I> houen.</NOTE> to your heystez &middot; a hundreth &amp; fyfty.</L>
<L>Let vs gedir to vs our gomez &middot; our goddes wyll vs help;</L>
<L>And when he seys vs suche a sowme &middot; sore wyll he drede.</L>
<L N="2533">&YOGH;a, bot &thorn;en a wolfe, quod &thorn;e we &middot; wyll wery mony flokkez,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e grekez &middot; ouergose &thorn;e barbres."</L>
<L>By &thorn;is sir philip son &thorn;e fers &middot; of fightand bernes</L>
<L>Had semblyd hym a sowme vnsene &middot; &amp; &thorn;us says &thorn;e text,</L>
<L>Two hundreth thousand in thede &middot; all of thro knyghtez.</L>
<L N="2538">Rydez furth in aray &middot; remewys hys tentes,<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2538*">And thoght to loge &thorn;ar &amp; rest &middot; &amp; ease hym &thorn;at nyght.</L>
<L>Vntill a water he wendes &middot; as &thorn;e writt shewys,</L>
<L N="2540">&THORN;at with &thorn;e marche-men &middot; of Mocian es haldyn;</L>
<L>Clerar &thorn;en cristall &middot; &amp; cold as a chyll;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arin couett &thorn;e kyng &middot; hys Cors to be bathyd.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai wan of hys wedez &middot; &amp; wessh hym all ouer,</L>
<L N="2544">Whar-&thorn;orow he hynt suche a harme &middot; &thorn;at hetterly hym grefyd.</L>
<L>The chele after chawfyng &middot; enchafys so hys harmes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was fallen in a feuer &middot; or he lest wende.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>&THORN;en murnyd all &thorn;e massydons &middot; as murvell wer ellez.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai hym sawe so be seke &middot; sayd ichone to o&thorn;er:</L>
<L>"Be &thorn;is disease to sir Dary &middot; &amp; to hys dukez knawyn,</L>
<L>He sall vs sett on a-saute &middot; &amp; surely vs Combre."</L>
<L N="2551">Yff &thorn;ai wer sory &amp; so &middot; no selly me thynke,</L>
<L>For ay &thorn;e heylh of &thorn;e hede &middot; helpis all &thorn;e membrys.</L>
<L>&THORN;en callys to hym &thorn;e Conquerour &middot; a clerke of hys Awne,</L>
<L>On philipp, hys fysycyan &middot; hys fare to byholde;</L>
<L>Off all maner of medycine &middot; man &thorn;at most kowth,</L>
<L N="2556">A &yogh;ong berdles<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> d <I>is above the line</I>.</NOTE> bern &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellys,</L>
<L>Sayd: "letes lyghtly my lord &middot; for in a lytyll stounde</L>
<L>My-self with a Syrope &middot; shall safe you bylyfe."</L>
<L>&THORN;en was &thorn;ar permeon &thorn;e prouud &middot; a prince of his hoste,</L>
<L N="2560">&THORN;at held &thorn;e erth of Ermony &middot; &amp; enmyte hed</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;is Clerke of &thorn;e kengez &middot; &amp; be no cause ellez</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e lede was lofed &middot; &amp; with &thorn;e lord cheryst;</L>
<L>&THORN;en says he to sir A[lexander] &middot; anone suche a pystyll:</L>
<L N="2564">"Kepys you," quod he, "Conquerour &middot; &amp; kachez nott hys drynkez;</L>
<L>For Darius after hys deth &middot; hys doghter hase hym hyght,</L>
<L>And you to sla by som slyght &middot; to seyse hym hys landez."</L>
<L>Yitt was &thorn;e bern not a beyne &middot; bassyd of hys wordez,</L>
<L N="2568">He assuryd hym so sadly &middot; &thorn;e syroppe he fangez,</L>
<L>&THORN;e licour in hys Awne lofe &middot; &thorn;e letter in &thorn;e to&thorn;er,</L>
<L>And into philipp face &middot; fast he byholdes.<MILESTONE N="29a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He bad hym drede neuer a dele &middot; bot drynke it Swyth,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en &thorn;e pistyll of &thorn;e prince &middot; he put hym in hand.</L>
<L>The leche lukyd ouer &thorn;e lynes &middot; "my lordyng," he sayd,</L>
<L>"I ne am noght gylty of &thorn;is &middot; by all &thorn;e godes owte!"</L>
<L>Als fast was he fyssh-hole &middot; &amp; philip he clepys,</L>
<L N="2576">Halsys hym full hertly &middot; &amp; of hys heylle thankez,</L>
<L>Sayd, "wele knew &thorn;ou my kynde &middot; &thorn;i conscience I lofe,</L>
<L>First suppyd of &thorn;i syroppe &middot; syne sesyd &thorn;e my letter.</L>
<L N="2579">"My lofely Lord, be &yogh;our leffe &middot; lettes hym apere,</L>
<L>The tulke &thorn;at suche a trayne &middot; has attachyd to my-seluen."
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>&THORN;en after for permeon hys prince &middot; prestely he sendes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar &thorn;e trechour was tane &middot; &amp; for hys trayne hated.</L>
<L>&THORN;en mevys he forth with hys men &middot; &amp; medy he wynnez</L>
<L N="2584">Enterly to hys empyre &middot; &amp; Ermonye &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>To a deserte &thorn;en he drof &middot; was dry &amp; no waterez,</L>
<L>Throgh andriake to eufraten &middot; &amp; settes &thorn;ar hys tentes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I>&mdash;And &thorn;e knyghtez of &thorn;e coste as &thorn;ai &thorn;e case seghen; <I>but this is l.</I> 2641, <I>out of place</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And askez a brigg ouer &thorn;e burne &middot; of bargez with chynez;</L>
<L N="2588">Commandes hys knyghtez ouer to carye &middot; &thorn;ai hed kokell hertes,</L>
<L>Seghen &thorn;e streme be so styff &middot; &thorn;ai stoned &thorn;e helder,</L>
<L>For lest &thorn;e festynyng had faylyd &middot; &amp; &thorn;aim &thorn;e flude drenchyd.</L>
<L N="2591">&THORN;en makys laddes ouer to lend &middot; &amp; lokers of bestes,</L>
<L>And monyshyd &thorn;en iche moderson &middot; &thorn;aim manly to sewe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;itt wer hys baratours abaist &middot; &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;e bern wrothed,</L>
<L>Foundez first on before &middot; &amp; all folows after.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar passys owt of paradyse &middot; twa brade flomes,</L>
<L N="2596">Throgh medy &amp; mesopothany &middot; &thorn;ai mouen, as I fynd,</L>
<L>And so to babyloyne &thorn;ai bowe &middot; &thorn;at is &thorn;e burne of tigre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er is eufrates full euen &middot; rynnez so to Nilus.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Cuttes &thorn;e kyng in two hys cablys &middot; &amp; to hys knyghtes says:</L>
<L>"Lo! &thorn;of vs fallys nowe to flee &middot; we may no ferre wend;</L>
<L N="2601">&THORN;arfore I breke," quod &thorn;e berne &middot; "our bakkez neuer to torne,</L>
<L>And if we did, withowtyn dome &middot; to dye all at ones;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at folows hase &thorn;e floure &middot; &amp; he flees neuer.<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2604">Be light &amp; lachys &thorn;ou lose &middot; it is a lordez gamme.</L>
<L>For I make a-wowe &thorn;at massydoyn &middot; shall see vs no more,</L>
<L>Tyll all &thorn;e barbrens vs bowe &middot; &thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> may we blyth bee."
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="11" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000174.tif" N="152">
<HEAD><B>Vndecimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now has ser Darie &thorn;e derfe &middot; of dukis &amp; princes</L>
<L>Heued vp a hoge ost &middot; &amp; fyue hundreth kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L N="2609">Ere chosen to chiftans &middot; &amp; chargid &thorn;aim to lede;</L>
<L>Trottis him on to Tigre<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Tirgre, <I>corrected to</I> Tigre.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; &thorn;are his tentis settis;</L>
<L>&THORN;an mett &thorn;ai on &thorn;e o&thorn;ire morne &middot; with a mekill nombre,</L>
<L N="2612">Sire Alexander &thorn;e hathill &middot; armed on blonkis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e multitude ware to me &middot; meruaile to reken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sammed was on ai&thorn;ir side &middot; many sadd thousand.</L>
<L>Now ere &thorn;e baners out bred &middot; &amp; &thorn;e bate ne&yogh;is,</L>
<L N="2616">Blew bemys of bras &middot; buskis to-gedire,</L>
<L>&THORN;e crie of &thorn;e clarions &middot; &thorn;e cloudis it persyd;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e dewt<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> dowt.</NOTE> of &thorn;e dyn &middot; daunced stedis.</L>
<L N="2619">Bathe &thorn;e twa batails &middot; bremely assemblis,</L>
<L>And aithire segg with his sowme &middot; so&yogh;t vn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> othire.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tis on cursours &middot; kest &thorn;an in fewtire,</L>
<L>Taches in-to targetis &middot; tamed &thorn;aire brenys.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was stomling of stedis &middot; sticking of erles,</L>
<L N="2624">Sharpe schudering of schote &middot; schering of mailes,</L>
<L>So stalworthly within a stond &middot; sterid &thorn;aim &thorn;e grekis,<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e barb[r]yne blod &middot; all &thorn;e fild flowis.</L>
<L>Sone as ser Darie &thorn;e deth &middot; of his douth sees,</L>
<L N="2628">&THORN;e pite of &thorn;e Persens &middot; him prickis in his saule,</L>
<L>Sees his mene&yogh;e so mynesch &middot; &amp; his men fangid,</L>
<L>A few &thorn;at fresch ware vndefoulid &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t tournes.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was ane of his ost &middot; ane odd man of strenth,</L>
<L N="2632">A burly berne &amp; a bald &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>A segg at he ensurid had &middot; to sese him his do&yogh;tir,</L>
<L>If he mi&yogh;t sla with any sle&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e seniour of grece.</L>
<L>He cled him all in clene stele &middot; a conyschaunce ouire,</L>
<L N="2636">&THORN;at made was &amp; merkid &middot; on &thorn;e messedone armes,</L>
<L>Aires him to ser Alexander &middot; in all-&thorn;ir-mast puple,
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>As he a hathill ware of his &middot; behind him he stelis,</L>
<L>A bri&yogh;t brynnand brand &middot; he braidis out of shethe,</L>
<L N="2640">And &thorn;ur&yogh;e-out &thorn;e helme in-to &thorn;e hede &middot; he hurt him a littill.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e kni&yogh;tis of oure cost &middot; as &thorn;ai &thorn;e cas sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;an fange &thorn;ai &thorn;is ilk freke &middot; &amp; be-fore &thorn;e kyng bryngis.</L>
<L>"Quat now? my worthi werreours?" &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng said,</L>
<L N="2644">He wend wele at he ware &middot; a wee of his awen,</L>
<L>"Qui has &thorn;ou brest so my brayn &middot; &amp; with a brand wondid</L>
<L>&YOGH;our sekire seruant in same &middot; all were I sire callid,</L>
<L>All ware I halden as for hede &middot; &yogh;our helpere at nede?"</L>
<L N="2648">"Nay, hope &yogh;e neuire," quod &thorn;e hathil &middot; "ser hi&yogh;e emperoure,</L>
<L>Me any Messedone to be &middot; &thorn;ou ames of &thorn;ine awen,</L>
<L>Bot of cruell kind &middot; comen of barbres.</L>
<L N="2651">And &thorn;is I did for ser Darius &middot; his do&yogh;tir me hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And cordid on &thorn;is condicion &middot; to couple hire to wyfe,</L>
<L>And he went out of &thorn;e werd &middot; to wild all his regne,</L>
<L>To hew &thorn;i hede fra &thorn;i hals &middot; &amp; anys it him shewe."<MILESTONE N="46a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an callis oure kyng him his kni&yogh;tis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The first</I> i <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;aire consaile to frayn,</L>
<L N="2656">"Quat sall be done him for &thorn;is dede?" &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai bedene sware,</L>
<L>Sum, at he hangid suld be hi&yogh;e &middot; sum &thorn;e hede priued,</L>
<L>Sum bedis in a bale-fire &middot; brin him to poudire.</L>
<L>"Quat has he fauted?" quod &thorn;e frek &middot; "&thorn;of he him forced haue</L>
<L N="2660">&THORN;e charges<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. changs, <I>with stroke above</I> gs.</NOTE> of his chiftan &middot; chefely to fill?</L>
<L>He &thorn;at him demes to &thorn;e dede &middot; he dampnes him-selfe,</L>
<L>And di&yogh;tis him his awen dome &middot; &amp; &thorn;at dare I proue.</L>
<L N="2663">For demed I any of my douth &middot; ser darye to spill,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e &thorn;is gentill man enioyne &middot; suld him be iugid &thorn;en."
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="156"></L>
<L>He latis &thorn;e Persyn in pesse &middot; pas with his hele,</L>
<L>Mekill for his mayn strenth &middot; &amp; for his mi&yogh;t praysed.</L>
<L N="2667">As sone as Darye &thorn;e derfe &middot; of &thorn;is dede heris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> sauyd vnslayne &middot; he semblis his kny&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Vp to a mi&yogh;ti montayne &middot; his men &thorn;aire he schewis,</L>
<L>And gessis him wele &thorn;are to degrayd &middot; &thorn;e grekis maistir.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fandis he furth in-to &thorn;e fild &middot; &amp; fled als beliue,</L>
<L N="2672">And Alexander with his ost &middot; him asperly folowed</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e bu[r]&yogh;e of Batran &middot; &amp; bildid &thorn;are his tentis,</L>
<L>Mas him glad<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ginge glad, <I>with</I> ginge <I>struck through.</I></NOTE> with his ginge &middot; &amp; to his godis offirs.</L>
<L N="2675">&THORN;e cite &thorn;an he assailid &middot; &amp; sesid on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;e bur&yogh;es &thorn;are a-boute &middot; &amp; busked &thorn;are his sete.</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand he tresour vntald &middot; &amp; als &thorn;e trew spouse</L>
<L>Of ser Dary, bath his dame &middot; &amp; all his dere childire.</L>
<L>Now dose him fra Darius &middot; a dereworth prince,</L>
<L N="2680">Aires to ser Alexander &middot; adoures him lawe,</L>
<L>"I haue erdid with &yogh;oure enmy &middot; ser emperoure," he said,</L>
<L>"As soiet serued haue I &thorn;at sire &middot; many sere wyntir;</L>
<L>And all my trauaill I tint &middot; for tuke I no gudes.<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2684">Bot wald it now &yogh;our worthines &middot; to wend with my-selfe,</L>
<L>A ten Mille vs take &middot; of tulkis enarmed,</L>
<L>I sall &yogh;ow hete in &yogh;oure hand &middot; to haue at &yogh;oure will</L>
<L>Sire Dary, with &thorn;e mast dole &middot; of his derfe erles."</L>
<L N="2688">"Nay, leue, lat ane," quod &thorn;e lord &middot; "&thorn;en leue I<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. leu&emacr; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>; <I>with</I> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> <I>altered to</I> I.</NOTE> no straungers,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou be willi in &thorn;i witt &middot; to werray &thorn;ine awen,</L>
<L>Ne tell &thorn;ou me no&yogh;t &thorn;at tale &middot; I trow no&yogh;t &thorn;i wordis."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is ser Dary fro his dukis &middot; deuysid his pistill:</L>
<L N="2692">&THORN;e kyng of kyngs was callid &middot; &amp; clere god bathe,</L>
<L>&THORN;us, vndirstand I, was &thorn;e stile &middot; &amp; sti&yogh;t in &thorn;are-eftir:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> estir.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&yogh;our satrapaires, &yogh;our seruant &middot; with seruand obeschen;
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>Sire, we haue wayued to &yogh;ow writtis &middot; &yogh;it write we &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="2696">How &thorn;is maistir of Messedone &middot; has on oure marchis entrid,</L>
<L>Brynd vp oure biggingis &middot; bretted oure kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>And we ouire-sett be to sare &middot; to suffire any langire.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &yogh;our dignite bydene &middot; we drerily be-seke,</L>
<L N="2700">A gayns &thorn;e force of oure faa &middot; vs forthire a quile."</L>
<L>Quen he had red all &thorn;e rawis &middot; for rancour he swellis,</L>
<L>And out on-ane to Alexander &middot; all &thorn;us he writis.</L>
<L>"I, Dary, with &thorn;e dignite &middot; &thorn;e diademe of Persee,</L>
<L N="2704">Of all &thorn;e kyngis &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;at corouned was euire,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, my seruand, I say &middot; as me was sent late,</L>
<L>How &thorn;i lawnes &amp; &thorn;i litillaike &middot; &thorn;ou lickyns to my hi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot parde, &thorn;i prouidence &middot; inpossible it semes,</L>
<L N="2708">A heuy As to be houyn &middot; vp to &thorn;e sternes,</L>
<L>A thing threuyn is &amp; thike &middot; &amp; &thorn;arnes &thorn;e wyngis,</L>
<L>And fautis &thorn;e fethirhames &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fli&yogh;t-loomes.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;i mynd neuir &thorn;e mare &middot; lat mounte in-to pride</L>
<L N="2712">For chance of na cheualry &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou a-cheued hase.</L>
<L>For vertu ne no victori &middot; ne vant noght &thorn;i-selfe;<MILESTONE N="47a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at enhansis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ens enhansis; <I>with</I> ens <I>expuncted.</I></NOTE> him to he&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;e heldire he declynes.</L>
<L>I haue herd of &thorn;i hendlaike &middot; of heraudis &amp; of othire,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i noblay now o newe time &middot; a-nentes my modire.</L>
<L N="2717">Bathe to my wyfe &amp; to my barnes &middot; quat bounte &thorn;ou shewis,</L>
<L>Quat curtassy &amp; kyndlaike &middot; I ken alto-gedire.</L>
<L>Bot surely all &thorn;e seson &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;am so pleses,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou fangis me neuire to &thorn;i frynd &middot; fyne quen &thorn;e likis.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou wirke &thorn;aim all &thorn;e wa &middot; &amp; wrak at &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare vnfryndschip &thorn;arfore &middot; fall sall &thorn;e neuire;</L>
<L N="2723">For-&thorn;i to put &thorn;am to pyne &middot; I pray &thorn;e no&yogh;t wande,</L>
<L>For myn angire on &thorn;ine arrogance &middot; sall at &thorn;e last kindill."</L>
<L>. . . . . </L>

<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="160">
<L>Quen he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line.</I></NOTE> had lokid ouir &thorn;e lines &middot; he la&yogh;es at his wordis,</L>
<L>And ditis agayn to ser Dary &middot; &thorn;is dete &thorn;at folo&yogh;es:</L>
<L>&para; "I, Alexander, &thorn;e eldest &middot; &amp; all myne ane</L>
<L N="2728">Of kyng Ph[ilip] &amp; his fere &middot; &thorn;at frely lady,</L>
<L>Honourd Olimpades &middot; &thorn;at anely me fosterd,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng of Persy &middot; &thorn;is prolouge I write:</L>
<L>Sire, vanite &amp; vayne-glori &middot; &amp; vices of pride</L>
<L N="2732">&THORN;a ere &thorn;e gaudis, as I gesse &middot; &thorn;at all gods hatis,</L>
<L>And ilka dedly douth &middot; &thorn;ai driffe &thorn;am to punesch,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has dri&yogh;ten of vndedlynes &middot; dra&yogh;en &thorn;aim to name.</L>
<L>&THORN;is similitude to &thorn;i-selfe &middot; I say all-to-gedire,</L>
<L N="2736">&THORN;at a-suris so in &thorn;i surquitry &middot; &amp; sesis neuire-mare</L>
<L>To bost ne to blasfeme &middot; blyn will &thorn;ou nouthire.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;i gold &amp; &thorn;i gudis &middot; a god &thorn;ou &thorn;e makis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou vp-braydis me for &thorn;e beute &middot; &thorn;at I &thorn;i blod schewid,</L>
<L N="2740">As to &thorn;i modire I mene &middot; &amp; to &thorn;i mery childir,</L>
<L>&THORN;are mas &thorn;ou &thorn;e to malicole &middot; &amp; meenes for litill.</L>
<L>I wro&yogh;t it no&thorn;ire for &thorn;i will &middot; ne for &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line.</I></NOTE> wale threte.<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If I kid &thorn;am curtassy &middot; it come fra my-selfe,</L>
<L N="2744">Haly of oure awen hert &middot; &amp; of oure hynd thewis;</L>
<L>Ne we prid vs for na prouwis &middot; predestayned we ere,</L>
<L>Oure gods gayn vs &thorn;are-to &middot; &thorn;at gretly &thorn;ou spises.</L>
<L N="2747">Latt now &thorn;is lettre be &thorn;e last &middot; &amp; loke to &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>For sekire &amp; on my surement &middot; I seke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. se slk, <I>blotted, and altered to</I> seke <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;ow agayns."</L>
<L>&THORN;is brefe he bedis &thorn;am to bere &middot; &thorn;at bro&yogh;t him &thorn;e to&thorn;ire,</L>
<L N="2750">And takis &thorn;am of his tresoure &middot; &amp; twynnes with &thorn;aim faire.</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;ai to Persy ware past &middot; a pistill he enfourmes,</L>
<L>Wrate a writt of his will &middot; so sendis to his princes,</L>
<L>His seruandis &amp; his seneschalls &middot; out of sere rewmes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us comandis he &thorn;am clene &middot; &thorn;e kyng his stile.</L>
<L>&para; "I, Alexander, &thorn;at as aire &middot; avaunced is in grece,</L>
<L N="2756">&THORN;e son of Ph[ilip] &thorn;e fers &middot; as I first tald,</L>
<L>And als of Olimpades &middot; myne honurable modire,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>&THORN;us send I to my satraparis &middot; my princes &amp; my dukes,</L>
<L>My pers out of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. oft.</NOTE> siphagoyne &middot; salutis &amp; grace,</L>
<L N="2760">Of &thorn;e sele of Surry &middot; my seggis &amp; myn erles,</L>
<L>My kni&yogh;tis out of Capados &middot; &amp; all my kid lordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ledis out of Landace &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e landis out-by.</L>
<L>I comand &yogh;ow on &thorn;e clere faithe &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e my croune a&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="2764">&THORN;at belyue to Alysaundire &middot; &thorn;at is myn awen cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilkane of &yogh;ow send be your-selfe &middot; of sere slayn bestis,</L>
<L>Of fresch &amp; of fyne wro&yogh;t &middot; fellis a thousand,</L>
<L>Sum grayne to be ne&thorn;ire gloues &middot; graythid to my kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="2768">Sum pured pelloure depurid &middot; to put in oure wedis,</L>
<L>Lat kest &thorn;am apon camels &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;at kith lengis,</L>
<L>And aires with &thorn;aim to Eufraten &middot; &thorn;is erand haues in mynd."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was a man, as me mynes &middot; in &thorn;e morne-qwile,<MILESTONE N="48a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2772">Was of ser Daris a duke &middot; &thorn;e derfe Emperoure,</L>
<L>Ane &thorn;at Nostanda was named &middot; &amp; a noble prince,</L>
<L>&THORN;at certified his souerane &middot; &thorn;ir sa&yogh;es in a pistill:</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Dari, duke of ilk a douth &middot; &amp; dri&yogh;ten &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L N="2776">&THORN;e grete glorius god &middot; graythid in &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">'&thorn;i' <I>blotted in</I> MS.</NOTE> trone,</L>
<L>Nostanday, to &yogh;our nobilnes &middot; &thorn;at ay my nek bowis,</L>
<L>With seruage to &yogh;our senurie &middot; my-selfe I comand.</L>
<L>It semed no&yogh;t &yogh;oure seruand &middot; sire, vndistreyned</L>
<L N="2780">Vn-to &yogh;our mekill maieste &middot; &thorn;is mater to write,</L>
<L>Bot I am depely distressid &middot; &thorn;is dede for to wirke,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;is myscheffe to myn &middot; malegrefe my chekis.</L>
<L>For wete it wele &yogh;our worthines &middot; &thorn;at of our wale<NOTE PLACE="foot">faes <I>crossed through</I>.</NOTE> princes</L>
<L N="2784">Twa of &thorn;e tethiest ere tint &middot; &amp; termynd of lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lost was now &thorn;e last day &middot; a litill fra Tygre,</L>
<L>In batail apon bent fild &middot; in-bland with &thorn;e grekis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was I gird to &thorn;e grond &middot; &amp; greuously woundid,</L>
<L>Vnnethe it cheuyd me &thorn;at chance<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. can chance; can <I>struck out.</I></NOTE> &middot; to chape to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fil&yogh;t.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="2789">And o&thorn;ire many of oure men &middot; mi&yogh;tfull kni&yogh;tis,
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>And erlis of all &yogh;our empire<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. emperire.</NOTE> &middot; enterely deuydid,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure lore &amp; &yogh;our legaunce &middot; lethirly forsaken,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. saken forsaken; <I>with</I> saken <I>struck out.</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="2792">Aires &thorn;aim to ser Alexander &middot; &amp; on-ane &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;aim faire vndirfange &middot; enfeffid &thorn;aim belyue,</L>
<L>In palais, in prouince &middot; in principall regnes."</L>
<L N="2795">&THORN;en to Nostanda on next &middot; &thorn;us notis he a lettir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld semple him a sowme &middot; &amp; set &thorn;aim agaynes.</L>
<L>Anothire pistill lete he pas &middot; to Porrus of ynde,</L>
<L>To come &amp; helpe with his here &middot; &amp; he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> him &thorn;us swaris:</L>
<L>&para; "I, Porrus, &thorn;at possessid am &middot; &thorn;e partyse of yynde,</L>
<L N="2800">And am &thorn;e coron be kynd &middot; of clene all &thorn;at Iles,<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sire Dary, with &thorn;i dyademe &middot; drest on &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at salutis I send &middot; &thorn;e sele of myn armes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou prayes vn-to my person &middot; my powere to sempble,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ow enforce with my folke &middot; &yogh;our faes to withstand;</L>
<L>And I am boun at &yogh;our bode &middot; &amp; buxsom was euire,</L>
<L>To he&yogh;e &amp; to help &yogh;our hest &middot; quen I my hele lastis.</L>
<L>Bot now a langour me lettis &middot; &thorn;at I la&yogh;t haue,</L>
<L N="2808">Slike a seknes for-sothe &middot; is on my-selfe halden,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I ne may streyne me ne stere &middot; for stondis so hard,</L>
<L>Bot lyse in langwysches &amp; lokis &middot; quen my lyfe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lefe, <I>corrected to</I> lyfe.</NOTE> endis.</L>
<L>And as warysche I [of] my warke &middot; &thorn;at I am in wonden,</L>
<L N="2812">As me is wa for &thorn;i wo&yogh;e &middot; &amp; &thorn;i wrange bathe,</L>
<L>I may no&yogh;t ryde &yogh;ow to reschow &middot; my reuthe is &thorn;e mare.</L>
<L>Bot I sall leue &amp; be lechid &middot; for-&thorn;i be li&yogh;t-hertid;</L>
<L N="2815">And I be couird of my coth &middot; care for na grekis,</L>
<L>Amay &thorn;e for na Messedoynes &middot; ne men vndire heuen;</L>
<L>For I sall hele all in hast &middot; &amp; hale to &yogh;oure kythis</L>
<L>With ten legions at &thorn;e last &middot; &amp; all of lele kny&yogh;tis."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is Rodogars &thorn;e riche &middot; &thorn;at renewid lady,</L>
<L N="2820">&THORN;e dere dame of Dari &middot; of &thorn;is dede heris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire awen child with Alexander &middot; amed eft to fe&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And sorowis selcuthly sare &middot; &amp; sendis him a pistill;
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>&para; "To kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kynd, <I>corrected to</I> kyng.</NOTE> dary<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. 1 dary.</NOTE> &thorn;e derfe &middot; &thorn;e derrest of my childire,</L>
<L>Rodogoras &thorn;e riche quene" &middot; &thorn;is rauth scho him writis:</L>
<L N="2825">"Bald baratour on bent &middot; borne of my bosom,</L>
<L>Here send I &thorn;e, my swete &middot; salutis &amp; ioy.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has heuyd vp &thorn;i huge ost &middot; as I haue herd tell,</L>
<L N="2828">Samed all &thorn;i saudiours &middot; &amp; semblid &thorn;i pupill,</L>
<L>And etils to ser Alexander &middot; eft to assaill.</L>
<L>Wete &thorn;ou wele it is no&yogh;t worthe &middot; ware &thorn;e be tyme;<MILESTONE N="49a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For had &thorn;ou gedird all &thorn;e gomes &middot; I gesse, of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it to with-stand him a stonde &middot; &thorn;i strenthe ware to littill.</L>
<L N="2833">For godis prouidence apert &middot; ay prestly him helpis,</L>
<L>Sauys &amp; sustenes him-selfe &middot; &amp; socurs him euire.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i hoo with &thorn;i hautes &middot; &amp; &thorn;ine vnhemed wittis,</L>
<L N="2836">A-vaile of &thorn;i vanite &middot; &amp; of &thorn;i vayne pride,</L>
<L>Obey &thorn;e to &thorn;e baratour &middot; &thorn;e best I con rede;</L>
<L>Magnifie him with &thorn;i mouthe &middot; &amp; meke &thorn;i hert,</L>
<L>For any hathill vndire heuen &middot; &thorn;at at he ne hade may,</L>
<L N="2840">Mare sekire it ware him to forsake &middot; &thorn;en sewe any forthire;</L>
<L>In pese &amp; in pacience &middot; possede at he mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>[&THORN;an] Be excludit out of his erd &middot; &amp; euire-mare duell." </L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;is rawis had rede &middot; he rewfully wepid,</L>
<L N="2844">His eldirs &amp; his ancestris &middot; als he remembris;</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh;t how pride &thorn;aim depriued: &middot; &amp; here a passe ende.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000175.tif" N="153">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Nowe hafys sir Dary</B> &thorn;e derf &middot; of dukez &amp; princez</L>
<L N="2608">Hefyd vp a hoge hoste &middot; of fyfe C knyghtez</L>
<L>Er chosyn for chyftanes &middot; &amp; chargett &thorn;aim to lede;</L>
<L>Trottes on to tygre &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar hys tentes settes;</L>
<L>&THORN;en mette &thorn;ai on &thorn;e to&thorn;er morne &middot; with a muche nombre,</L>
<L>Sir Alexander &amp; hys athell men &middot; armed on &thorn;ar blonkez.</L>
<L N="2613">The multitude to me &middot; wer mervell to Reken,</L>
<L>&THORN;e[r] sammed was on &thorn;at o&thorn;er syde &middot; mony sad hundreth.</L>
<L>Nowe er &thorn;es baners oute brade &middot; &amp; &thorn;e bates neghez,</L>
<L N="2616">Blew bemes of brase &middot; &amp; buskyn to-gedre,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cry of &thorn;e Clarions &middot; the clodez it persyd;</L>
<L>And for doute of &thorn;e dynne &middot; dauncen stedes.</L>
<L>Both &thorn;e two batels &middot; bremly assemble,</L>
<L N="2620">And seggez with hys soumez &middot; soght vnto o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Knytes on &thorn;air coursours &middot; kestyn in fewtre,</L>
<L>Tachyng into targettes &middot; tamyd &thorn;air brynnes.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was stomblyng of stedes &middot; stykkyng of Erles,</L>
<L N="2624">Sharpe shoderyng of shote &middot; sheryng of malys,</L>
<L>So stalwartly in a stounde &middot; steryn &thorn;aim &thorn;e grekez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e Barbren blode &middot; all &thorn;e bent flowez.</L>
<L>Sone as sir Dary &thorn;e deth &middot; of hys doghty hedys,</L>
<L N="2628">The pite of &thorn;e persyens &middot; hym prikkez in hys sawle,</L>
<L>Seys hys meyn&yogh;e so amenyst &middot; &amp; hys men fonged,</L>
<L>A ffew &thorn;at fresh wer vndefowled &middot; to &thorn;e flyght turnes.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yt was on wer of hys oste &middot; an odde man of Strenth,</L>
<L N="2632">A borely berne &amp; a bald &middot; als &thorn;e buke tellys,</L>
<L>A segge &thorn;at he sured hed &middot; to seyse hym hys doghter,</L>
<L>Yf he myght slae with ony sleght &middot; &thorn;e seneour of grece.</L>
<L>He clad hym all in clene stele &middot; a Conyscaunce ouer,</L>
<L N="2636">&THORN;at mad was &amp; markyd &middot; on massidons armes,</L>
<L>Kayres hym to sir A[lexander] &middot; in all &thorn;e most prese,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Catchword</I>&mdash;as he.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>As he an athell war of hys &middot; b[e]hynd hym he stelez,<MILESTONE N="30a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A bryght brynnand brand &middot; he brade owt of sheth,</L>
<L N="2640">And &thorn;orow &thorn;e helme into &thorn;e heued &middot; he hurt hym a lytyll.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e knyghtes of &thorn;e coste &middot; as &thorn;ai &thorn;e case sawgh,</L>
<L>&THORN;en fange &thorn;ai &thorn;is ilke freke &middot; &amp; byfore &thorn;e kyng brynggez.</L>
<L>"What nowe? my worthi werayour" &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng sayd,</L>
<L N="2644">He wend &thorn;at witterly it were &middot; a wee of hys awne,</L>
<L>"Why hase &thorn;ou bryssyd so my brane &middot; &amp; with a swerd woundet</L>
<L>Your sekir seruand in same &middot; all wer I sir clepyd,</L>
<L>All wer I haldyn for hede &middot; &yogh;our helpar at nede?"</L>
<L>"Nay, hope neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. nereuer.</NOTE>," quod &thorn;e athell &middot; "sir hegh Emperoure,</L>
<L N="2649">Me ony massydon to be &middot; &thorn;ou myssys of &thorn;i Awne,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e cruell kynde &middot; Comen of &thorn;e barbrys.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us I dyd, for sir Darius &middot; hys doghter hyght me,</L>
<L>And cordytt vnder &thorn;is condicion &middot; to coupill hir to wyfe,</L>
<L>And qwen he went of &thorn;is warld &middot; to weld all hys realme,</L>
<L>To hewe &thorn;i hede from &thorn;i halse &middot; &amp; onys it hym shewe."</L>
<L><B>Now kyng Alexander</B> callys &thorn;en hys knyghtes &middot; &thorn;air counsell to frayne,</L>
<L N="2656">"What suld be done hym for &thorn;is dede" &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai bydome<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> beden.</NOTE> sone,</L>
<L>Some, &thorn;at he hanged suld be &middot; &amp; some &thorn;e hede pershed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. prishyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Some bydes in a bale-fyre &middot; hym bryn all to poudre.</L>
<L>"What hase he fautyd?" quod &thorn;e freke &middot; "&thorn;of he hym forsyd hafe</L>
<L N="2660">The charge of hys chiftane &middot; chefely to fylle?</L>
<L>He &thorn;at hym demys to be dede &middot; he dampnes hym-seluen,</L>
<L>And dytes hys awne dome &middot; &amp; &thorn;at dar I prefe.</L>
<L N="2663">For demyd I ony of my doghty &middot; sir dary to spyll,</L>
<L>As he is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> &yogh;e this.</NOTE> gentell-man enjoyne &middot; suld hym-self be iugged &thorn;en."
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>He lattes &thorn;e persen in pes &middot; pas with hys heyle,</L>
<L>Mekyll for hys mayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. maynte.</NOTE> strenth &middot; &amp; for hys myght doys prayss.</L>
<L N="2667">Als sone as sir Dary &thorn;e derfe &middot; of &thorn;is dede herys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was saffed so vnslayne &middot; he sembles hys kneghtez,</L>
<L>Vp tyll a maghty<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.</NOTE> mountane &middot; hys men &thorn;ar he schewez,</L>
<L N="2670">And gessys hym &yogh;itt degrad &middot; &thorn;e grekyn maister.</L>
<L>&THORN;en foundez he forth in-to &thorn;e feld &middot; &amp; fled als belyfe,</L>
<L>And A[lexander] with hys hoste &middot; hym asperly folows</L>
<L>Right to &thorn;e burgh of batran &middot; &amp; byggyd &thorn;ar hys tentes,<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And makez hym glad with hys geng &middot; &amp; to hys goddez offers.</L>
<L><B>&THORN;e Cyte &thorn;an</B> he assaylyd &middot; &amp; sesyd it vppon &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;e burghes &thorn;ar aboute &middot; &amp; buskett &thorn;ar hys sete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2677">&thorn;ar fand tresour<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. turesour.</NOTE> vntalde &middot; &amp; &thorn;e trew spouse</L>
<L>O[f] sir Dary, both hys dame &middot; &amp; hys dere chelder.</L>
<L>Now doys hym on from Darius &middot; a darworth prince,</L>
<L N="2680">Kayres hym to alexander &middot; &amp; adours hym lowe,</L>
<L>"I haue erdyd with your enmite &middot; sir emperour," he sayd,</L>
<L>"As sugett seruyd &thorn;at syre &middot; mony sere wynter;</L>
<L>And all my travell I tynt &middot; for tuke I no gudez.</L>
<L N="2684">Bot wald now your worthynes &middot; to wende with my|seluen,</L>
<L>And ten thouusand vs take &middot; of tulkez ennarmed,</L>
<L>I shall you hete hym in your hand &middot; to haue at your wille</L>
<L>Sir Dary, witt &thorn;e most dele &middot; of hys derfe Erles."</L>
<L>"Na, leyfe, lett be," quod &thorn;e lord &middot; "&thorn;ar leuyn &thorn;e no lede,</L>
<L N="2689">&THORN;at &thorn;ou be willy in &thorn;i witte &middot; to werre &thorn;ine awne,</L>
<L>Na tell &thorn;ou me not &thorn;at tale &middot; I trowe noght &thorn;i wordez."</L>
<L><B>By &thorn;is sir Dary</B>fro hys dukez &middot; devyse[d] hath a pistyll:</L>
<L N="2692">The kyng of kyngez he hym cald &middot; &amp; clere god both,</L>
<L>&THORN;us, vnderstandyng I, was &thorn;e style &middot; &amp; styght in &thorn;ar-after:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;our satrapers, your soueraynte &middot; with seruise obeysshyng;
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>Sir, we haue send to you writtes &middot; &yogh;itt writte we &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="2696">How &thorn;is maister oute of massidoyne &middot; our marches hath enteryd,</L>
<L>Brynt vp our biggenges &middot; bryttynd our kneghtez,</L>
<L>And we ouersett be so sore &middot; to suffre ony lenger.</L>
<L>For whi your dignite bedene &middot; we derely besekyn,</L>
<L N="2700">Ayayne &thorn;e force of our foes &middot; vs furthers a while."</L>
<L>When he had rekkend all &thorn;e rawes &middot; for rankour he swellez,</L>
<L>And oute anone to A[lexander] &middot; all &thorn;us he writtez:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>"<B>I, Dary, with &thorn;e dignite</B> &middot; &thorn;e dyademe of pers,</L>
<L N="2704">Of all kyngez kyng &middot; &thorn;at Crouned was euer,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, my seruand, I say &middot; als me was sent late,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> &thorn;i.</NOTE> lownys in &thorn;i lityllake &middot; &thorn;ou likens to my hert.</L>
<L>Bot parde, &thorn;i prouydens<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. peruydens.</NOTE> &middot; inpossible it semys,</L>
<L N="2708">A hevy asse to heff &middot; on hye to &thorn;e sternes,<MILESTONE N="31a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A thyng &thorn;at thryffyn is and thyke &middot; &amp; &thorn;arnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;arnes.</NOTE> wengez,</L>
<L>And fawtes bath &thorn;e fethirhames &middot; &amp; &thorn;e flyght-lomes.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i mynd neuer &thorn;e more &middot; to mounte &thorn;e to pryde</L>
<L N="2712">For chaunce of no chevallry &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou chefyd hase.</L>
<L>For vertew ne victory &middot; avaunte noght &thorn;i-selfe;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at enhaunses hym to hygh &middot; &thorn;e lawer he declines.</L>
<L>I haue herd &yogh;it of &thorn;i hynlake &middot; at harhaldes &amp; at o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="2716">O[f] &thorn;i noblay nowe anew &middot; anence my awyn modre.</L>
<L>Both to my bird &amp; my barnes &middot; qwat bounte &thorn;ou schewys,</L>
<L>What curtasy &amp; hyndlake &middot; I ken all-to-geder.</L>
<L>Bot surly all &thorn;e seson &middot; &thorn;ou &thorn;aim so ples,</L>
<L N="2720">&THORN;ou fonnges me neuer to &thorn;i frend &middot; fyne if &thorn;ou likez.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;e more frendship &thorn;arfore &middot; fall shall &thorn;e neuer;</L>
<L N="2723">For-&thorn;i put &thorn;aim to pyne &middot; I pray &thorn;e nogh[t] wonnd,</L>
<L>For my angre on &thorn;i arrogaunce &middot; sall at &thorn;e last kyndyll;</L>
<L N="2724*">&THORN;arfor do &thorn;ou &thorn;i best &middot; god forbyd &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;an, <I>altered to</I> &thorn;ou.</NOTE> spare."
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>When he lukyd ouer &thorn;e lynes &middot; he smyllys at hys wordes,</L>
<L>And dytes ayayn to sir Dary &middot; &thorn;e deteys &thorn;at folows:</L>
<L>"<B>I, A[lexander], &thorn;e eldest</B> &middot; &amp; all my one<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2728">Of kyng philip &amp; hys fere &middot; &thorn;at frelich lady,</L>
<L>Honord Olymphades &middot; &thorn;at only me fosterd,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng owte of persye &middot; &thorn;is proloug I writte:</L>
<L>Sir, vanyte &amp; vaneglory &middot; &amp; vicys of pride</L>
<L N="2732">&THORN;es er &thorn;e gawdes, I ges &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ees goddes hatez,</L>
<L>And iche dedly do &middot; &thorn;ai dreffe &thorn;aim to ponysh,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hase dryghten of vndedlynes &middot; drawyn &thorn;aim onone.</L>
<L>&THORN;is similitude of &thorn;i-self &middot; I say all-to-geder,</L>
<L N="2736">&THORN;at assurys so &thorn;i surquidry &middot; &amp; seses neuer more</L>
<L>To bost &amp; to blasfleme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> blasfeme.</NOTE> &middot; blyn wyll &thorn;ou now&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;i gold &amp; &thorn;i gudez &middot; a god &thorn;ou &thorn;e makys,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou vpbardez<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> vpbradez.</NOTE> me for &thorn;e bewte &middot; &thorn;at I &thorn;i blude schewyd,</L>
<L N="2740">As to &thorn;i moder I mene &middot; &amp; to &thorn;i mery childer,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makys &thorn;e to malycole &middot; &amp; menys &thorn;e for lityll.<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wroght it nowder for &thorn;i wille &middot; ne for &thorn;i wale thoght.</L>
<L>Yff I kyd &thorn;aim ony curtasy &middot; it Come of my-seluen,</L>
<L N="2744">Holy of owr awne hert &middot; &amp; of our hend thewys;</L>
<L>Na we pride vs for no prowez &middot; predestinate vs here,</L>
<L>Our goddes gyffyn vs &thorn;ar-to &middot; &thorn;at grettly &thorn;ou dispysys.</L>
<L>Latt nowe &thorn;is letter be last &middot; &amp; luke to &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L N="2748">For sekerly withoute surement &middot; I seche &thorn;e agayns."</L>
<L>&THORN;is brefe he biddes &thorn;aim bere &middot; &thorn;at broght hym &thorn;e to&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Takys &thorn;am of hys tresour &middot; &amp; twynnys with &thorn;aim faire.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai to persye was past &middot; a pistyll he enformes,</L>
<L>Wrote a writte of hys wille &middot; &amp; wafed to hys Princez,</L>
<L N="2753">Hys seruandes &amp; hys senescals &middot; oute of sere landes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us Comandes he &thorn;aim clene &middot; &thorn;e kyng in hys style.</L>
<L>"<B>I, A[lexander],</B> &thorn;at as heyr &middot; avaunsyd am in grece,</L>
<L N="2756">&THORN;e son of philipp &thorn;e fers &middot; as I first told,</L>
<L>And also of Olympades &middot; my honorable lady,
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="163"></L>
<L>&THORN;us send I to my satrapars &middot; salutez of grace,</L>
<L>My peres oute of prynphagoyne &middot; my princez &amp; my dukez,</L>
<L N="2760">Of &thorn;e seneour of surry &middot; my seggez &amp; my erlez,</L>
<L>My knytes oute of Capadoce &middot; &amp; all my kyd Lordez,</L>
<L>The ledes oute of Landace &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e Landes vmbe.</L>
<L>I command you on &thorn;e Clere fayth &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;e my crowne awe,</L>
<L N="2764">&THORN;at als belyfe to alexaunder &middot; vnto my awne Cyte,</L>
<L>Ilk one send be &thorn;aim-self &middot; of sere slayn bestes,</L>
<L>Off fresh &amp; of fyne slayn &middot; fellys a thouusand,</L>
<L>Some grayne to be grathyd &middot; to my bernez byhofe,</L>
<L N="2768">Some puryd pelour &amp; depuryd &middot; to put in our wedes,</L>
<L>And cast &thorn;aim vppon camels &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;at kyth lenges,</L>
<L>And karys with &thorn;aim to eufraten &middot; &thorn;is erand haue in mynd."</L>
<L>&THORN;e[n] was a man, as me of menys &middot; in &thorn;e morne-while,</L>
<L N="2772">Was of sir Daryus a duke &middot; &thorn;e derf emperoure,</L>
<L>One &thorn;at Nostandy was namyd &middot; a noble Prince,<MILESTONE N="32a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at certyfyed hys souerente &middot; &thorn;ees sawez in a pistill:</L>
<L>"<B>Syre</B><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> e <I>is above the line in</I> MS.</NOTE> Dary, duke of iche douth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Syre duke of a Dary iche douth; <I>with a above the line.</I></NOTE> &middot; drightyn &thorn;i-seluen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2776">The grete glorius god &middot; grathyd in &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L>Nostandy, to your nobelnes &middot; &amp; ay my neke bowe,</L>
<L>With seruage to your senyoury &middot; my-seluen I Comaund.</L>
<L>It semyd not your seruand &middot; [syre], vndistreynyd</L>
<L N="2780">Vnto your mekyll mageste &middot; &thorn;ees materys to writte,</L>
<L>Bot I am depely distryssyd &middot; &thorn;is dede for to wirke,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;is mischeff to mene &middot; mawgre<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. mawgra.</NOTE> my chekez.</L>
<L>For wete it wele &yogh;our worthynes &middot; &thorn;at of our wale princez</L>
<L N="2784">Two of &thorn;e tithiest er tynt &middot; &amp; termyd of lyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lost wer nowe &thorn;e last day &middot; a lityll fro tygre,</L>
<L>In batell on bent feld &middot; in-bland with &thorn;e grekez.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was I girde to &thorn;e ground &middot; &amp; greuously woundit,</L>
<L>Vnneth me chefyd in &thorn;at chaunce &middot; to chape to &thorn;e flyght;</L>
<L N="2789">And o&thorn;er mony of owr men &middot; mightfull knyghtes,
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>And erls of our empire &middot; enterely distroed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er your legeance &middot; lethirly forsakyn,</L>
<L N="2792">Karyn &thorn;aim to sir A[lexander] &middot; &amp; onone &yogh;elden.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;aim fair vnderfongez &middot; &amp; feffys &thorn;aim in Landes,</L>
<L>In palacys, in prouynce &middot; &amp; principall regnes."</L>
<L><B>Then</B> to Nostady on next &middot; notez he a letter,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld semble hym a sowme &middot; &amp; sett &thorn;am agayns.</L>
<L N="2797">A-no&thorn;er pistell lete he passe &middot; to porrus of Inde,</L>
<L>To Come &amp; help with hys heer &middot; &amp; he hym &thorn;us aunswers:</L>
<L>"<B>I, Porrus,</B> &thorn;at possessyd am &middot; &thorn;e partyes of Inde,</L>
<L N="2800">And am &thorn;e crowne by kend &middot; clene of all &thorn;e yles,</L>
<L>Sir Dary, with &thorn;i diademe &middot; dressyd in &thorn;i trone,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e with salutes I send &middot; &thorn;e sealle of my Armez.</L>
<L>You pray vnto my person &middot; my power to assemble,</L>
<L>And you enforce with my folke &middot; &yogh;our foes to withstond;</L>
<L N="2805">I am bowne at &thorn;i bode &middot; &amp; buxme was euer,</L>
<L>To hye &amp; to helpe at &yogh;our hest &middot; whils my hele Lastes.<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bott nowe a langor me lettes &middot; &thorn;at I laght haue,</L>
<L N="2808">. . . . .</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may strene me ne stirre &middot; for stoundes &thorn;at I haue,</L>
<L>Bott lyse &amp; lukes lang &middot; when my lyfe endes.</L>
<L>And as euer I warysh of werk &middot; &thorn;at I am woundit in,</L>
<L N="2812">As me es wo for &thorn;i wogh &middot; &amp; &thorn;i wrange both,</L>
<L>I may not ryde you to rescew &middot; &thorn;e reuth is &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Bott I shall lefe &amp; be lightyd &middot; &thorn;arfore be &yogh;e light;</L>
<L>And be I couered of my cothe &middot; kare for no grekys,</L>
<L N="2816">Remefe you for no massydons &middot; ne man vppon erth;</L>
<L>For I sall hele all in hast &middot; &amp; hye to your kythez</L>
<L>With ten legions at &thorn;e lest &middot; &amp; all of lele knyghtes."</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at Rodogors &thorn;e ryche &middot; &thorn;e reuerent Lady,</L>
<L N="2820">The dere dame of Dary &middot; of &thorn;is dede herys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir Awne Childe with A[lexander] &middot; etlyd &yogh;itte to fight,</L>
<L>And sorows selkouthly sore &middot; &amp; sendes hym a pistyll;
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>"<B>To</B> kyng Dary &thorn;e derf &middot; &thorn;e derrest of hir childer,</L>
<L>Rodogors &thorn;e riche whene" &middot; &thorn;us rathe scho hym writtes:</L>
<L N="2825">"Bald baratour on bent &middot; berne of my-seluen,</L>
<L>Here send I &thorn;e, my swete &middot; salutes of Ioy.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hase hefyd vpp &thorn;i hoge hoste &middot; as I haue late herd,</L>
<L N="2828">Sammyd all &thorn;i sougeours &middot; &amp; semblyd &thorn;i peple,</L>
<L>And ettlys &thorn;e sir Alexander &middot; efte to assayle.</L>
<L>Bott wete &thorn;ou wele it is not worth &middot; &amp; were ye be tyme;</L>
<L>For hed &thorn;ou gedderyd all &thorn;e gomez &middot; I gesse, in &thorn;e werld,</L>
<L N="2832">To withstond hym a stoure &middot; &thorn;i strenth wer to lityll.</L>
<L>For goddes prouydence a-pert &middot; ay prestly hym helpys,</L>
<L>Saffys &amp; socours hym-self &middot; &amp; sustayns hym euer.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i hoo with &thorn;i hatness &middot; &amp; &thorn;i vn-hemmyd wittes,</L>
<L N="2836">Avale of &thorn;i vanyte &middot; &amp; of &thorn;i vayn pride,</L>
<L>Obey ye to &thorn;is baratour &middot; &thorn;e best I can rede;</L>
<L>Magnyfye hym with &thorn;i mouth &middot; &amp; mekyn &thorn;i hert,</L>
<L>For ony hatell vnder heuen &middot; for power &thorn;ai haue may,<MILESTONE N="33a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2840">More sekir &thorn;ai wer to forsake &middot; &amp; sewe ony for&thorn;er;</L>
<L>In pease &amp; in pacience &middot; possede &thorn;at he myght,</L>
<L>&THORN;en be exclud oute of hys erth &middot; &amp; neuer in ease dwell."</L>
<L N="2842*">Sir Dary for &thorn;oo dytez &middot; was deply diseassyd;</L>
<L>When he &thorn;oo rawez had redde &middot; rewfully he wepys,</L>
<L N="2844">Hys alders &amp; hys auncesters &middot; als he remenbrys;</L>
<L>Thoght how pride &thorn;aim depriffyd &middot; &amp; here a passe endes.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="12" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000188.tif" N="166">
<HEAD><B>Duodecimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en aires him on ser Alexander &middot; furth with his princes,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite-ward of Susys &middot; him-selfe he aproches.</L>
<L N="2848">&THORN;are-in ser Darius duellid &middot; with his derfe ostis,</L>
<L>So ne&yogh;e he come to &thorn;a cliffis &middot; he kend ouire &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at comaunds he he[s] kni&yogh;tis &middot; to cutt doune belyue
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Bowis of buskis &amp; of braunches &middot; of bolis &amp; of lindes,</L>
<L N="2852">And bynde to &thorn;aire hors feete &middot; of bobis of herbis,</L>
<L>Bath to Meeris &amp; to mulis &middot; &amp; all maner of bestis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e popill out of Persy &middot; &thorn;at slike a pake sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Beheld on he to &thorn;e hillis &middot; &amp; heterly was stroub[l]id;</L>
<L N="2856">&THORN;ai ware so woundird of &thorn;at werke &middot; &amp; wetirly it semed</L>
<L>As all &thorn;e grond &amp; &thorn;e greues &middot; had glid &thorn;aim agayns.</L>
<L>So ne&yogh;e &thorn;e cite he so&yogh;t &middot; &amp; sett vp his tentis,<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at thre days to &thorn;at thede &middot; him tharne &amp; na mare.</L>
<L>Said: "let ane dryue to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp; to; <I>with</I> &amp; <I>subpuncted</I>.</NOTE> Dary &middot; &amp; bede him dryffe sone,</L>
<L>Or put him to my powere &middot; &amp; plede we na langire."</L>
<L N="2862">&THORN;e same ni&yogh;t in his slepe &middot; him soda[n]ly a-perid</L>
<L>Amon, his awen god &middot; in aung[e]ls wyse,</L>
<L>In a mery mantill &middot; of mervailous hewis,</L>
<L N="2865">Meuand as a Messedone<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Messedono.</NOTE> &middot; in Marcure fourme;</L>
<L>Said: "vn-to Susys my son &middot; na sandisman &thorn;ou send,</L>
<L>Bot fange my fygour to &thorn;e fast &middot; &amp; fand furth &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>Clethe &thorn;e with my conyschaunce &middot; &amp; for na care drede,</L>
<L>I hete &thorn;e haly my help &middot; na harme sall &thorn;ou suffire."</L>
<L>&THORN;an slade he sli&yogh;ly a-way &middot; &amp; he fra slepe ryse,</L>
<L N="2871">A breme blasand blis &middot; in his brist rysys.</L>
<L>He knew his kni&yogh;tis &thorn;at cas &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai him clene redd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> suld graythe him to ga<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> &middot; as him his god chargis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an callis to him &thorn;is conquirour &middot; ane of his kid prince[s],</L>
<L N="2875">Emynelaus, &thorn;at his erlis &middot; &amp; his ost<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> ledes,</L>
<L>Hend &amp; hardy of his hand &middot; a huge man of strenthe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-to lede lelist to his lord &middot; leuand of lyue.</L>
<L>He bad him boun him belyue &middot; &amp; on a blonk worth,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ire foole with him fange &middot; &amp; founde with himselfe.</L>
<L N="2880">Strad vp him-selfe on a stede &middot; in starand wedis,</L>
<L>And on a cursoure &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &middot; with<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. on with; on <I>being struck through</I>.</NOTE> a collt folo&yogh;es.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete flode of Granton &middot; to-gedire &thorn;ai ride,</L>
<L N="2883">&THORN;ai fand it forsen &thorn;aim be-fore &middot; a fote-thike yse.
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e streme of Strama &middot; with many steds clepid,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;e pure propure name &middot; in percynne tonge.</L>
<L N="2886">&THORN;an Alexander belyue &middot; his wedes he changis,</L>
<L>&THORN;is renke with his Ronsees &middot; he ridis ouire &amp; leuys.</L>
<L>"A! lat me lend with &yogh;ow, lord" &middot; &thorn;e lede<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bede.</NOTE> him besekis,</L>
<L>"For drede &thorn;at angire or a-ventour &middot; or any slike fall."<MILESTONE N="50a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2890">"Nay, houe &thorn;ou here," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "vn-to my hame-come.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at I saw in my slepe &middot; sall be my sekire helpe."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he braides on &thorn;e blonke &middot; &amp; broches him in &thorn;e syd,</L>
<L>Bowis him to-ward &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &middot; as bri&yogh;t as ane aungell.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is reuere at I first rede &middot; be rewle of his kynde,</L>
<L N="2895">As wele in seson of Somere &middot; as in &thorn;e sad wintre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is neuer bot on ni&yogh;tis &middot; so naytely it fresys,</L>
<L>Till any powere to pas &middot; or preke on with stedis.</L>
<L N="2898">&YOGH;it has &thorn;e floum, as I fynd &middot; a forelange obrede,</L>
<L>And euire-ilke mornyng it meltis &middot; for mi&yogh;t of &thorn;e son;</L>
<L>With slike a reryd &thorn;an it rynnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. remes, <I>corrected to</I> rynnes.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e romance it witnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at qua so tuke it in &thorn;at tyme &middot; tint ware for euire.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is enproched him oure prince &middot; vn-to &thorn;e proude cite,</L>
<L>Band his blonke at a barrere &middot; with-out &thorn;e bur&yogh;e &yogh;atis.</L>
<L N="2904">&THORN;e Persyns of his passag &middot; was passyngly wondird,</L>
<L>And gesses him to be gode &middot; for glori of his wedis.</L>
<L>"Quat dones man ert &thorn;ou?" quod Dary &middot; &amp; drafe him agayne.</L>
<L>"Sire Alexander," quod &thorn;is athill &middot; "has all &thorn;us me sent,</L>
<L>Bedis buske &thorn;e to batell &middot; quat bade makis &thorn;ou here?</L>
<L>Outhire &yogh;are &thorn;e &yogh;apely &thorn;ar-to &middot; or till his &yogh;okke bowe."</L>
<L N="2910">"Qwe&thorn;ire &thorn;u be he?" quod &thorn;e hathill &middot; "so hately &thorn;ou spekis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou melis no&yogh;t as a minister &middot; a messangere bowis;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou carpis euyn as a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> kyng &middot; &thorn;at closid ware in pride.</L>
<L N="2913">Bot I am dred neuire a dele &middot; of all &thorn;i bald sa&yogh;es.
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;i souerayne sake &middot; &thorn;at sent &thorn;e &thorn;us hedire,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sall &thorn;ou sit with my-selfe &middot; &amp; soupe or &thorn;ou wynde."</L>
<L>He ra&yogh;t him &thorn;an be &thorn;e arme &middot; &amp; reuerence<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. reuercence.</NOTE> him makis,</L>
<L>And to his palais a-pert &middot; with princes him ledis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are aires him in ser Alexander &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us he thinkis,</L>
<L N="2919">"&THORN;is ilke bar-bryn berne &middot; grete beute me schewys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here &thorn;us hyndly be &thorn;e hand &middot; ledis to his Innes;<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is hame with help of my god &middot; I haue sall he[r]|eftir."</L>
<L N="2922">So silis he furth with &thorn;e sire &middot; in-to a somere-hall,</L>
<L>&THORN;are sesonde was a soper &middot; &thorn;e sotelest vndire heuen.</L>
<L>Sire Darius drawis to &thorn;e dese &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ir dere princes,</L>
<L>Settis &thorn;is sire with him-selfe &middot; lete serue &thorn;aim to-gedire.</L>
<L N="2926">&THORN;at bild was all of brynt gold &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bath, &thorn;e bordis &amp; &thorn;e benkes &middot; beten of &thorn;at ilke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wessell to vyse on &middot; was verraly &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e sale of a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. same a; <I>with</I> same <I>struck through.</I></NOTE> sute &middot; set full of stanes.</L>
<L N="2930">&THORN;e popill of Persy &middot; opon &thorn;is prince waitis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e litillaike of his like &middot; lathely &thorn;at &thorn;ai spyse;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e wisedome &amp; &thorn;e worthenes &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e wale thewis</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at cors was enclosed &middot; kend &thorn;ai full litill.</L>
<L>Butlers full besyly &middot; bro&yogh;t vp &thorn;e wyne,</L>
<L>In grete gobletis of gold &middot; graythid full of &yogh;ymmes;</L>
<L N="2936">And Alexander belyue &middot; as he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> had ay dronken,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he clekis vp &thorn;e coupe &middot; &amp; putis in his bosom.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ire boll was him bro&yogh;t &middot; &amp; bathe he deuoydid,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it he threw to &thorn;e thrid &middot; &amp; thrast in &thorn;are-eftir.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. as a &thorn;e.</NOTE> clientis &thorn;at knew &middot; at of &thorn;e coupe serued,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai knele doun before &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; him &thorn;e cas tald.</L>
<L N="2942">&THORN;an has ser Dary dedeyne &middot; &amp; derfely he lokes,</L>
<L>Rysys him vp renysch &middot; &amp; re&yogh;t in his sete,</L>
<L>"Quat faris &thorn;ou with," quod he, "frynde? &middot; a fon &thorn;e besemes;</L>
<L>Quy voydis &thorn;ou my vessell? &middot; it is a vile schame."
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="174"></L>
<L N="2946">"Sire, it is &thorn;e custum," quod &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &middot; "in oure kyngis fest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, be it ane, be it o&thorn;ire &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ai of drinke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gestis sall haue &thorn;e goblettis &middot; &amp; &thorn;aim gud &thorn;inke,</L>
<L>To wild &amp; wende with a-way &middot; &amp; wirke quat &thorn;aim likes;</L>
<L>Bot sen &thorn;is vse is here vn-honourable &middot; here I &thorn;am leue;"<MILESTONE N="51a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2951">Braidis &thorn;aim furth withouten bade &middot; &thorn;e butlers &thorn;aim yeldis.</L>
<L>"Now sothely," quod &thorn;an ilk a segge &middot; softly to-gedire,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is maner at he melis of &middot; is menskefull &amp; noble."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;are ane proude pere &middot; a prince at &thorn;e table,</L>
<L>Anepo, &thorn;at on Alexander &middot; all-way be-haldis,</L>
<L N="2956">&THORN;an mynes him anes in Messedone &middot; he had &thorn;e man sene,</L>
<L>Quen he was sent to his syre &middot; to feche &thorn;aire trouage.</L>
<L>His vertuse &amp; his vysage &middot; his voise he remenbris,</L>
<L>His fourme &amp; his fetoure<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fetuore.</NOTE> &middot; his figoure a-vysis,</L>
<L N="2960">He studis &amp; he stuynes &middot; he stemes with-in,</L>
<L>"Is &thorn;is no&yogh;t Philip son &thorn;e firs &middot; &thorn;e fedare of grece?"</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he sle&yogh;ly vp so&yogh;t &middot; &amp; his sete leuys,</L>
<L>Dro&yogh;e him euyn to ser Dary &middot; &thorn;are he on dese bydis,</L>
<L>Said, "surely, ser, &thorn;is sandisman &middot; &thorn;at sittis &yogh;ow be-forne</L>
<L>Is Alexander him awen self &middot; or all myn ame faillis."</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;is gouernour of grece &middot; is of &thorn;is gaude ware,</L>
<L>He torkans with &amp; vndire-tuke &middot; he touched of him-selfe,</L>
<L>Herd a nyngkiling of his name &middot; &amp; naytis him to ryse,</L>
<L N="2969">Buskis him vp at a braide &middot; &amp; fra &thorn;e burde rysys.</L>
<L>He tas a torche fia a tulke &middot; &thorn;at by &thorn;e table standis,</L>
<L>Felly fangis it in<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. l in; <I>the</I> l <I>being an imperfect</I> h, <I>due to</I> his <I>following.</I></NOTE> his fist &middot; &amp; to his fole wyndis,</L>
<L>Fyndis him faire him before &middot; &thorn;are he him feste hade,</L>
<L N="2973">Ra&yogh;t him radly &thorn;e reyne &middot; &amp; on his rige worthis.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he brochis his blonke &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e blode fames,</L>
<L>Sparis out spacly &middot; as sparke out of gledes.
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="176"></L>
<L N="2976">Be &thorn;e li&yogh;t at he led &middot; laches he &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>And fandis fast to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t &middot; with a fers will.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pepill of &thorn;e palais &middot; quen &thorn;ai his passe sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Rusches vp in a res &middot; rynnes in-to chambres,</L>
<L>Sum araies &thorn;aim in ringis &middot; &amp; sum in row brenys,<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2980*">. . . . .</L>
<L>With hard hattis on &thorn;aire hedis &middot; hied to &thorn;aire horsis,</L>
<L>Prekis eftir &thorn;e prince &middot; prestly enarmed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. enr enarmed; <I>with</I> enr <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot now was ni&yogh;t on &thorn;am ne&yogh;ed &middot; &thorn;at noyd &thorn;aim sare.</L>
<L>Sone ware &thorn;ai willid fra &thorn;e way &middot; &thorn;e wod was so thike,</L>
<L N="2985">Sum on bu&yogh;es &amp; on brerys &middot; blemysched &thorn;e face,</L>
<L>Sum ware dreuyn doun in dikis &middot; sum in depe myrys;</L>
<L>Bot Alexander at myn ame &middot; &thorn;aire a&yogh;e is a-schapid,</L>
<L>Ay trottis him to &thorn;e trod-gate &middot; as him &thorn;e torche wyssis.</L>
<L N="2989">Sire Dary as a drery man &middot; duellis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> e <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> at hame,</L>
<L>With princes in his palais &middot; all pense he sittis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e baldnes of &thorn;is baratour &middot; he besyly remembris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at skapid so sone skatheles &middot; fra all his schathill dukis.</L>
<L N="2993">&THORN;an was an ymage within &middot; as I am enfourmede,</L>
<L>Of Sexeres &thorn;at sum-quyle &middot; &thorn;at cite had to welde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh; welde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forgid all of fyne gold &middot; &amp; fettild [in] his seete;</L>
<L N="2996">Vndire &thorn;e souerayne sege &middot; &thorn;are sett ere &thorn;e lawis.</L>
<L>And sodanly &thorn;at semylacre &middot; as tellis &thorn;e textis,</L>
<L>It all to-paschis in-to peces &middot; &amp; to poudire dryuys.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e wale kyng waa &middot; &amp; wepand he said:</L>
<L N="3000">"&THORN;is be-takens trombling of my tild &middot; &amp; tene of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> my regne."</L>
<L>And Alexander all &thorn;at quile &middot; asperly rydis</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete flode of Granton &middot; &amp; it on a glace fyndis.</L>
<L N="3003">Or he was so&yogh;t to &thorn;e side &middot; &yogh;it sondird &thorn;e qweryns,</L>
<L>His hors it hunyschist for euire &middot; &amp; he with hard schapid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires he with Emynelows &middot; euen to his princes,</L>
<L>And derfly on &thorn;e to&thorn;ir day &middot; a douth he assembles,
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="178"></L>
<L N="3007">Twa hundreth thousand on a throm &middot; all of threuen kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Cairis him vp to a cliffe &middot; &amp; comfurthis his hostis;</L>
<L>"Sall neuir &thorn;e Persyns pake &middot; be pere to &thorn;e grekis,</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai ma ware be many &middot; mayes no&yogh;t &yogh;our hertis;</L>
<L>Full many flees may fell &middot; bot a fewe waspis."<MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3012">And all &thorn;e company clene &middot; comendid his wittis.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000189.tif" N="167">
<HEAD>Dublin<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Vndecimus.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fast kayrez hym on sir A[lexander] &middot; with hys athell princez,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cyte-ward of susys &middot; hym-self he aproched.</L>
<L N="2848">&thorn;ar as sir Dary in dwellyd &middot; with hys derfe hostes,</L>
<L>So negh he Come &thorn;e clyffe &middot; he kend ouer &thorn;e cyte.</L>
<L N="2850">With &thorn;at he Commandes hys knytes &middot; to cutte downe be-lyffe
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bowes &amp; &thorn;e bobbez &amp; braunches &middot; of bulesse &amp; of lyndez,</L>
<L>And bynd vnto &thorn;air blonnkez fete &middot; of buskez &amp; erbes,</L>
<L>Both to merys &amp; to mulez &middot; &amp; all maner of bestes.</L>
<L N="2854">The peple oute of persye &middot; &thorn;at suche a pake seghen,</L>
<L>Byheld on high to &thorn;e hyllez &middot; &amp; hetterly wer stourbed;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wer son wondderytt of &thorn;at werke &middot; &thorn;at witterly &thorn;am semyd</L>
<L>As all &thorn;e ground &amp; &thorn;e gravez &middot; had gane &thorn;aim ayayns.</L>
<L>So negh &thorn;e Cyte he &thorn;ame soght &middot; &amp; sett vp hys tentes,</L>
<L N="2859">&THORN;at thre days to &thorn;at thede &middot; he tharnyd &amp; no more.</L>
<L>Sayd: "latt on dryfe to sir Dary &middot; latt drysse hym to feght,</L>
<L>Or put hym to my power &middot; &amp; plete we no lenger."</L>
<L N="2862">&THORN;e same nyght in hys slepe &middot; to hym sodanly aperyd<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota sompnium Alexandri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amoyn, hys awne god &middot; in angels wyse,</L>
<L>In A mery mantyll &middot; of mervalous hewys,</L>
<L>Meuand as a massydon &middot; in mercurius forme;</L>
<L N="2866">And sayd: "vnto Susys &middot; no Sondesman &thorn;ou wafe,</L>
<L>Bott fonge &thorn;i figour to &thorn;e fast &middot; &amp; fonde furth &thorn;i-seluen,</L>
<L>Cleth &thorn;e with my Conysaunce &middot; &amp; for no care dred,</L>
<L>I hete &thorn;e holy my help &middot; no harme sall &thorn;ou hynte."</L>
<L>&THORN;e[n] slode he slyghtly away &middot; when he fra slepe rysys,<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2871">A breme blasand blysse &middot; in hys hert kyndels.</L>
<L>Be-knewe hys knyghtes of hys case &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai hym clene redyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shuld grath hym to go &middot; as hys god chargyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;en callys to hym &thorn;e conquerour &middot; one of hys kyd princez,</L>
<L N="2875">Emenylaus, &thorn;at hys Erlez &middot; &amp; hys hoste ledes,</L>
<L>Hende &amp; hardy of hys hand &middot; &amp; hoge man of strenth,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto lelyst to hys lord &middot; of all ledes oute.</L>
<L>He bad hym bowne hym belyfe &middot; &amp; on a blonke worth,</L>
<L N="2879">Ano&thorn;er fole with hym fange &middot; &amp; found with hym-selfe.</L>
<L>Strode hym-self vp on a stede &middot; in a starand wede,</L>
<L>And on a cou[r]sour &thorn;e knyght &middot; with a colt folowd.</L>
<L N="2882">To &thorn;e grete flode of gratun &middot; to-geder &thorn;ai ryddyn,</L>
<L>And fyndyn it frosyn &thorn;aim byfore &middot; a fute-thyke ysyd.
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>Thys is &thorn;e streme of Struma &middot; with mony stedes clepyd,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it pure propre name &middot; in persyens tounge.</L>
<L N="2886"><B>Then A[lexander]</B> als belyfe &middot; hys abytt chaungez,</L>
<L>Thys renke with hys rounsey &middot; he rydes ouer &amp; lefys.</L>
<L>"Na! latt me lend with &thorn;e, lord" &middot; &thorn;e lede hym bysekys,</L>
<L>"Lest anger or aventur &middot; or ony suche falle."</L>
<L N="2890">"Nay hofe &thorn;ou here," quod &thorn;e athyll &middot; "vnto my agayn|Come;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at I seght in my slepe &middot; shall me sekir helpe."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he brades on hys blonnke &middot; &amp; brochez hym in &thorn;e sydes,</L>
<L>Bowys hym on toward &thorn;e burgh &middot; als bright as an angell.</L>
<L>Thys reuer &thorn;at I first rede of &middot; be rewle of hys kynde,</L>
<L N="2895">Als wele in seasun of somer &middot; as in &thorn;e sad wynter,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is neuer bott of nyghtys &middot; so nataly it fresys,</L>
<L>To ony power on to passe &middot; or preke with a stede.</L>
<L N="2898">&YOGH;it hase &thorn;e flode, as I fynd &middot; a furelenth of brede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota naturam aque de struma.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euerilke mornyng it meltes &middot; for myght of &thorn;e son;</L>
<L>With suche a rerde &thorn;en it rynnys &middot; &thorn;e Romayns it wittnes,</L>
<L N="2901">&THORN;at who tuke it in &thorn;at tyme &middot; war termyd for euer.</L>
<L><B>Be</B> &thorn;is aprochyd hym &thorn;e Prince &middot; vnto &thorn;e prouude Cite,<MILESTONE N="34a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>band hys blonnke at a barre &middot; withoute &thorn;e brode &yogh;atez.</L>
<L>The persyens of hys passage &middot; wer passandly wounderyd,</L>
<L>And gessyn hym all to be god &middot; for glory of hys gere.</L>
<L N="2906">"What domesman art &thorn;ou?" quod Dary &middot; &amp; drofe hym ayayns.</L>
<L>"Sir A[lexander]," quod &thorn;is athell &middot; "hase all &thorn;us me send,</L>
<L>Byddes &thorn;e to batell buske &middot; what bode mase &thorn;ou here?</L>
<L>Ouder &yogh;are &thorn;e &yogh;apely &thorn;arto &middot; or to his &yogh;okke bowe."</L>
<L N="2910">"Wheder &thorn;ou be he?" &thorn;e hathell sayd, &middot; "so hetterly &thorn;ou spekez,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou melles noght as a messenger &middot; a mynyster bowez;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou Carpys likar to A kyng &middot; &thorn;at Closyd wer in pride.</L>
<L N="2913">Bot I am dred neuer a dele &middot; of all &thorn;i derfe sawez,
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="173"></L>
<L N="2914">&YOGH;itt for &thorn;i souerand sake &middot; &thorn;at send &thorn;e &thorn;us hyder,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shall sitt with my-self &middot; &amp; soupe or &thorn;ou wende."</L>
<L>He raght hym by &thorn;e right harme &middot; &amp; reuerens hym makys,</L>
<L>And to hys palays full pert &middot; with princez hym ledes,</L>
<L><B>&THORN;ar</B> kayres hym on Sir A[lexander] &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us he thynkez,</L>
<L N="2919">"&THORN;us ilke barberen berne &middot; grete bewte me schewez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here &thorn;us hyndly be hand &middot; hase lede me to Innes;</L>
<L>Thys home<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. holme; <I>but marked for correction.</I></NOTE> with helpe of my goddez &middot; I hafe sall her|after."</L>
<L N="2922">So sylez forth with &thorn;is Sire &middot; into a somer-halle,</L>
<L>Thar sesund was a soper &middot; &thorn;e sotellest vnder heuen.</L>
<L>Sir Darius drawys to &thorn;e deyse &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er dere princez,</L>
<L>Settes &thorn;is sire with hym-selfe &middot; lete serue &thorn;aim to-geder.</L>
<L N="2926">&THORN;at belde was all of brynt gold &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellys,</L>
<L>With both &thorn;e burdez &amp; &thorn;e benche &middot; betyn of &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>The vessell to vyse on &middot; veraly of &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e sale of a sute &middot; sett full of Stanes.</L>
<L N="2930">The peple oute of persey &middot; apon &thorn;e prince waytyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lityllayke of hys lyth &middot; lothly &thorn;ai spysyn;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e wysdome &amp; &thorn;e worthines &middot; of hys wale thewe&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at cors was closyd &middot; knew &thorn;ai full lytyll.</L>
<L N="2934">Botlers full besely &middot; broght vp &thorn;e wynez,</L>
<L>In grete goblettes of gold &middot; grathyd fulle of gemmys;<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And A[lexander] als belyfe &middot; as he hed onys drunkyn,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he clyght vp a cupe &middot; &amp; cromys in hys bosom.</L>
<L N="2938">Ano&thorn;er boll was hym broght &middot; &amp; both he devoyded,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dovoydede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;itt he threwe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> h <I>is above the line in</I> MS</NOTE> to &thorn;e thryde &middot; &amp; thristyn &thorn;ar-after.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e clyentez it knew &middot; &thorn;at of &thorn;e cope serued,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai knele downe bifore &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; hym &thorn;e case taldyn.</L>
<L N="2942">&THORN;en hase <I>sir</I> Dary disdayne &middot; &amp; darfly he lukes,</L>
<L>Rerys hym vpp &amp; remevys &middot; in hys sete riche,</L>
<L>"What farys with," quod he, "frende? &middot; a fonne &thorn;ou be|semys;</L>
<L>Whi woydes &thorn;ou my veseall? &middot; it is a vyle schame."
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="175"></L>
<L N="2946">"Sir, it is our costome," quod &thorn;e knyt &middot; "in our kyngez fest,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, be it one, be it o&thorn;er &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ai of drynkyn,</L>
<L>The gestes sall haue &thorn;e goblettez &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai gude thynke,</L>
<L N="2949">To wyld &amp; wynd away &middot; &amp; werke what &thorn;aim likez;</L>
<L>Bot sen &thorn;e vse is here vn-honorable &middot; here I &thorn;am lefe;"</L>
<L>Brades &thorn;am forth with-owtyn bode &middot; &thorn;e butler &thorn;aim &yogh;eldes.</L>
<L>"Nowe, sir," quod euerilke segge &middot; softly to o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is maner &thorn;at he mellys of &middot; is menskefull &amp; noble."</L>
<L N="2954"><B>Then</B> was &thorn;ar one, a prouude &middot; prince at &thorn;e tabyll,</L>
<L>Anepo, &thorn;at on Alexander &middot; alway byholdes,</L>
<L>&THORN;en menys onys in massydon &middot; he had &thorn;e man knawyn,</L>
<L>When he was sent be hys sire &middot; to sese &thorn;air truage.</L>
<L N="2958">Hys vertuez &amp; hys visage &middot; hys voyce he remenbris,</L>
<L>Hys forme &amp; hys facion &middot; hys fygure he visys,</L>
<L>He stodes &amp; he staddes with &middot; &amp; stempmys hym within,</L>
<L>"Es noght &thorn;is philyp son &thorn;e fers &middot; fennder<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. founder, <I>altered to</I> fennder.</NOTE> of grece?"</L>
<L N="2962">With &thorn;at he shyllghly vp slayde &middot; &amp; hys sete left,</L>
<L>Droght hym euen to sir Dary &middot; &thorn;ar he on deyse bydes,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at surely sir, &thorn;is sondesman &middot; &thorn;at sittes yow aforne</L>
<L>Is A[lexander] hym-self &middot; or all my ame falys."</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;is gouernour of grece &middot; apon &thorn;is gaud<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gauyd.</NOTE> wates,</L>
<L N="2967">He torkys with &amp; vndertuke &middot; it tochyd of hym-self,</L>
<L>Harde a nyckyng of hys name &middot; &amp; natys hym to ryse,<MILESTONE N="35a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Buskys hym vp at brade &middot; &amp; fro &thorn;e borde voydes.</L>
<L><B>He</B> takys a torche fro a tulke &middot; &thorn;at be &thorn;e burde standes,</L>
<L N="2971">Felly fange it in hys fyst &middot; &amp; to hys fole wendes,</L>
<L>Fyndes hym faire hym bifore &middot; &thorn;ar as he hym fest had,</L>
<L>Raght hym radly &thorn;e reyne &middot; &amp; on hys rigge ascendes.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he brochez hys blonnke &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e blode folows,</L>
<L N="2975">Sparrys oute sarply<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; for</I> spacly.</NOTE> &middot; as<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp;.</NOTE> sparke doys on gledes.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>By &thorn;e light &thorn;at he hed &middot; lacchys on hys way,</L>
<L>And fonndez fast to flyght &middot; with a fers wille.</L>
<L N="2978">The peple of &thorn;e palays &middot; when &thorn;ai hym passe sigh,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai russhyn vp in a reys &middot; rynnyn into chaumbres,</L>
<L>Some arays &thorn;aim in rynggez &middot; some in rawe brenys,</L>
<L N="2980*">Some in stalwart stuffe &middot; &amp; some in stele plates</L>
<L>With hard hattes on &thorn;air heddez &middot; hyen to &thorn;air blonnkez,</L>
<L N="2982">Prikkyn after &thorn;e prince &middot; prestly ennarmed.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en was nyght on &thorn;aim negh &middot; &thorn;at noyed &thorn;aim sore.</L>
<L>Sone wer &thorn;ai welt fro &thorn;aire way &middot; &thorn;e wod was so thykke,</L>
<L>Some of bowez &amp; of breres &middot; blemyst &thorn;e face,</L>
<L N="2986">Some wer drefyn into dykez &middot; some depe mires;</L>
<L>Bot A[lexander] at my ayme &middot; &thorn;ar augerly eschapys,</L>
<L>And ay trotes on &thorn;e troyde-gate &middot; als hym &thorn;e torche vysys.</L>
<L><B>Sir</B> Dary as a drery man &middot; dwelland in hys trone,</L>
<L N="2990">With princez in hys palays &middot; all pensey he sittes,</L>
<L>The baldnes of &thorn;is baratour &middot; he belyfe remenbris,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scapett so sone schatheles &middot; fro all hys schatell dukez.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was ane ymage within &middot; as I am enformed,</L>
<L N="2994">Off serexies &thorn;at some-while &middot; &thorn;e Cyte hed to weld,</L>
<L>Forgyd all of fyne gold &middot; &amp; feteld in hys sete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fete.</NOTE></L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at souerent segge &middot; y-sett war &thorn;air lawez.</L>
<L>And sodanly &thorn;at symylacre &middot; as says me &thorn;e text,</L>
<L N="2998">All to-paschys into peces &middot; &amp; into powder dryfez.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was &thorn;e wale kyng woo &middot; &amp; wepand he sayd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is betokyns trublyng of my teld &middot; &amp; tene to my realme."<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And A[lexander] &thorn;e while &middot; asperly rydes</L>
<L N="3002">To &thorn;e grete flude of grantum &middot; &amp; it as glas fyndes.</L>
<L>And be he soght to &thorn;e syde &middot; &yogh;itt sounderd &thorn;e qwernes,</L>
<L>Hys hors it honyshyd for euer &middot; &amp; he with hard schapyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;en kayres he with Emenylaus &middot; euen to hys princez,</L>
<L>And derfly of &thorn;at o&thorn;er day &middot; of doghty he assemblez,
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="179"></L>
<L N="3007">Twa C M in a thrume &middot; all of trefe knytes,</L>
<L>Cayrez hym vp to a Clyff &middot; &amp; comforthez hys hostez;</L>
<L>"Sall neuer &thorn;e persiens pakke &middot; be pere to &thorn;e grekez,</L>
<L N="3010">And &thorn;of &thorn;ai war mo be mony &middot; mayse nott in hertes;</L>
<L>Full fele fleys may nott felle &middot; bott a few wasspez."</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e Company clene &middot; Comendyd &thorn;an hys wittes.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="13" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000200.tif" N="178">
<HEAD><B>Cerciusdecimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be &thorn;is ser Dary was di&yogh;t &middot; whit his dere erles,</L>
<L>Heuyd vp a huge ost &middot; &amp; hast him to ryde,</L>
<L N="3015">His ginge &amp; all his garysons &middot; in glyssynand wedis,</L>
<L>Gaes him on to granton &middot; &amp; graithes &thorn;are his tentis.</L>
<L>His stoure was so stalworthe &amp; store &middot; &amp; strange to a-byde,</L>
<L>He had of men out of mynde &middot; many mayn hundreth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sike a si&yogh;t &amp; a sowme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> me <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> &middot; of seggis enarmed</L>
<L N="3020">Was neuer sene, I suppose &middot; sen &thorn;e sege of troy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chiftayne had chariotis &middot; chosen for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L>Ten thousand be tale &middot; tried for &thorn;e were.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware sett a&thorn;ire side &middot; full of sythe-bladis,</L>
<L N="3024">Kene keruand as knyfes &middot; &amp; cursers &thorn;am drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e next day be &thorn;e none &middot; new note ryses,</L>
<L>Aithire freke with his folke &middot; in &thorn;e fild metis,</L>
<L>And bald bernes on bent &middot; banars vnfaldis,</L>
<L N="3028">Put pennons on pollis &middot; payntid of siluir.</L>
<L>Alexander as belyue &middot; is armed vp clene,</L>
<L>Bounes him to his blonke &middot; &thorn;e best vndire heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e blonk Bucifal &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L N="3032">A foole worth<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. with, <I>altered to</I> worth <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> fyfty of &thorn;e firste &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e flode drouned.</L>
<L>He spynnes him out a grete space &middot; fra he[s] peris all,</L>
<L>Couers him full clenly &middot; &amp; closed in his gere.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>&THORN;e powere out of Persy &middot; quen &thorn;ay &thorn;e prince sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="3036">Frayed was of his fourme &middot; so ferdfull him semed.</L>
<L>&para; Now ere &thorn;e batails boune &middot; with braggins in trumpis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e breme bemen blaste &middot; beres to &thorn;e welken.</L>
<L>Alexander all&thorn;ire first &middot; on &thorn;aim all<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> he settis,</L>
<L N="3040">And aithire ward<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> at a wapp &middot; wi&yogh;tly inIoynes.<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Archars &amp; all men &middot; asperly fi&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are was Iusting o Ioy &middot; Iopons a-tamed;</L>
<L>Siles doun on aithire side &middot; selcuth kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="3044">Sum darid, sum dede &middot; sum depe wondid.</L>
<L>So fell<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. felle felle.</NOTE> fli&yogh;t was of flanys &middot; as I fynd wreten,</L>
<L>Of arrows &amp; of all quat &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e aire blindid;</L>
<L>Hogere on to be-hald &middot; &thorn;an of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. oerf.</NOTE> haile-stanes,</L>
<L N="3048">And all &thorn;e fild full of folke &middot; fyue mile large.</L>
<L>Als sone as &thorn;e son vp so&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;e sla&yogh;tere begynnes,</L>
<L>And so to &thorn;e son-sett &middot; slakid &thorn;ai neuire.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at &thorn;e barbryne blode &middot; be-gan to discende,</L>
<L N="3052">&THORN;e proudest of &thorn;e Persyns &middot; past out<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ont.</NOTE> of lyue.</L>
<L>Sone as ser Dary it deuysid &middot; &amp; se&yogh;is his foke faile,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he bedis &thorn;am<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;am &thorn;aim.</NOTE> &thorn;e bake &middot; &amp; bidis na langir;</L>
<L>&THORN;en quen &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;aim.</NOTE> fange to &yogh;e fli&yogh;t &middot; was furth in with euyn,</L>
<L N="3056">And mirke out<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ont.</NOTE> of mesure &middot; na man &thorn;aim a-pered.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;e chariotis in &thorn;e chace &middot; choppid &thorn;aim to deth,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cartis &thorn;at I carpid of &middot; with &thorn;e kene sythis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are fell as fele &thorn;am before &middot; of fotemen &amp; othire,</L>
<L N="3060">As risonis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> risoms, <I>or</I> risoins.</NOTE> in a ranke fild &middot; quen riders it spillen.</L>
<L>Sire Dary dryue in &thorn;e derke &middot; &amp; his douth folows,</L>
<L>Gaes him on to grantun &middot; vn-to &thorn;e grete burne,</L>
<L>Fand it frosen him before &middot; as fell for &thorn;e time,</L>
<L N="3064">Past him on with his pers &middot; a pake out of nombre.</L>
<L>His folke fellis all &thorn;e flode &middot; a forelange o brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e streme fra &thorn;e a strande &middot; stre&yogh;t to &thorn;at othire.</L>
<L>Sone fra him-self was at &thorn;e side &middot; it sonders behind,
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="182"></L>
<L N="3068">And all at lent ware on-loft &middot; loste &thorn;ar &thorn;e swete.</L>
<L>&THORN;us many deed &thorn;at day &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Of pollis out of Persye &middot; withouten &thorn;e grekis,<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thre hundreth Mille thra men &middot; &thorn;at tharned<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. thrarned.</NOTE> &thorn;aire lyues,</L>
<L N="3072">With &thorn;e fooles &amp; &thorn;e folke &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e flode drouned.</L>
<L>&THORN;is senioure out of Susys &middot; to his cite wendis,</L>
<L>Fallis doun on his face &middot; flat in &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L>"Wa is me!" quod he, "wriche &middot; wa is me vnhappy!"</L>
<L N="3076">Si&yogh;is selcuthely sare &middot; &amp; sadly he wepys,</L>
<L>"I &thorn;at was stra&yogh;t to &thorn;e sternes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. stremes.</NOTE> &middot; am streken now to grond,</L>
<L>Now craton, now caitefe &middot; now am I kast vndire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had of the Orient all ouire &middot; homage vmqwile.</L>
<L N="3080">Wist any we quat him suld worth &middot; &thorn;is werd wald he leue,</L>
<L>Full sympill in a seteqwile &middot; seke to &thorn;e cloudes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai at mast ere of mi&yogh;t &middot; smyten all to poudire."</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at with; &thorn;at <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at reufully he rase &middot; &amp; renkis out he sendis,</L>
<L N="3084">To Alexander belyue &middot; &amp; all slike a pistill.</L>
<L>&para; "I, drery kynge on my dese &middot; Darius of Persy,</L>
<L>To Alexander &thorn;at Aire &middot; &thorn;at all has to wild,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lege lord of my lyfe &middot; to lose or to saue,</L>
<L N="3088">&THORN;us send I to my souerayne &middot; salutis &amp; ioy.</L>
<L>So wyde is &thorn;e wisdom &middot; &thorn;at wonne[s] in &yogh;our saule,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele &yogh;e wate, of all men &middot; at I worthid here before,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>Ye are wise.</B></NOTE></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e notis &thorn;at ere now &middot; &amp; quat on next sewes.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &yogh;our werke ay be witt &middot; &yogh;e wirke vnreproued.</L>
<L>Sire, I knawlage me a creatour &middot; &amp; come of a woman,</L>
<L>Heues no&yogh;t &yogh;our hert vp to hi&yogh;e &middot; take hede to &yogh;our end;</L>
<L>It limps no&yogh;t all-way &thorn;e last &middot; to licken with &thorn;e first,</L>
<L N="3096">Quat suld a kni&yogh;t mare to kepe &middot; bot conquire his enmy?</L>
<L>Was no&yogh;t Sexes him-selfe &middot; &thorn;e souereynest in erth,</L>
<L>And cheued him of cheualry &middot; chekis out of nombre?</L>
<L>&YOGH;it for his will out of worde &middot; was won in-to pride,
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="184"></L>
<L N="3100">In &thorn;e lede here of Elanda &middot; lithirly he feyned.<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;inke &thorn;at allanely of god &middot; &thorn;is ouirlaike &thorn;ou haues,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i haue mercy on &thorn;i men &middot; &thorn;i meche we<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. de.</NOTE> beseke,</L>
<L>Als of &yogh;oure grete gudnes &middot; to grant vs oure modire,</L>
<L>Oure bride, oure barnes out of bande &middot; for besandis eno&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="3105">For all &thorn;e feete<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fadirs feete; <I>with</I> fadirs <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> at oure fadirs &middot; in &thorn;e fold<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fuld, <I>corrected to</I> fold.</NOTE> hade,</L>
<L>In Battri &amp; in &thorn;is bild &middot; &thorn;e bur&yogh;e of Elanda,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maistri &amp; &thorn;e maieste &middot; of Mede &amp; of Persy,</L>
<L N="3108">With all &thorn;e Iolyte &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &amp; oi; oi <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> Ioy &middot; &thorn;at Iubiter vs lenes."</L>
<L>&THORN;e seggis at fra Susses &middot; was sent with &thorn;e pistill</L>
<L>Aires to ser Alexander &middot; onone hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. it hit.</NOTE> him reches;</L>
<L N="3111">And he dos on before his ost &middot; openly to rede,</L>
<L>And all his kni&yogh;tis for &thorn;e carpe &middot; ware kenely reioysed.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was ane Permeon, a pere &middot; a prince of his oste,</L>
<L>Enclynes him doun to &thorn;e kyng &middot; said: "kid emperoure,</L>
<L>Resayue &thorn;is risches, I rede &middot; &thorn;at &yogh;ow &thorn;is renke bedis,</L>
<L N="3116">And lyuers him his ladis &middot; &amp; all his lele childire."</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander belyue &middot; &thorn;a hathels he callis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e berne at bro&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bor&yogh;t.</NOTE> him &thorn;e brefe &middot; said: "bowis to &yogh;our lord,</L>
<L>And say,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> me wondirs, I-wisse &middot; if he it wete wald,</L>
<L N="3120">For any mede a-pon mold &middot; his meneyhe to lyuire?</L>
<L>If he be fallen vndire fote &middot; &amp; his folke streyned,</L>
<L>And vencust of oure violence &middot; quat vailis him his hestis?</L>
<L N="3123">His person &amp; his prouynce &middot; he put it in my will,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eld him vndire my &yogh;oke &middot; &thorn;an &yogh;erne I na mare.</L>
<L>And if [he] grant him no&yogh;t de-grayd &middot; bot for &thorn;e gre threpis,</L>
<L>Bid buske him eft to &thorn;e bent &middot; vs bataill to &yogh;eld."</L>
<L>&THORN;us monest he &thorn;e messangers &middot; &thorn;aire maistir to say,</L>
<L N="3128">Geuys &thorn;am giftis full gude &middot; &amp; lete &thorn;am ga swyth.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an comands he his kni&yogh;tis &middot; &thorn;e corses vp to gedire,
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e douth at was dede &middot; &amp; di&yogh;t &thorn;am in graues.</L>
<L N="3131">And at wondid was, I-wis &middot; as &thorn;e writt tellis,</L>
<L>To serche &thorn;aire saluys &amp; &thorn;ar saris &middot; with surgens noble.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e grete flode of Granton &middot; now graythis he his tentis,<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Honoured &thorn;are his ald<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. h ald.</NOTE> gods &middot; &amp; offirs &thorn;am nouches;</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand he palais vp pi&yogh;t &middot; &amp; many proud hames,</L>
<L N="3136">Sum-quile of Sexes ware sett &middot; &thorn;e sire of &thorn;o landis.</L>
<L>&THORN;a bildis he bedis &thorn;am to brin &middot; sone of his bone rewis,</L>
<L>And bad na beren be sa bald &middot; a brand for to kyndill.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was a brade bent fild &middot; was beried full of kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="3140">Of ald peres out of Persy &middot; prince &amp; dukes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Messedones in &thorn;e mold &middot; mynes to &thorn;e graues,</L>
<L>Fand coupis all of clene gold &middot; &amp; costious stanes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sepulture of a sire &middot; &thorn;at of Surre was kyng.</L>
<L N="3144">Him was &thorn;e name Ninus &middot; was in a noke fonden,</L>
<L>Was of ane athill amatist &middot; &amp; all within<NOTE PLACE="foot">with <I>is in the margin</I>.</NOTE> grauen,</L>
<L>Plantid full of palmetres &middot; &amp; many proud fowles,</L>
<L>And slike a clerete it kest &middot; &thorn;u[r]&yogh;e kynd of it-selfe,</L>
<L N="3148">&THORN;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>.</NOTE> mi&yogh;t haue kend without &thorn;e kist &middot; &thorn;e corps all|to-gedire.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was a tenefull toure &middot; &amp; tulkis in-closid;</L>
<L>Sum ware &thorn;e handis of hewen &middot; &amp; sum wondid ho&yogh;es,</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;e e&yogh;en, sum &thorn;e eres &middot; &amp; egirly cries</L>
<L N="3152">On Alexander eftir help &middot; &amp; he &thorn;am all liuers.</L>
<L>He wepis on &thorn;am for wa &middot; said, "wa is me, my childire!"</L>
<L>And ilkane of his talentis &middot; he takis ten thousand.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ware &thorn;ai di&yogh;t of ser Dary &middot; for he dedeyne hade,</L>
<L N="3156">&thorn;at &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at, <I>corrected to</I> &thorn;ai.</NOTE> ware comen doun of kyngis &middot; &amp; be no cause ellis.</L>
<L>Be now &thorn;e douth of ser Daris &middot; &thorn;e derfe messangere</L>
<L>Fra Alexander agayn &middot; his answare him bro&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;an girdis out to grete &middot; eft graythis him to fy&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e honoryd here out of ynde &middot; &thorn;us ordans a pistill.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at &thorn;e sceptoure &amp; &thorn;e soile &middot; sesid am of Persy,</L>
<L>To Porrus vndire my present &middot; plesance &amp; ioy.</L>
<L>First wrate I to &yogh;our worthines &middot; &yogh;it write I &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="3164">To help vs at &thorn;ire hathill men &middot; &thorn;at haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at haue <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> wald my regne,</L>
<L>And, be &yogh;e sure, &thorn;e same way &middot; is to &yogh;our-self ettild.<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he &thorn;at werrais vs with &middot; &thorn;e wildare of grece,</L>
<L N="3167">Is wrawid &amp; wrathfull of will &middot; &amp; wode as a lyon,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>And if I sande men &amp; sammen &middot; seggis out of nombre,</L>
<L>And cokke with &thorn;e conquirour &middot; till I be cald drepid,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it me is better on &thorn;e bent &middot; in bataile be slayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;an se &thorn;e lose of my ledis &middot; &amp; ay leue in sorowe.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &yogh;oure lordschip as legeman &middot; I lawly be-seke,</L>
<L N="3173">As I &thorn;at am in angwisch &middot; myne askyng to fill;</L>
<L>Ten schilling of my trew gold &middot; a man &thorn;at is armed,</L>
<L>And fyue to a fote-man &middot; faithely I hete.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sall I ordane to &yogh;our ane &middot; quare-euire oure ost liggis,</L>
<L N="3177">A ix score of new geere &middot; of nurtrid maydens.</L>
<L>Bucifalon &thorn;e bald stede &middot; sall bathe be oure awen,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e armes of Alexander &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e pilage."</L>
<L>&para; Now flees &thorn;ar fra &thorn;e fell kynge &middot; a fone of his kni&yogh;tes,</L>
<L N="3181">To Alexander beliue &middot; &amp; all &thorn;us him tald,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at ser Dary with his dukis &middot; eft drissis him to fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Had prayd eftir powere &middot; to Porrus of ynde.</L>
<L N="3184">&THORN;an ordans him &thorn;is honorable &middot; with his ost flitis,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e Persyns king &middot; him ordans to ride,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e name of an Emperoure &middot; ne wald he neuire fange,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;en &thorn;at souerayne ware slayne &middot; or &yogh;ild him his regne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. rege, <I>altered to</I> regne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3188">Sone as &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;at kith &middot; of his come herys,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he ferly a-fri&yogh;t &middot; &amp; his folke bathe.</L>
<L>Than kest &thorn;am twa of his kni&yogh;tis &middot; him causeles to spill,
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai trowid &thorn;an of Alexander &middot; to adill &thorn;aim a mede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ire traitours on &thorn;is trechoure &middot; trowthis has strakid,</L>
<L N="3193">Lendis &thorn;aim on-loft to &thorn;e lorde &middot; la&yogh;t out swerdis.</L>
<L>"Quat sall I dre&yogh;e," quod ser Dary &middot; "my dere-worth childire?</L>
<L>First cald I &yogh;ow my clyentis &middot; &thorn;at now I call lordis,</L>
<L N="3196">Semes &yogh;ow no&yogh;t it suffice &middot; my sorowe with-out,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as a bitand brand &middot; me brettens with-in,</L>
<L>And slaa &yogh;e me &thorn;us sudanly? &middot; &thorn;e se[n]ioure of grece,<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;e.</NOTE> will me wreke on &yogh;oure werke &middot; wers &thorn;an of thefes!"</L>
<L>&THORN;ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ai.</NOTE> meuyd &thorn;aim<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ai him.</NOTE> na mercy &middot; bot maynly him woundid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at doun he hildis all to-hewyn &middot; &thorn;aire handis be-twene.</L>
<L>&THORN;an dryfes furthe &thorn;a dones men &middot; &amp; halfe dede him leuys,</L>
<L N="3203">Famand<NOTE PLACE="foot">Famend, <I>altered to</I> Famand.</NOTE> out of fresch blod &middot; &amp; here a fitt end.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000201.tif" N="179">
<HEAD>Dublin</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>By</B> &thorn;is sir Dary was dight &middot; with hys derfe Erlez,</L>
<L N="3014">Hefyd vp a hoge hoste &middot; &amp; hastyd hym to ryde,</L>
<L>Hys genge &amp; hys garyson &middot; in glasynand wedes,</L>
<L>Gose hym to grantum &middot; &amp; grathez vp hys tentes.</L>
<L>Hys stoure was stalwort &amp; sture &middot; &amp; strang to abyde,</L>
<L>He hed of men for to mynd &middot; mony mayne hundreth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at suche a sight &amp; a some &middot; of seggez enarmed</L>
<L N="3020">Was neuer [sene], I suppoyse &middot; sen &thorn;e seyge of troye.</L>
<L>The Chyftanys hed chariottes &middot; chosyn for &thorn;e nonest,</L>
<L>A Ten thouusand be tale &middot; tried for &thorn;e were.</L>
<L>And &thorn;oo wer sett on ather syde &middot; full of sythe-blades,</L>
<L N="3024">Kene keruand as knyffes &middot; &amp; coursours &thorn;aim drawys.</L>
<L>The next day be &thorn;e none &middot; new note rysys,</L>
<L>Ather freke with hys folke &middot; in &thorn;e feld metyn,</L>
<L>And bald bernez on bent &middot; banerys vnfaldyn,</L>
<L N="3028">Puttyn penons on pollez &middot; payntyd with syluer.</L>
<L>A[lexander] als belyfe &middot; es armyd vp Clene,</L>
<L>Bownez hym on hys blonnke &middot; &thorn;e best vnder heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e bald bucyfall &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellez,</L>
<L N="3032">A fole worth fyfty of &thorn;at &middot; at in &thorn;e flude drownyd.</L>
<L>He spedes hym on a grete space &middot; fro hys pers all,</L>
<L>Couerys hym full clenly &middot; &amp; closys hym in hys gere.<MILESTONE N="36a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>The power of persee &middot; when &thorn;ai &thorn;e prince see,</L>
<L N="3036">Was ferly frayd of hys forme &middot; so ferdfull he semyd.</L>
<L>Nowe er &thorn;e batels bowne &middot; with braggyng of trompettes,</L>
<L>The breme beeme blast &middot; beryd to &thorn;e welkyn.</L>
<L>A[lexander] all-&thorn;ar first &middot; on &thorn;aim all settes,</L>
<L N="3040">And ayther ward at a wappe &middot; wigh[t]ly enioynez.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota bellum inter Darium &amp; Alexan|drum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Archers &amp; all men &middot; asperly shotyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was Iustyng of Ioy &middot; Iopons attamyd;</L>
<L>Seghen downe on ather syde &middot; semelych knytes,</L>
<L N="3044">Some dasyd, some dede &middot; some depe woundytt.</L>
<L>So fell flyght was of flonys &middot; as I fynd writtyn,</L>
<L>Of arows &amp; of alblastres &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e Ayre blyndyd;</L>
<L>Huger to byhalde &middot; &thorn;en &thorn;e hayle-stormes,</L>
<L N="3048">And all &thorn;e feld full of folke &middot; fyfe myle large.</L>
<L>Als sone as &thorn;e son hup soght &middot; &thorn;e slaghter begynnys,</L>
<L>And to sett was &thorn;e same &middot; sesytt &thorn;ai neuer.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;at &thorn;e barbaryn blode &middot; began to desend,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. defend.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3052">The proudest of &thorn;e persyens &middot; passyd owte of lyfe.</L>
<L>Sone as sir Dary devysyd &middot; &amp; sawe hys doghty falle,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he biddes &thorn;am &thorn;e bake &middot; &amp; bydes no langer;</L>
<L N="3055">&THORN;en qwen &thorn;ai fange to &thorn;e flyght &middot; was nerehand euen,</L>
<L>And merke withowte mesur &middot; na man myght &thorn;am folow.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;e chariottes in &thorn;e chase &middot; chopyd &thorn;aim to deth,</L>
<L>The cartes &thorn;at I Carpyd of &middot; with &thorn;e kene sythez,</L>
<L N="3059">&THORN;ai fell all fey &thorn;aim byfore &middot; with fotemen &amp; o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>As ressynnys in a ranke feld &middot; when men ouer rydes.</L>
<L>Sir Dary dryfys in &thorn;e dirke &middot; &amp; hys doghty folows,</L>
<L>Goys hym on to grantum &middot; vnto &thorn;e grete burne,</L>
<L N="3063">Fande it frosyn hym byfore &middot; as fell for &thorn;e tyme,</L>
<L>Passys ouer with hys perys &middot; a pak oute of nowmbre.</L>
<L>Hys floke fyllys at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> al.</NOTE> &thorn;e flud &middot; a furelonge of brede,</L>
<L>The streme fra &thorn;at one strande &middot; streght vnto &thorn;at o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Sone fra hym-self was at &thorn;e syde &middot; it sounderytt byhynd,
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="183"></L>
<L N="3068">And all &thorn;at lent wer on-lofte &middot; lost haue &thorn;e swete.<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;us mony deyd &thorn;is day &middot; as demys me writtes,</L>
<L>Off polles oute of persye &middot; withoute &thorn;e prouude grekys,</L>
<L>Thre C Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. e. Three hundred thousand.</NOTE> of throo &middot; &thorn;at tharnyd &thorn;air lyfez,</L>
<L N="3072">With &thorn;e folez &amp; &thorn;e folke &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e flude drynched.</L>
<L>&THORN;is seneour vnto susys &middot; hys awne cyte wendes,</L>
<L>Fallys downe on hys face &middot; flatt in &thorn;e sale,</L>
<L>"Wo is me!" quod &thorn;e wreche &middot; "wo is me vnhappyn!"</L>
<L N="3076">Sighez selkouthly sore &middot; &amp; sadly he wepys,</L>
<L>"I &thorn;at was straught to &thorn;e sternes &middot; am strykyn nowe to ground,</L>
<L>Nowe a crathan &amp; a knaffe &middot; nowe am I kest vnder,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had of the Orient all ouer &middot; homage vmwhile.</L>
<L N="3080">Wist ony wee qwat hym suld worth &middot; &thorn;is werld wald he lefe,</L>
<L>Full symple in a sete-while &middot; sekyn to &thorn;e clodes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;at most er of myght &middot; meltyn all to powder."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at he rewfully rose &middot; &amp; renkes oute he sendes,</L>
<L N="3084">To A[lexander] als bylyfe &middot; &amp; all suche a Pistyll.</L>
<L>"<B>I, drery</B> Kyng on my dese &middot; Darius of Perys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Epistola.</NOTE></L>
<L>To A[lexander] &thorn;e heyr &middot; &thorn;at all hase to weld,</L>
<L>&THORN;e leyge lord of my lyfe &middot; to lese or to safe,</L>
<L N="3088">&THORN;us send I to my soueren &middot; salutes of Ioy.</L>
<L>So wyde is &thorn;e wisdome &middot; &thorn;at wonnys in your saule,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wele &yogh;e wate of all &thorn;at was &middot; &amp; worth here byfore,</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;e notes &thorn;at er nowe &middot; &amp; what on next sewys.</L>
<L N="3092">For-&thorn;i &yogh;e wirke euer by witte &middot; ye werke vnreprefytt.</L>
<L>Sir, I knalegh me a creatur &middot; &amp; Comyn of A woman,</L>
<L>Hefys nott your hert to hye &middot; bott hedes to your ende;</L>
<L>It lympys nott allway &thorn;e last &middot; be lykkynd to &thorn;e first,</L>
<L>Quatt suld a knyght more Couett &middot; &thorn;en conquer hys foes?</L>
<L N="3097">Was not Seryxes hym-self &middot; &thorn;e soueranest on ground,</L>
<L>And chefyd hym nott of cheualry &middot; chekez oute of nombre?</L>
<L>&YOGH;itt for hys will oute of warde &middot; was wonne into pride,
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="185"></L>
<L N="3100">In &thorn;e lede of Elanda &middot; lythirly he fynyd.</L>
<L>Thynke howe only of god &middot; &thorn;is ouerlake &thorn;ou fonges,<MILESTONE N="37a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For-&thorn;i haue mercy of &thorn;i man &middot; &thorn;i myght we besekyn,</L>
<L>All of &thorn;i grete gudenesse &middot; to graunt vs our moder,</L>
<L>Our birde, our barnez oute of bandes &middot; for besaundes enoghe,</L>
<L N="3105">For all &thorn;e feetez &thorn;at our fadir &middot; in &thorn;e molde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> folde.</NOTE> hyddyn,</L>
<L>In battrye &amp; in &thorn;is beld &middot; &thorn;e burgh of elanda,</L>
<L>The maistre &amp; &thorn;e maieste &middot; of medy &amp; of perse,</L>
<L N="3108">With all &thorn;e Iolyte &amp; Ioy &middot; &thorn;at Iubiter vs lennys."</L>
<L>&THORN;e segges &thorn;at fra susys &middot; was sent with &thorn;is pistill</L>
<L>Caryn &thorn;aim to A[lexander] &middot; onone &amp; it hym raghten;</L>
<L>And he doys one before hys hostez &middot; it opynly to rede,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e knyghtes for &thorn;e carpe &middot; wer clenly reioysyd.</L>
<L N="3113">&THORN;en was one permeon, a pere &middot; A prince of hys hoste,</L>
<L>Enclynes downe byfore &thorn;e kyng &middot; sayd: "kyd Emperour,</L>
<L>Resaue, I rede, &thorn;is rechez &middot; &thorn;is renkez &thorn;at &thorn;ou byddes,</L>
<L>And leuerys hym hys lades &middot; &amp; all hys leue childer."</L>
<L N="3117">&THORN;en A[lexander] als belyfe &middot; &thorn;is athell he clepys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bernes &thorn;at broght hym &thorn;e breve &middot; sayd: "bowys to your Lord,</L>
<L>And says, me wonderys, I-wysse &middot; yf he it wene suld,</L>
<L>For ony mede vppon molde &middot; hys meyn&yogh;ey to delyver?</L>
<L N="3121">Yff he be fallyn vnder fote &middot; &amp; hys folke strenyd,</L>
<L>And vencust of our vyolence &middot; what valys hym hys heestes?</L>
<L>Hys person &amp; hys prouynce &middot; let put in my wyll,</L>
<L>And &yogh;iff hym vndir in &yogh;oke &middot; I &yogh;arne hym no mare.</L>
<L N="3125">And yff he graunt hym nott degradyd &middot; bott for &thorn;e gree threpys,</L>
<L>Byd hym buske hym eft to &thorn;e bent &amp; batell vs &yogh;eld."</L>
<L>&THORN;us monyshest he &thorn;is messyngers &middot; &thorn;air maister at say,</L>
<L>Gyffys &thorn;aim gyftes full gude &middot; &amp; byddes &thorn;aim go swyth.</L>
<L N="3129"><B>And</B> &thorn;en commaundez he hys knyghtes &middot; &thorn;e corsez vp to gedder,
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e doghty &thorn;at was dede &middot; &amp; dight &thorn;aim in grafys.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at woundytt was, I-wysse &middot; as &thorn;e writte tellys,</L>
<L>He gart seke &thorn;air sarys, &amp; &thorn;aim salue &middot; with suurgers<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> surgens.</NOTE> noble.</L>
<L N="3133">At &thorn;e flude of grantum &middot; nowe grathez he hys tentes,</L>
<L>Honours hys olde goddes &middot; &amp; offers &thorn;aim ouchez;</L>
<L>&THORN;air fande he palays vp pight &middot; &amp; mony prouude homez,<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Some-while of Serxes was set &middot; &thorn;e syre of &thorn;air landez.</L>
<L>&THORN;ose beldes he byddes &thorn;aim bryn &middot; &amp; syne of hys bode rewys,</L>
<L>And bad no berne be so bald &middot; a brand for to kyndyll.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was a brode bent feld &middot; was full of beryd kyngez,</L>
<L N="3140">Off olde perys oute of pers &middot; of Princez &amp; Dukez.</L>
<L>The massydoyns in &thorn;e mold &middot; mynyn into &thorn;e grafez,</L>
<L>Founde coupes all of clene gold &middot; &amp; costyous stonez,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sepulturre of a syre &middot; of Surry was crownyd.</L>
<L N="3144">Hym was &thorn;e name Ninus &middot; was in a noke founden,</L>
<L>Was of ane athyll amatyst &middot; &amp; all within grafen,</L>
<L>Plantyd all with palmetres &middot; &amp; mony prouude fowlez,</L>
<L>And suche a clarett<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> clartee.</NOTE> it kest &middot; &thorn;orow kynde of hym-seluen,</L>
<L N="3148">Men myght haue kend withoute kyst &middot; &thorn;e cors all|to-geder.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was a tenefull toure &middot; &amp; tulkez inclosyd;</L>
<L>Some was &thorn;e harmes of heven &middot; &amp; some &thorn;e lygez wantyd,</L>
<L>Some &thorn;e hoghez, some &thorn;e eres &middot; &amp; egerly cryden</L>
<L>On A[lexander] after help &middot; &amp; he &thorn;aim all delyuerys.</L>
<L N="3153">He wepys on &thorn;aim for woo &middot; sayd: "woo is me, my childer!"</L>
<L>And ichone of hys talentes &middot; he takys ten thouusand.</L>
<L>&THORN;us war &thorn;ai dyght of Sir Dary &middot; for he disdayne hed,</L>
<L N="3156">&THORN;at &thorn;ai war comyn of kyngez &middot; &amp; be no cause ellez.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;en &thorn;e Doghty of sir Darius &middot; our derf messengers</L>
<L>Fro A[lexander] ayayn &middot; hys Answer hase broghtyn;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;en gyrdes oute to grete &middot; &amp; grathez hym to fyght,
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e honourd heere oute of Inde &middot; &thorn;us Ordayns he a pistyll.</L>
<L N="3161">"<B>That</B> &thorn;e septour &amp; &thorn;e soyle &middot; sesyd am of pers,</L>
<L>To porrus vnder my prynt &middot; plesaunce &amp; Ioy.</L>
<L>First wrote I to your worthynes &middot; &yogh;itt write I &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="3164">To help vs Anest &thorn;ees athell men &middot; &thorn;at hery wald oure realme,</L>
<L>And, be &yogh;e sure, &thorn;e same way &middot; is to your-selfe etteld.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at werrys vs &middot; is &thorn;e weldar of grece,</L>
<L N="3167">Es wrawyd &amp; wrathfull of will &middot; &amp; wode as a lyon,</L>
<L N="3167*">As wawes of &thorn;e wild see &middot; when wynd &thorn;aim dis|trobles;<MILESTONE N="38a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3168">And &thorn;of I somme &amp; samme &middot; seggez oute of nombre,</L>
<L>And cok with &thorn;is conquerour &middot; tyll I be cold drepyd,</L>
<L>&YOGH;itt is me better on &thorn;e bent &middot; in batell to fayle,</L>
<L>&THORN;en see &thorn;e losse of my ledes &middot; &amp; ay lefe in sorow.</L>
<L N="3172">For-&thorn;i your lordship as lege man &middot; I lofely beseche,</L>
<L>As I &thorn;at am in angres &middot; my askyns fullfyll;</L>
<L>Ten schelyng of my trew gold &middot; a tulke &thorn;at is armyd,</L>
<L N="3175">And fyfe to A foteman &middot; faythfully I hete.</L>
<L>&YOGH;itt shall I ordayne to your one &middot; whar-euer our hoste liggez,</L>
<L>Nyne score of new gere &middot; of norturryd maydens.</L>
<L N="3178">Bucyfall &thorn;e bald stede &middot; sall als be your awne,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e armez of Sir A[lexander] &middot; &amp; all &thorn;e o&thorn;er pelage."</L>
<L>Nowe fleen &thorn;ai fro &thorn;is fell kyng &middot; a some of hys knyghtes,</L>
<L>To A[lexander] als belyfe &middot; als &thorn;us hym told,</L>
<L N="3182">How &thorn;at Sir Dary<NOTE PLACE="foot">he <I>added here, but struck out</I>.</NOTE> with hys dukez &middot; dressyd &thorn;aim to fyght,</L>
<L>Had send after power &middot; to porrus of Inde.</L>
<L>&THORN;en ordayns hym &thorn;is honorable &middot; &amp; with hys hoste flyttes,</L>
<L>Ayayns &thorn;e persyen Prince &middot; he purpose to ryde,</L>
<L N="3186">For &thorn;e name of emperour &middot; wald he neuer fonnge,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at soueren wer slayn &middot; &amp; seysyd to hym &thorn;e realme.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;at kyth &middot; of hys Come herys,</L>
<L N="3189">&THORN;en was he ferly affrayd &middot; &amp; hys folke both.</L>
<L>And &thorn;en kest two of hys knyghtes &middot; to causles hym spyll,
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>&THORN;am afterward of A[lexander] &middot; attelland a mede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ees tratours on &thorn;at trichory &middot; trouthez han stroken,</L>
<L N="3193">Lenden &thorn;aim on-loft to &thorn;e lord &middot; laghtyn oute swerdes.</L>
<L>"What sall I dre," quod sir Dary &middot; "my dere worthy childer?</L>
<L>First cald I yow my clyentes &middot; &thorn;at now I calle Lordes,</L>
<L>Semys you nott it shuld suffyce &middot; my sorow now withoute,</L>
<L N="3197">&THORN;at as a bytand brand &middot; me bytes within,</L>
<L>And sla &yogh;e me &thorn;us sodonly? &middot; &thorn;e senyour of grece,</L>
<L>He will me wreke on your werke &middot; wers &thorn;en of theffes!"</L>
<L N="3200">&thorn;ar mevyd &thorn;aim no mercy &middot; bott manly hym woundit,<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at downe he heldes all to-hewyn &middot; &thorn;air handes bytwene.</L>
<L>&THORN;en dryfen forth &thorn;oo Domesmen &middot; &amp; halfdede hym lefes,</L>
<L N="3203">Fomand oute of freche blode &middot; &amp; here a fytt endes.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="14" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000212.tif" N="190">
<HEAD><B>Quartusdecimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>Ashmole</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quen Alexander of &thorn;is athill &middot; &thorn;is auntir hadd herd,</L>
<L>How he was di&yogh;t of his douth &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e dede woundid,</L>
<L>He stre&yogh;t him to struma &middot; &amp; ouire &thorn;e streme ridis,</L>
<L>So&yogh;t him in Sussys &middot; him-selfe with his ost.</L>
<L N="3208">&THORN;e pepill out of Persy &middot; quen &thorn;ai oure prince see,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ode &thorn;ai furthe &amp; vn-&yogh;arkid &middot; &thorn;e &yogh;atis of &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Resayues him full rially &middot; with reuerence &amp; ioy,</L>
<L>Said: "welcum be &thorn;ou, werraiour &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e erd loutis!"</L>
<L N="3212">Sone as &thorn;ir weried wi&yogh;tis &middot; was ware of hes come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at slo&yogh;e so &thorn;aire souerayne &middot; &thorn;at neuire sake hadd,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai he&yogh;e &thorn;aim to holes &amp; hyrnes &middot; &amp; hydis &thorn;aim belyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh;t, or &thorn;ai wist of his will &middot; &thorn;ai wald no&yogh;t apere.</L>
<L N="3216">&THORN;an gase he vp be degrece &middot; the grecen maistir,</L>
<L>Passis in-to &thorn;e palais &middot; a paradyce semed,</L>
<L>Was on &thorn;e make of &thorn;at mote &middot; no&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I> we, <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> mervalled a litill,
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&THORN;at compast was of Cusys &middot; &thorn;at kynge was of Persy.</L>
<L N="3220">&THORN;e flore vndire &thorn;e fote &middot; fynely was paued,</L>
<L>Couerd all of cristall &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire clere stanes.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it ware &thorn;e wawes of &thorn;e wanes &middot; wro&yogh;t, as I rede,</L>
<L>Polischid all of pure gold<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gold gold, <I>but corrected</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; of plate werkis.</L>
<L N="3224">And &thorn;at was streken full of sternys &middot; &amp; of sere gemmys,</L>
<L>With bri&yogh;t blasynand bees &middot; as bemes of &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hathill hedis vp-on he&yogh;e &middot; &amp; hogely he wondirs,<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at euire suld emperoure in erth &middot; slike ane herde wild.</L>
<L N="3228">Quen he had ferlyd his fill &middot; apon &thorn;at faire hame,</L>
<L>&THORN;ur&yogh;e-out &thorn;e sale &thorn;an he so&yogh;t &middot; in-to &thorn;e selfe chambre,</L>
<L>&THORN;are quare &thorn;e lord in lay &middot; with laythely woundis,</L>
<L>Girdid out as gutars &middot; in grete gill-stremes,</L>
<L N="3232">&YOGH;it was &thorn;are lyfe in his like &middot; litill if it semed,</L>
<L>At ilk blast of his breth &middot; &thorn;e blode fra him glidis,</L>
<L>Sire Alexander him avysis &middot; &amp; authly him thinke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pure pete of his payn &middot; persid his hert.</L>
<L N="3236">&THORN;an nymes he fra his awyn neke &middot; an emperoures mantill,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> couirs ouire &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; clappis him in armes,</L>
<L>With grym gretyng &amp; gro &middot; &amp; grysely terys;</L>
<L>Bad: "comfurth &thorn;e, ser conquirour &middot; &amp; of &thorn;i care ryse,</L>
<L N="3240">Don a&yogh;ayne &thorn;e dignite &middot; &thorn;e diademe of Pers,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e ri&yogh;tis of &thorn;i rewme &middot; resayue as before.</L>
<L>My pure powarfull gods &middot; I prestly pauoure,</L>
<L N="3243">&THORN;ine empire &amp; &thorn;ine erytage &middot; enterely &thorn;e to &yogh;eld;</L>
<L>Suld neuir na gome be to glade &middot; &thorn;ofe he grete ware,</L>
<L>Of his ne&yogh;bour noy &middot; enentis him-selfe,</L>
<L>Quen fortune foundis him fra &middot; &amp; him &thorn;e fete schewis,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e welth him at-wendis &middot; &amp; &thorn;e werd changis.</L>
<L N="3248">Brynge furth &thorn;i banes, &amp; with my brand &middot; I sall &thorn;i dede venge."</L>
<L>&THORN;is sa&yogh;e sobband he said &middot; &amp; &thorn;e segge wakyns,
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>Hyndely hildis him vp &middot; &amp; his hand kyssis,</L>
<L N="3251">&THORN;e brest &amp; &thorn;e bare necke &middot; &amp; breues &thorn;ire wordis:</L>
<L>&para; "A! Alexander, athill son" &middot; &amp; augrily granys,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e depe distruccion of &yogh;our dome &middot; has many day bene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> knawyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e welth of &thorn;e werld &middot; worthis at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>To cayrayne &amp; corupcion &middot; clene all-to-gedire.</L>
<L N="3256">&THORN;e warnes of &thorn;i wale gode &middot; &thorn;at wist all before,</L>
<L>And fully feld all &thorn;e fare &middot; &thorn;at fall suld on erthe;<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner made he man &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e his mi&yogh;t first,</L>
<L>Suld no&yogh;t be foun in him fast &middot; ne ferme ne stable,</L>
<L>Bot houande here a hand-qwile &middot; &amp; hingand in payse,</L>
<L N="3261">Now in leuell, now on-loft &middot; now on lawe vndire.</L>
<L>All werdly &thorn;ing, I-wis &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e will of oure lord,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e contrare clene &middot; is at a clamp turned.</L>
<L>For had he wor&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I> wro&yogh;t.</NOTE> ay to wees &middot; welth &amp; na nothire,</L>
<L N="3265">So grete had bene vayn glorie &middot; glotony &amp; pride,</L>
<L>Suld nane haue gessid &thorn;at grace &middot; come of god, bot of &thorn;aim-selfe;</L>
<L>So fra &thorn;e makare o mold &middot; suld many man haue erryd.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="3268">So feyle had bene &thorn;e frelettis &middot; folo&yogh;and oure kynd,</L>
<L>We had bene drawen all bedene &middot; in-to disspaire clene,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e godness of god &middot; no&yogh;t a grew<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I> st. <I>standing alone</I>.</NOTE> traisted.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i he wald of his will &middot; his werkis to be changand,</L>
<L N="3272">&THORN;at, quen a hathill ware ouire hi&yogh;e &middot; in happ &amp; in welthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he knew no&yogh;t his creatour &middot; bi-cause of his pride,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e dike of debonerte &middot; droune bud him nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was his will at it worthid &middot; wene &thorn;ou na nothire,</L>
<L N="3276">&THORN;e gome his god at for-gatt &middot; for any grace here,</L>
<L>His welth to wite all a-way &middot; &amp; wickidnes apere,</L>
<L>To ken &thorn;e caytefe to knaw &middot; qua caused him on first.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same ensampill of my-selfe &middot; now is betid, &thorn;ou sees;
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="196"></L>
<L N="3280">So grete I grew of my gods &middot; &amp; gold in my cofirs,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kindly gods creatoure &middot; I kend no&yogh;t my-selfe,</L>
<L>Bot for his felo&yogh;e &amp; his fere &middot; faithly me leued,</L>
<L>&THORN;us prosperite &amp; pride &middot; so purely me blyndid,</L>
<L N="3284">I couthe no&yogh;t se fra my sege &middot; to &thorn;e soile vndire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at at me failed &thorn;an to fynd &middot; fast at myn e&yogh;en.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e myrrour now of meknes &middot; I may a myle knawe,<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If any hathill be so hard &middot; with vnhapp woundid,</L>
<L N="3288">So at he hopis him no helpe &middot; of &thorn;e he&yogh;e fadire,</L>
<L>&THORN;an liftis oure lord him on-loft &middot; his langour he breggis,</L>
<L>In-hanses him in hand-quile &middot; &amp; heues him to welthis</L>
<L>So he&yogh;e, &thorn;at he for vn-hele &middot; se&yogh;es no&yogh;t his dri&yogh;ten.</L>
<L N="3292">Lat &thorn;an him knaw his creatour &middot; in kindling of ioy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;at lawene has a lede &middot; may lyft, if him thinke,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at bringis him on-loft &middot; breten all to poudire.</L>
<L>&THORN;i saule, son, in-to surquitery &middot; lat seke neuire &thorn;e hi&yogh;hare,</L>
<L N="3296">For gre &thorn;e graunt ere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> is.</NOTE> of god &middot; &amp; no&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Added in the margin.</I></NOTE> of &thorn;i grete strenthis.</L>
<L>If all &thorn;e limp as &thorn;e list &middot; loke to &thorn;ine ende,</L>
<L>For die &thorn;e bose, quen all is done &middot; &amp; ay &thorn;i day scortis.</L>
<L>&para; Me &thorn;ink<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Me &thorn;ink me.</NOTE> my lyfe as to &thorn;e len&yogh;th &middot; is like to &thorn;is werke,</L>
<L N="3300">&THORN;at &thorn;is coppis opon kell-wyse &middot; knytt in &thorn;e wo&yogh;es,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e lest winde of &thorn;e werd &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e werd touches,</L>
<L>&THORN;e note anentis ilk ane &middot; &amp; all to no&yogh;t worthis.</L>
<L>Lo! so &thorn;e quele of qwistsumnes &middot; my qualite has changid!</L>
<L N="3304">I, &thorn;at was &yogh;ustirday so &yogh;ape &middot; &amp; &yogh;emed all &thorn;e werld,</L>
<L>To day am dreuyn all to dust &middot; to dolour &amp; paynes,</L>
<L>Has no&yogh;t o maistri so meche &middot; as mi&yogh;t of my-selfe.</L>
<L>My dere son," quod Daryus &middot; "it drawes nere &thorn;e tyme;</L>
<L N="3308">My banes, on my benyson &middot; bery with &thorn;i hand,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e proued princes out of Pers<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Perers.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; with &thorn;e proude grekis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maistirlings of Messedoyne &middot; &yogh;e me to mold bring.
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>Lat &thorn;an oure kyng-domes a-corde &middot; &amp; cock we na langir,</L>
<L N="3312">Bot ay perpetuall pes &middot; oure partys betwene.</L>
<L>Vn-to &yogh;oure mekill maieste &middot; my modire I comande,</L>
<L>Rodogarus &thorn;e riall &middot; &amp; rewis on my bride;</L>
<L>My do&yogh;tir Rosan &thorn;e riche &middot; resayues to &yogh;our spouse,</L>
<L N="3316">It comys wele of hi&yogh;e kyn &middot; kyngis to descend.<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tak tent to &thorn;at at I tell &middot; be tendire of my kni&yogh;tis."</L>
<L>And with &thorn;is speke at he spake &middot; &thorn;e sprete he &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was his body enbawmed &middot; &amp;, as he bede, grauen.</L>
<L N="3320">&THORN;is bald baratoure him bare &middot; &amp; as a barne gretis,</L>
<L>So did &thorn;e pepill out of Persy &middot; bot for his pite mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an for &thorn;e dethe of Dary &middot; be dowble of &thorn;e twa.</L>
<L>And Alexander belyue &middot; as he was enterid,</L>
<L N="3324">He meues agayn to &thorn;e mote &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e morne eftir,</L>
<L>Vp to &thorn;e souerayne sege &middot; with Septour he wyndis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cusus &thorn;e conquirour &middot; of clere gold maked.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mody men of Messedone &middot; &thorn;e maistirs of Persy</L>
<L N="3328">&THORN;an put &thorn;am in-to presens &middot; as &thorn;e prose tellis;</L>
<L>Sire Darius awen dyademe &middot; &thorn;ai did on his hede,</L>
<L>A coron, ane &thorn;e costious &middot; &thorn;at euire kyng weryd,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e propurest of proiecte &middot; &thorn;at euire prince bere.</L>
<L N="3332">&THORN;e massy werke was &thorn;e menest &middot; made of &thorn;e noble,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pride &thorn;ar-of for to proue &middot; it pyned any cristen;</L>
<L>It gaue so glorius a gleme &middot; of gold &amp; of stanes,</L>
<L N="3335">&THORN;at as &thorn;e loge for &thorn;e li&yogh;t &middot; lemed as of heuen.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sete &thorn;are him-selfe satte &middot; in soyte with &thorn;e croune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was lift a-pon loft &middot; on o&thorn;ire litill segis,</L>
<L>Seuyn cubet of clere gold &middot; was countid &thorn;e hi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And vij degrece was &thorn;ar grayd &middot; for gate vp of kingis,</L>
<L N="3340">And &thorn;ai ware Ientilly Ioyned &middot; in a Ioyly wyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first an athil Amatast &middot; as I am infourmed,</L>
<L>And of a Smeth [s]maragadane &middot; Smyten was &thorn;e to&thorn;ir;</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid of a Topas a-tyred &middot; &amp; trelest &amp; grauen;</L>
<L N="3344">&THORN;e ferd degre a Granate &middot; a gracious gemme;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyfte was of ane Adomant &middot; all-to-gedire makid;<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e sext of gletirand gold &middot; gayle was forgid;
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ouirmast, all of &thorn;e erth &middot; with-out o&thorn;ire werkis,</L>
<L N="3348">Apon &thorn;is wyse ware &thorn;ai grayd &middot; &amp; for grete cause.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first was of an Amatist &middot; &thorn;at all chaye demes</L>
<L>Riche, said &thorn;e romance &middot; &amp; ronkenes of wynes,</L>
<L>Lattis na dronkynnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. droncynnes, <I>altered to</I> dronkynnes.</NOTE> &thorn;am dere &middot; &thorn;at douth at it beris.</L>
<L N="3352">&THORN;e same wyse mon a wee &middot; waite to him-selfe,</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t at couettis to clym &middot; to kyngs astate,</L>
<L>Him bus haue warnes him with &middot; of wit &amp; of mynde,</L>
<L N="3355">&THORN;at he wirke no&yogh;t on &thorn;e wethire halfe &middot; for wathe apon erth.</L>
<L>&THORN;e s[e]cunde was of Smaragdone &middot; &thorn;at ay &thorn;e si&yogh;t kepis;</L>
<L>Quat berne as beris it him on &middot; it bri&yogh;tens his e&yogh;en.</L>
<L>So bus a kyng to consaile &middot; haue a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ai.</NOTE> clere hert,</L>
<L N="3359">To se at syttis him to se &middot; &amp; sagely to wirke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid was a Topas, I trow &middot; at to &thorn;e trone lengis;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is so clere of his kind &middot; &thorn;e clause me recordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at qua-sum-euire in &thorn;at ilk &middot; his ymage behaldis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e face is to &thorn;e fold-ward &middot; &thorn;e fete to &thorn;e firment.</L>
<L N="3364">So comes it wele for a kyng &middot; to knaw till his end,</L>
<L>How ay &thorn;e top to &thorn;e taa &middot; is turned at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Quen fortune festis him &middot; he fendis beliue,</L>
<L N="3367">And all his dignite bedene &middot; driues in-to poudire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferd was a granate, I gesse &middot; goules althire fynest;</L>
<L>Is nane so redy, as I rede &middot; of all &thorn;e riche stanes;</L>
<L>Slike color a&yogh;e a kyng wele &middot; in conyschance to bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schape to na schauadry &middot; &thorn;at schend suld his fame.</L>
<L N="3372">&THORN;e fift was all of adomant &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is he &thorn;at is so hard &middot; &thorn;at hurt may nane tole;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. thole tole; <I>with</I> thole <I>struck out.</I></NOTE><MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is nothire stele ne na stane &middot; so stife it may perce,</L>
<L>And growis out of &thorn;e grete see &middot; in graynes &amp; in cragis.</L>
<L N="3376">If any Naue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. aue, <I>altered to</I> Naue <I>in the margin.</I></NOTE> to it ne&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;at naylid is with iryn,</L>
<L>&THORN;en cleuys it ay to &thorn;e clife &middot; carryg &amp; othyre;
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>Bot blode of body, sais &thorn;e buke &middot; bees it neuire percid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lansed, <I>altered to</I> percid.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or &thorn;e natour of anothire thing &middot; &thorn;at nedis no&yogh;t to reken.</L>
<L N="3380">&THORN;at same kynd suld a kyng &middot; of his craft vse,</L>
<L>So stable &amp; so stedfast &middot; to stand in his werkes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for na prayere ne pres &middot; ne plesaunce on erthe,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e rake of ri&yogh;twysnes &middot; ren suld he neuire.</L>
<L N="3384">&THORN;e Sext was of gold &middot; graciously hewen,</L>
<L>Of all metals o mold &middot; &thorn;e maistir &amp; &thorn;e syre;</L>
<L>&THORN;e same cure is a kyng &middot; be kind of his leggis,</L>
<L>To gy &amp; gouerne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gounere.</NOTE> his gomes &middot; &thorn;e grettest he is makid.</L>
<L N="3388">&THORN;e seuynt vp to &thorn;e sege &middot; was of &thorn;e selfe erth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is na mare for to mene &middot; as me my mynd tellis,</L>
<L>Bot ilka kyng suld him knaw &middot; cried of &thorn;e soile,</L>
<L N="3391">And to &thorn;e same sustenance &middot; sodanly to worthe.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sett oure syre in his sete &middot; with septoure in hand,</L>
<L>In pelour &amp; in pall &middot; &amp; proud men him by.</L>
<L>&THORN;an lete he lettres belyue &middot; with ledis out to send,</L>
<L>&THORN;ur&yogh;e all &thorn;e prouynce of pers<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. perers.</NOTE> &middot; promicid &thorn;is werkis.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e kyng with-outen compere &middot; of kyngis all othire,</L>
<L N="3397">Of all &thorn;e lordis now &thorn;e lord &middot; &thorn;at lefis apon erth,</L>
<L>Sire Alexander, athill son &middot; of Amon his dri&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>And als of Olimpades &middot; anyly consayued,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e souerayns &amp; &thorn;e Senescalls &middot; &thorn;e sires &amp; &thorn;e maistris,</L>
<L N="3401">And all &thorn;e pers out of persy &middot; princes &amp; dukis,<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustis &amp; &thorn;e gentils &middot; &amp; Iugemen of lawe,</L>
<L>Bathe citi&yogh;ens &amp; seriant &middot; salutis of grace.</L>
<L N="3404">Syn it lokid has &thorn;e largenes &middot; of &thorn;e lord of heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me &thorn;is diademe of Dary &middot; demed is &amp; graunted,</L>
<L>And to be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> here &thorn;us enhansid &middot; in his hi&yogh;e trone,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sall be glad of my degre &middot; &amp; gretly reioyd,</L>
<L N="3408">And ordans aiquare ouire all &middot; honourable princes,</L>
<L>Gouernours &amp; gardens &middot; of all &thorn;e grete bur&yogh;es,</L>
<L>As was in Darius days &middot; to deme men &thorn;e ri&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>And clene all &thorn;e clientis &middot; to kepe &thorn;aire demayndes.</L>
<L>Ilk a pepill his possession<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. posseciion, <I>altered to</I> possession.</NOTE> &middot; in pes mo&yogh;t he broweke,</L>
<L N="3413">Armoure &amp; actons &middot; y latt all &thorn;at be kepid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kepis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Caires &thorn;am to castells &middot; &amp; in kinge houses,</L>
<L>And none so bald, ere I bide &middot; to bere &thorn;am na mare.</L>
<L N="3416">And fra &thorn;is marche to Messedone &middot; quils I am maistir here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e passage in aithire part &middot; sall playn be &amp; open,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comers out of aithire coste &middot; to caire vndistrobbed,</L>
<L>With message &amp; Marchandise &middot; &amp; al manire of nedis."</L>
<L N="3420">&para; Now is his pistils all past &middot; &amp; pese he comandis;</L>
<L>"Quilke of my fryndis ere &thorn;e folke &middot; &thorn;at my faa slo&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e drepars of Dary &middot; now doo &thorn;am a-pere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may weld for &thorn;is werke &middot; wirschip to mede.</L>
<L N="3424">My mekill mi&yogh;tfull gods &middot; I maynly &yogh;ow swere,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e lay at I leue &middot; &amp; be my lufed modire,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here the</I> Dublin MS. <I>ends</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e worthe wage &thorn;aim wayue &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue wele serued."</L>
<L>&THORN;an all &thorn;e pepill out of Persy &middot; pouret out to wepe;</L>
<L N="3428">Bathe Besan &amp; Anabras &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ware &thorn;e banes of his body &middot; baldly &thorn;am shawis;</L>
<L>Said: "we to-hewid him [with] oure handis &middot; hi&yogh;e emperoure."</L>
<L N="3431">&THORN;ai wend wele &thorn;aim to wyn &middot; a waryson for euire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad he bernes &thorn;aim to bynd &middot; &amp; bringe &thorn;aim be-lyue<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e gudmans graue &middot; &amp; hewe of &thorn;aire hedis.</L>
<L>"Allas, my lord," quod &thorn;a ledis &middot; "&amp; &yogh;e so late swore,</L>
<L N="3435">To &yogh;our worthi gods, &yogh;our wale dame &middot; we suld no waa suffire!"</L>
<L>"Siris, as &yogh;e worthi ware, I-wisse &middot; I wate wele I hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And bot &yogh;our harmes were vnhid &middot; I held no&yogh;t myne athis.</L>
<L>For sen I wan in-to &thorn;e werld &middot; my witt has bene aye,</L>
<L>Quen treid was a trechory &middot; &thorn;e tulkis to be hedid."</L>
<L N="3440">&THORN;an he did &thorn;aim to deth &middot; as dri&yogh;ten him praysed,
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>&THORN;e prouynce pi&yogh;t is in pes &middot; &amp; princes ere maked,</L>
<L>An<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. And.</NOTE> ald derling<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. derlingis.</NOTE> of Darius &middot; was duke made of pers,</L>
<L N="3443">Request of &thorn;e rials &middot; ane of his riche vncles.</L>
<L>Oure emperoure, quen &thorn;is was endid &middot; erly on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>With all &thorn;a alyens him by &middot; &amp; ancient lordis,</L>
<L>He gase a-gayne to de-grece &middot; vp to &thorn;e gilt trone,</L>
<L N="3447">Dobbed in his diademe &middot; &amp; di&yogh;t as be-fore;</L>
<L>As Dary demed, or he deid &middot; his do&yogh;tir he comandes,</L>
<L>Mad Rosan &thorn;e riche &middot; radly to apere,</L>
<L>Hire hede vn-helid was on hi&yogh;e &middot; &amp; hild all in trissis,</L>
<L>Vm-by-clappid with a coronacle &middot; of costious stanes;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e manere of &thorn;at marche was &middot; he wedd hire to wyfe,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sege with him-selfe &middot; to sitt he hir makis,</L>
<L>Comands hire as a conquyres &middot; of kny&yogh;tis to be louted,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e pepill out of Persy &middot; was passandly ioyed.</L>
<L N="3456">&THORN;ai gone agraythen vp &thorn;aire gods &middot; on gilten segis,</L>
<L>Sayed: "&thorn;ou ert duke of ilk dome &middot; &amp; dri&yogh;tin &thorn;i-selfe!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he fraid in his flesche &middot; bad, "feyne of <I>&yogh;our</I> wordis!</L>
<L>I am a coruptible kyng &middot; &amp; of clay fourmed!"</L>
<L N="3460">&THORN;an out onone to Aristotil &middot; &amp; to his awen modire<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of all his weris &amp; his welth &middot; he wrate alto-gedire;</L>
<L>And a&yogh;t daies all bedene &middot; he dites in his pistill,</L>
<L N="3463">For reuerence of Rosan &middot; to revell &amp; halowe.</L>
<L>Al be &thorn;e metire bot mene &middot; &thorn;us mekill haue I ioyned;</L>
<L>Forthi, lordis, be <I>&yogh;our</I> leue &middot; list &yogh;ow to suffire.</L>
<L>Now will I tary for a time &middot; &amp; tempire my wittis;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at sti&yogh;e to &thorn;e sternes &middot; sti&yogh;till vs in heuen!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000213.tif" N="191">
<HEAD>Dublin<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Duodecimus.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Q[u]hen</B> A[lexander] of &thorn;is athell &middot; &thorn;is aunturs had herd,</L>
<L>How he was dyght of hys doughty &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e deth woundit,</L>
<L>He straght hym on to struma &middot; ouer &thorn;e streme rydes,</L>
<L>Soght on to susys &middot; hym-self with hys hostez.</L>
<L N="3208">&THORN;e peple oute of persye &middot; when &thorn;ai &thorn;is Prince see,</L>
<L>&THORN;en &yogh;ode &thorn;ai furth &amp; vn&yogh;arkyd &middot; &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e Cyte,</L>
<L>Resaved hym full ryally &middot; with reuerence enogh,</L>
<L>Sayd: "welcom be &thorn;ou, weryour &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e werld loutes!"</L>
<L N="3212">Sone as &thorn;ees warryd wightez &middot; was war of hys come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Sloghen so &thorn;air souerent &middot; &thorn;at neuer &thorn;aim gilt made,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai hyen &thorn;aim to holez &middot; &amp; hyden &thorn;aim belyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;oght, or &thorn;ai wist of hys wyll &middot; &thorn;ai wald not apere.</L>
<L N="3216">&THORN;en goyse he vp be degrees &middot; &thorn;e greken maister,</L>
<L>Passyd vnto &thorn;e palacys &middot; &thorn;at paradyse semyd,</L>
<L>Was in makke of &thorn;at mote &middot; noght mervaylled a lytyll,
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Compast was of Susys &middot; &thorn;at kyng was of pers.</L>
<L N="3220">&THORN;e flore vnder fute &middot; fynely was pafvyd,</L>
<L>Couered all of cristall &middot; &amp; o&thorn;er clere stonez.</L>
<L>&YOGH;itt wer &thorn;e wallez of &thorn;e wane &middot; wroght, as I rede,</L>
<L>Polyshyd all of pure gold &middot; &amp; of plate werkes.</L>
<L N="3224">And &thorn;at was strengkyllyd full of sternez &middot; &amp; strykyn with gemmys,</L>
<L>With bright blasenand beys &middot; as bemys of &thorn;e sonne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hathell hedes vp on hight &middot; &amp; hugely he wounderez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer suld Emperour in erth &middot; suche a place welde.</L>
<L N="3228">Qwen he had farlyd hys fyll &middot; on &thorn;ees fair homez,</L>
<L>T[h]rogh-oute &thorn;e sale &thorn;an he soght &middot; vnto &thorn;e self chaumbre,<MILESTONE N="39a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;ar as &thorn;e lord in lay &middot; with lothlyche woundes,</L>
<L>Gyrrdand oute as gutters &middot; in grete gylle-stormez,</L>
<L N="3232">&YOGH;itt was &thorn;ar lyfe in hys lyre &middot; lytyll yf it semyd,</L>
<L>Att Iche blast of hys breth &middot; &thorn;e blode fro hym &yogh;ettes,</L>
<L>Sir A[lexander] on hym avysys &middot; &amp; trewly hym thynkez;</L>
<L>&THORN;e pure pite of hys payn &middot; persyd hys hert.</L>
<L N="3236">&THORN;en nymmez he fro hys awne neke &middot; ane emperours mantell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he Couerys ouer &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; clepys hym in harmez,</L>
<L>With greme gretyng &amp; grone &middot; &amp; gryslyche terys;</L>
<L>Bad: "comforth &thorn;e, sir conquerour &middot; &amp; of &thorn;i care ryse,</L>
<L N="3240">&THORN;u dose ayayn &thorn;i dignite &middot; &thorn;e dyademe of pers,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e rightez of my realme &middot; resayve als before.</L>
<L>My pure powerfull goddes &middot; prestly adoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;ine empyre &amp; &thorn;i herytage &middot; &thorn;e purely to &yogh;eld;</L>
<L N="3244">Suld neuer no gome be glad &middot; &thorn;of he grett wer,</L>
<L>Off hys neghburs noye &middot; anentes hym-seluen.</L>
<L>When fortune fundes hym fro &middot; &amp; hym &thorn;e fete schewys,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e welthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wethche.</NOTE> &thorn;at he weldes &middot; &amp; &thorn;e werld chaungez,</L>
<L N="3248">Bryng fforth &thorn;i banes, &amp; with a brand &middot; &thorn;i bale shall I venge."</L>
<L>&THORN;is sagh sobband he sayd &middot; &amp; so &thorn;e segge wakyns,
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>Hendly halsys hym vmbe &middot; &amp; hys hande kyssys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e brest &amp; on &thorn;e bare neke &middot; &amp; brevys &thorn;ees wordez:</L>
<L N="3252">"A! Alexander, athyll son" &middot; and augerdly gronys,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e depe distruccion of &thorn;i dome &middot; hase mony day ben knawen,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e welth of &thorn;is werld &middot; waystes be &thorn;e last</L>
<L>To caryon &amp; corrupcion &middot; clene all-to-geder.</L>
<L N="3256">The wyssyng of &thorn;e wale god &middot; &thorn;at wist all before,</L>
<L>And fully fele all &thorn;e fare &middot; &thorn;at falle shuld on erth;</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner made he man &middot; &thorn;orow hys myght first,</L>
<L>Suld not be funde in hym fastnes &middot; ne ferme be ne stabyll,</L>
<L N="3260">Bot hofand here an hand-while &middot; &amp; hyngand on payse,</L>
<L>Now in leuell, nowe on-loft &middot; nowe in law vnder.</L>
<L>All wordly &thorn;[i]ng, I-wys &middot; &thorn;orow wyll of &thorn;at Lord,<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Into &thorn;e contray clene &middot; is at a clampe turnyd.</L>
<L N="3264">For hed he wroght ay to wees &middot; welth &amp; none o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>So grete had ben vaneglory &middot; glotony &amp; Pride,</L>
<L>Suld nane haue gessyd &thorn;aim grace &middot; of god, bott of &thorn;aim|seluen;</L>
<L N="3267">So from &thorn;e maker of man &middot; myght mony haue erryd.</L>
<L N="3267*">And had he shapyn Ay to shalkez &middot; shendship &amp; illys,</L>
<L N="3268">So fele had ben &thorn;e frekes &middot; folowand our kynd,</L>
<L>We had ben drawyn all bedene &middot; into dispare clene,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e gudnes of god &middot; noght a dele traistytt.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i he wald of hys will &middot; all warkys to be chaunged,</L>
<L N="3272">&THORN;at, when on athyll was so wele &middot; in happe &amp; in heyle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he knew not hys creatour &middot; be-cause of hys pryde,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e Dyche of debonerte &middot; drench must hym nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was hys wille &thorn;at it shuld &thorn;us worth &middot; wete &thorn;ou no no&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="3276">The gome &thorn;at hys god forgatt &middot; for ony grace here,</L>
<L>Hys welth to wyte away &middot; &amp; wrychednes to apere,</L>
<L>To ken &thorn;e catyff to knaw &middot; who causyd hym on first.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sampyll of my Awne self &middot; &thorn;ou seys nowe betyd;
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="197"></L>
<L N="3280">So grete I grew of my gudez &middot; &amp; gold in my coffers,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kendly goddes creature &middot; I knew nott my-seluen,</L>
<L>Bott for hys felow &amp; hys fere &middot; faythfully me made,</L>
<L>&THORN;us prosperite &amp; pride<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. proride.</NOTE> &middot; propyrly me blyndyd,</L>
<L N="3284">I kouth noght see fro my seyge &middot; to &thorn;e sette vnder,</L>
<L>&THORN;at at me faylyd to fynd &middot; fast at my eeyn.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e myrrow[r] of mekenes &middot; I may a myle knaw,</L>
<L>Yff ony hathell be so hard &middot; with vnhappe woundit,</L>
<L N="3288">So &thorn;at he hopys hym no help &middot; of &thorn;e hye fader,</L>
<L>&THORN;en lyftes &thorn;e kyng hym on-loft &middot; hys langor abreggez,</L>
<L>Enhaunses hym in hand-while &middot; &amp; hefys hym on-loft</L>
<L N="3291">So he, &thorn;at ere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I> ere, <I>read</I> he.</NOTE> for vnsele &middot; segh nott hys Dryghtyn.</L>
<L>Lete &thorn;en hym know hys creature &middot; in kyndyllyng of Ioy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he laghtnes may lede &middot; &amp; lyft when hym thynkez,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at brynges hym abowe &middot; bryttynd all to powder.</L>
<L N="3295">&THORN;i sawle, sir, into Surquydry &middot; latt sech neuer &thorn;e heyere,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Leaf</I> 40 <I>is lost</I>.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="199">
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>What berne &thorn;at berys it hym on &middot; it brightyns hys syght.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio">; <I>leaf</I> 40 <I>being lost</I>.]</NOTE></L>
<L>So buse a kyng to consayve &middot; hafe a clere hert,</L>
<L N="3359">To se &thorn;at sittes hym to see &middot; &amp; sagely to wirche.</L>
<L>The thryd was a topas, I trowe &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e trone longyd;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is So clere of hys kynde &middot; &thorn;e clause it recordes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at who-someuer in &thorn;at ilke &middot; hys vysage behaldes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e face is to &thorn;e foldward &middot; &thorn;e fete into &thorn;e welkyn.</L>
<L N="3364">So comys it wele to a kyng &middot; to knaw to hys ende,</L>
<L>Howe ay &thorn;e topp to &thorn;e toes &middot; is turnyd at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>When fortoune fraystes frely hym in-fere &middot; he fyndes hym belyfe,</L>
<L N="3367">And all hys dignite bedene &middot; dryfys into Powder.</L>
<L>The fourte was a granate &middot; &thorn;at glowys all &thorn;ar fynest;</L>
<L>Is none so rede, as I rede &middot; of all &thorn;e ryche stones;</L>
<L>Suche colour aght a kyng wele &middot; in countenaunce to bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he shope to no cheualdre &middot; &thorn;at shend shuld hys name.</L>
<L N="3372">The fyft was all of Adamant &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellys;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is he &thorn;at is so hard &middot; &thorn;at hurt may no tule;</L>
<L>Is no&thorn;er stele nor no stone &middot; so styff may it perce,</L>
<L>And growys out of &thorn;e grete see &middot; in granes &amp; in Craggez.</L>
<L N="3376">Yff ony navy to it negh &middot; &thorn;at nalyd is with Irne,</L>
<L>&THORN;en clefys it ay to &thorn;e clyff &middot; carrak &amp; o&thorn;er;
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Withowte blode of body, says &thorn;e buke &middot; beys it neuer persyd,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e nature of a-no&thorn;er thyng &middot; &thorn;at nedes noght to rekyn.</L>
<L N="3380">The same kynd shuld a kyng &middot; of hys craft vse,</L>
<L>So stabyll &amp; so stedfast &middot; to stond in hys werkez,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for no prayer ne preese &middot; ne plesaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. plesaaunce.</NOTE> on erth,</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;e rakke of rightwyssnes &middot; rynne shuld he neuer.</L>
<L N="3384">The sext degree was of gold &middot; graciously hewyn,</L>
<L>Off all &thorn;e metallys of mold &middot; &thorn;e maister &amp; &thorn;e syre;</L>
<L>The same cure is a kyng &middot; be kend of hys leigez,</L>
<L>To gye &amp; goueryne hys gomes &middot; &thorn;e grettest is he grathyd.</L>
<L N="3388">The Seuente vp to &thorn;e sege &middot; was of &thorn;e self erth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is no more for to mene &middot; as me &thorn;e writte tellys,</L>
<L>Bot euerilke kyng shuld hym knawe &middot; create of &thorn;e soyle,</L>
<L N="3391">And to &thorn;e same substance &middot; sodanly to worth.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sett our Syre in hys sete &middot; with septour in hand,<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In pelour &amp; in palle &middot; &amp; prouude men hym vmbe.</L>
<L>&THORN;en lete he letterys belyfe &middot; with ledes oute to send,</L>
<L>&THORN;orow all &thorn;e prouynce of pers &middot; pronounsand &thorn;ees wordez:</L>
<L>"<B>The</B> kyng withowtyn compere &middot; of kyngez all o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="3397">Of all lordes nowe lord &middot; &thorn;at lefyn vppon erth,</L>
<L>Sir A[lexander], athyll son &middot; of amon hys drightyn,</L>
<L>And also of Olympades &middot; only consaved,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e souerayns &amp; senescallez, &middot; &thorn;e syrez &amp; &thorn;e maisterys,</L>
<L N="3401">And all &thorn;e peres oute of pers &middot; princez &amp; dukez,</L>
<L>&THORN;e iustice &amp; &thorn;e gentyles &middot; &thorn;e iuggez of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Both cyte&yogh;eyns &amp; sergeantez &middot; salutes of grace.</L>
<L N="3404">Seth lukkyd hath &thorn;e largenes &middot; of &thorn;e lord of heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me &thorn;is Diademe of Dary &middot; demyd is &amp; grauntyd,</L>
<L>And to be here &thorn;us inhaunsyd &middot; in hys hye trone,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shall be glad of my degree &middot; &amp; gretly reiossed,</L>
<L N="3408">And ordayns ouer all &amp; ay &middot; honorable princez,</L>
<L>Gouernours &amp; gardens &middot; of all my grete burghez,</L>
<L>As was in Darius days &middot; to deme men &thorn;e right,
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>And clene all our clientes &middot; to kepe &thorn;air demaundes,</L>
<L>Iche peple &thorn;air possession &middot; in pease myght &thorn;ai broke,</L>
<L N="3413">Armors &amp; actons &middot; lat all &thorn;at be kepyd,</L>
<L>Cayrez &thorn;aim to castellys &middot; &amp; to kyngez housez,</L>
<L>And none so bold, or I byd &middot; to bere &thorn;aim no more.</L>
<L N="3416">And fro &thorn;is marche to massydoyne &middot; whil I am maister here,</L>
<L>The passage shall in ather parte &middot; plane be &amp; opyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Comers oute of athir coste &middot; to cayre vndistourblett,</L>
<L>With message &amp; with merchaundyse &middot; &amp; all maner of nedes."</L>
<L><B>Nowe</B> er hys pistellys forth past &middot; &amp; pease he Commandez;</L>
<L>"Which of my frendes er &thorn;e folke &middot; &thorn;at my foe slogh,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wer &thorn;e drepers of sir Dary &middot; nowe doys &thorn;aim apere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may weld for &thorn;air werk &middot; worship &amp; mede.</L>
<L N="3424">My mekyll myghtfull goddes &middot; I maynly you swere,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e lay &thorn;at I lefe &middot; &amp; be my lofyd moder,</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>[<I>Here ends the fragment in the</I> Dublin MS.]</TRAILER>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="15" TYPE="passus"><PB REF="00000228.tif" N="206">
<HEAD><B>Quintusdecimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3468">Lordis, will &yogh;e me lithe &middot; &amp; lestin a stonde,</L>
<L>Now sall I kithe vs a carpe &middot; of a kyng riche,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e auntours of ser Alexander &middot; &thorn;at aire was of grece,</L>
<L>How all &thorn;e werd at his will &middot; he wan or he deid.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="207"></L>
<L N="3472">&THORN;e lattir ende of his lyfe &middot; me list &yogh;ow to tell.</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e first is in fittis &middot; &amp; folowand &thorn;e lettir,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at made &yogh;ow &thorn;is mirth &middot; oft mynes his saule,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dri&yogh;tin deyne him to dele &middot; a dele of his blis.</L>
<L N="3476">Sone as ser Dary was deid &middot; &amp; done out of lyue,</L>
<L>And Alexander as<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. as ar; <I>with</I> ar <I>struck out.</I></NOTE> aire &middot; had all for to wild,</L>
<L>Resayued to his riche quene &middot; Rosan his do&yogh;tir,</L>
<L>And was &thorn;e croune be-kend &middot; of clene all &thorn;us ends,</L>
<L>He gedird him a grete ost &middot; &amp; graythid him to ride,</L>
<L N="3481">A powere of &thorn;e Persens &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e prowde grekis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Messedones &amp; all men &middot; he [maynly] comandis</L>
<L>On kyng Porrus to preke &middot; &amp; prese him with armes.</L>
<L N="3484">Now gase he furthe with his ging &middot; &thorn;e gaynest in-to ynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are many daies be dissert &middot; he dryfes with his ost,</L>
<L>Be hi&yogh;e hillis &amp; howis &middot; &amp; be holu&yogh;e do&umacr;nes,</L>
<L N="3487">Be wast &amp; be wildirnes &middot; &amp; be watirles bournes.<MILESTONE N="60a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sone was he wery of &thorn;e way &middot; so was his wale kni&yogh;tis;</L>
<L>Menyd &thorn;aim &thorn;e Messedones &middot; emang &thorn;aim-selfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said, it mi&yogh;t be sufficient &middot; &thorn;e sesyng of Persy,</L>
<L>And him &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at se; <I>with</I> se <I>struck out.</I></NOTE> trouage on tyme &middot; has tane of oure eldirs.</L>
<L N="3492">"Quat suld we fonde any ferre &middot; now faylis oure strent[h]is;</L>
<L>&THORN;is erd of ynde is ilk dele &middot; enhabet with bestis,</L>
<L>And he bet willis all &thorn;e werd &middot; be weris him to loute,</L>
<L>His flesche is fostard &amp; fedd &middot; be fi&yogh;t &amp; by sternes.</L>
<L N="3496">And were his person in pes &middot; bot for a pure tyme,</L>
<L>&THORN;an suld he faile as a freke &middot; at &thorn;e fode wantis.</L>
<L>Bot lat vs leue him at longe &middot; &amp; lende to oure hames,</L>
<L>And pas quedire as him plese &middot; with &thorn;e proud barbres."</L>
<L N="3500">Sone as oure kyng of his kni&yogh;tis &middot; &thorn;is carpe vndire|stondis,</L>
<L>He mas to stand all &thorn;e stoure &middot; &amp; standis vp in &thorn;e myddis,</L>
<L>"Bald baratours on bent &middot; blythly me heris,
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>All &thorn;e pepill out of Persy &middot; ere put in my will;</L>
<L N="3504">All ware rebell in arest &middot; now is &thorn;e rewme<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. rewe, <I>altered to</I> rewme.</NOTE> &yogh;old,</L>
<L>And I your kyng as &yogh;e knaw &middot; with croune &amp; with septour.</L>
<L>And now &yogh;e leue me &thorn;us li&yogh;tly &middot; bot for a litill pyne,</L>
<L>To caire a-gayne to &yogh;our kithid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> kichid.</NOTE> &middot; I can no&yogh;t &thorn;are-on.</L>
<L>Knaw &yogh;e no&yogh;t how in &yogh;our care &middot; I cu[m]furth &yogh;ow anys,</L>
<L>Quene &yogh;e dout so &thorn;e dites &middot; of Darus in his pistill?</L>
<L>Eft quen we ferd in-to fild &middot; &amp; with oure faes mett,</L>
<L>I was &thorn;e first &yogh;ow before &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e fild entrid,</L>
<L N="3512">So&yogh;t in-to Sussys &middot; my-selfe for<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. oo, <I>corrected to</I> for.</NOTE> &yogh;oure hele,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e habet of Amon &middot; oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a oure; <I>with</I> a <I>expuncted</I>.</NOTE> allirs dri&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>Put my person in plegg &middot; &amp; perils a hundreth,</L>
<L>And in-to tourment on-tald &middot; me tuke for &yogh;our sake.</L>
<L>Bot wetis it wele with-out wene &middot; I wene in my saule,<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3517">As I &yogh;it haue hediretoward &middot; heried all my faes,</L>
<L>So sall I gete hus ay &thorn;e gree &middot; with my gud helpe,</L>
<L>And for na tene at may betide &middot; turne sall I neuire,</L>
<L>If &yogh;e will lend in-to &yogh;our landis &middot; loke at &yogh;our hertis!</L>
<L N="3521">Bot me to do slike a dede &middot; dri&yogh;tin it schilde!</L>
<L>I sall neuire graithe me to grece &middot; gase quen &yogh;ow likis,</L>
<L N="3523">Or mare wirschip I haue won &middot; for wathe vndire heuen."</L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;is reson had redd &middot; &thorn;an rewid his princes,</L>
<L>And of forge[f]nes of &thorn;aire gilt &middot; his grace &thorn;ai be-seke.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;tis callis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> fallis.</NOTE> him on kneys &middot; said: "kid emperoure,</L>
<L>All oure life &amp; oure lose &middot; is lent in &yogh;our handis,</L>
<L N="3528">Oure-selfe &amp; oure seruage &middot; is surely &yogh;oure awen,</L>
<L>Ai at &yogh;oure beding to be &middot; oure bodi &amp; oure gudis,</L>
<L>Quare-euer &yogh;e wend in all &thorn;e werd &middot; in watir or in erthe,</L>
<L>Ay mekely at &yogh;our mandment &middot; &yogh;our maieste to folowe.</L>
<L N="3532">If we suld die all-bedene &middot; at an day tyme,</L>
<L>We sall neuer spise &yogh;ow ne sporne &middot; in speche ne in dede,</L>
<L>Ne neuire &yogh;our rialte renay &middot; bot rede to sewe,
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="209"></L>
<L>Quils any blast of oure breth &middot; in oure brest lengis."</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ede he furth in-to ynde &middot; &amp; in &thorn;ase Iles weres;</L>
<L N="3537">Quen all &thorn;e iolite of giugne &middot; &amp; Iulus was endid,</L>
<L>And messangers a-pon &thorn;e marche &middot; him metis belyue,</L>
<L>Fra kyng Porrus &thorn;e proude &middot; &thorn;is pistill him bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; "I, Porrus, &thorn;at as principall &middot; possessid am in ynde,</L>
<L>To &thorn;is michare out of Messedone &middot; &thorn;is mandment I write.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou, Alexander, &thorn;ou Ape &middot; &thorn;ou Amla&yogh;e out of grece,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou litill thefe, &thorn;ou losangere &middot; &thorn;ou lurkare in cites,</L>
<L N="3544">Sen &thorn;ou ert destayned to die &middot; &amp; dedely &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L N="3545">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> As; <I>the usual idiom</I>.</NOTE> agayn dri&yogh;tin of vnde[d]lynes &middot; quat may &thorn;i dede vaile?</L>
<L>Madding marrid has &thorn;i mode &middot; &amp; &thorn;i mynd changid.<MILESTONE N="61a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sen god has sent &thorn;e with to see &middot; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;i witt failes,</L>
<L>I hope &thorn;ou wenes at we be like &middot; to &thorn;ire lethire Persyns,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;i lordschip to loute &middot; has now on late strayned.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ou fellid has in fi&yogh;t &middot; a fi&yogh;t at was sympull,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. symplille.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3551">Now muses &thorn;ou to &thorn;i miserie &middot; my maieste to bowe.</L>
<L>If gomes be gouerners of gods &middot; &thorn;an mai &thorn;i gesse worth;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;e land here on lawe &middot; be lickned to &thorn;e heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ministracion of men &middot; to me were to febill.</L>
<L>All dri&yogh;tens &amp; dewessis &middot; ere dute of my name;</L>
<L N="3556">Ane ser Denys, a duke &middot; gane many wintire,</L>
<L>He bed vs bataill on bent &middot; &amp; &thorn;e back turned.</L>
<L>And or &thorn;at Sexes him-selfe &middot; sesid was in Persy,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e marche of Messedone &middot; made vs trouage.</L>
<L N="3560">Bot for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> partise ere vn-prophetable &middot; vs plese &thorn;aim na langir,</L>
<L>Ai wald &thorn;e wise haue wale soile &middot; mare &thorn;an a wast lee.</L>
<L>Caire agayn to &thorn;i kith &middot; caiteffe, I bidd,</L>
<L>Here na lordschip &thorn;e limpis &middot; quat list &thorn;e disyre."</L>
<L N="3564">&para; Sone as &thorn;is clause to oure kyng &middot; [was] comyn &amp; deliuere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> deliuered.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be-fore his bachelers on brade &middot; he bedis it to rede.
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>His tulkis of &thorn;is titill &middot; quen &thorn;ai &thorn;e tenour herd,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ware &thorn;ai sory of &thorn;a sawes &middot; &amp; selly frayed.</L>
<L N="3568">"Quat now, my worthe werrayouris?" &middot; &thorn;e wale kyng sayd,</L>
<L>"For Porrus pistill, I pray &middot; ne for his proud wordis,</L>
<L>No for na manas he mas &middot; mayes no&yogh;t &yogh;oure hertis.</L>
<L>Did no&yogh;t ser Dary to vs write &middot; his pistill with pride,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e berbrens bernes &middot; in bestis &thorn;am affyed,</L>
<L N="3573">As lebards, lesards, &amp; lenxis &middot; lions &amp; tigris?"</L>
<L>With comfurth of his contenance &middot; his kny&yogh;tis he gladis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an to Porrus apart &middot; &thorn;is pistill he writis.<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; "I, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at at.</NOTE> &thorn;e kyng am of kyng[s] &middot; &amp; crouned of lordis,</L>
<L N="3577">&THORN;e eldist child of Amon &middot; &thorn;at all has to wild,</L>
<L>And honourd Olimpades &middot; with him ane geten,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e oddest aire out of ynde &middot; &thorn;is answare I make.</L>
<L>I-wis, oure wittis with &thorn;i wordis &middot; &thorn;ou has wele scharpid,</L>
<L N="3581">And made vs bald with &thorn;i bost &middot; &thorn;e bataill to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>Oure boundis ere barrayne &amp; bare &middot; &amp; &thorn;ine full of welth;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kenir is oure corage &middot; &yogh;oure kyng-dome to wyn,</L>
<L>To put away oure pouerte &middot; &amp; pas to &yogh;oure hi&yogh;tes.</L>
<L N="3585">And ga no&yogh;t, as &yogh;e gude ware &middot; agayn &yogh;ow to fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot a berne full of bost &middot; a barbrene prince,</L>
<L>Wenand me &amp; all &thorn;e werd &middot; to waike to &yogh;ow-selfe."</L>
<L>Quen Porrus with his preue men &middot; &thorn;is pistill had redd,</L>
<L N="3589">&THORN;an was he wondirly wrathe &middot; &amp; wi&yogh;tly asembles</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;tis &amp; &thorn;e captayns &middot; of all &thorn;e coste by,</L>
<L>His champions, his chiftans &middot; his cheualry to-gedire.</L>
<L>He feris him a faire flote &middot; was fed for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L N="3593">Of vnicornes, of olyfauntis &middot; &amp; wondirfulle bestis,</L>
<L>As ilkane vsyd with in ynde &middot; vmquile with to fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And aires agayne Alexander &middot; with armes him to mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e powere of sir Porrus &middot; was passandly many;</L>
<L>A stour stiffe vndire stele &middot; &thorn;e strangest of &thorn;e werde</L>
<L N="3598">Of sithid chariotis him sued &middot; a selcuth nombre,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e fewist, as I find &middot; a fouretene thousand;
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>With-outen bachelers on blonkis &middot; &amp; bowmen on fote,</L>
<L>Foure hundreth Olyfants in-fere &middot; folowid him enarmi[d],</L>
<L>With ilkane bunden on his bake &middot; a borden castell,</L>
<L N="3603">And thretty tulkis in ilk toure &middot; tired in platis.</L>
<L>Oure mey-he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. be before.</NOTE> out of Messedone &middot; quen &thorn;ai so many sa&yogh;e,<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an ware &thorn;ai storbet of &thorn;at stoure &middot; so was &thorn;e stythe Persyns.</L>
<L>All &thorn;e athils of sir Alexander &middot; was ar&yogh;ed in &thorn;aire hertis</L>
<L>To mache with sike a multitude &middot; of men &amp; of bestis.</L>
<L N="3608">&THORN;an was &thorn;ir chiftans chosen &middot; cheualous kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L>&THORN;at buskid ware on bathe halfe &middot; &thorn;e bataill to rewle.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai tuke vp &thorn;e trumpis &middot; be thretty at anes,</L>
<L>A-grydis grymly to-gedir &middot; &thorn;e grekes &amp; barbres.</L>
<L N="3612">Sire Alexander was armed &middot; &amp; askis his stede</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e bald bocifalon &middot; &amp; on his bake worthes;</L>
<L>Mare &thorn;an a stanecast at a count &middot; be-fore<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. be before.</NOTE> his kni&yogh;tis all</L>
<L>He standis vp in his stereps &middot; in starand maylis.</L>
<L N="3616">&THORN;e men out of Medy &middot; he mas, &amp; of Pers,</L>
<L>To enverom alle &thorn;e vaward &middot; of all &thorn;e vile yndes,</L>
<L>And he was graythid [with] a ging &middot; of grekis kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L>And maistres out [of] Messedone &middot; &thorn;is meyhe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> meynhe.</NOTE> to helpe.</L>
<L N="3620">&THORN;e pepill out of Persye &middot; ware petusly woundid</L>
<L>Of Olifauntis ouir all &middot; with horrible hurtis;</L>
<L>All at vnweried a-way &middot; wynnes in &thorn;e stoundis</L>
<L>Durst neuir his face to his faes &middot; eft on fold bide.</L>
<L N="3624">Sire Alexander him a-visis &middot; &amp; ames in his wittis</L>
<L>How he mi&yogh;t bring it a-boute &middot; &thorn;ire bestis to devoide;</L>
<L>And mas to beete all of bras &middot; as bernes it ware,</L>
<L>And full of glorand gledis &middot; &thorn;aim to &thorn;e gorge fillis;</L>
<L N="3628">Ane instrument all of iren &middot; &thorn;are ymage to bere,</L>
<L>Was compast on carte-wise &middot; &amp; cursoures &thorn;aim dre&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ire Olifantis of ynde &middot; quen &thorn;ai &thorn;are-on waite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wend &thorn;ai ware wees &middot; &amp; wyndis &thorn;aim agayn</L>
<L N="3632">To drepe &thorn;aim as &thorn;aire first did &middot; disclosid &thorn;ai &thorn;e chaviles,
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>And sone was snaypid on &thorn;e snowte &middot; with &thorn;e snart hetis.<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at &thorn;ai fonge to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t &middot; be fifty at anes,</L>
<L>Of ilkan athill ware &thorn;ai a&yogh;ed &middot; &thorn;at any armes werid.</L>
<L>Sone as ser Porrus of &thorn;e poynte &middot; &amp; o &thorn;e plite waytis,</L>
<L N="3637">&THORN;an was he tangid with tene &middot; &amp; turbled vnfaire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an preses in &thorn;e Persyns &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e proud Medis</L>
<L>With arowis &amp; with othire armes &middot; agayn all &thorn;e yndis,</L>
<L N="3640">Tolls of &thorn;e tirantis &middot; &amp; termynd o lyue,</L>
<L>Se&yogh;es doun on aithire side &middot; a sowme out of nounbre,</L>
<L>Thretti dais on a throm &middot; &thorn;ai threpid euire elike,</L>
<L>So lange at &thorn;e lest way &middot; as lastid &thorn;e bataill.</L>
<L N="3644">&THORN;are was &thorn;e Medis martird &middot; &amp; many of Perses</L>
<L>Gorred &amp; gais<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> girt (struck)? cf. l. 3651.</NOTE> &thorn;ur&yogh;e &middot; &amp; grysely woundid.</L>
<L>Oure mody kyng of Messedone &middot; &thorn;e myschefe be-haldis,</L>
<L>Seis &thorn;aim faile so ethfully &middot; &amp; felly was greued.</L>
<L N="3648">Apon &thorn;e bald bucifelon &middot; brant vp he sittis,</L>
<L>Springis out a spere &middot; sperid all &thorn;e platis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e brest of &thorn;e bataill &middot; he baldly a-prochid,</L>
<L>Girdis doun of &thorn;e grettis &middot; &amp; &thorn;e gree wynnys.</L>
<L N="3652">His awen men of Messedone &middot; maynly &thorn;ai fe&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So did his gomes out [of] grece &middot; &amp; gate a grete name.</L>
<L>Sone discendid &thorn;are doun &middot; &thorn;e du&yogh;tiest of ynde,</L>
<L>And Porrus prekis fra &thorn;e place &middot; &amp; &thorn;e playn voidis,</L>
<L N="3656">His ledis at left ware o lyue &middot; lendis him eftire.</L>
<L>And Alexander in &thorn;at angle &middot; all &thorn;e ni&yogh;t logis,</L>
<L>Offirs all his old gods &middot; his honour &thorn;am thankis,</L>
<L>As wele &thorn;e ynde as his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he.</NOTE> awen &middot; he graue &thorn;aim all.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="16" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>Sextus Decimus [passus] Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3660">&THORN;e secund<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sed&umacr;.</NOTE> day with a saute &middot; a cite he takis,<MILESTONE N="63a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e proddest ane at Porrus &middot; possessour was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> euire.</L>
<L>He past in-to his palais &middot; &amp; in &thorn;e place findis</L>
<L>&THORN;at semed no synfull saule &middot; &thorn;e selcuthe to trowe.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>First fand he &thorn;are of fyne gold &middot; a foure hundreth postis,</L>
<L N="3665">With crafti coronals &amp; clene &middot; coruen of &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>Be-twene &thorn;e pelers was pi&yogh;t &middot; with precious leuys,</L>
<L>Gilden wynes with grapis &middot; of gracious stanes.</L>
<L N="3668">Sum were of cristall clere &middot; clustrid to-gedire;</L>
<L>Sum made ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wade w; <I>but corrected</I>.</NOTE> of Margarits &middot; &thorn;e mast of &thorn;e werd;</L>
<L>Sum was smeth smaragdyns &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire small gemmes,</L>
<L>And new nychometis &middot; nemellus endentid,</L>
<L N="3672">&THORN;at ware as semely &middot; quen &thorn;ai ware samen,</L>
<L>And all pargestis of plate &middot; as pure as &thorn;e noble.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Messedons in &thorn;am merkid &middot; with &thorn;aire mekill brandis,</L>
<L N="3675">And &thorn;e thinnest was a nynche thicke &middot; quen &thorn;ai ware &thorn;ur&yogh;e persed;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o ware strenkild with stanes &middot; as sterne o &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>With charbokl[e]s on &thorn;e champ &middot; &amp; with chefe perles.</L>
<L>Smeten was smaragdans &middot; in-to &thorn;e smeth werkis,</L>
<L>And athill amytists als &middot; in aungels licknes;</L>
<L N="3680">Of Euor &amp; of Olifants &middot; was ordand &thorn;e &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>With barrers of ane Ebyn-tree &middot; bonden with cheynes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ebyn, as &thorn;e buke sais &middot; brin will neuir,</L>
<L>And growis in &thorn;e Iles of ynde &middot; as Isodry tellis.</L>
<L N="3684">&THORN;e solers was of Sypris &middot; all of a soyte makid;</L>
<L>And Symolacres in &thorn;e sale &middot; was sett vp-on trones</L>
<L>All of glittirand gold &middot; as gomes it were,</L>
<L>Discheualer with chaplets &middot; of changand hewes;</L>
<L N="3688">And ilka tulke a tabernacle &middot; tildid was ouire,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was grauen all grayd &middot; of gilden platis,</L>
<L>Flamband all in filour &middot; &amp; fewlis en-blanchid,</L>
<L>Mekely merkid &amp; made &middot; of all manere of kyndis;<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;a ware proudly depaynt &middot; &thorn;e pennes &amp; &thorn;e wingis,</L>
<L N="3693">Of all colours to a-counte &middot; as &thorn;ai ere cled here;</L>
<L>Of fethirhame &amp; all fare &middot; as feetely enjoyned,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ai ware shapen o &thorn;e schell &middot; to schew to oure e&yogh;en.</L>
<L N="3696">Bet was all of brent gold &middot; &thorn;e billis &amp; &thorn;e chauyls,</L>
<L>And, quen as Porrus con plese &middot; in presens of lordis,
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai made as mery melody &middot; &amp; musik &thorn;ai sanng</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e moneths of Mai &middot; or mydsomere euyn!</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand he vessale of value &middot; to vyse out of nombre,</L>
<L N="3701">Gurds &amp; Goblets &middot; of gold althire-finest,</L>
<L>Coupis all of cristall &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire clere gemmes;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai fande bot a fewe dele &middot; forged of siluir.</L>
<L>&THORN;an rade he fra &thorn;a regions &middot; &amp; remewid his hostis;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e &yogh;atis of Caspy he come &middot; &amp; sett doun his tentis,</L>
<L N="3706">A lande, as &thorn;e buke tellis &middot; a large &amp; a noble,</L>
<L>All sauand bot serpentis &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire sere bestis.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mode qwene of Amazoyne &middot; &thorn;an makis him &thorn;is pistill.</L>
<L>"I, &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng am of kyngs &middot; &amp; kiddist of lordis,</L>
<L N="3710">Alexander, athil child &middot; of Amon oure dri&yogh;tin,</L>
<L>To Calistride &thorn;e conquirese &middot; comfurth &amp; ioye!</L>
<L>Oure weris &amp; oure wirschips &middot; &amp; of oure wale notis,</L>
<L>How we<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. h we.</NOTE> haue done ser Dary &middot; &amp; drepid his kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Couerd all his kyngdoms &middot; &amp; conquirid his landis,</L>
<L>I leue it to &yogh;our ladyschip &middot; &thorn;is lange no&yogh;t vnknawen.</L>
<L N="3716">With Porrus in &thorn;e playn fild &middot; proued haue my strenthis,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ire fele, &thorn;at ware to faynt &middot; oure force to with|stand.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &yogh;our landis, if &yogh;ow list &middot; to leuire fra oure handis,</L>
<L N="3719">Tas tite vn-to &yogh;our tresory &middot; &amp; trebute vs pays."</L>
<L>&THORN;an writis agayne &thorn;e wale quene &middot; &amp; on &thorn;is wyse spekis:</L>
<L>"I, Calistride, &thorn;e conquirese &middot; &thorn;at kepis all &thorn;is endis,</L>
<L N="3722">With &thorn;e mery mai[d]ons<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ma&imacr;os.</NOTE> of Amazoyne &middot; &thorn;e mi&yogh;tist in erthe,</L>
<L>And othire birdis ebland &middot; &thorn;e biggist in erthe,<MILESTONE N="64a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e modi kyng of Messedone &middot; message of blisse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure saule sa full of sapient &middot; sedis &amp; floures,</L>
<L N="3726">&THORN;at all &thorn;e present is apert &middot; puttis &thorn;ou in mynde,</L>
<L>And has of cases &thorn;at ere to come &middot; a knawlage in dole.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i oure soile or &thorn;ou seke &middot; vmse &thorn;e be tyme,
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="215"></L>
<L>Quat tene &amp; torfare may tide &middot; &amp; tent to &thorn;ine ende.</L>
<L N="3730">&THORN;are werraid neuir with vs na wee &middot; &thorn;at wirschip achewid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne was heried in hast &middot; or had a he&yogh;e schame.</L>
<L>For ilka lered man of lyue &middot; him so lethir haldis,</L>
<L>If he &thorn;at for distruccion doun &middot; in-to &thorn;e depe fallis.</L>
<L N="3734">Bot oure werkis &amp; of oure wonynge-stede &middot; if &yogh;e wald knawe,</L>
<L>I sal declare &yogh;ow &thorn;e cas &middot; clene by &thorn;ire writtis.</L>
<L>Oure inhabetting, ser, is in an Ilee &middot; &amp; amed as a sercle,</L>
<L>With rynand all aboute oure erd &middot; an endles wattre.</L>
<L>And we ere of females at &thorn;e fewis &middot; foure &amp; xx<SUP>ti</SUP> Mille,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. e. thousand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3739">And twa hundreth &thorn;ar-to &middot; &amp; all of tried ladis.</L>
<L>A preue planke is at a place &middot; to pas &amp; to entre,</L>
<L>Oure bernes bildis no&yogh;t vs by &middot; bot ouir &thorn;e bourne wyndis.</L>
<L N="3742">Bot &yogh;et be-&yogh;onde ilka &yogh;ere &middot; make we vs festis,</L>
<L>And thretti dais all be-dene &middot; oure delitis hauntis.</L>
<L>If any consaue &thorn;ar a knaf &middot; &thorn;an kepis him his modire</L>
<L>Vij &yogh;ere with-in oure-selfe &middot; &amp; sendis him his fadir.</L>
<L>And be scho lyuir of a lasse &middot; scho lengis in oure bur&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="3747">And is oure thewis of oure thede &middot; thryfandly enfourmed.</L>
<L>Quen we to fe&yogh;t with oure faes &middot; fares out of wanes,</L>
<L>A hundreth thousand I hope we be &middot; on horses enarmed,</L>
<L N="3750">&THORN;a leues in oure lede &middot; oure lithis to defend.</L>
<L>Quen we repaire with &thorn;e palme &middot; &thorn;an prayses vs oure feris.</L>
<L>And, buske &yogh;e to oure bondsward &middot; vs bataill to &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et sall we maynly on &thorn;e marche &middot; mete &yogh;ow in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> armes.<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To lithe vs all if &thorn;ou limpes &middot; na louyng &thorn;ou gettis,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou wynnes no&yogh;t bot wemen &middot; &thorn;are-of na worde rysis.</L>
<L>Bot &amp; god graunt vs &thorn;e gree &middot; grete glorie haue we &thorn;an,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e athelist emperoure we wan &middot; euen at oure will.</L>
<L>Be no&yogh;t to sturten with &thorn;i sturte &middot; to stryue vs a-gayn,</L>
<L>For many leres may &thorn;e limpe &middot; slik as &thorn;ou no&yogh;t wenes!"
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>Quen he had lokid ouir &thorn;e lyne &middot; he la&yogh;es at hire wordis,</L>
<L N="3761">And to &thorn;at lady belyme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> belyue.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;is lettre he writis.</L>
<L>&para; "I, Alexander, &thorn;at am aire &middot; of Amon him-selfe,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maistres out of Amazoyne &middot; many-fald ioyes!</L>
<L>Thre partys of &thorn;e proud werde &middot; I playnly haue won,</L>
<L N="3765">Affrike &amp; Asye &middot; and Europ &thorn;at othire.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was neuire man a-pon mold &middot; oure mi&yogh;tis to with|stand,</L>
<L>And fe&yogh;t with vs in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e fild; &middot; &yogh;ow fallis &thorn;e same.</L>
<L>Bot be-cause we lufe &yogh;our comyng &middot; we consall &yogh;ow blyth</L>
<L>To pas out with &yogh;our paramours &middot; &amp; pere vs be-forne.</L>
<L N="3770">On Amon oure athill sire &middot; an athe I &yogh;ow make,</L>
<L>Of vs to suffire na sare &middot; to sauely to wende,</L>
<L>Bathe oure gold &yogh;ow to gefe &middot; &amp; of oure gud kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>To mary to &yogh;oure maidens &middot; &amp; make &thorn;am a vaunced."</L>
<L N="3774">Sone as &thorn;ai wist of his will &middot; &thorn;ai wi&yogh;tly him sente</L>
<L>Ten vncorsayd coltis &middot; &thorn;e clennest of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>And as mony to amend &middot; of milk-quyte stedis,</L>
<L N="3777">Of mony &amp; of mekill quat &middot; mayn giftis.</L>
<L>Dame Calistride &thorn;e conquiris &middot; comes with hire ladis,</L>
<L>Mas hire pes with oure prince &middot; &amp; pas to hire landis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="17" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Decimus septimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en come a sande to &thorn;is sire &middot; in &thorn;e same tyme,<MILESTONE N="65a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at kyng porrus &thorn;e proud &middot; with pers out of ynde</L>
<L>Was in &thorn;e bonds of Batriane &middot; &amp; eft<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. oft <I>or</I> ost.</NOTE> had assemblid</L>
<L N="3783">Ano&thorn;ire ost of odmen &middot; him eft on to ride.</L>
<L>As hastely as he it herd &middot; his ostis he flittis,</L>
<L>And athils harnest on hors &middot; a hundreth &amp; fyfti</L>
<L>Was chosene<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. chosens.</NOTE> to chiftans &middot; &amp; all of chefe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. chede, <I>altered to</I> chefe.</NOTE> dukes,</L>
<L N="3787">Ordand of oure emperoure &middot; his ostis to lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us pas he furthe with his princes &middot; ser Porrus to mete,</L>
<L>In August eftir Iuli &middot; as &thorn;e boke tellis.
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>All ware &thorn;ai swollen of &thorn;e swete &middot; &amp; sweltid on &thorn;e son;</L>
<L>Sum in &thorn;aire harnais for hete &middot; was honest for euire.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went be waldis &amp; be wastis &middot; &thorn;ar watirs ware nane,</L>
<L>And armed bud &thorn;am all bee &middot; for angwischis o bestis,</L>
<L N="3794">As colwers &amp; for coltris &middot; &amp; crabbid snakis,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ire warla&yogh;es wild &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e wod duelled.</L>
<L>As ai stremand sternes &middot; stared all &thorn;aire wedis,</L>
<L>Of gai glitirand gold &middot; glesenyd &thorn;aire schildis.</L>
<L N="3798">&THORN;ai dro&yogh;e furth be dissert &middot; &amp; drinkles &thorn;ai spill,</L>
<L>Was nouthire waldis in &thorn;ar walke &middot; ne watir to fynde.</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t &thorn;at zephall was callid &middot; fand in a cole schade</L>
<L>A litill drysnyng of dewe &middot; was droppid fra &thorn;e heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was in a holo&yogh;e stane &middot; &amp; in his helme fillis,</L>
<L>And bringis it to oure bald kyng &middot; to brigge with his hetis.</L>
<L N="3804">&THORN;an Alexander to &thorn;is athill &middot; all &thorn;us he spekis,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is solayne sope if I sup &middot; quethire sustene it may</L>
<L>&THORN;e menbris of &thorn;e Messedones &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e many Persens,</L>
<L>Or I my-selfe sall be serued &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai sitt with nyfils?"</L>
<L>"Sire, &yogh;e sall first be refreschid" &middot; faythly he sayd.</L>
<L N="3809">"Quat? &amp; &yogh;e perisch?" quod &thorn;e prince &middot; "&amp; pas out o lyue?</L>
<L>Que&thorn;ir euir me list &thorn;an to lefe &middot; with langour &amp; sorowe?"<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And hilds it doun out of &thorn;e helme &middot; befor his athils all.</L>
<L>&THORN;an slike a comfurth &thorn;am enclosed &middot; for his kynd wordis,</L>
<L>As all &thorn;e watir of &thorn;e werd &middot; ware in &thorn;aire wambs hellid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ferd &thorn;ai furth till a fflode &middot; &amp; findis all &thorn;e strandis</L>
<L N="3815">Full of Redis, as I rede &middot; rughere &thorn;an thornes.</L>
<L>His folke fell to it fast &middot; &amp; freschely &thorn;ai drynke,</L>
<L>Bot was na<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. r na.</NOTE> renke at to it ran &middot; at euire rase eftire.</L>
<L>It was so keruand &amp; kene! &middot; &thorn;an was his kni&yogh;tis stroubid</L>
<L>Mare for &thorn;e bale of &thorn;aire bestis &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Put for</I> than.</NOTE> brist of &thorn;aim-selfe.</L>
<L>For with his florantis olifants &middot; him folowed a thousand,</L>
<L N="3821">Of sithid chariotis &amp; soo &middot; &amp; sextene hundreth,</L>
<L>With co&yogh;rres<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic</I>.</NOTE> &amp; with clene floure &middot; camels and mules,</L>
<L>And out of nounbre of nowte &middot; at nedid to his ostis,
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>Thre C Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot">I.e. Three hundred thousand.</NOTE> in thede &middot; of thra men of armes.</L>
<L>Be now &thorn;ai ware so ne&yogh;e tane &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ai for nede supposid,</L>
<L N="3826">Sum of his awen vryn &middot; &amp; sum on Iren lickid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was sorowe any segge &middot; &thorn;e si&yogh;t to be-hald!</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires him on ser Alexander &middot; with angwischis &amp; payne,</L>
<L>Ay folo&yogh;e furth by &thorn;e flumme &middot; at I first tald,</L>
<L N="3830">And at &thorn;e a&yogh;tand houre &middot; I ame, of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&THORN;an comes &thorn;aim to a castell &middot; was closid in &thorn;e borne.</L>
<L>It was a mervalous mote &middot; made all of redis,</L>
<L>And foure forlange, I finde &middot; &thorn;e flode was o brede.</L>
<L N="3834">A fewe within &thorn;e forslet &middot; of folke &thorn;are a-perid,</L>
<L>Waiteand out at wyndows &middot; to wondire on his ostis.</L>
<L>Sire Alexander bad his men &middot; aske &thorn;aim of ynde,</L>
<L>And frayne quare &thorn;ai find mi&yogh;t &middot; any fresch watir;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;an hent in &thorn;aire hedis &middot; &amp; hidd &thorn;am belyue.<MILESTONE N="66a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3839">And he felly with flane &middot; flingis at &thorn;e wallis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it for na spell at he spirid &middot; spek wald &thorn;ai neuire.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an comandis he his kni&yogh;t[is] &middot; kenely to swymme,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai all bare, saue &thorn;e breke &middot; with brandis in hand,</L>
<L N="3843">&THORN;an thringis in on a throw &middot; thretty &amp; seuyn.</L>
<L>Als fast as &thorn;ai &thorn;e forthing-dole &middot; had of &thorn;e flode past,</L>
<L>&THORN;an girds &thorn;are vp fra &thorn;e ground &middot; &amp; grymly &thorn;aim woundis</L>
<L>Of Seeles &amp; of see-Bules &middot; a swyth grete nounbre,</L>
<L>Dro&yogh;e &thorn;am doun in-to &thorn;e depe &middot; &amp; drouned &thorn;am for euire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;ede he &thorn;ine with his erles<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. el erles, <I>but corrected</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; egirly him thristis;</L>
<L N="3849">Lebards lendis &thorn;aim agaynes &middot; leons &amp; beres;</L>
<L>Dragons &amp; dromondaris &middot; &amp; of &thorn;ir derfe Tigirs</L>
<L>Fra morne to &thorn;e mirke ni&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;aim maynly assailed.</L>
<L N="3852">&THORN;us ra&yogh;t he fra &thorn;is reuir &middot; be many ru&yogh;e waies</L>
<L>To it was meten to &thorn;e mere &middot; to myd-ouir-vndorne.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come he streke on a staunke &middot; &thorn;e store me tellis,</L>
<L>Was neuir na hony in na hyue &middot; vndire heuen swettir.</L>
<L N="3856">A foure furelange or fyue &middot; it was of full brede,</L>
<L>Umby-thorned<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Umby-thonred.</NOTE> with a thike wod &middot; thre mile a-boute,
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>Was all of &thorn;e Rede ryse &middot; as I redd first;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he cuttis doun clene &middot; &amp; kindils in fyris.</L>
<L N="3860">He gert tild vp his tentis &middot; be &thorn;at terne syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o&yogh;t &thorn;are a longe quile to lie &middot; &amp; lachen his esee.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mone ouir &thorn;e montayns &middot; meryly it schynes</L>
<L>Or he mi&yogh;t drinke any drope &middot; &amp; &thorn;en his dole ne&yogh;es.</L>
<L N="3864">&THORN;an comes &thorn;are-out creuesses &middot; of manykins hewis,</L>
<L>Scorpions &thorn;aim to scere &middot; &amp; scalid neddirs,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai so large &amp; so laith &middot; &amp; so lowd schrikis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e soile of &thorn;a sidis &middot; of &thorn;e sound ryngis.<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3868">Dragons dryfes doun o dri&yogh;t &middot; fra &thorn;e derfe hillis,</L>
<L>With kene carefull crie &middot; and crestis on &thorn;aire hedis,</L>
<L>Grisely gapand &amp; grim &middot; with gilden brestis,</L>
<L>And flawmes feruent as fyre &middot; flo&yogh;e fra &thorn;aire e&yogh;en;</L>
<L N="3872">&THORN;ai drewe toward oure douth &middot; with dedly blastis.</L>
<L>Sir Alexander &amp; his ost &middot; was ar&yogh;ed vnfaire,</L>
<L>Was &thorn;are na freke in &thorn;e fild &middot; &thorn;at faithly he leued</L>
<L>To be deuowrid &amp; devoidid &middot; &amp; vencuste for euire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;an comfurthid his kni&yogh;tis &middot; all if he care &thorn;oled:</L>
<L>"Mi bald baratours," he bad &middot; "a-baste no&yogh;t &yogh;oure hertis;</L>
<L N="3878">Seis ensampill at my-selfe &middot; &amp; seke &yogh;e na ferre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ferrre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot hedis haly to my hand &middot; &amp; harmes &thorn;ar-eftire."</L>
<L>A brand &amp; a bri&yogh;t schild &middot; bremely he hentis,</L>
<L>Fe&yogh;tis freschely &amp; fast &middot; with &thorn;a fell bestis,</L>
<L>Dasches dragons doun &middot; geuys &thorn;aim depe woundis,</L>
<L N="3883">Slaes of &thorn;a serpentis &middot; many sadd hundreth.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bildid of his bachelers &middot; &amp; braidis to &thorn;aire wapen;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai ware mased &amp; amayd &middot; maynely &thorn;aim fe&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;ar twenti &thorn;at time &middot; tangid to dede,</L>
<L N="3887">And &thorn;at &thorn;e comliest kni&yogh;tis &middot; at &thorn;e kyng ledis;</L>
<L>Of athill archars als &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>A-boute a thretty in &thorn;at thede &middot; tharned &thorn;aire lyfes.</L>
<L>&THORN;us many deid of his douth &middot; as &thorn;e boke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. beke.</NOTE> tellis,</L>
<L N="3891">And him limpis all &thorn;e loose &middot; be &thorn;e lattire end.</L>
<L>Now comes a company of Crabbe-fische &middot; as calues gret,
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>Meuand of &thorn;is marras &middot; oure men to assaill,</L>
<L>With backis, as &thorn;e buke sais &middot; biggir &amp; hardere</L>
<L N="3895">&THORN;an ony comon cogill-stane &middot; or cocatryse scales.<MILESTONE N="67a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quen kni&yogh;tis of oure conquirours &middot; kest at &thorn;am lances,</L>
<L>Was nane so wele-stelid poynt &middot; at &thorn;am perse mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Bot gomes with &thorn;aire greues in twa &middot; in &thorn;e gledis spurned,</L>
<L N="3899">And all at left ware o lyue &middot; in-to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to, <I>with</I> in <I>and</I> &thorn;e <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> lo&yogh;e entirs.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ai had fyneschid &thorn;is fi&yogh;t &middot; was ferre in with euyn,</L>
<L>Foure houres full farne &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fifte<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fi&yogh;te, <I>altered to</I> fifte.</NOTE> neghes.</L>
<L>And leons quyte as lylly &middot; lent &thorn;am agayn,</L>
<L N="3903">Of bodis biggire &thorn;an bules &middot; berand vnfaire.</L>
<L>Oure kni&yogh;tis at &thorn;e first come<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. cl come.</NOTE> &middot; clenly &thorn;aim slo&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Alto bretind &thorn;aim on bent &middot; &amp; bro&yogh;t &thorn;aim on fli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wild berys in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e wast &middot; fra &thorn;e wodd comes,</L>
<L N="3907">With ilka tenefull tothe &middot; as tyndis of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. l of.</NOTE> harowis,</L>
<L>A cubete lenth, sais &thorn;e clause &middot; cald was &thorn;e lest.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai seke out be sundres &middot; sexti to-gedire,</L>
<L>With wild men of &thorn;e wast &middot; &amp; women e-bland,</L>
<L N="3911">With sex handis, &amp; soo &middot; sett out of kynd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai held in hettirly &middot; &amp; hurtis of his kni&yogh;tis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai with brandis &amp; bowis &middot; bremely &thorn;aim woundis,</L>
<L>Slo&yogh;e of &thorn;a sauagyus &middot; a sowme out of nombre,</L>
<L>And many scopid into &thorn;e scoghe &middot; without scath mare.</L>
<L N="3916">Sire Alexander &amp; his ost &middot; angwisch enduris,</L>
<L>Was waik, as na wondre was &middot; &amp; wery for-fo&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>And &thorn;am he bedis at a braide &middot; to beet vp &thorn;e stank,</L>
<L N="3919">With-out his ost ouir all &middot; horrible fires.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come a beste of a busche &middot; with a blak heued,</L>
<L>Mad &amp; merkid as a Meere &middot; &thorn;e mast of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>Fere fersere &thorn;an an olifant &middot; as we find written,</L>
<L N="3923">Stayrand on to &thorn;e staunke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I> to &thorn;e stank, <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;e stour to asaill.<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is breme best bare &middot; as<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. as as.</NOTE> &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Before forne in &thorn;e fronte &middot; thre fell tyndis,
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>Hedous horns &amp; hoge &middot; &amp; hi&yogh;t in &thorn;aire tonge</L>
<L N="3927">Adanttrocay with all men &middot; as I am enfourmed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. in enfourmed.</NOTE></L>
<L>Before scho drank of &thorn;is dam &middot; his douth sho assaild,</L>
<L>And oure kyng with his carpe &middot; his kni&yogh;tis he gladis.</L>
<L>A&yogh;t &amp; tuenti men of armes &middot; onone scho delyuird,</L>
<L N="3931">Bernes was di&yogh;t &thorn;e deth &middot; with dintis enoghe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an mys out of &thorn;is marras &middot; as any mayn foxes<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. faxes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Come furth, &amp; fedd &thorn;aim in-fere &middot; of &thorn;e ded corses.</L>
<L>All at was bitten of &thorn;a best &middot; was at a brunt dede,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it &thorn;ai noyed bot a nykid &middot; to nane &thorn;at was ermed.</L>
<L>&THORN;an flo&yogh;e &thorn;ar by &thorn;e firmament &middot; of &thorn;a foule Backes,</L>
<L N="3937">Als store &amp; as stalword &middot; as &thorn;ire sedill dowis</L>
<L>With mekill ma&yogh;ten teeth &middot; as it of men ware;</L>
<L>And at vn-armed<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> was &middot; &thorn;ai asperly wondid,</L>
<L>Of sum &thorn;ai nyppid fra &thorn;e nebb &middot; &thorn;e nose be &thorn;e e&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="3941">Of sum &thorn;ai ete of &thorn;aire eris &middot; euen by &thorn;e rotis,</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;ai luggid of &thorn;e lippis &middot; &thorn;e lire fra &thorn;e chekis,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ar bitis, as &thorn;e buke sais &middot; blemest na kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come a fli&yogh;tir in of fowls &middot; as fast as it dawid,</L>
<L N="3945">To vise on as vowtres &middot; as vermeon hewid,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire boukis &amp; &thorn;ar bathire fete &middot; was of blak sable,</L>
<L>And did bot plaid by &thorn;e pepill &middot; &amp; fed &thorn;aim on fyschis.</L>
<L>Quen he had voidid &thorn;is vermyn &middot; &amp; vencust &thorn;at of ynde,</L>
<L N="3949">Out of &thorn;is perlaous<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; read</I> peralous.</NOTE> place &middot; he past with his ost</L>
<L>In-to the boundis of Bactry &middot; &thorn;ar bildid he his tentis.<MILESTONE N="68a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are reches was of redde gold &middot; &amp; many riche gemes;</L>
<L>And clene all &thorn;at contre &middot; qwen &thorn;ai his come wist,</L>
<L N="3953">&THORN;ai mett him full manerly &middot; &amp; mekely resayued</L>
<L>With presentes of pirre &middot; &amp; many proude giftes,</L>
<L>And thretti dayis in &thorn;at thede &middot; he tholes &amp; abidis.</L>
<L>A sertane folke was in &thorn;at soile &middot; &thorn;at Serres ere callid,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e lyndis in &thorn;at land &middot; with leves<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. levys, <I>altered to</I> leves.</NOTE> as wolle.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ire Serres, at I said &middot; &thorn;aim in &thorn;e Somere gedirs,</L>
<L>And makis &thorn;aim wedis &thorn;ar-of &middot; to were for wintris blastis.
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="222"></L>
<L N="3960">&THORN;ire baratours bawers &middot; ere bremly reioyed</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e conquest of &thorn;ire cocatrices &middot; &amp; of &thorn;a kene bestis;</L>
<L>And now he caire[s] fra &thorn;at kithe &middot; &amp; comes in a stounde</L>
<L>Quare Porrus with his powere &middot; on a playn lengis.</L>
<L N="3964">Sire Alexander &amp; his ost &middot; caires<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a cayres.</NOTE> &thorn;aim a-gayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a gyn gayne; <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>With brade<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. brade brade; <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE> baners &amp; bri&yogh;t &middot; &amp; bragging of troumpis.</L>
<L>Apon &thorn;e bald bocifalon &middot; before his men all</L>
<L>He flingis out a forelange &middot; his feris to assaile.</L>
<L N="3968">&THORN;e Persens putt &thorn;aim in pres &middot; &amp; &thorn;e proude grekis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Medis &amp; &thorn;e Messedons &middot; maynely &thorn;ai fe&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai swey doun as swiftly &middot; &thorn;a swart men of ynde,</L>
<L>As euire did corne in a croft &middot; be-fore a kene sithe.</L>
<L N="3972">Quen sir Porrus sa&yogh;e his princes &middot; in &thorn;e prese faile,</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires he out be-for his ost &middot; on Alexander callis:</L>
<L>"It comes," he said, "to na kyng &middot; ne kidd emperoure</L>
<L>To latt his pepill &thorn;us pas &middot; &amp; perisch in ydill;</L>
<L>It fallis mare faire him &thorn;e fi&yogh;t &middot; to fynesch him-selfe.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i lat stedill all oure stoure &middot; &amp; stedd &thorn;am esoundire,</L>
<L N="3978">&THORN;i semble o &thorn;e taa syde &middot; &amp; myne on &thorn;e tothire;</L>
<L>Lat vs twa termyn &thorn;e taite &middot; be-twene vs alane.<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If I be vencust in &thorn;e vaile &middot; &amp; voidid of my lyfe,</L>
<L>Lat all my seggis &amp; soile &middot; be to &thorn;i-selfe &yogh;olden;</L>
<L N="3982">And if &thorn;ou failis in &thorn;e fild &middot; &amp; I &thorn;e floure wynn,</L>
<L>Latt &thorn;an &thorn;ine erlis &amp; &thorn;ine erd &middot; myne empire obeyi."</L>
<L>Thus porrus in his hi&yogh;e pride &middot; to oure kyng spekis,</L>
<L>For he was litill &amp; laghe &middot; him laythly dispices.</L>
<L N="3986">For quen he wan to wax &middot; &thorn;e writt me recordis,</L>
<L>Thre cubettis fra &thorn;e croune doun &middot; his cors had a lenghte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e person of ser Porrus &middot; past him &thorn;at hi&yogh;t twyse,</L>
<L>He feetis him forth in his force &middot; &amp; in his faire hi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e prowis &amp; &thorn;e prouidens &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e pure thewis</L>
<L N="3991">&THORN;at lurkis with-in &thorn;is lede &middot; full litill he kennes.</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;e partise in pes &middot; &amp; &thorn;ai &thorn;e place dele;</L>
<L>Aithire kyng with his cause &middot; encontres on othire.
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>Sire Porrus with a proude swerd &middot; him on &thorn;e pan strikis</L>
<L>So snelle at he snatirs with &middot; nere snaypid him for euire.</L>
<L N="3996">&THORN;an kastis vp a kene crie &middot; &thorn;e kni&yogh;tis out of ynde,</L>
<L>For he was dased of &thorn;e dint &middot; &amp; half dede him semyd.</L>
<L>Porrus, as a prince suld &middot; persayued &thorn;ar latis,</L>
<L>Turnes him toward his tulkis &middot; &amp; titely rehetis.</L>
<L N="4000">Sire Alexander him avises &middot; &amp; his aande takis,</L>
<L>As bald barratour &amp; breme &middot; his brand vp he liftis,</L>
<L N="4002">With bathe his handis in-to &thorn;e brayne &middot; his basenet he cleuys,</L>
<L N="4002*">And he fallis doun fey &middot; &amp; fynes in &thorn;at stound.</L>
<L N="4003">&THORN;e pepill of ser Porrus &middot; quen &thorn;ai [him] pas sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>With all manere of men &middot; maynly &thorn;ai fi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"A! wriches!" quod &thorn;e wale kyng &middot; &amp; wisely he spekis,</L>
<L>"Eftir &thorn;e deth of <I>&yogh;our</I> duke &middot; quat deynes &yogh;owe to stryue?</L>
<L>Wete &yogh;e wele," quod &thorn;e wee &middot; "be werrayours la&yogh;es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at quen &thorn;e gouernoure is gane &middot; &thorn;an is &thorn;e gomes wastid."<MILESTONE N="69a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4009">"Sire, it is better for to bate &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e bent faile,</L>
<L>&THORN;an se &thorn;is rewthe on &yogh;our<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> our.</NOTE> renkis &middot; &amp; reft be &yogh;our<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> our.</NOTE> gudis."</L>
<L>"Sirs, blynes of &yogh;our bataile &middot; &amp; bowes to &yogh;oure landis;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure fermes &amp; &yogh;oure fraunches &middot; I frely &yogh;ow grant;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e haue cockid for &yogh;our kyng &middot; &yogh;e sall no care suffire!"</L>
<L>And &thorn;an callid him on knese &middot; &amp; kest doun &thorn;aire armes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai come to &thorn;is conquirour &middot; comend him as dri&yogh;tin,</L>
<L N="4016">&THORN;an sett he sales vp of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> silke &middot; &amp; sacrifece makis.</L>
<L>Sire Porrus, as him wele fell &middot; he proudely enteris,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e fey in &thorn;e fild &middot; &amp; here a fitt ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="18" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>Decimus octauus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an aires he furth with his erlis &middot; &amp; entris an Ile,</L>
<L>Quare &thorn;ir Exidraces as Ermets &middot; inhabet in caues,</L>
<L>A progenie of pore men &middot; &thorn;at neuir pride hauntis,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;e gentill genosophis &middot; &thorn;am in &thorn;e gest callis.</L>
<L N="4023">Is &thorn;are na bost &thorn;aim ebland &middot; ne bataills vsyd,
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="224"></L>
<L N="4024">Nouthire cites in to sytt &middot; cellis, nor na tounes,</L>
<L>Bot crepis in-to creuesse &middot; &amp; craggis on hillis,</L>
<L>And ay is naked [as] a nedill &middot; as natour &thorn;am schapis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at contre &middot; quen he &thorn;e come heres</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is prince &amp; his parray &middot; &thorn;is pistill he him sendis.</L>
<L N="4029">"We, corruptible creatours &middot; &amp; cald as be-fore,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mode man of Messedone &middot; all &thorn;us-gate I write.</L>
<L>Sire, it is sayd to oure-selfe &middot; with sere mens tongis,</L>
<L N="4032">How &thorn;ou comes in-to oure kith-ward &middot; to cumbre vs with care,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at Vs wondres, I-wis &middot; for wyn may &yogh;e nouthire<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> neuir?</NOTE><MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nouthire gold ne na gude &middot; at euer gode fourmed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fourmned.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sen at we Ioy nouthire gemmes &middot; ne Iuwels in cofirs,</L>
<L N="4036">Pelour, pirre, ne perle &middot; ne na proude wedis,</L>
<L>Ne sauand bot to sustene with &middot; oure awen sary craftis,</L>
<L>Quat in &thorn;is time may &yogh;e take &middot; if &yogh;e oure termes entre?</L>
<L>If &yogh;e will seke in-to oure soile &middot; &amp; sett vs agayne,</L>
<L>Oure simpilnes &amp; oure sobirte &middot; forsake sall we neuire."</L>
<L>Quen he had lokid ouire &thorn;e lefe &middot; a lettre he in-dities,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he aproched all with pes &middot; &amp; in na plite ellis.</L>
<L>Quen he was entrid &thorn;ar erde &middot; &amp; sees &thorn;aim all nakid,</L>
<L>And won as it ware wildirnes &middot; in wastis &amp; greues,</L>
<L>Darke in dennes vndire dounes &middot; &amp; in derne holis,</L>
<L N="4046">And bath &thorn;ar bridis &amp; &thorn;ar barnes &middot; with bestes on &thorn;e fellis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fild fellis; <I>corrected.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander at &thorn;am askis &middot; &amp; all him a-wondres:</L>
<L>"Haue &yogh;e na houses ne na hames &middot; ne holis in to bery?"</L>
<L N="4049">And &thorn;ar &thorn;ai schewid him in schurrys &middot; to schellis &amp; to caues,</L>
<L>Said, "here we ilka day duell &middot; deuyse how &yogh;ow likis."</L>
<L>Quen he &thorn;aire simpilnes sees &middot; he soro&yogh;es in his hert,</L>
<L>Pleynes of &thorn;aire pouerte &middot; &amp; profurs &thorn;aim full faire,</L>
<L>"Quat euire &yogh;e will in all &thorn;e werd &middot; or I wend, askis,</L>
<L N="4054">And I sall gladly &yogh;ow geue &middot; with a gud will."
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>"Sire, neuire to dee," quod &thorn;ai &thorn;an &middot; "bot euire dure o lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we desire &yogh;ow bedene &middot; &amp; &thorn;an do vs na mare."</L>
<L>"Be dri&yogh;tin, sirs, I am a duke &middot; dedelike my-selfe,</L>
<L N="4058">For&thorn;i vnde[d]lynes to dele &middot; I dowe be na ways."</L>
<L>"Now sen it worthis," quod &thorn;a wees &middot; "wriche, for to die,</L>
<L N="4060">Quarto hi&yogh;is &thorn;ou fra half to halfe &middot; &amp; all &thorn;is harme wirkis?"</L>
<L>"Sire, be my croune," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "&thorn;e cause at I haue<MILESTONE N="70a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is purly gods prouidens &middot; predestayned it is before.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e se, wele seldom is &thorn;e see &middot; with him-selfe turbild</L>
<L>Bot with &thorn;ir walowand windis; &middot; my will ware to rifte,</L>
<L>Bot a-no&thorn;ir gast, &amp; no&yogh;t my gast &middot; &thorn;ar-of my gast lettis;"</L>
<L>And wendis a-way with &thorn;at word &middot; &amp; wemles &thorn;aim leuys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund day with vp son &middot; he with his sowme ne&yogh;es,</L>
<L>Quare &thorn;ire Imagis ere &thorn;at Arculious &middot; had in an Ile rerid.</L>
<L N="4069">&THORN;e tane was all athill gold &middot; of siluir &thorn;e tothire,</L>
<L>Twelfe cubettis fra &thorn;e topp doun &middot; &amp; twa was &thorn;e brede.</L>
<L>He made his pepill &thorn;aim to perse &middot; to proue &thorn;am with-in,</L>
<L>Quethire &thorn;ai ware hologhe or hale &middot; &amp; hale he &thorn;am fyndis,</L>
<L>Sa&yogh;e &thorn;aim thike &thorn;ur&yogh;e-out &middot; &amp; aithire thrill stoppis,</L>
<L N="4074">And fillis &thorn;am florentis &middot; a fyftene hundreth.</L>
<L>&THORN;an drafe he &thorn;ine with his dukis &middot; in a deyne entris,</L>
<L N="4076">A wilsom wast &amp; wild &middot; &amp; wondirly colde,</L>
<L>As mirke as any mydni&yogh;t &middot; quen &thorn;e mone failes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnnethes ken may a kni&yogh;t &middot; to se to his fere.</L>
<L N="4079">Fifty days be desert &middot; he foundis with his folke,</L>
<L>Till he come blesenand on a brym &middot; was welland hate,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e ferre halfe of &thorn;e bourne &middot; was wemen on hors,</L>
<L>&THORN;at frely faire ware of face &middot; bot foule ware clethid.</L>
<L>Sum beris all of brent gold &middot; brandis in &thorn;aire handis,</L>
<L>Sum bataill-axes &amp; with bowes &middot; all of bri&yogh;t siluir,</L>
<L>For brase is nane with &thorn;a bonds &middot; ne no bige Iren;</L>
<L N="4086">Ne neuire na berne &thorn;am ebland &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>&THORN;an wald his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> his.</NOTE> pepill &amp; his princes &middot; haue past ouir &thorn;e bourne,</L>
<L>And mi&yogh;t no&yogh;t for &thorn;e morsure &middot; &amp; maynyng of bestis,</L>
<L N="4089">It was so borely &amp; brade &middot; &amp; bred full of ydres,<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of dragons &amp; of othire deuyls &middot; &amp; doukand neddirs.</L>
<L>&THORN;an caires furth oure conquirour &middot; with his kid ostis,</L>
<L N="4092">Lede &thorn;am be &thorn;e left side &middot; of &thorn;e lande of ynde,</L>
<L>Sone was he dreuyn with his dukis &middot; in-to a dryi meere,</L>
<L>Was full of gladen &amp; of gale &middot; &amp; of grete redis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sny&yogh;es &thorn;ar, out of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. if, <I>altered to</I> of.</NOTE> &thorn;at snyth hill &middot; as with a snayles pas,</L>
<L N="4096">A burly best with a bake &middot; as bedell as a sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Kene tethe as a knyfe &middot; a cowdrife breste,</L>
<L>Of sembalaunce as a see-bule &middot; &amp; slo&yogh;e him twa kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>Wald &thorn;ar na brande in him bite &middot; ne no bigge launce,</L>
<L>Bot alto-maukid hire with maces &middot; &amp; mellis of Iren.</L>
<L N="4101">A twenti dais ouire ten &middot; with torfare &thorn;ai ride;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e formast forest of ynde &middot; oure folke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> all aprochid.</L>
<L>Euyn at &thorn;e flode of Eumare &middot; oure emperoure logis,</L>
<L N="4104">And at &thorn;e xj houre &middot; I ame, as it ware,</L>
<L>Of Olifants out of &thorn;e ways &middot; an endles nounbre</L>
<L>Come with a carefull crie &middot; oure kni&yogh;tis to assaill.</L>
<L>A-pon &thorn;e bald Bucifalon &middot; he bremely ascendis,</L>
<L>Bedis of his swiers ga swyth &middot; &amp; swyne with &thorn;aim take.</L>
<L N="4109">&THORN;ai ware a-baiste all belyue &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at durst na berne on &thorn;e bent &middot; a-bide bot him-selfe.</L>
<L>"Be no&yogh;t a-baist, my bachelars" &middot; &thorn;e bald kyng sayd,</L>
<L N="4112">"For with &thorn;e sweling of &thorn;e swyne &middot; we sall &thorn;aim all voide."</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai did al bedene &middot; &amp; sum oure douth slo&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Tuke out &thorn;e tuskis &amp; &thorn;e tethe &middot; &amp; ternen of &thorn;e skinnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er dai be desert &middot; &thorn;am destaned to ride,</L>
<L N="4116">Be &thorn;e wild ynde woddis &middot; &amp; wemen &thorn;ai faund</L>
<L>With bare hedes as a barne &middot; &amp; berdis to &thorn;e pappis,<MILESTONE N="71a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>And had na hattir &thorn;am to hele &middot; bot hidis of bestis.</L>
<L>His seggis sesid of &thorn;am sum &middot; &amp; to him-selfe bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;an askid &thorn;am of ynde &middot; &amp; at &thorn;am enquires,</L>
<L N="4121">Quat was &thorn;aire viaunce in &thorn;a vales &middot; "ser, venyson," &thorn;ai said,</L>
<L>"Slike as we haunt in &thorn;ar holis &middot; with hunting in tymes."</L>
<L>&THORN;en ferd &thorn;ai furth all in fere &middot; &amp; to fild comys,</L>
<L N="4124">Euyn to &thorn;e heued of Eumaure &middot; as I first rekend.</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand &thorn;ai bernys &amp; bridis &middot; &amp; all bale-nakid,</L>
<L>At was resild as a resch &middot; &amp; roghe as a<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> abr, <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> bere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;e custom of &thorn;ar kinde &middot; as &thorn;e clause tellis,</L>
<L>Als wele to bide in &thorn;e bourne &middot; as on &thorn;e brade lande.</L>
<L N="4129">Onone as &thorn;ai on Alexander &middot; &amp; on his ost waites,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai flee as fast in-to flode &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e founce plangid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ferd &thorn;ai furthe be &thorn;e frithis &middot; fiftene dais.</L>
<L>And sa &thorn;ai willid in-to a wod &middot; was full [of] wild bestis,</L>
<L N="4133">Rynoceros, as I rede &middot; &thorn;e romance &thorn;am callis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai assembild on oure seggis &middot; bot &thorn;ai ware sone drepid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sexti days with his seggis &middot; he so&yogh;t be disert,</L>
<L N="4136">Till he was won in-to a werd &middot; all of wast fildis,</L>
<L>Quare nouthire holtis was ne hilles &middot; ne no hi&yogh;e [h]eggis,</L>
<L>Bot all as planir &amp; as playn &middot; as a playn table.</L>
<L N="4139">Euen at &thorn;e elleuynt houre &middot; or euynsange tyme,</L>
<L>Quen he had tild vp his tentis &middot; turbils &thorn;e welken;</L>
<L>&THORN;e semblant sorowis of &thorn;e soile &middot; &amp; &thorn;e son wadis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e werd wannes at a wap &middot; &amp; &thorn;e wedire gloumes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fell a fli&yogh;t &amp; a fire &middot; betwene &thorn;e foure wyndis,</L>
<L N="4144">Aquiloun &amp; Affrike &middot; &amp; ewrus &thorn;e thrid,</L>
<L>Vulturnus &thorn;e violent &middot; &thorn;at voidis doun &thorn;e leuys,<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e south &amp; of all sydis &middot; sadly &thorn;ai mete,</L>
<L>A breme blast<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. A breme a blast.</NOTE> on &thorn;e bent &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;aire tents it to-terid &middot; &amp; turned doun &thorn;e hallis;</L>
<L N="4149">&thorn;ar pauylyons of pirre &middot; &thorn;aire payntid clathis
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>It alto-schatird, &amp; to-scailed &middot; &thorn;am in sondire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was kni&yogh;tis of &thorn;e case &middot; kenely affraid,</L>
<L N="4152">And ilka segge be him-selfe &middot; said<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> vn-to othire,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e writhe of &thorn;e wale god &middot; I wate, on vs li&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>For oure founding ouire his forbod &middot; so ferre to &thorn;e est."</L>
<L>&THORN;an comforthis &thorn;aim &thorn;e conquirour &middot; &amp; carpis on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="4156">Bad, "baise &yogh;ow no&yogh;t, my baratours &middot; ne batis no&yogh;t &yogh;our hertis,</L>
<L>It is na greme of oure gode &middot; ne grefe at vs fallis,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e entring of &thorn;e equinox &middot; it euire elike-dele kyndils."</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e wedire wex wele &middot; &amp; &thorn;e wynde pesid,</L>
<L>As, be &thorn;e bale neuir so breme &middot; it blynnes at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ferd &thorn;ai forth fra fild to fild &middot; &amp; freschly assemblis</L>
<L>All at was sperpolid on &thorn;e spene &middot; &amp; spilt with &thorn;e blastis.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;an fandis he furth, as I fynd &middot; fyue &amp; twenti days,</L>
<L N="4164">Come to a velans vale &middot; &thorn;are was a vile cheele,</L>
<L>Quare flaggis of &thorn;e fell snawe &middot; fell fra &thorn;e heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a-brade, sais &thorn;e buke &middot; as battis ere of woll.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bett he many bri&yogh;t fire &middot; &amp; lest it blin nold,</L>
<L>And made his folk with &thorn;aire feete &middot; as flores it to trede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hete was &thorn;am a hoge helpe &middot; &amp; hettirly it voidis,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it was perischist, or he past &middot; a part of his kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an vmby-clappis &thorn;aim a cloude &middot; &amp; couirs all ouire,<MILESTONE N="72a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4172">As any pynaund pik &middot; &thorn;e planetis it hidis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at so thestir &amp; so thik &middot; a thre dais eftir,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sa&yogh;e na leme of &thorn;e lyft &middot; ne li&yogh;t of &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fell &thorn;ar fra &thorn;e firmament &middot; as it ware fell sparkis,</L>
<L N="4176">Ropand doun o rede fire &middot; &thorn;an any rayn thikire;</L>
<L>&THORN;aire cabons &amp; &thorn;ar couertours &middot; it kindils on a lowe,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ar pauillions of pall &middot; it to poudire wastis.</L>
<L>It tinds on tend lowe &middot; trappour of stede,</L>
<L N="4180">And many costious costis &middot; consumes in-to askis,</L>
<L>Bages &amp; baners &middot; it blemyschid &amp; swellis,</L>
<L>And quare it ne&yogh;es on &thorn;e nakid &middot; it noyis for euire.
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>&THORN;an knelis doun oure conquirour &middot; &amp; callis on his dri&yogh;tins,</L>
<L N="4184">Giffe &thorn;am siluir &amp; so &middot; &amp; <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line.</I></NOTE>sens at &thorn;aim castis.</L>
<L>Vnneth his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Vnneth is his; <I>with</I> is <I>underlined, and</I> his <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> prayer was past &middot; quen purid all &thorn;e cloudis,</L>
<L>And stint was all &thorn;e stikill stormes &middot; in a stand-quile.</L>
<L>&THORN;en rade he in aray &middot; remowis his ostis,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete flode of Gangem &middot; &amp; graythid &thorn;ar his tents.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="6"></L>
<L>His bernes blischis ouir &thorn;e bourne &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e banke sa&yogh;e</L>
<L N="4190">Quare thre wees in a wraa &middot; welk &thorn;aim allane.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="7"></L>
<L>Sire Alexander bad an athil &middot; aske &thorn;em of ynde,</L>
<L>Quase &thorn;ai ware, quethin &thorn;ai were &middot; &amp; of quat kind.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai him swiftly swarid &middot; with a swete steuyn,</L>
<L>"We ere bald Bragmenys &middot; &thorn;at neuir bale tho&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;an list &thorn;e lord on his lyfe &middot; haue with &thorn;at ledis spoken,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t he haue won ouir &thorn;e watir &middot; for wounding of bestis,</L>
<L N="4197">As see-bule &amp; serpentis &middot; &amp; soukand locerhes,<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bathe eddirs &amp; ascres &middot; &amp; atterand wormes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ire Cocatricesse in creuessis &middot; &thorn;ar kindiles &thorn;ai brede,</L>
<L N="4200">Scorpions many<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> score &middot; scautand neddirs;</L>
<L>And all-way bot in angwisch<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> august.</NOTE> &middot; as &thorn;e buk sais,</L>
<L>And saue &thorn;e Iolite of Iuly &middot; &thorn;ai Iowke in &thorn;a strandis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">July and August.</NOTE></L>
<L>Quen he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> persayued be na poynt &middot; at he pas mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he sary in &thorn;at sithe &middot; &amp; sadly he pleyned,</L>
<L N="4205">Callid to his carpentars &middot; &amp; of his kid wri&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Bad make him boun at a braide &middot; a barge all of redis.</L>
<L>Quen it was done at his diuyse &middot; &amp; dra&yogh;en ouer with hidis,</L>
<L N="4208">Pared &amp; parreld at his pay &middot; pickid &amp; taloghid,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="8"></L>
<L>&THORN;an bowes &thorn;arin a bachelere &middot; to bragmeyn he wendis,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e souereayn sire of &thorn;e soile &middot; &amp; sesid him &thorn;is pistill.</L>
<L>&para; "I, &thorn;at kyng am of kyngis &middot; &amp; crouned of lordis,</L>
<L N="4212">Alexander &thorn;e aire &middot; of Amone oure dri&yogh;tin,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e quene Olimpades &middot; &thorn;at I am of sprongen,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, ser Dindyn, on &thorn;i dese &middot; dities of Ioye.</L>
<L>Sen we chapid out of childhede &middot; &amp; cheued to eldire,
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="230"></L>
<L N="4216">&THORN;at we cuthe any-gates gesse &middot; betwyx gud &amp; ill,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="9"></L>
<L>Syne was oure will ay with witt &middot; to warisch oure saule,</L>
<L>And kest out all vnclennes &middot; &amp; clene it deuoidid;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e philisophour in his fourme &middot; vs feetly declares,</L>
<L N="4220">&THORN;at sa&yogh;e with-outen sapience &middot; it seldoum aproues.</L>
<L>And it is wayued vs to wete &middot; &amp; warned now late,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all oure leuyng &amp; oure la&yogh;es &middot; &yogh;e wetirly dispice,</L>
<L>And &yogh;our manars fra all othire mens &middot; so mekill ere deffirrid,<MILESTONE N="73a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4224">&THORN;at nouthire in see ne in soile &middot; seke &yogh;e na helpe.</L>
<L>Bott deyned it &yogh;our doctryne &middot; bedene vs to write,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure customes &amp; &yogh;oure conscience &middot; &amp; of &yogh;our clene thewis,</L>
<L>We mi&yogh;t sum connynge per cas &middot; chach of &yogh;oure wordis,</L>
<L N="4228">And &yogh;our lare of a leke &middot; suld neuire &thorn;e les worth.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="10"></L>
<L>Slike similitude of science &middot; is sett, as of kynde,</L>
<L>As of a blesand brand &middot; or of a bri&yogh;t candill.</L>
<L>For many li&yogh;tis of a li&yogh;t &middot; is li&yogh;tid othire-quile,</L>
<L N="4232">And &yogh;it &thorn;e li&yogh;t at &thorn;am li&yogh;tis &middot; is li&yogh;tid as before."</L>
<L>Quen he had waytid ouer &thorn;is writtis &middot; his mynd he remembris,</L>
<L>And be &thorn;e same sandisman &middot; him send sike anothire.</L>
<L>&para; "I, ser Dindimus, a duke &middot; &thorn;at neuire deere wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4236">Blith berne on my benke &middot; &thorn;e Bragmeyns maistir,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="11"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e modi kynge of Messedone &middot; &thorn;is maundment I write.</L>
<L>Sire Alexander, &thorn;e athill &middot; at all &thorn;e werd loutis,</L>
<L>Sire, &thorn;e tenour of &thorn;i titill &middot; I trow, be na mare,</L>
<L N="4240">Bot anly wisdom &amp; witt &middot; &thorn;ou willis in &thorn;i saule.</L>
<L>And bettir it is to &thorn;ine a-bofe &middot; &thorn;an buschels of siluir,</L>
<L>And mare passand of prisse &middot; &thorn;an all &thorn;i proude rewmes.</L>
<L>Sen &yogh;e discrecion disire &middot; we depely &yogh;ow pray;</L>
<L>For a kyng with-outen cunnyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cunmynge.</NOTE> &middot; he can no&yogh;t distreyne</L>
<L>His subiectis, &amp; to be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> subi[e]ctis &middot; as subiectis a&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Bot subiectis till his subiectis &middot; his subiectis him makis.
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="231"></L>
<L N="4247">&THORN;ou prayes vs to &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> person &middot; a pistill to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> pis, <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> write</L>
<L>Of all oure lefyng &amp; oure la&yogh;es &middot; &amp; oure land techis;</L>
<L>Quare-of &thorn;e proces to preue &middot; vnpossible it were,<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4250">And if we did it to dome &middot; it dose &yogh;ow na gude.</L>
<L>For &thorn;i tent is all on terrandry<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. terranrry, <I>alt. to</I> terrandry.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; tourment of armes,</L>
<L>In bost &amp; in bobans &middot; in bataills &amp; stryuys,</L>
<L>A craft till oure condicions &middot; at a-cordis bot litill;</L>
<L N="4254">For simpilnes &amp; surquitry &middot; a-sewis no&yogh;t to-gedire.</L>
<L>Bot leue &yogh;e no&yogh;t we be to he&yogh;e &middot; ne hauten of will</L>
<L>To steryn or to sturtyn &middot; or sterid to enuy;</L>
<L>A partie of oure propertes &middot; &amp; of oure pure thewis<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="12"></L>
<L N="4258">&YOGH;it sall I send &yogh;ow to say &middot; sen &yogh;e me so&yogh;t haue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="19" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Decimus Nonus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sire, we &thorn;e Bragmeyns blode &middot; birdis &amp; othire,</L>
<L>A lowly lyfe in oure land &middot; we lede, and a clene.</L>
<L>All ydolatris in oure Ile &middot; ere vttirly devoidid,</L>
<L N="4262">&amp; to na syn vndire son &middot; a-sent we vs neuire.</L>
<L>All &thorn;at ouire mesure is to mekill &middot; emell we declyne,</L>
<L>And nouthire couet we na corne &middot; bot &thorn;at vs kind leues,</L>
<L N="4265">&THORN;at is &thorn;e filling<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. filning, <I>corr. to</I> filling.</NOTE> of fode &middot; &thorn;at ilk flesch askis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-to suffirand oure-selfe &middot; &amp; sobire as a mayden.</L>
<L>Hald we no hors for na harow &middot; ne na horned stottis,</L>
<L>Ne nauthire sondire we &thorn;e soile &middot; ne na sede sawis,</L>
<L>Seke we neuire no sustinance &middot; to saue with oure lyuys.</L>
<L>Set we na saynes in &thorn;e see &middot; ne sese we na fischis,</L>
<L>Ne nouthire hunt we ne hauke &middot; ne hent we na foules,</L>
<L N="4272">Bot sike as growis on &thorn;e gronde &middot; with-outen gomes werke.<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at we fede vs with in-fere &middot; &amp; fillis full oure tables,</L>
<L>A dayntefull diete &middot; &thorn;at damage vs neuire.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>Haue we no cures of courte &middot; ne na cointe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. comite; <I>but indistinct</I>.</NOTE> sewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The former</I> e <I>in</I> sewes <I>is above the line</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="13"></L>
<L N="4276">Swanes ne na swete thing &middot; to swell oure wames.</L>
<L>All superfluyte of soule &middot; &amp; surfet vs wlattis,</L>
<L>To pegge vs as a peny hoge &middot; &thorn;at praysis no&yogh;t oure la&yogh;es.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i failis vs all infirmit[e]s &middot; of ffeuyre &amp; of ells,</L>
<L N="4280">Ne for na febill at we fele &middot; na fysyke vs nedis.</L>
<L>Vs mistris neuire na medcyne &middot; for malidy on erthe,</L>
<L>Bot ay as fresche &amp; as fere &middot; a[s] fisch quen he plays.</L>
<L>Oure lord has lemett vs elike &middot; &thorn;e lenthe of oure days,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar leues na lede in oure lande &middot; langire &thorn;an othire.</L>
<L N="4285">If he be sexti &yogh;ere of sowme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> me <I>added above the line</I>.</NOTE> &middot; &thorn;at a segge lastis,</L>
<L>His successoure has bot &thorn;e same &middot; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e saule &yogh;eldis.</L>
<L>We chaufe vs at na Chymmneys &middot; for chelis of wintir,</L>
<L>Ne comes na clathis on oure corps &middot; for na cald wyndis.</L>
<L N="4289">We bede no&yogh;t to blemysch oure blode &middot; with bodely dissires.</L>
<L>Perseuerance of pacience &middot; &amp; pes we reserue;<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="14"></L>
<L>Oure inward enmys ilkane &middot; we inwardly drepis,</L>
<L N="4292">&THORN;at is to say, all &thorn;e syn &middot; at solp may &thorn;e saule,</L>
<L>As surfet, surquidry, &amp; slawth &middot; &thorn;e seuyn all bedene;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at oure werraours without &middot; vs worthis no&yogh;t at drede.</L>
<L N="4295">For wele sonere is a cite &middot; sesid, or a castell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at segid is on bath sidis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sidid, <I>alt. to</I> sidis.</NOTE> &middot; [than] &thorn;at segid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gegid, <I>alt. to</I> segid.</NOTE> is with-out.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wirkis bot on &thorn;a witerward &middot; &amp; worthis &thorn;aim ouire,</L>
<L>And suffirs so within &thorn;i flesche &middot; &thorn;e faes of &thorn;e saule.</L>
<L>And we sitt all-way so sure &middot; be sand &amp; be wattir,</L>
<L N="4300">&THORN;at na supowell vndire son &middot; seke we vs neuire,<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne schroude to scheld with oure schap &middot; bot &thorn;e schire banes,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e braunches of &thorn;e bowis &middot; &thorn;at beris vs oure fodis.</L>
<L>Haue we na deliteable drinke &middot; of diuerse wynes,
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="233"></L>
<L N="4304">Bot watir of a wale well &middot; or of a wild bourne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sullepe sire &middot; at sett all &thorn;e werde,</L>
<L>In him we lely<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lyly lely; <I>with</I> lyly <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> beleue &middot; &amp; in na la&yogh;e ellis.</L>
<L>In all oure di&yogh;ans on daies &middot; &thorn;at duke we comend,</L>
<L>Wele wenand in anothire werd &middot; to won ay o-lyue.</L>
<L>And quat as pertenys to na profe &middot; vs plese no&yogh;t at lesten,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="15"></L>
<L N="4310">Ne mekills<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> mekill.</NOTE> mellis no&yogh;t oure mouth &middot; bot mesure oure wordis.</L>
<L>Quen as we speke any spech &middot; we speke ai &thorn;e treuth,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an is still as a stane &middot; &amp; stirs it na ferryn.</L>
<L>Riches ne no rede gold &middot; rose we &thorn;am nouthire,</L>
<L N="4314">Bot ay voide of enuy &middot; &amp; of vayne tho&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>Is &thorn;ar na berne vs eblande &middot; biggir &thorn;an anothire,</L>
<L>Of land ne of lor[d]schip &middot; bot all elike simple.</L>
<L N="4317">&THORN;e pouert of oure persons &middot; for plente we hald,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quilke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. quikke; <I>wrongly</I>.</NOTE> is part vs, all &thorn;e pake &middot; be parcells euyn.</L>
<L>Is &thorn;ar na brag in oure bondis &middot; ne bering of armes,</L>
<L N="4320">B[o]t ay perpetuall pes &middot; pi&yogh;t in oure landis.</L>
<L>Ne nouthire Iugement ne Iayll &middot; ne Iustice of aire;</L>
<L>For dose na douth &thorn;ar no dere &middot; to dome to be callid.</L>
<L>Ne custome in oure contre &middot; contraris oure la&yogh;es,</L>
<L N="4324">Is &thorn;ar na mercy ne methe &middot; in oure marche vsyd;</L>
<L>And I sall quethe &thorn;e forqui &middot; &amp; quat is &thorn;e cause:</L>
<L>&thorn;ar dose na modirson o-mys &middot; na mercy to craue,</L>
<L>For auyrice &amp; errogaunce &middot; &amp; all we devoide,<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to na licherous lustes &middot; leeue ve<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; for</I> we.</NOTE> oure membris,</L>
<L N="4329">A-vowtri ne na vayne glorie &middot; ne na vice hauntis,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="16"></L>
<L>Ne neuire to-pli&yogh;t worth a perle &middot; to-ponyscht be-fore.</L>
<L>Fynd we na faute in na freke &middot; &thorn;at vs emange duellis,</L>
<L N="4332">For ay on reson &amp; on ri&yogh;t &middot; rewelle we oure-selfe.</L>
<L>Ne se&yogh;es na segge of oure sede &middot; sodanly of lyue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e aire within oure habitacle &middot; is ai vn-corumpid.</L>
<L>Nouthire to toly ne to taunde &middot; transmitte we na vebbis,</L>
<L N="4336">To vermylion ne violett &middot; ne variant littis.
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>Oure paramours vs to plese &middot; ne pride &thorn;aim beweues,</L>
<L>Nouthire ffurrers, filetts, ne frengs &middot; ne frettis of perle.</L>
<L>Is &thorn;am na surcote of silke &middot; ne serkis of raynes,</L>
<L N="4340">Ne kirtils of camlyn &middot; bot as &thorn;am kynd leues.</L>
<L>Ne ne&yogh;e we neuire &thorn;aim on ni&yogh;t &middot; to naite for na luste,</L>
<L>Bot for to sustayne oure sede &middot; &amp; syn ay to voide.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="17"></L>
<L>Make we na salues for na sares &middot; ne na somir-bathis,</L>
<L N="4344">Bot with &thorn;e wale dewe &middot; &amp; with &thorn;e warme son.</L>
<L>Howe durst any be so bald &middot; to blemysche for schame</L>
<L>&THORN;e hand-werke of &thorn;at hi&yogh;e gode &middot; &thorn;at all oure happe haues?</L>
<L>List vs na lordschips lache &middot; of ledis as oure-selfe,</L>
<L N="4348">For all oure libertes elike &middot; ere lante vs &amp; paysed;</L>
<L>And to sett him in-to seruitute &middot; a syn vs it thinke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god has fourmed to be free &middot; &amp; to his face licknud.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> licknid; <I>with misformed</I> n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Make we na vessall of virre &middot; ne of na clere siluir,</L>
<L N="4352">Ne store staned strenthis &middot; ne na stithe hames,</L>
<L>Manere mynstre, ne mote &middot; ne marbryn werkis,</L>
<L>Bot duells here in disolatis &middot; in dennes &amp; in cauys;</L>
<L>Ne nouthire housing we haue &middot; ay quils we here duell,</L>
<L>Bot at is fetid of flesch &middot; &amp; of na fraunche piers;<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4357">&THORN;at is &thorn;e carions kistis &middot; &thorn;at couers &thorn;e saule,</L>
<L>A full faynt forcelett &middot; &amp; of fen makid.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="18"></L>
<L>We ere na sailers on &thorn;e see &middot; to sell ne to byi;</L>
<L>Ne rede we neuire na retorik &middot; ne rial to speke;</L>
<L N="4361">Bot certis in all simpilnes &middot; sett we oure wordis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at latis neuire lesing &middot; in oure lippis spring.</L>
<L>Ne folo&yogh;e we na ficesyens &middot; ne philisophour scolis,</L>
<L>As sophistri &amp; slik thing &middot; to sott with &thorn;e pepill.</L>
<L N="4365">It is bot wiles &amp; wrenkis &middot; at &thorn;ai with dele,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;are fete &amp; &thorn;ar fare &middot; in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written above the line</I>.</NOTE> falshede it endis.</L>
<L>Lufe we no laike in oure lede &middot; ne la&yogh;and mirthis,</L>
<L N="4368">Bot quen vs pleses to play &middot; we passe &amp; we rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e actis of oure auncestours &middot; &amp; of &thorn;ar athill thewis;</L>
<L>And quen we gamen suld &amp; glade &middot; we grete &amp; we pleyn.
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="235"></L>
<L>And othire sertis wee see<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written above the line.</I></NOTE> &middot; &thorn;at solace oure hertis;</L>
<L N="4372">First, &thorn;e faire firmament &middot; fichid full of sterres,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="19"></L>
<L>&THORN;e rede son, quen he ryses &middot; &amp; rynnys in his sercle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all &thorn;e land with his leme &middot; lewis &amp; cleres;</L>
<L N="4375">&THORN;e playne purperyn see &middot; full of prode fischis,</L>
<L>For tide ne for tempest &middot; it touchis no&yogh;t oure kythis,</L>
<L>Ne neuire sondres oure soile &middot; bot sesis at &thorn;e brinkis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="20" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Vicesimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anothire mirthe is in May &middot; &thorn;at vs maste ioyes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e faire floryscht filds &middot; of floures &amp; of herbys,</L>
<L>Quare-of &thorn;e breth as of bawme &middot; blawis in oure noose,</L>
<L N="4381">&THORN;at ilk sensitife saule &middot; mast souorly delyte,</L>
<L>As in &thorn;e woddis for to walke &middot; vndire wale schawis,</L>
<L>Quen all is lokin ouire with leuys &middot; as it ware littill heuen.<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an haue we liking to lithe &middot; &thorn;e late of &thorn;e foules,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swo&yogh;ing of &thorn;e swift wynde &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e swete wellis.</L>
<L N="4386">&THORN;e kind of &thorn;ire customs &middot; we kepe euire-mare,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="20"></L>
<L>&THORN;e quilk, I hope, ser, &thorn;e to hald &middot; vnhalesom it ware.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou will chalang &thorn;aim be chaunce &middot; chese if &thorn;e likis,</L>
<L>For here is written all &thorn;i will &middot; &amp; we na writh serue.</L>
<L N="4390">As &thorn;e tenour of &yogh;our titill is &middot; oure techis haue we schawid,</L>
<L>Oure dedis &amp; of oure disciplyne &middot; a dele of &thorn;aim aythir;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i lare a litill-quat &middot; likis me to write,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lere write; <I>with</I> lere <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e sothe of oure solitude &middot; will serue &thorn;e stille aftir.</L>
<L N="4394">Sire, &yogh;e haue la&yogh;t now on late &middot; within a lite &yogh;eres</L>
<L>All Europ &amp; Asie &middot; &amp; Auffrik &thorn;e mare;</L>
<L>&THORN;at seising burde sufficiant &middot; &thorn;ofe so&yogh;t &yogh;e na ferre.</L>
<L>Bot ay mekill wald haue mare &middot; as many man spellis;</L>
<L N="4398">&THORN;e son, for sake of &yogh;our syn &middot; sesys his li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Be-cause of &yogh;oure couatise &middot; to clym to his bounds.
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e with wodnes of weris &middot; all &thorn;e werde fretis,</L>
<L N="4401">And &yogh;it for-fe&yogh;tils &yogh;oure face &middot; all fasting it semes.</L>
<L>A-nothire la&yogh;e is in &yogh;oure lande &middot; at oure lord hatis,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="21"></L>
<L>As, slaa &yogh;oure sonnes in sacrifice &middot; &amp; othire synnys many,</L>
<L N="4404">To sawe emang &thorn;ir simpill men &middot; sedis of debate,</L>
<L>And make a terant of a tulke &middot; &thorn;at neuire tene tho&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soile ne &thorn;e foure sees &middot; suffice &yogh;owe nouthire,</L>
<L N="4407">Bot if &yogh;e mi&yogh;t ken &thorn;e costis &middot; of &thorn;e clere heuen.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure giltis growis of &yogh;our gods &middot; or god geue &thorn;am sorowe,</L>
<L>For many modirson &thorn;ai marre &middot; mi&yogh;t ellis haue bene safe.</L>
<L>A-vise &yogh;ow now be Venus &middot; quat vertous him folo&yogh;es,</L>
<L N="4411">&THORN;e Iusule of Iupitir &middot; &amp; of his Iapis als,</L>
<L>Dame Proserpyne, a prophetese &middot; of &yogh;oure praysid la&yogh;es;<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Latis &thorn;is be witnes of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> my wordis &middot; &amp; waitis now &thorn;ar tetchis.</L>
<L>Venus was a-vowtrere &middot; &amp; many vice hauntid,</L>
<L N="4415">And Iupitir a Iettoure &middot; &thorn;at Iapid many ladis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dadis ladis; <I>with</I> dadis <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Dame proserpine in preue place &middot; playd as hire likid.</L>
<L>Loo, sary sottis, slike a sowme &middot; of synnars &yogh;e lufe!<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="22"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e lett men of &thorn;ar libertes &middot; at &thorn;am oure lord grauntid,</L>
<L>Thryngis &thorn;am in-to thraldom &middot; &amp; of thaire &thorn;ede spoiles.</L>
<L N="4420">Vn-iust is &yogh;our Iugementis &middot; so is &yogh;oure Iugis all;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dedis of &yogh;our domesmen &middot; &yogh;e for dere halde.</L>
<L>Is &thorn;are na renke in &yogh;oure rewme &middot; &thorn;at othire rewill kepis,</L>
<L>Bot "&thorn;us me &thorn;inke" &amp; "so me &thorn;inke" &middot; &amp; threpis it is lawe!</L>
<L N="4424">&THORN;us fra &thorn;e rote of ri&yogh;twisnes &middot; rauyst ere &yogh;e clene,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e way of wickidnes &middot; be warla&yogh;es gidid.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e hald na wee of &thorn;e werd &middot; of witt worthe a myte,</L>
<L>Bot he can practise &amp; paynt &middot; &amp; polisch his wordis.</L>
<L>For all &yogh;oure wisdom, I-wis &middot; is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> wroken to &yogh;our tongis,</L>
<L N="4429">And all &thorn;e sauour of &yogh;oure sauls &middot; is sattild in &yogh;our mouthis.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure grete garisons of gold &middot; vngastly &yogh;e spende
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>In bigging of burgis &middot; &amp; bilding of toures;</L>
<L>And quen &yogh;e sitt in &yogh;oure sale &middot; with syris &amp; dukis,</L>
<L>&THORN;an haue &yogh;ee seggis &yogh;ow to serue &middot; sowmes enogh.</L>
<L N="4434">&THORN;an as a Mare at a moghe &middot; &yogh;oure mawis &yogh;e fill,</L>
<L>With bakin mete &amp; with briddis &middot; bolnes &yogh;oure paunches,</L>
<L>Stuffis so &yogh;our stomake &middot; with stullis &amp; of wynes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnethis haldis, be &yogh;e hoo &middot; &thorn;e hide of &yogh;ow hale!</L>
<L>Quat dewis &yogh;ow &thorn;an &thorn;ire diatis &middot; &amp; all &thorn;is dere fode,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sowping in vnseson &middot; &yogh;oure surfete of drinkis,</L>
<L N="4440">Bot settis &yogh;ow in-to sekenes &middot; of sere-lepy kyndis,<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And gers &yogh;ow die or &yogh;oure day &middot; many dre&yogh;e wyntir?</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;e couett &amp; craue &middot; castels &amp; rewmes,</L>
<L>And thristis eftir all thingis &middot; at in &yogh;oure tho&yogh;t rynnes,</L>
<L N="4444">Iaspre, Iuwels, &amp; gemmes &middot; &amp; Iettand perle:</L>
<L>And all sall leue &yogh;ow at &thorn;e laste &middot; &amp; in-to laire worth!</L>
<L>And maydese &yogh;it, for all your molle &middot; &thorn;at modire ws<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> &yogh;ow.</NOTE> cried,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fourmed &thorn;e flode &amp; &thorn;e flynt &middot; &amp; &thorn;e faire lyndis.</L>
<L>And, as I brefe it in &thorn;is bull &middot; &thorn;e bragmeyns takens</L>
<L>Surmontis all &yogh;our sapientis &middot; &amp; oure assemy thewis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. twethewis, <I>alt. to</I> thewis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4450">And o&thorn;ir werkis of wast &middot; is wro&yogh;t in &yogh;oure landis,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="23"></L>
<L>As, graffis garnyscht of gold &middot; &amp; gilten tombis,</L>
<L>Thurghis to thrawyn in &middot; quen &yogh;e &thorn;raa worthe,</L>
<L>Sum of siluir, sum of sipirs &middot; sum of sere gemmes.</L>
<L>&THORN;us make &yogh;e vessels in vayne &middot; to &yogh;oure foule corses,</L>
<L>To crom in &yogh;oure cariouns &middot; &thorn;at kind &yogh;ow defendis,</L>
<L N="4456">&THORN;at ilk slymand slugh &middot; quen &yogh;e ere slide hyne,</L>
<L>And will no&yogh;t suffire &thorn;e erth &middot; to haue at him fallis.</L>
<L>For iolite of Iupitir &middot; &yogh;e ioyen vp templis,</L>
<L>With Imagis of &yogh;oure ydolatry &middot; all within payntid;</L>
<L N="4460">Symolacris vp sett &middot; of Seropis &amp; othir,</L>
<L>And slees in-to &thorn;e sacrifis &middot; many sere bestis.</L>
<L>Quen &yogh;e haue tildid vp-on [top] &middot; &yogh;our trouthles gods,</L>
<L>Sum of gold, sum of glas &middot; sum of gray marbill,</L>
<L N="4464">Sum of latoun &amp; of lede &middot; &amp; sum of li&yogh;t siluir,</L>
<L>And sum ere tiffid all of tree &middot; &amp; sum of tyn pured,
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>&THORN;an fall &yogh;e flatt on &thorn;e fold &middot; with fees &thorn;aim adoures,</L>
<L>Bath Amon &amp; Appolyne &middot; &amp; asskis at &thorn;am welthys;</L>
<L N="4468">Of any gud at &yogh;e geet &middot; a gift ye &thorn;am offirre,</L>
<L>A quantite of all-quat &middot; of quike &amp; of ellis;<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;e latt as &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t all leth &middot; at ony lede wald,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai may send &yogh;ow bot vnsele &middot; &amp; no&yogh;t o&thorn;ir godis.</L>
<L N="4472">&THORN;us &yogh;e comende &thorn;aim on knees &middot; as cocards suld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nouthire si&yogh;t has ne saule &middot; bot of segge werke;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue na sauour, I suppose &middot; how &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of heuen</L>
<L N="4475">He has na hert vs to here &middot; ne no hathill ellis</L>
<L>For calues ne for kidis blode &middot; ne for na crispe wethris,</L>
<L>Bot an[1]y for oure orisons &middot; &amp; for na no&thorn;ire giftis.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="24"></L>
<L>God se&yogh;is oure sa&yogh;es for his son &middot; at in him-selfe duellis;</L>
<L N="4479">For sekire god is &thorn;e son &middot; &thorn;at all oure sede loues.</L>
<L>And sothly, by &thorn;e same son &middot; we ere him all like,</L>
<L>And all he sustayned of &thorn;at son &middot; &thorn;at any saule wildis.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i vnhappy we &yogh;ow hald &middot; &thorn;at in &yogh;oure hertis leues</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure kind with slike a conquirour &middot; to comen or to euen.</L>
<L N="4484">And othire harlotry &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> to hald, <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> hant &middot; &thorn;at heris &thorn;e goste,</L>
<L>Of fornicacion &amp; filth &middot; &amp; many foule synnes,</L>
<L>Maumentry, &amp; manslatir &middot; mosardry &amp; pride,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dose &yogh;ow dompe to &thorn;e devill &middot; quen he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> &yogh;e.</NOTE> ere dede hethen.</L>
<L N="4488">And we<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;e, <I>but underlined, and corrected to</I> we <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e contrari clene &middot; kepis all oure lyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may bowe to &thorn;at blis &middot; &thorn;at neuir sall haue ende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e gronde &yogh;ow no&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> no&yogh;t; <I>but the second</I> no&yogh;t <I>is underlined</I>.</NOTE> on<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ai (?)</NOTE> a god &middot; &thorn;at all of glett fourmed,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="25"></L>
<L>&THORN;at note newid all of no&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;at neuire sall haue ende,</L>
<L>Bot o&thorn;ire many do &yogh;e menske &middot; ere him na<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. no, <I>alt. to</I> na.</NOTE> mare sibbe</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e flesch of &thorn;e fysch<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fesch, <I>alt. to</I> fysch.</NOTE> &middot; to &thorn;e faire me[m]bree.</L>
<L>Ilk lede &thorn;at li&yogh;t is of &yogh;our lede &middot; &yogh;e call &thorn;e litill werde,</L>
<L>And gesse wele as many gods &middot; as growis in him membris;</L>
<L>Ilk a parcele of his person a-proprid &middot; is a-pert dri&yogh;tin,</L>
<L>And euire-ilk lym, it awne lust eftir &middot; as him list craues!
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>For marcure was mansla&yogh;t &middot; a mammlere of wordis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e graith him to be gouenoure &middot; &amp; god of &thorn;e tonge.</L>
<L>And Arcules has aythire arme &middot; in his awen warde,<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e xij wondirfull werkis &middot; he wro&yogh;t with his handis.</L>
<L N="4502">Mars for his maisterris &middot; &amp; for his many weris,</L>
<L>Him brefe &yogh;e for his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;our his; <I>with</I> &yogh;our <I>marked for erasure</I>.</NOTE> baratris &middot; &thorn;e breste to defend.</L>
<L>Dame Iuno was a iettir &middot; &amp; ioyned full of iree,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i scho hedis to &thorn;e hert &middot; &amp; has it to &yogh;eme.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="26"></L>
<L N="4506">Bary<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> Bacy, <I>i. e.</I> Bacchus; <I>see</I> l. 4525.</NOTE> he was brayne-wode &middot; for bebbing of wynes,</L>
<L>For&thorn;i [&thorn;e] swire &amp; &thorn;e swalow &middot; &thorn;at swiere he kepis.</L>
<L>Cupido has &thorn;e custodi &middot; &amp; cure of &thorn;e mawe,</L>
<L>For he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> was couatus &amp; cursid &middot; vnclene of him-selfe.</L>
<L N="4510">Serenon is sustenour &middot; &amp; sire of &thorn;e wambe,</L>
<L>For hem was quartirs of qwete &middot; vmqwile out of nombre.</L>
<L>Dame venus &thorn;e a-v[er]ous<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a vious.</NOTE> &middot; for vices opon ni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Is possessour &amp; principale &middot; of all &thorn;e preue menbris.</L>
<L N="4514">&THORN;us ilk cantell of &yogh;oure cors &middot; &yogh;e call &thorn;am dri&yogh;tins,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="27"></L>
<L>Deu[i]dis it in-to duesses &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire deuels many.</L>
<L>Of ilk gobet of &thorn;at glett &middot; &yogh;e a god make,</L>
<L>And leues no&yogh;t as mekill as a lym &middot; &yogh;our liches on to stand.</L>
<L N="4518">&YOGH;e haue na hoping in &thorn;at hathill &middot; at on hi&yogh;e sittis,</L>
<L>How he &yogh;oure nase &amp; &yogh;oure nebb &middot; &amp; all of no&yogh;t cried,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;inkis on &thorn;ir othir thefis &middot; &amp; &thorn;am as thrall seruys,</L>
<L>And sacrifice to ilk a segge &middot; a sere-lepy gifte.</L>
<L N="4522">To Mars in his mynstir &middot; at maynteines &thorn;e weris,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bringe him a wild bare &middot; for his wale dedis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e carcas of a fatt kid &middot; &thorn;at carayne is worthe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bring &yogh;e to ser bacus &middot; to bere vp his drinke.</L>
<L N="4526">And Iupitir &thorn;at Ioglour &middot; sum Iape bos haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hs haue, <I>with</I> hs <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>A bullok or a fell bule &middot; is bro&yogh;t to his temple.</L>
<L>And Iuno &thorn;e Ientill &middot; for ioy of his pride,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e presand hire a pakoke &middot; with pennes of an Aungell.
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="240"></L>
<L N="4530">Minerua<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Minuera.</NOTE> was a maistres &middot; of many kingis werkis,</L>
<L>A ratland ni&yogh;t ravyn &middot; is him to rent &yogh;olden.</L>
<L>To Venus &thorn;e vowtriere &middot; may no&yogh;t ells a-vaile,<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot ilk moneth to mede &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> a.</NOTE> mi[l]ke-quite doufe.</L>
<L N="4534">Appollo with a quite swan &middot; is paid him to tende;</L>
<L>A manere of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> corne to mercure &middot; &thorn;at we &thorn;i muld call.</L>
<L>And Serenon is sone serued &thorn;at sees to &thorn;e paunche;</L>
<L>Haue he a boll full of bran &middot; bedis he na mare.</L>
<L>And Ercules as emperoure &middot; emyddis all he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. y he; <I>with</I> y <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> standis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. stondis, <I>alt. to</I> standis.</NOTE>;<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="28"></L>
<L>And for he preuyd ay &thorn;e prise &middot; in prowis of armes,</L>
<L N="4540">He has a hatt on his hede &middot; hi&yogh;tild o floures,</L>
<L>Of palme &amp; of peruyk &middot; &amp; othire proud blossoms.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kirke of cupido &middot; is clenly a-rayed,</L>
<L N="4543">&THORN;e stallis &amp; in all stedis &middot; strowid with Rose.</L>
<L>Lo, to so many mayned gods &middot; &yogh;our menbris &yogh;e dele,</L>
<L>And will no&yogh;t knaw &yogh;our creatour &middot; at &yogh;ow of clay fourmed.</L>
<L>&THORN;ire deme &yogh;e for &yogh;our dri&yogh;tins &middot; &thorn;at drepis &thorn;e saule;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai may sende &yogh;ow na sele &middot; bot sla &yogh;ow within.</L>
<L N="4548">As many of &thorn;at feleschip &middot; as &yogh;e trow &amp; adoures,</L>
<L>As many turmentis &amp; tene &middot; &yogh;ow tidis in hell.</L>
<L>A-vise &yogh;ow now quat velany &middot; &amp; vices &thorn;ai &yogh;ow teche:</L>
<L>Ane leris &yogh;ow to be licherus &middot; &amp; leris &yogh;ow to syn;</L>
<L N="4552">Ane, to be grindand gluttis &middot; &amp; glorand dronkin;</L>
<L>And ane, to bragg &amp; to bost &middot; &amp; bate with &thorn;e pepill.</L>
<L>If &yogh;e be herd of &yogh;our happ<NOTE PLACE="foot">happ <I>marked for erasure</I>.</NOTE> &middot; vn-happe &thorn;ai &yogh;ow ken;</L>
<L>For&thorn;i bot harlotry or harme &middot; is at &yogh;e here craue;</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e hede to &yogh;our hestis &middot; &yogh;our hert is a-meued,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="29"></L>
<L>So que&thorn;ir &thorn;ai here or els-quat &middot; it hurtis ay &thorn;e saule.</L>
<L>&YOGH;our doctours ere &yogh;oure duesses &middot; &thorn;aire ditis alegis,</L>
<L N="4559">How &thorn;at &thorn;ai hampire in &yogh;our here &middot; with many hard payn.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cause all vnkindnes &middot; &amp; corperall lustis,
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>As surquitry &amp; sacrilag &middot; &amp; othire sere tecches;</L>
<L>Constrene &yogh;ow in-to cauatise &middot; to clame all &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L N="4563">To rayme &amp; to robry &middot; to rayme men &thorn;aire godis,</L>
<L>Wailaway to wriches &middot; &amp; wa is &yogh;ow in erthe;<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Herefore &yogh;e hinge mon in hell &middot; quen &yogh;e ere hethen passed!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e kyng of his carpe &middot; crabbid vnfaire,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="30"></L>
<L>For he was spetous of speche &middot; &amp; spised his dri&yogh;tins;</L>
<L>Quen he had lokid on &thorn;e lyne &middot; he lappid it to-gedire,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to godire.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="31"></L>
<L>And notid to him a-nothire new &middot; &thorn;at now next fologhes.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="21" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>Vicesimus primus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;e kynge crouned of kyngis &middot; o lordis all othire,</L>
<L>Ser Alexander &thorn;e athelest &middot; of Amons childire,</L>
<L N="4572">And of &thorn;e quene Olimpades &middot; &thorn;at I was of geten,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e best of bragmeyns &middot; blissing &amp; hele<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. helee.</NOTE>!</L>
<L>Sire, be &thorn;is sothe at &yogh;e say &middot; of all seggis oute</L>
<L>&YOGH;e may be sett be &yogh;ow-selfe &middot; for syn doo &yogh;e neuire!</L>
<L>Bot sothely slike a simpilnes &middot; as me my saule demys,</L>
<L>It comes bot of acustoumes &middot; &amp; of na clene thewes.</L>
<L>And ow&thorn;ir &yogh;e gesse at &yogh;e be gods &middot; for &yogh;oure gud werkis,</L>
<L>Or deynes with oure dri&yogh;tins &middot; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> we, <I>underlined</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at we &thorn;am dere hald.</L>
<L N="4580">&YOGH;e say &yogh;e sawe neuire soile &middot; ne na citis biggis;<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="32"></L>
<L>How suld &yogh;e telle withouten toles &middot; or any tild rere?</L>
<L>Is &thorn;er non Instrumentis of Iren &middot; in all &thorn;at Ile founden,</L>
<L>Ne nakin metall of to make &middot; messelyne ne othire.</L>
<L>For-quy as bestis on &thorn;e bent &middot; &yogh;e growe on &thorn;e greuys,</L>
<L N="4585">Refete &yogh;ow with refuse &middot; of rotis &amp; of herbys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e same wyse dose a wolfe &middot; &thorn;at wantis of his pray;</L>
<L>Quen he has faute of his flesch &middot; he fallis to &thorn;e soile!</L>
<L>Lo, if me list in-to &yogh;oure land &middot; with all my ledis entre,</L>
<L>Quat wisdom at &yogh;our wricchidnes &middot; or witt mi&yogh;t I lere?</L>
<L N="4590">&THORN;e lede is litill to loue &middot; &thorn;at leuys ay in sorowe,</L>
<L>Bot mekill mare he is menskid &middot; &thorn;at in a mene duellis.
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="242"></L>
<L>Ware &thorn;ai so wyse &thorn;at has waes &middot; qua ware so<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> wyse h, <I>underlined</I>.</NOTE> wide praysed<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &thorn;a &thorn;at lepros ere &amp; lame &middot; &thorn;at neuire of leth knewe?</L>
<L N="4594">If I &yogh;oure parties aproche &middot; &amp; pi&yogh;t vp my tentis,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="33"></L>
<L>If I it mi&yogh;t, as I ne may &middot; for missyng of schipis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are suld my folk for defaute &middot; be famyscht for euire,</L>
<L>And worthe in a wale quile &middot; to wricchis as &yogh;our-selfe!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e say &yogh;our women has na wedis &middot; &thorn;e werd with to plese,</L>
<L N="4599">Garlands ne no gay gere &middot; to glyffe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A curl over the</I> g.</NOTE> in &yogh;our e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Silke of Sipris, ne say &middot; ne saffrond kellis;</L>
<L>For-quy &thorn;are is nane to gete &middot; now neuyn I &thorn;e cause!</L>
<L>Adultery on all wise als &yogh;e deuoyde,</L>
<L N="4603">Echchewis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Ethchewis.</NOTE> ay &thorn;at caffare &middot; as castite wald;</L>
<L>If &yogh;e na will haue to &thorn;at werk &middot; it wondres me littill;</L>
<L>How suld &yogh;e nayte euir &thorn;at note &middot; &thorn;at ne&yogh;es neuir &thorn;e fode?</L>
<L>Slik lust is lang on &thorn;e leuir &middot; &amp; likand spices</L>
<L N="4607">Mast cherischid &amp; encheson &middot; of chasteand metis;</L>
<L>And &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> bot fede &yogh;ow with frute &middot; at flays no&yogh;t &yogh;oure hongir,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i neuire ailes &yogh;ow &thorn;at apetite &middot; &thorn;ir artis with to dele.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="34"></L>
<L>Is &thorn;ar na lare in &yogh;oure land &middot; labour of scolis,</L>
<L N="4611">Fesike, ne no philosofy &middot; ne no fourme ellis,</L>
<L>Piromancie, ne poisei &middot; ne practyse of lawe,</L>
<L>Ne neuire na mercy &yogh;ow emell &middot; as mynes me &yogh;our pistill;</L>
<L>All &thorn;is condicions I call &middot; bot comon of bestis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has no sent in &thorn;aire saule &middot; ne sauour in na gude.</L>
<L N="4616">Bot we &thorn;at fourmed is &amp; fast &middot; &amp; has a fre will</L>
<L>Differris as in oure fraunches &middot; fere fra &yogh;oure kynde.</L>
<L>It ware no possible poynt &middot; to paise in my witt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at all mi&yogh;t ay be eftir ane &middot; with-outen any chaunge.</L>
<L N="4620">For eftir baret or bale &middot; blis vs aperis,</L>
<L>And eftir wele comys wa &middot; for so &thorn;e werd askis.
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="243"></L>
<L>Ouir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> On.</NOTE> wild is many ways wraiste &middot; as &thorn;e wedire skiftis;<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="35"></L>
<L>For a clere cloudles day &middot; mas a clene mynde;<MILESTONE N="80a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4624">Quen it is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> bri&yogh;t all a-bowte &middot; it blithis oure hertis.</L>
<L>And be &thorn;ar gold in oure gate &middot; or any gud stanes,</L>
<L>We do bot foules it with oure fete &middot; vs fayns it na more,</L>
<L>And quen it walows &middot; &amp; wannes all oure thestres,</L>
<L N="4628">&YOGH;et ere we toghid to &amp; fra &middot; be turnyng of eldris.</L>
<L>For quilk a frek is bot a fant &middot; &thorn;an is he first simple,</L>
<L>And quen he preues fra &thorn;at prike &middot; &thorn;an is he proud-lokid,</L>
<L>Metis on &thorn;e medill merke &middot; &amp; &thorn;are his mynd stablis.</L>
<L N="4632">Mekill variaunce of vertus &middot; enveronis oure saules,</L>
<L>For we ere fetid full faire &middot; &amp; has oure fyue wittis.</L>
<L>Ane, oure si&yogh;t with to see &middot; &amp; sauour at &thorn;e nasee,</L>
<L>And ane to tast &amp; to touche &middot; &amp; &thorn;en oure twa eris.</L>
<L N="4636">Of all &thorn;e frutis on &thorn;e fold &middot; we fange at oure will,</L>
<L>Bath venyson &amp; volatile &middot; &amp; variand fisches.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="36"></L>
<L>If &yogh;e refreyne &yogh;ow &thorn;ar-fra &middot; it falis bot of pride</L>
<L N="4639">Or ellis &yogh;ow writhis with &yogh;our wele &middot; for &yogh;e na welth haue!</L>
<L>Be many opynion I prefe &middot; &thorn;at pure is &yogh;oure tecches</L>
<L>Mare fonden opon foly &middot; &thorn;an ficchid on reson."</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;e kith &middot; &thorn;e clause had devysid,</L>
<L>He settis him doun full sobirly &middot; &amp; sendis him anothire.</L>
<L>&para; "I, sir Dyndyn &thorn;e derrest &middot; at duells in &thorn;is Ile,</L>
<L N="4645">&THORN;e best of &thorn;e bragmeyns &middot; of bounte &amp; of thewis,</L>
<L>To Alexander, &thorn;at aire &middot; &thorn;at erles all &thorn;e werd,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="37"></L>
<L>&THORN;e souerayne sire of all &thorn;e soile &middot; salus &amp; ioye.</L>
<L>Sire, we erd no&yogh;t in elementis &middot; as euirmare to duell,</L>
<L>Bot as qua pas a pilgrymage &middot; fra Parysch to rome;</L>
<L>To othire hames vs hi&yogh;e &middot; quen we ere hethen voided,</L>
<L N="4651">And in &thorn;e cites of syn &middot; &thorn;an sitt we na langire.</L>
<L>Vse we nane Epocrise &middot; ne ire, ne no theftis,</L>
<L>Ne nothire gesse we vs gods &middot; ne grym at oure dri&yogh;tin.</L>
<L>For many seerties we seet &middot; &thorn;at sysed all &thorn;e werde,</L>
<L>And wro&yogh;t &thorn;e will of ilk we &middot; to wale as him likid.<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>And he &thorn;at wayues ay &thorn;e werst &middot; &amp; wirkis &thorn;e bettir,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="38"></L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ate, <I>with</I> e <I>expuncted</I>.</NOTE> gome is gods gud frend &middot; &amp; god neuire &thorn;e hildire.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is similitude &thorn;at oure sede &middot; &thorn;ou settis [in] my pistill,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same ensampill, as me semes &middot; in-to &yogh;oure-self touches,</L>
<L>For so &thorn;e qwele of qwistounes &middot; &yogh;oure qualite encreses,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no&thorn;ir gesse &yogh;e gouernour &middot; no god bot &yogh;our-selfe!</L>
<L N="4662">&YOGH;e brixsill our<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&yogh;our, altered to our</I>.</NOTE> benignite &middot; oure bonerte repreues,</L>
<L>And beris a-pon vs blasfeme &middot; &thorn;at neuire bale tho&yogh;t.</L>
<L>All be we suggets in oure-selfe &middot; &amp; simpill oure latis,</L>
<L>Voide &amp; vacand of vices &middot; as virgyns it ware,</L>
<L N="4666">Neuir-&thorn;e-les of a la&yogh;e &middot; hald we vs dri&yogh;tins.</L>
<L>It is &yogh;oure-selfe &amp; no&yogh;t oure-self &middot; &thorn;at ai &thorn;e self hantis;</L>
<L>Aboundance of Auoure &middot; &yogh;ow all has englaymed,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e bot fage ay &thorn;e flesche &middot; &amp; felsen it wele.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bide no besynes of bedis &middot; bot to &thorn;e body clethe,</L>
<L>Els &yogh;e may cast &yogh;ow to be coynt &middot; &yogh;e count for na ferrir.</L>
<L N="4672">With soft serkis of silke &middot; &yogh;oure sidis vm-loke,</L>
<L>Doubeletis of damaske &middot; &amp; sum of dere tars,</L>
<L>With ilka fingire on &yogh;oure fist &middot; fillid full of ryngis,</L>
<L N="4675">Schard al of shire<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. schre, <I>altered to</I> schire.</NOTE> gold &middot; as it a schryne were.</L>
<L>Quat profetis &yogh;ow &thorn;is paraile &middot; &amp; all &thorn;is proud iettis?</L>
<L>For nouthire saues it &thorn;e saule &middot; ne &yogh;our-selfe fedis.</L>
<L>Bot we, &thorn;at knawis wele &amp; ken &middot; &thorn;e kynd of &thorn;e noble,</L>
<L>Quen we ere drinkeles &amp; dry &middot; we draw to &thorn;e bourne;</L>
<L N="4680">And be &thorn;ar gold in oure gate &middot; or any gud stanes,</L>
<L>We do bot foulis it with oure fete &middot; vs faynes it na more.</L>
<L>For nouthire purgis it oure pli&yogh;t &middot; ne priues it oure hungir,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="39"></L>
<L>Ne nou&thorn;ir salues it oure sares &middot; ne sesis it oure thrist.</L>
<L>For folowid it slike a fraunchis &middot; at it<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> vs fede wald,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cursed laike o couatis &middot; ware clene<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. chene.</NOTE> with it drenchid.</L>
<L N="4686">&YOGH;e vise &yogh;ow &thorn;ar-of vessell &middot; for vanyte &amp; pride;<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As gud ware crestyns of clathe &middot; &thorn;e caryon to serue.
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>I se na godlaik in gold &middot; bot grefe to &thorn;e saule,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fastir it fallis on a freke &middot; &thorn;e fastir he couettis."</L>
<L N="4690">Sire Alexander all at ese &middot; avisis him on &thorn;is pistill,</L>
<L>And wayues<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> waynes.</NOTE> to him a-no&thorn;ire writt &middot; at on &thorn;is wyse spellis.<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="40"></L>
<L>&para; "Hi&yogh;e kyng with-out comparison &middot; of kyngis all o&thorn;ire,</L>
<L>Of all lordis &thorn;e lord &middot; &thorn;at leues vndire heuen,</L>
<L N="4694">Sire Alexander, &thorn;e aire &middot; of Amon oure dri&yogh;tin,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e, ser Dyndyn on &thorn;i dese &middot; &thorn;is dities I write.</L>
<L>In slike a side of &thorn;e soile &middot; &yogh;our-selfe is in-closid,<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="41"></L>
<L>May wele na wee, if he wald &middot; wyn to &yogh;our kithis.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i enhabete &yogh;e in angwysch &middot; at &yogh;oure vnthankis;</L>
<L>And all &yogh;oure lefing &amp; &yogh;oure lare<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> &middot; at &yogh;e so loude prayse,</L>
<L N="4700">It comis bot of a kyndnes &middot; &amp; of na clene thewys.</L>
<L>And als &yogh;e fonde may na for&thorn;ire &middot; to hi&yogh;en &yogh;oure name,</L>
<L>Bot pyned &thorn;ar in a parroke &middot; inparkid as bestis,</L>
<L>&thorn;us pere to &thorn;ir presons &middot; &thorn;at ay in payn lengis,</L>
<L N="4704">And he &thorn;at se&yogh;is to vs sage &middot; &yogh;e bot a sott call.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Be &thorn;e be &thorn;e; with Be <I>altered to</I> Bet, <I>and the second</I> be &thorn;e <I>underlined;</I> Bot be &thorn;e <I>is probably intended</I>.</NOTE> grace of my god<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> &middot; mi&yogh;t I &yogh;our grond entre,</L>
<L>I suld &yogh;ow ken to be kni&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; clethe &yogh;ow with armes."<MILESTONE UNIT="AlexDind page" N="42"></L>
<L>&THORN;an pi&yogh;t oure prince in &thorn;at place &middot; a pelare<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A curl over the</I> e.</NOTE> of marble,</L>
<L>Quare-on a tulke with a toile &middot; &thorn;is titill vp he wrate,</L>
<L N="4709">Sum langage on latine &middot; &amp; lettres of ynde,</L>
<L>Sum was graithid o grew &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;us to-gedire spekis:</L>
<L>"I, Philip son &thorn;e fell kyng &middot; &thorn;e fondere of grece,</L>
<L>Sire Alexander &thorn;e athill &middot; &thorn;[a]t a&yogh;e all &thorn;e barbres</L>
<L N="4713">Eftir &thorn;e day &amp; &thorn;e dethe &middot; of Dary &amp; of Porrus,</L>
<L>&THORN;us fere I folo&yogh;ed haue my faes;" &middot; &amp; here a fitt end.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>End of</I> Alexander and Dindimus.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="22" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Vicesimus secundus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now gase he fra gangan &middot; and all his ging eftir,<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fondis forth with his folke &middot; &amp; a fild entris,
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="246"></L>
<L N="4717">Vmfaldin with a faire wod &middot; florischt<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. florischst.</NOTE> out ouire</L>
<L>Of Appils &amp; almands &middot; &amp; all manere of frutis.</L>
<L>All &thorn;e chiere of &thorn;e champe &middot; was chargid with floures,</L>
<L>Acrea, sais oure autour &middot; &thorn;at angill is hatten.</L>
<L N="4721">&YOGH;it wont men in &thorn;a woddis &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L>Of Ioynttours as Ieants &middot; in Iopons of hidis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware fedd all of frute &middot; &amp; of na fode ellis,</L>
<L>Of grapis &amp; of gernets &middot; &amp; othire gude spices,</L>
<L N="4725">Of sike as growis in &thorn;e grewis &middot; I tald of before.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware as rughe as a resche &middot; &thorn;e bake &amp; &thorn;e sidis;</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;ai persayued of oure prince &middot; &amp; slik a pake Armed,</L>
<L>&THORN;an stode &thorn;ai glorand on his gome &middot; with grisely mawis.</L>
<L>And he mas heraud &amp; heres &middot; to hant for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L>And sett vp a scharp schoute &middot; at all &thorn;e schaw ryngis.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai for skere of &thorn;e skrike &middot; in-to &thorn;e schaw fledd,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai hadd herd neuire of how &middot; ne of mans noyse;</L>
<L>And sex hundreth was slane &middot; &amp; sesid with oure kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>And foure and threti, as I flode<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. flode, <I>in the margin, substituted for</I> fynd.</NOTE> &middot; was in &thorn;e fild drepid,</L>
<L N="4735">And iiij<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> score on &thorn;is side &middot; &amp; seuen at was armed</L>
<L>Was with &thorn;e churles in &thorn;e chace &middot; choppid to deth.</L>
<L>&thorn;us thre daies in &thorn;at thede &middot; thurgh-out &thorn;ai lengid,</L>
<L>And dietis &thorn;am with damysens &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ir dere frute.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ferd he furth to a flumme &middot; &amp; sett &thorn;are his tentis,</L>
<L N="4740">And newly eftir &thorn;e none &middot; or nere &thorn;are-aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;are coms a bonde of a brenke &middot; &amp; breed &thorn;aim vnfaire;</L>
<L>A burly best &amp; a bigg &middot; was as<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> a man shapen,</L>
<L>Vmquile he groned as a galt &middot; with grysely latis,</L>
<L>Vmquile he noys as a nowte &middot; as a nox quen he lawes,<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4745">&YOGH;armand &amp; &yogh;erand &middot; a &yogh;oten him semed;</L>
<L>And was as bristils as a bare &middot; all &thorn;e body ouire;</L>
<L>Dom as a dore-nayle &middot; &amp; defe was he bathe,</L>
<L>With laith leggis &amp; lange &middot; &amp; twa laue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> lane.</NOTE> eres;</L>
<L N="4749">A heuy hede &amp; a hoge &middot; as it a hors ware,
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>And large was his odd lome &middot; &thorn;e lenthe of a &yogh;erde.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at comands oure kyng &middot; his kni&yogh;tis him to <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> take,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai a-saillid him sone &middot; bot he na segge dredis,</L>
<L N="4753">For nouthire fondis he to flee &middot; ne na fens made,</L>
<L>Bot stude &amp; stared as a stott &middot; &amp; stirred he na forthire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an callis to him &thorn;e conquirour &middot; a comly mayden,</L>
<L>Bad hire be bro&yogh;t be-fore &thorn;e best &middot; &amp; bare to be nakid.</L>
<L>And he be-held on &thorn;at hend &middot; &amp; hissis as a neddire,</L>
<L N="4758">He wald haue strangild hire stre&yogh;t &middot; ne had stiffe men bene;</L>
<L>He wald haue schowid on &thorn;at schene &middot; had no&yogh;t men halden,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e prince pauelion &middot; prestly him lede.</L>
<L>Quen he had ferlied his fill &middot; on his foule schapp,</L>
<L N="4762">He gers &thorn;aim bynde him at a braid &middot; &amp; brent him to poudire.</L>
<L>&THORN;en rade he fra &thorn;at reuir &middot; &amp; remowid his ost</L>
<L>In-till a brade bent fild &middot; &amp; bildid vp his tentis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are fande he lindis on &thorn;at lande &middot; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. a &thorn;e, <I>but corrected.</I></NOTE> lenthe of a spere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware frett full of frute &middot; &thorn;e fairest of &thorn;e werde.</L>
<L N="4767">It ware to tere any tong to tell &middot; of &thorn;a trees kinde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai wald sett with &thorn;e son &middot; &amp; with &thorn;e son rise.</L>
<L>Fra morewane to &thorn;e mydday &middot; merely &thorn;ai spring,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an discende &thorn;ai doun &middot; as &thorn;e day passis.</L>
<L>Lo, &thorn;is was a wondirfull werk &middot; bot gods awen will,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld wax soo &amp; wane &middot; within a wale time.</L>
<L>For, fra it dro&yogh;e to &thorn;e derke &middot; ay till it dawid eftir,</L>
<L N="4774">It was bot vacant &amp; voide &middot; as vanite it were.<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng in his caban &middot; with his kni&yogh;tis he ligis,</L>
<L>Tutand out of his tents &middot; &amp; &thorn;e trees waitis.</L>
<L>A bad a berne of a bobb &middot; bring him a nappill;</L>
<L N="4778">&THORN;an bowis furth a bachelere &middot; his bedinge to fill;</L>
<L>And he was sodanly sesid &middot; &amp; slane with a sprete.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at enverrouns all &thorn;e vale &middot; a voice fra &thorn;e heuen,</L>
<L>Said, "qua so fangis o &thorn;is frute &middot; bees fey in a stounde!"
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it bred &thorn;ar briddis in &thorn;a braunches &middot; at blith was &amp; tame,</L>
<L>And if a man had &thorn;aim hent &middot; or with his hand touchid,</L>
<L>&THORN;an flo&yogh;e &thorn;ar flawmes out of fire &middot; before &amp; be-hind,</L>
<L>And quare it li&yogh;t on his like &middot; it lichid him for euire.</L>
<L>Now bowis furth &thorn;is baratour &middot; &amp; bidis na langire,</L>
<L>Vp at a ma&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written</I> ma&yogh;tene; <I>see</I> l. 4883.</NOTE> mountane &middot; he myns with his ost,</L>
<L N="4788">And viij daies be-dene &middot; &thorn;e dri&yogh;e was, &amp; mare,</L>
<L>Or he mi&yogh;t couire to &thorn;e copp &middot; fra &thorn;e caue vndire.</L>
<L>Quen he was comen to &thorn;e crest &middot; his kni&yogh;tis wald haue esid;</L>
<L>And namely a new note &middot; neghis on hand,</L>
<L>Of dragons &amp; of dromondaris &middot; &amp; of diuerse neddirs,</L>
<L N="4793">Of liones &amp; of leopards &middot; &amp; othire laith bestis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was hurling on hi&yogh;e &middot; as it in hell ware,</L>
<L>Quat of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ost.</NOTE> wrestling of wormes &middot; &amp; wonding of kni&yogh;tis.</L>
<L>As gotis out of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> guttars &middot; in golanand wedres,</L>
<L N="4797">So voidis doun &thorn;e vemon &middot; be vermyns schaftis.</L>
<L>At o&thorn;ir time of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of of.</NOTE> oure tulkis &middot; was tangid to dede,</L>
<L>And slayn with &thorn;a serpents &middot; a sowme out of noimbre.</L>
<L>So hard &thorn;ai hampird oure heere &middot; &amp; herid oure erles,</L>
<L>Vnneth it chansid &thorn;aim &thorn;e cheke &middot; &thorn;e cheffire to worthe.</L>
<L>Quen he sckonfet &amp; skerrid &middot; all &thorn;a skathill fendis,</L>
<L>&THORN;en metis he doun of &thorn;e mounte &middot; in-to a mirk vale,</L>
<L N="4804">A drere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. dre&yogh;e.</NOTE> dale &amp; a depe &middot; a dym &amp; a thestir.</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;[t] &thorn;are na saule vndire son &middot; see to a-nothire;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware vmbe-thonrid<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> vmbe-thourid.</NOTE> in &thorn;at thede &middot; with slike a thike cloude,<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t fele it with &thorn;aire fiste &middot; as flabband webbis;</L>
<L>With all &thorn;e bothom full of bournes &middot; bri&yogh;t as &thorn;e siluire,</L>
<L N="4809">And bery-bobis on &thorn;e braes &middot; brethand as mirre.</L>
<L>&thorn;us drafe &thorn;ai furth in derknes &middot; a ne&yogh;en daies euen,</L>
<L>So lang &thorn;aim lackis at &thorn;e last &middot; &thorn;e li&yogh;t of &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>&THORN;an come &thorn;ai blesnand till a barme &middot; of a brent lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lawe, <I>substituted for</I> schawe.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>Ne&yogh;e throtild with &thorn;e thik aire &middot; &amp; thrange in &thorn;are andes.</L>
<L N="4814">&THORN;ai labourde<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. babourde.</NOTE> vp a-gayn &thorn;e lift &middot; an elleuen dais,</L>
<L>&amp; quen &thorn;ai couert to &thorn;e crest &middot; &thorn;en clerid &thorn;e welkyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e schaftis of &thorn;e schire son &middot; schirkind &thorn;e cloudis,</L>
<L N="4817">And gods glorious gleme &middot; glent &thorn;am e-maunge.</L>
<L>&THORN;an past &thorn;ai doun fra &thorn;at pike &middot; in-to a playn launde,</L>
<L>Quare all &thorn;e gronde was of gols &middot; &amp; growen full of Impis,</L>
<L>A cubete lenth, sais &thorn;e clause &middot; cald was &thorn;e maste,</L>
<L>Quare-of &thorn;e feloure &amp; &thorn;e frute &middot; as fygis it sawourd.</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand &thorn;ai Revers,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Written in the margin, as a substitute for</I> &thorn;iuers.</NOTE> as I rede &middot; ricchest of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L N="4823">&THORN;of it ware Ioly Iurdan &middot; or Iacobs well;</L>
<L>Was neuir no mede ne no milke &middot; so mild vndire heuen,</L>
<L>Ne cliffe of cristall so clere &middot; at euire god fourmed.</L>
<L>A hundreth daies &amp; a halfe &middot; he held be &thorn;a playnes,</L>
<L>Till he was comen till a cliffe &middot; at to &thorn;e cloudis semed,</L>
<L N="4828">&THORN;at was so staire &amp; so stepe &middot; &thorn;e store me tellis,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;t &thorn;ar no wee bot with wyngis &middot; win to &thorn;e topp.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it fand he clouen &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e clynt &middot; twa crasid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. traside.</NOTE> gatis,</L>
<L>Ane to &thorn;e noke of &thorn;e north &middot; a-nothire to &thorn;e est.</L>
<L>Sire Alexander him a-vises &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> all him a-wondres,</L>
<L N="4833">And trowid it was wro&yogh;t &middot; of na lede werkis.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at stairis he forth &thorn;e stye &middot; &thorn;at stre&yogh;t to &thorn;e est,</L>
<L>And seuen dais with his men &middot; he so&yogh;t be &thorn;a costis.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e a&yogh;tent day &middot; eftire &thorn;e prime,</L>
<L N="4837">A Basilisk in a browe &middot; breis &thorn;aim vn-faire,</L>
<L>A stra&yogh;till &amp; a stithe worme &middot; stinkand of elde,<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And is so bittir &amp; so breme &middot; &amp; bicchid in him-selfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with &thorn;e stinke &amp; &thorn;e strenth &middot; he stroyes no&yogh;t allane,</L>
<L>Bot quat he settis on his si&yogh;t &middot; he slaes in a stonde.</L>
<L N="4842">He vemons in &thorn;e vaward &middot; valiant kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Maistirs out of Messedone &middot; of Mede &amp; of Persee;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai se&yogh;e doun sodanly &middot; slane of &thorn;aire blonkis,</L>
<L>To step &amp; to stand-dede &middot; &amp; in &thorn;e strete liggis.
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="250"></L>
<L N="4846">With &thorn;at areris all &thorn;e route &middot; &amp; radly &thorn;ai said,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e writh of &thorn;e wale god<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &middot; vs of &thorn;e wai lettis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng to knaw of &thorn;at case &middot; vp to &thorn;e cliffe wendis,</L>
<L>Sa&yogh;e quare &thorn;e same serpent &middot; slepit in a roke.</L>
<L>&THORN;an mas he bonds in a braide &middot; at sall na pepill pas,</L>
<L N="4851">In bole &amp; in balan &middot; buskes he his fetes,</L>
<L>A blason as a berne-dure &middot; &thorn;at all &thorn;e body schildis,</L>
<L>And fiches in a fyne glas &middot; on &thorn;e fere side.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sc[h]rewe in &thorn;e schewere &middot; his schadow be-haldis,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;e sla&yogh;tir of his si&yogh;t &middot; in-to him-selfe entris.</L>
<L N="4856">&THORN;an cals oure kyng him his kni&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; comandis him to bryn,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai as sone as &thorn;ai him sa&yogh;e &middot; him for his sle&yogh;t thankis.</L>
<L>Sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Cone.</NOTE> as &thorn;is balefull best &middot; was bro&yogh;t out o lyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ridis furth oure riche kyng &middot; &amp; remowis his ost.</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is way at he went &middot; sone worthis him a nende,</L>
<L N="4861">So at he flitt may na ferre &middot; ne his folke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fokke.</NOTE> nouthire.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was so hedous &amp; so hoge &middot; hillis &thorn;am beforn,</L>
<L>Clo&yogh;es at was cloude &middot; he clynterand torres,</L>
<L>Rochis &amp; rogh stanes &middot; rokkis vnfaire,</L>
<L N="4865">Scutis to &thorn;e scharpe schew &middot; sckerres a hundreth.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;aris he him &yogh;apely &middot; &amp; a-&yogh;ayne turnes,</L>
<L>And past in-to &thorn;e proud playn &middot; I proued to &yogh;ow first,<MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at all was brett-full of bowis &middot; &amp; blossoms so swete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bawme ne braunche o aloes &middot; bettir was neuire.</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;ens oure note<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows</I> o, <I>expuncted</I>.</NOTE> men be northe &middot; nymes &thorn;aim &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="4871">And &thorn;at &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Perhaps</I> &thorn;aim.</NOTE> fonde all &thorn;e flote &middot; fiftene dayis.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai croke ouire crosse &middot; to cache &thorn;aim anothire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at led &thorn;am to &thorn;e left hand &middot; &amp; &thorn;at a lange quile;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ai dryfe furth &thorn;e dri&yogh;t &middot; of daies foure score,</L>
<L N="4875">Till at &thorn;ai come till a cliffe &middot; as &thorn;e clause tellis,</L>
<L>Ane egge &thorn;at was all ouire &middot; of Adamand stanes,</L>
<L>With, hingand in &thorn;e rughe roches &middot; rede gold cheynes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;are graythed of degreces &middot; for gomes vp to wynde,
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="251"></L>
<L N="4879">Twa thousand be tale &middot; &amp; fyue trew hundrethe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware sett so in soute<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> sonte.</NOTE> &middot; of safers fyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e noblay to neuen &middot; it neyd any cristen.</L>
<L>&THORN;are logis &thorn;e leue kyng &middot; late on an euen,</L>
<L>Vndire &thorn;is ma&yogh;te mountayne &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e morne eftir,</L>
<L N="4884">&THORN;are setts he furth of sere gods &middot; a selle nounbre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he honours &amp; his ost &middot; &amp; offirs ilk ane.</L>
<L>Syne tas he with him titly &middot; his twelue tried prince[s],</L>
<L>Gas him vp be degreces &middot; to &thorn;e grete lawe,</L>
<L N="4888">Trenes to &thorn;e topward &middot; &thorn;at touched to &thorn;e cloudis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t lend &thorn;ar o-loft &middot; &amp; waite eftir wondirs.</L>
<L>Vp-on &thorn;e cop of &thorn;e cliffe &middot; a closure he fyndis,</L>
<L>A palais, anc of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e precioussest &middot; &amp; proudest in erth,</L>
<L N="4892">A bild, as &thorn;e buke sais &middot; with twa brade &yogh;atis,</L>
<L>And seuenty wyndows beside &middot; of serelepis werkes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;atis ware of &yogh;eten gold &middot; &yogh;arkid of platis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e windows on &thorn;e selfe wyse &middot; as &thorn;e writ schews<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Substituted for</I> schis.</NOTE>;<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware coruen full clene &middot; &amp; clustrid with gemmes,</L>
<L N="4897">Sti&yogh;t staffull of stanes &middot; stagis &amp; othire.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was a mynstir on &thorn;e mounte &middot; of metall as &thorn;e nobill,</L>
<L>Vmbe-gildid with a garden &middot; of golden vynes,</L>
<L>Was chatrid full of chefe frute &middot; of charbocle stanes,</L>
<L N="4901">With-outen mesure emaunge &middot; of margrite grete.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Substituted for</I> stanes; <I>see line above</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is hame at houes on &thorn;is hill &middot; was in &thorn;e hi&yogh;e est,</L>
<L>Forthi &yogh;it hedirto it hat &middot; &thorn;e hous of the son.</L>
<L>It was so precious a place &middot; &amp; proudly a-tired,</L>
<L N="4905">&THORN;are was na place it a pere &middot; bot paradyse selfe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="23" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Vicesimus tertius passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en aires furth ser Alexander &middot; in-to &thorn;is athill temple,</L>
<L>With Caulus &amp; with cleopas &middot; &amp; othire kidd princes,</L>
<L>And fand a berne in a bedd &middot; bawnand alane,</L>
<L>Ane of &thorn;e graciousest gomes &middot; &thorn;at euire god fourmed.</L>
<L N="4910">All lemed of his letere &middot; &thorn;e loge as of heuen,
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>For it was gayly begane &middot; with golden webbis.</L>
<L N="4912">A blewe bleaut o-bofe &middot; brad him al ouire,</L>
<L>Was browde all with brent gold &middot; full of bri&yogh;t aungels.</L>
<L>&THORN;e testre trased full of trones &middot; with trimballand wingis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e silloure full of Seraphens &middot; &amp; othire sere halows,</L>
<L>With curtyns all of clene silke &middot; &amp; coddis of &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>With cumly knottis &amp; with koyntis &middot; &amp; knopis of perle.</L>
<L N="4918">It ware to tere me to tell &middot; &thorn;e tirement to-gedire,</L>
<L>Or a nany<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic in</I> MS.</NOTE> clerke &middot; &thorn;e cost to de-vise;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ristis in &thorn;at rowme &middot; &thorn;e romance it tellis,<MILESTONE N="85a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Was ane of &thorn;e borliest bernes &middot; &thorn;at euire body hade,</L>
<L N="4922">With fell face as &thorn;e fire &middot; &amp; ferly faire schapen,</L>
<L>Balgh brade in &thorn;e brest &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e bely sklendire.</L>
<L>His cheuelere as chauele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> chaaele; <I>indistinct</I>.</NOTE> &middot; for changing of eld,</L>
<L N="4925">And as bla&yogh;t was his berd &middot; as any bri&yogh;t snaw.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Substituted for</I> swaw.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone as oure prince with his peris &middot; his person avyses,</L>
<L>He gesse him wele to be god &middot; &amp; of na gome kind.</L>
<L>He knelis doun with his kni&yogh;tis &middot; on &thorn;e cald erthe,</L>
<L>With haile him hailsis on he&yogh;e &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ir hend wordis.</L>
<L N="4930">&THORN;e renke within &thorn;e redell &middot; &thorn;an raxsils his armes,</L>
<L>Rymed him full renyschly &middot; &amp; rekind &thorn;ir wordis:</L>
<L>"Haile, Alexander!" quod &thorn;is athill &middot; "at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> all &thorn;e erth weldis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ert welcum, I-wis &middot; &amp; all &thorn;i wale princes.</L>
<L>Sire, &thorn;ou sall see with &thorn;i si&yogh;t &middot; slike signes, or &thorn;ou passe,</L>
<L N="4935">As neuire segge vndire son &middot; sa&yogh;e bot &thorn;ine ane.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou sall here apon happis &middot; or &thorn;ou hethen founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuire hathill vndire heuen &middot; herd bot &thorn;i-selfe."</L>
<L>"A! A! happy haly here man" &middot; quod &thorn;is hathill &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="4939">"How &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuynes my name &middot; &amp; &thorn;ou me neuire kend?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;is, sothly, ser," saied &thorn;e segge &middot; "&thorn;i-selfe &amp; &thorn;i werkis,</L>
<L>Or any drope of &thorn;i delume &middot; drechet had &thorn;e erd.</L>
<L>List &thorn;e no&yogh;t loke on &thorn;e lindis &middot; &thorn;at leuys euire mare,
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>&THORN;at has &thorn;e surname of &thorn;e son &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e mone alls;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to mene, bot of &thorn;e mone &middot; &amp; mi&yogh;t has to speke,</L>
<L>And tell &thorn;e trewly all &thorn;e text &middot; quat tide sall here-eftir?"</L>
<L N="4946">"&YOGH;is, by my croune," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; &amp; kyndly was ioyed,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is word I wald, be &yogh;our will &middot; no&yogh;t all &thorn;e werd leuir!"</L>
<L>"Ser, waite at &thorn;ou be wemles &middot; for woman touching,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &yogh;e leuely on &thorn;am loke &middot; &amp; lesten <I>&yogh;our</I> wirdis.<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For be &yogh;e pure of &thorn;at pli&yogh;t &middot; &yogh;e may &thorn;is place entre,</L>
<L N="4951">&THORN;at is &thorn;e sette of &thorn;at sire &middot; &thorn;at sett all &thorn;e werd."</L>
<L>"Ser, I am clene of &thorn;at craft &middot; I knaw wele my-selfe,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou oure gide to &thorn;e greuys &middot; apon gods name."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at bownes him &thorn;at berne &middot; &amp; fra his bed ryses,</L>
<L>Cled all in clene gold &middot; kirtill &amp; mantill,</L>
<L N="4956">A grym grisely gome &middot; with grete gray lokis;</L>
<L>Al glitered &thorn;e ground &middot; for glori of his wedis.</L>
<L>"Sirs, &yogh;e &thorn;at will has to wend &middot; <I>&yogh;our</I> wapens deuoidis,</L>
<L>Nymes of <I>&yogh;our</I> nethirgloue &middot; &amp; nakens &yogh;oure leggis,</L>
<L>Pesan, pancere, &amp; platis &middot; all to &yogh;oure preue clathis,</L>
<L N="4961">Iopon &amp; iesserand &middot; &amp; radly me folows!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng at his comaundment &middot; with his kni&yogh;tis him spoilis,</L>
<L>Puttis of to &thorn;e selfe serke &middot; senture &amp; othire,</L>
<L N="4964">Takis with him ser telomew &middot; an of his princes,</L>
<L>And Antiet, an athill duke &middot; &amp; eftir him wendis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ferd furth all in fere &middot; &thorn;ir foure all to-gedire;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lede at was &thorn;ar ladisman &middot; &thorn;e lord &amp; his kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L>Went &thorn;ur&yogh;e a wale wode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Here follows an</I> s <I>erased.</I></NOTE> &middot; was wondire of to tell,</L>
<L>As it ware hi&yogh;tild in &thorn;at hill &middot; with handis of aungels.</L>
<L>For &thorn;are ware tacchid vp trees &middot; &thorn;e triest of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>A hundreth fote to &thorn;e hede &middot; &thorn;e hi&yogh;t was &amp; mare,</L>
<L N="4972">Lyke oleues out of lebany &middot; &amp; lores so grene,</L>
<L>With sichomures<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sichourmes.</NOTE> &amp; sipresses &middot; &amp; sedrisse e-blande.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar trekild doun of &thorn;a &middot; teres of iemmes,</L>
<L N="4975">Boyland out of &thorn;e barke &middot; bawme &amp; mirre,
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>Of scence &amp; of othire salue &middot; as sechis out of wellis,<MILESTONE N="86a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at rase neuire of Aromitike &middot; sike rekils in erth.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai fande a ferly faire tre &middot; quare-on na frute groued,</L>
<L>Was void of all hire verdure &middot; &amp; vacant of leues,</L>
<L N="4980">A hundreth fote &amp; a halfe &middot; it had of le&yogh;t large,</L>
<L>With-outen bark ou&thorn;ir bast &middot; full of bare pirnes.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar bade a brid on a boghe &middot; a-bofe in &thorn;e topp,</L>
<L>Was of a port of a paa &middot; with sike a proude crest,</L>
<L>With bathe &thorn;e chekis &amp; &thorn;e chauyls &middot; as a chykin brid,</L>
<L>And all gilden<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wing lidin gilden; <I>with</I> wing lidin <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> was hire gorg &middot; with golden fethirs,</L>
<L>All hire hames be-hind &middot; was hewid as a purpure.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e body &amp; &thorn;e brest &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e bely vndire</L>
<L N="4988">Was finely florischt &amp; faire &middot; with frekild pennys,</L>
<L>Of gold graynes &amp; of goules &middot; full of gray mascles.</L>
<L>&THORN;an waitis on hire &thorn;e wale kyng &middot; &amp; wondire him thinke,</L>
<L>Was in &thorn;e figure of hire fourme &middot; no&yogh;t ferlid a littill.</L>
<L N="4992">"Quat loke &yogh;e?" quod &thorn;e ladisman &middot; "do lendis on<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> forthire,</L>
<L>&YOGH;one is a fereles foule &middot; a Fenix we calle."</L>
<L>&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;am.</NOTE> bowe &thorn;a forthe all ebland &middot; &amp; to &thorn;ire treis comes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e plants of &thorn;e proud son &middot; &amp; of &thorn;e pale mone.</L>
<L>"Behalds now," quod &thorn;is hare man &middot; "to &thorn;ir haly bowis,</L>
<L>And quat &thorn;ou will of &thorn;aim to wete &middot; wis in &thorn;i saghe.</L>
<L>Appose &thorn;aim all in preuate &middot; bot make na playn wordis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou may swythe haue a sware &middot; at swike sall &thorn;e neuire.</L>
<L N="5000">&THORN;an may &thorn;ou gesse in &thorn;i gast &middot; it is a gude sprete</L>
<L>&THORN;at sends &thorn;e sike asouerance<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. asouerante.</NOTE> &middot; &amp; sees to &thorn;i tho&yogh;tis."</L>
<L>&THORN;ire boles was, as &thorn;e boke sayes &middot; borly &amp; hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="5003">&THORN;e lind of &thorn;e li&yogh;t son &middot; louely clethid,</L>
<L>With feylour as of fine gold &middot; &thorn;at ferly faire lemes,<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ir loken ouire with leues &middot; as it ware li&yogh;t siluir.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Alexander at &thorn;is athill &middot; askis a demande,</L>
<L>"In quatkyn manir of lede &middot; sall me &thorn;ir treis sware?"
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="255"></L>
<L N="5008">"Sothly, ser, &thorn;e son-tree" &middot; said &thorn;e segge &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Entris in with yndoyes &middot; &amp; endis in greke;</L>
<L>And mast-quat ay &thorn;e mone-tree &middot; &thorn;ur&yogh;e mi&yogh;t of hire kynde,</L>
<L>Quen it kithis vs any carpe &middot; &thorn;e contrarie spekis;</L>
<L N="5012">For scho begynes all in grew &middot; &amp; endis in ynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us be twinlepi tongis &middot; tell &thorn;ai oure wirdis."</L>
<L>&THORN;an knelis doun &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;e k conquirour.</NOTE> conquirour &middot; vn-to &thorn;e cald erthe,</L>
<L>And aithire bole eftir bole &middot; blithly he kissis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;t if he suld with &thorn;e thra &middot; of all &thorn;e thedes wete,</L>
<L N="5017">If he suld move agayn to Messedon &middot; quare his modire duellid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an schogs hire &thorn;e son-tree &middot; &amp; schoke hire schire leues,</L>
<L>And with a swe&yogh;and swo&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;is sware scho him &yogh;eldis:</L>
<L>"Sire, &thorn;ou ert lele of ilk lede &middot; &thorn;e lorde &amp; &thorn;e fadire;</L>
<L N="5021">Bot &thorn;i sire soile in na side &middot; see sall &thorn;ou neuire.</L>
<L>For &thorn;i modire nor &yogh;it Messedon &middot; &thorn;ou se&yogh;is &thorn;aim na mare."</L>
<L>&THORN;an list him lithe of his lyfe &middot; &amp; of his last ende:</L>
<L N="5024">"So maideux," quod &thorn;e mone-tree &middot; "&thorn;i meere bees na langir</L>
<L>Bot out &thorn;is anlepi &yogh;ere &middot; &amp; aftir viij monethis;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall he duale &thorn;e with a drinke &middot; at &thorn;ou full dere traistis."</L>
<L N="5027">&THORN;an makis he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> mournyng &amp; mane &middot; &amp; in his mynd thinkis,</L>
<L>Qua suld &thorn;at trecherous trayne &middot; of treson him wirke.</L>
<L>He said, "hende haly tree" &middot; &amp; halsid hire in armes,</L>
<L>"Quat person sall do me depresse &middot; I pray &thorn;e me tell?"</L>
<L>"Sire, sothely," said &thorn;e son-tree &middot; "if I<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e sothe neuened,</L>
<L>Qua suld &thorn;e wite out of &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;i werdis dele,</L>
<L>&THORN;an suld &thorn;ou slaa &thorn;e same segge &middot; &amp; so my sawis faile;</L>
<L N="5034">And &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> may worthe be na wai &middot; for ay my wordis standis."<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an lokid on him his ladisman &middot; said, "lefe of &thorn;i wordis,
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="256"></L>
<L>For writhing of &thorn;ir wale treeis &middot; &amp; willne &thorn;aim na mare.</L>
<L N="5037">Bot graythe &thorn;e, gome, on gods behalue &middot; and a-gayn turne,</L>
<L>For ouire &thorn;e lemetis of &thorn;ir lindis &middot; may no lede founde."</L>
<L>&THORN;en bownes agayn &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; baldly he wepis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he so skitly suld skifte &middot; &amp; fra<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; perhaps read</I> for.</NOTE> his skars terme.</L>
<L>So did his princes, sais &thorn;e prose &middot; for pete of him-selfe,</L>
<L N="5042">With &yogh;edire &yogh;oskingis &amp; &yogh;erre &middot; &yogh;ett out to grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bedis &thorn;aim &thorn;e barotour &middot; on bathe &thorn;aire e&yogh;en twa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld neuire &thorn;is note &middot; to nane of his ost neuyn,</L>
<L>Quat &thorn;ai beheld in &thorn;e hill &middot; &amp; herd with &thorn;aire eres;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;an styntis of his stoure &middot; &amp; steris his hert.</L>
<L N="5047">"If &yogh;e will gange," quod &thorn;is gide &middot; "a-gayn to &yogh;oure kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Moves &yogh;ow to &thorn;e nethire-ward &middot; next I it hald."</L>
<L>&THORN;an passis he to &thorn;is proud place &middot; &amp; oure kynge leues,</L>
<L>And he gose doun be grece &middot; a-gayn to his tentis.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar logis he fra &thorn;e late ni&yogh;t &middot; till efte &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. his &thorn;e; <I>with</I> his <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> li&yogh;t schewis,</L>
<L>With sare sighingis &amp; sadd &middot; for sake of his wirdis;</L>
<L N="5053">Costreynes him with his contenance &middot; to with his kni&yogh;tis play,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at bot sprang of &thorn;e splene &middot; &thorn;e sprite was vn-esid.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e day-rawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. day day rawe; <I>but corrected</I>.</NOTE> rase &middot; he risis vp belyue,</L>
<L>Riches him radly to ride &middot; &amp; remows his ost,</L>
<L N="5057">Driues on with his dukis &middot; day eftir othire,</L>
<L>Till he was meten to &thorn;e meere &middot; quare he &thorn;e monte entird,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e proud playn fild &middot; I proued &yogh;ow be-fore,</L>
<L>Quare all &thorn;e face of &thorn;e fild &middot; was of fyne goules.</L>
<L N="5061">&THORN;are pi&yogh;t he doun his pauylions &middot; &amp; with his princes bidis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e dri&yogh;t of a day &middot; he duellis in &thorn;a costis.</L>
<L>Betwene &thorn;a styes in a stound &middot; &thorn;at strekis &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;e mountis<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="257"></L>
<L>He mas twa pylars<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A curl over</I> p.</NOTE> doun to pynche &middot; all of playn marble,</L>
<L>And tacchis vp of treid gold &middot; a pelare in &thorn;e myddis,</L>
<L>With a prolouge in &thorn;at plate &middot; on aithire post writen.</L>
<L N="5067">"I, Alexander &thorn;e athill &middot; eftire &thorn;e date<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. datere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prince &amp; Persye &amp; Porrus &middot; &thorn;ire pilars en-haunsid.</L>
<L>Qua list &thorn;is lymit ouir-lende &middot; lene to &thorn;e left hand,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e rake on &thorn;e ri&yogh;t hand &middot; &thorn;at may na man passe."</L>
<L N="5071">&THORN;is titill was of twa tongis &middot; tane out &amp; grauen,</L>
<L>Of Ebru &amp; of yndoys &middot; &amp; of &thorn;ire ald lettres,</L>
<L>Of latine &amp; of othire lare &middot; &amp; leues out of grece,</L>
<L>Proudly prikid all in prose; &middot; &amp; here a pas endis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="24" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Vicesimus quartus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="5075">Now strekis he furth with his stour &middot; &amp; steris with his tentis,</L>
<L>He leuys all &thorn;e march-gats &middot; I neuend &yogh;ow before,</L>
<L>And nymmes a-nothire on &thorn;e north &middot; &thorn;e next to his kith,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e marche of Messedone &middot; was him mast qweme.</L>
<L>Sone was he lent in a lande &middot; a large &amp; a noble,</L>
<L>Preciosa, &thorn;e precious &middot; &thorn;e prose &thorn;us it callis;</L>
<L N="5081">And clene all &thorn;at contre &middot; quen &thorn;ai his come wist,</L>
<L>With sike as provid in &thorn;a partis &middot; presentis him faire,</L>
<L>Sum fellis of fischis &middot; ferly to tell,</L>
<L>Was like as of lepards &middot; &amp; lions skynnes;</L>
<L N="5085">Sum with lions on lyue &middot; &amp; lamprays slo&yogh;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sex cubettis clere &middot; was of clene lenghe.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar was a cite in<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn; in; <I>with</I> &thorn; <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at side &middot; asisid all with gemmes,</L>
<L N="5088">With-outen lyme or laire &middot; a lady it kepid,</L>
<L>A worthi wedow &amp; a wlonk &middot; with thre wale childire,<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at qwene Candace &thorn;e clere &middot; was callid in &thorn;a bonds.</L>
<L>Now sall I sothely of hire sons &middot; say &yogh;ow &thorn;e names;</L>
<L>&THORN;e first wos Candoyle callid &middot; a kni&yogh;t althire-fairest;</L>
<L N="5093">&THORN;e medilmast of &thorn;e men &middot; was Marcipy hatten;</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid Caraptus is cald &middot; &thorn;at kepid all hire landis.
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;e kyng of hire knew &middot; a clause he hire writis,</L>
<L>An Image all of athill gold &middot; of Amon hire sendis;</L>
<L>To mete him in &thorn;e montayns &middot; &thorn;at mild he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ho; <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> be-sechis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t sacrif[is]e samme &thorn;ar &middot; to his sere dri&yogh;tins.</L>
<L>Sone as &thorn;is princes of pris &middot; &thorn;is pistill had deuysid,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sendis scho to him sandis-men &middot; with selid lettris,</L>
<L N="5101">With tribute &amp; trouage &middot; &amp; many tried giftis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ire &thorn;e wordis of hire write &middot; at on &thorn;ese wyse spekis.</L>
<L N="5103">&para; "To &thorn;e kiddest kyng &middot; of kyngs all othire,</L>
<L>Sire Alexander &thorn;e athilest &middot; of Amons strinds,</L>
<L>I, Candace &thorn;e conquires &middot; coround of Mede,</L>
<L>To &yogh;our honoure with obeyaunce &middot; me ane I comaunde.</L>
<L>For it was purveid a-pert &middot; of &thorn;e kyng of heuen,</L>
<L>Pre-desteyned of his prouydence &middot; &amp; of his pure mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5109">&THORN;at &yogh;e suld pas in-to Pers &middot; &amp; prese it with armes.</L>
<L>Itale, Egipt, &amp; ynde &middot; &amp; all &thorn;ire Iles ouire,</L>
<L>&YOGH;our wirschip &amp; &yogh;our worthenes &middot; [in] all &thorn;e werd sprong,</L>
<L>&YOGH;our curtassy, &yogh;our kni&yogh;thede &middot; &amp; all &yogh;oure clene thewis.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at with men of &thorn;e mold &middot; no&yogh;t melid vs alane,</L>
<L N="5114">Bot dri&yogh;tins &amp; duesses &middot; &yogh;our dedis declaris.</L>
<L>For&thorn;i like it to &yogh;our lordschip &middot; &amp; lathis no&yogh;t my sawis.</L>
<L>We at ere voide ay of vice &middot; &amp; vacant of syn,<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5117">Quat suld we moue in-to &thorn;e montts? &middot; &thorn;at mysters bot litill,</L>
<L>Outhire Appole to adoure &middot; or any othire dri&yogh;tins.</L>
<L>Bot sen it syttis no&yogh;t to oure simpilnes &middot; &yogh;our sa&yogh;e to with-stande,</L>
<L>Ne no&thorn;ir to mele ne to mote &middot; &yogh;oure maieste a-gayn,</L>
<L N="5121">&YOGH;it sall I send &yogh;ow fra my soile &middot; a sertan of giftis,</L>
<L>For reuerence of &yogh;our rialte &middot; &amp; of &yogh;oure rosid werkis.</L>
<L>I drysse &yogh;ow here a diademe &middot; &yogh;oure druits to were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gaiest gift vndire god &middot; of gold &amp; of stanes,</L>
<L N="5125">And to &yogh;ow selfe of &thorn;e same &middot; o serelepy hewis,</L>
<L>A hundreth in a hale heere &middot; hi&yogh;tild with crestis,
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>And twa hundret &amp; ten &middot; be tale at &thorn;e leste,</L>
<L>Of rekanthes of rede gold &middot; railed of gemmes,</L>
<L N="5129">With pellicans &amp; pape-ioyes &middot; polischt<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. polischa, <I>altered to</I> polischt.</NOTE> &amp; grauen,</L>
<L>With cambs &amp; with coronacles &middot; all of clene perle,</L>
<L>Thretti goblettis of gold &middot; &thorn;e grattest in &thorn;e worde,</L>
<L>Fyue hundreth all of euyn elde &middot; of Ethyops childire,</L>
<L N="5133">Rynoseros,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lynoseros.</NOTE> a roghe best &middot; with raggid tyndis.</L>
<L>An a&yogh;te to<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fra to; <I>with</I> fra <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> &yogh;our empire &middot; I fra myn erd wayue,</L>
<L>Berrers of ane Ebyn-tree &middot; &amp; brilles a thousand,</L>
<L>Foure hundreth Olifants in fere &middot; &thorn;is fardill to bere,</L>
<L N="5137">And thretti hundreth of my thede &middot; &thorn;at threuen ere &amp; tame.</L>
<L>I presand &yogh;ow, of panters &middot; full of proud mascles,</L>
<L>Foure hundreth fellis &yogh;it to fee &middot; &thorn;at fynely ere tewid."</L>
<L>Of lepards &amp; of lionesses &middot; &thorn;is lady him sendis,</L>
<L>A purtrayour in preuate &middot; scho prays with &thorn;am to pas,</L>
<L>And his personele proporcions &middot; in perchemen hire bring.</L>
<L>All was done as scho demed &middot; &amp; he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> hire dere thankis,</L>
<L>And graithis hire giftis agayn &middot; &thorn;e gaiest vndire heuen.</L>
<L>&THORN;e payntour presentis his aport &middot; &amp; shoo was proud &thorn;en,</L>
<L>For scho had depely many day &middot; desyrid him to see.<MILESTONE N="89a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5147">&THORN;en wendis furth hire dere son &middot; a litill dais eftir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ser Candoile &thorn;e kene &middot; &thorn;at was hire kidd aire,</L>
<L>His wife &amp; his women &middot; &amp; with his wale feres,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cite &thorn;ai so&yogh;t &middot; to solace &thorn;ar hertis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of Bebrike &thorn;e bald &middot; him on &thorn;e bent metis,</L>
<L>With a company clene &middot; of kni&yogh;tis enarmed,</L>
<L N="5153">Maynes many of his men &middot; &amp; him his make refis,</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at lady had loued &middot; many lange wintire.</L>
<L>He gers a berne on a blonke &middot; hire bremely to cast</L>
<L>Before a bald bachelere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bachele, <I>altered to</I> bachelere.</NOTE> &middot; on a bigg stede;</L>
<L>Scho gaffe skirmand skrikis &middot; at all &thorn;e skowis range,</L>
<L>It mi&yogh;t a persid any hert &middot; to here how scho wepid.
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="260"></L>
<L>&THORN;an was ser Candoile in &thorn;at cas &middot; kenely distourbid,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. distrouubid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5160">Aires on as bely[ue] &middot; to Alexander tentis,</L>
<L>Tho&yogh;t he wald sewe to &thorn;at sire &middot; &amp; seke him of grace,</L>
<L>If he wald helpe with his heere &middot; &thorn;at hend to reschowe.</L>
<L>Be he &thorn;e pauylion a-prochid &middot; it past with-in euen,</L>
<L N="5164">And sone &thorn;e wacche-men with-out &middot; quen &thorn;ai him &thorn;are sawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai tuke him, &amp; to Telomew &middot; titte &thorn;ai him ledd,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mast praysed of &thorn;e pers &middot; bot &thorn;e prince selfe.</L>
<L N="5167">"Quat dons man ert &thorn;ou?" quod &thorn;e duke &middot; "&amp; quat dos &thorn;ou here,</L>
<L>Quat is &thorn;e cause of &thorn;i come? &middot; do kith vs &thorn;i name."</L>
<L>"Sirs, Candaces son &thorn;e conquires &middot; &amp; Candoile I hi&yogh;t;"</L>
<L>And clene tald him [of his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. tald him him care.</NOTE>] care &middot; &thorn;e cause all-to-gedire.</L>
<L>&THORN;an trines on ser Telomew &middot; &amp; fra his tent wyndis,</L>
<L>Comands ser Candoile to kepe &middot; in a kni&yogh;tis warde,</L>
<L N="5173">Cairys in-to a cabayne &middot; quare &thorn;e kyng liggis,</L>
<L>Fand him slowmand on slepe &middot; &amp; sleely him rayses,<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And tellis him of &thorn;at tithandis &middot; &thorn;e tale how itt standis,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ar was comyn slike a kni&yogh;t &middot; to craue him of help,</L>
<L N="5177">&THORN;e son of Candace &thorn;e quene &middot; &thorn;e kepare of Mede;</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e Bebrik kyng &middot; had him his wyfe refid.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, aire a-gayn," quod Alexander &middot; "in-to &thorn;ine awen tent;</L>
<L>Do on &thorn;i hede a dyademe &middot; &thorn;e derrest at I haue,</L>
<L N="5181">A croun all of clene gold &middot; &amp; a kyngis mantill,</L>
<L>A-se&yogh;ee &thorn;e doun in my sege &middot; as &thorn;ou my-selfe ware;</L>
<L>Lat com a-boute &thorn;e my kni&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; call ye my name,</L>
<L>with<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. w, <I>followed by a blot and</I> with; <I>probably</I> with with.</NOTE> li&yogh;t lions latis &middot; as a lord suld;</L>
<L N="5185">Say &thorn;i-selfe is my-selfe &middot; &amp; &thorn;an my-selfe call,</L>
<L>As I ware Antioc &thorn;at athill &middot; non aghe of me &thorn;ou stand,</L>
<L>And I sall hi&yogh;e to &thorn;i hest &middot; as [I] &thorn;i hathill ware.</L>
<L>Quen I com to &thorn;i call &middot; &amp; knele &thorn;e before,</L>
<L N="5189">&THORN;ou sall declare me &thorn;e cas &middot; of Candals auntir,
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>Befor his person apert &middot; ilk poynt as he touchid.</L>
<L>Be no&yogh;t a-baist quen I bow &middot; ne bede me<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne bede me <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> no&yogh;t to ryse,</L>
<L>Bot lat &thorn;i semblance be sadd &middot; quen &thorn;ou &thorn;i sa&yogh;e &yogh;ildis;</L>
<L>And sai &thorn;an, 'Antioc, myn athill' &middot; quen &thorn;ou has all tald,</L>
<L>'Latt se &thorn;i witt in &thorn;is werke' &middot; &amp; wysely me rede."</L>
<L>&THORN;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. La &thorn;an; <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE> trines furth ser Telomew &middot; &amp; tyris him belyue;</L>
<L N="5196">In emperouris aparell &middot; his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. his his; <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE> person he clethis.</L>
<L>And Alexander as belyue &middot; in antioks name,</L>
<L>Quen he was<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. had was; <I>corrected</I>.</NOTE> callid, with a kni&yogh;t &middot; he coms in a stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an tellis to him ser Telomew &middot; &thorn;e tale all-to-gedire,</L>
<L>Be-fore ser Candale &thorn;e kene &middot; his consaile him askis.</L>
<L>"Ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. With; <I>altered to</I> Ware.</NOTE> it &yogh;our will," quod &thorn;e wee &middot; "wale emperoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wald I fare with &thorn;is freke &middot; his fere to reskowe,</L>
<L>And bid &thorn;e Bebrike &middot; on bathe twa his e&yogh;en,<MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5204">Withouten bade to &thorn;is bri&yogh;t &middot; his brid to restore;</L>
<L>And say &thorn;at sire, on &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> be-half &middot; bot he hire sone &yogh;eld,</L>
<L>We sall his cite &amp; him-selfe &middot; synge in-to poudire!"</L>
<L>With &thorn;at inclynes &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &middot; &amp; kyndly him loues,</L>
<L N="5208">Said, "antiok, of all men &middot; ay be &thorn;ou Ioyed;</L>
<L>It semes &thorn;e, for &thorn;i sapience &middot; to sit in a trone,</L>
<L>And to be cled as a kyng &middot; with croune &amp; with septir!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an aires him furth ser Alexander &middot; as Antiok it ware,</L>
<L N="5212">Cairis on with candoile &middot; &amp; ca&yogh;t him his leue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wyfe, <I>altered to</I> leue.</NOTE></L>
<L>So&yogh;t furth &thorn;e same ni&yogh;t &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e cite wan,</L>
<L>Quare &thorn;e Bebrik kyng &middot; with &thorn;e bird lengis.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e wacchis on &thorn;e wallis &middot; &thorn;am wi&yogh;tly ascryes,</L>
<L>Qua &thorn;ai ware, &amp; of quethen &middot; &amp; quat was &thorn;ar errande.</L>
<L N="5217">"It is ser Candoile," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "is comyn for his spouse;</L>
<L>And I am messangere made &middot; &thorn;at mild to delyuire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e maistir out of Messedone &middot; &yogh;ow maynly enjoynes,</L>
<L N="5220">If &yogh;e &yogh;oure cite will saue &middot; to sese him his brid."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;e burgaige a-baiste &middot; &amp; brest vp &thorn;e &yogh;atis,
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e palais of &thorn;e proud kyng &middot; his paramour him tuke.</L>
<L>Sire Candoile to oure conquirour &middot; carpis &thorn;ire wordis,</L>
<L>And adoures him for his athill dede &middot; &amp; Antiok him calls.</L>
<L>"I pray &thorn;e, prince, with me pas &middot; to my praysid modire,</L>
<L N="5226">&THORN;at &thorn;ou may merote haue &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Above the line</I>.</NOTE> menske &middot; &amp; mede for &thorn;i werkis."</L>
<L>&THORN;an was oure kyng of &thorn;at carpe &middot; kyndly reioyed,</L>
<L>For him had list on hire to loke &middot; many lang wintir.</L>
<L>He said, "aire we to Alexander &middot; &amp; askis him his leue,</L>
<L>And I sall fayn with &thorn;e found &middot; &amp; felsyn &thorn;i will."<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;an trines he to ser Telomew &middot; at in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> his trone sittis,</L>
<L N="5232">La&yogh;t his leue at &thorn;e lede &middot; as he his lorde ware.</L>
<L>&THORN;is kid he for a coyntise &middot; &amp; kest slike a wile,</L>
<L>Lest he ware knawyn for &thorn;e kyng &middot; &thorn;e kni&yogh;t for to blinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an caires he furthe with Candoile &middot; vp at a cliffe wyndis,</L>
<L>A hidous hill &amp; a hi&yogh;e &middot; &thorn;at to &thorn;e heuen semed,</L>
<L N="5237">Was loken all in lange lindis &middot; like to &thorn;e cedres,</L>
<L>Growand full of gernetts &middot; &amp; gracious frutes.</L>
<L>&THORN;are fand &thorn;ai bery-buskis &middot; &amp; braunches with grapis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnnethes bere mi&yogh;t a berin &middot; a bole on his schuldire.</L>
<L>With hesils hild of hodere &middot; cloud lang &thorn;a appills,</L>
<L N="5242">And all &thorn;e woddis full of wolfes &middot; &amp; of wild apis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai bow vp to a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> banke &middot; &amp; &thorn;e burgh ne&yogh;es;</L>
<L>And Candace &thorn;e conquires &middot; quen scho &thorn;e cas heris,</L>
<L>How bathe hire barne &amp; his brid &middot; was bro&yogh;t hame sond,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was scho glad in hire gast &middot; &amp; gretly reioysed.</L>
<L>In-to a chambre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The</I> h <I>is above the line</I>.</NOTE> scho chese &middot; &amp; changid hire wedis;</L>
<L N="5248">A Robe all of rede gold &middot; &amp; &thorn;an a riche mantill,</L>
<L>A croune &amp; a corecheffe &middot; clustert with gemmes,</L>
<L>And [cam] doun of hire closere &middot; with kni&yogh;tis him to mete.</L>
<L>A grete gate be degrece &middot; agayn &thorn;aim scho foundis;</L>
<L>"Kys me, ser Candoile" &middot; &amp; clappis him in armes,
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="263"></L>
<L>Said, "welcum be &thorn;ou, wale son &middot; &amp; &thorn;ou, my wale do&yogh;tir!</L>
<L>And I am glad of &yogh;oure gest &middot; as gode geffe me ioye."</L>
<L N="5255">Sire Alexander hire a-vises &middot; &amp; all his hert li&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;o&yogh;t hire like at a loke &middot; his lady his modire.</L>
<L>Scho was so faire &amp; so fresche &middot; as faucon hire semed,</L>
<L>An elfe out of an-othire erde &middot; or ellis an Aungell.</L>
<L>Hire palais was full precious &middot; &thorn;of it parades ware,</L>
<L N="5260">Plied ouir with pure gold &middot; all &thorn;e plate-rofes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was ioyned full of gemes &middot; &amp; of ioly stanes,<MILESTONE N="91a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With breme blasenand bemes &middot; bri&yogh;t as &thorn;e son.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng with dame Candace &middot; &thorn;e castell he entres,</L>
<L N="5264">Silis in with &thorn;at semely &middot; in-to a somere-hall,</L>
<L>A strenthe, was sti&yogh;tild all of stagis &middot; &thorn;e stithest of &thorn;e werd,</L>
<L>Was nane so comly a close &middot; vndire &thorn;e can[o]pe of heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bild was all of brent gold &middot; &thorn;e beddis of &thorn;e same,</L>
<L N="5268">Pi&yogh;t full of pentests &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ire proude stanes,</L>
<L>Of Onycles &amp; orfrays &middot; &amp; orient perles,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;ire precious piers &middot; of paradise stremes,</L>
<L>Bathe &thorn;e benkis &amp; &thorn;e bordis &middot; bett of &thorn;e noble,</L>
<L N="5272">Smeten full of smaragdins &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ir small gemmes,</L>
<L>Of Acats &amp; of Amatistis &middot; &amp; adamants fyne,</L>
<L>Calcidoynes &amp; crisopaces &middot; &amp; o&thorn;ir clere bees.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilars ware of purfire &middot; polischt &amp; hewen,</L>
<L>With gomes grouelings of gold &middot; graythid for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L N="5277">Fondand on all foure &middot; on fote &amp; on handis,</L>
<L>Buskid vndire &thorn;e baisens &middot; to bere vp &thorn;e postis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are ran a reuire, as I rede &middot; vndire &thorn;at riche hame,</L>
<L>Was neuir na cristall so clere &middot; as was &thorn;a clere strandis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &amp; Candace &thorn;e quene &middot; &amp; Candeile hire aire,</L>
<L N="5282">&THORN;e same day in &thorn;e sale &middot; was serued to-gedire.</L>
<L>Scho sesis him on &thorn;e secunde day &middot; [&amp; sone] with him laches,</L>
<L>Ra&yogh;t him by &thorn;e ri&yogh;t hand &middot; &amp; raikis to a chambre,</L>
<L>Was parraillid all of plate-gold &middot; pariet &amp; o&thorn;ire,</L>
<L N="5286">With stoute starand stanes &middot; &thorn;at stremed as &thorn;e son.
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="264"></L>
<L>Was &thorn;ar na leuyand lede &middot; ne lyfe bot &thorn;am ane.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an scho laches him be-lyfe &middot; &amp; ledis him forthire,</L>
<L>In-to a clochere with a kay &middot; &thorn;e clennest of &thorn;e werde,</L>
<L N="5290">Was sammed all of sipris &middot; &amp; seder-tables.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="25" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>&para; Vicesimus quintus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is selere was be sorsry &middot; selcuthely foundid,<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Made for a mervall &middot; to meeue with engine;</L>
<L>Twenti tamed Olifants &middot; turned it a-boute,</L>
<L N="5294">Quirland all on queles &middot; quen &thorn;e quene entres.</L>
<L>Quen &thorn;ai ware sett &thorn;ar in samen &middot; on silkin webbis,</L>
<L>Sone begynnes it to gaa &middot; &amp; gretly he wondres.</L>
<L>"Ware slike a wondire in oure marche &middot; of Messedone," he said,</L>
<L>"It ware a daynte to deme &middot; for any duke oute!"</L>
<L N="5299">&THORN;an answars him &thorn;is athill quene &middot; &amp; Alexander him callid,</L>
<L>"Mekill grettir it ware to &yogh;ow of grece &middot; &amp; to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> gomes here."</L>
<L>&THORN;an stemes he with &thorn;e stoute kyng &middot; &amp; stiggis with his name;</L>
<L>His chere out of chere hew &middot; it changis in-to pale,</L>
<L>&THORN;an has &thorn;at hende him by &thorn;e hand &middot; &amp; hent vp a la&yogh;tir.</L>
<L N="5304">In to A preue parlour &middot; &thorn;ai passe bathe to-gedire,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar in perchement depayntid &middot; his person scho schewid.</L>
<L>Said, "se &thorn;i-selfe a sampill &middot; &thorn;at I &thorn;e sothe neuyn!"</L>
<L>As fast as he on &thorn;is figour &middot; festid his si&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="5308">All falowis his face &middot; &amp; his flesche trimblis;</L>
<L>"Qui fadis so &thorn;i faire hew?" &middot; said &thorn;e faire lady</L>
<L>"&THORN;e werreour of all &thorn;e werd &middot; &amp; wastoure of ynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at has brettend on &thorn;e bent &middot; &thorn;e barbrins folke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. fokke.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5312">&THORN;e pepill out of Panty &middot; &thorn;e Persens &amp; &thorn;e Medis.</L>
<L>Loo, now, &thorn;e here withouten hi&yogh;t &middot; in-to my handis sesed,
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>Bot in a womans ward &middot; for all &thorn;i wale dedis!</L>
<L>Ser, wete it wele &yogh;oure worthenes &middot; &thorn;at for na wele here</L>
<L>Suld neuire no hathill vndire heuen &middot; [be] to hi&yogh;e losed;</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e welthe of &thorn;e werd &middot; ware it a wee grantid,</L>
<L N="5318">It witis a-way at a wapp &middot; as &thorn;e wynd turnes."</L>
<L>&THORN;an chawfis him &thorn;at chiftane &middot; &amp; with him-selfe chidis,<MILESTONE N="92a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>All if he spared to spek &middot; his sprete he rehetis.</L>
<L>As any terand for tene &middot; he with his tethe gnaistes,</L>
<L N="5322">And hitterly on ilk side &middot; his heued he declines.</L>
<L>"Qui colkins &thorn;ou, ser conquirour &middot; &amp; crabbis so &thorn;i saule,</L>
<L>Quat may &thorn;i vertu now a-vaile &middot; &amp; all &thorn;ine vayn pride?"</L>
<L>"I swete," quod &thorn;e swete kyng &middot; "&thorn;at I na swerd haue,</L>
<L>For I na wapen haue, I-wis &middot; my writh with to venge!"</L>
<L>"Now, bald baratour on bent &middot; if &thorn;ou a brand hade,</L>
<L>Quat prowis mi&yogh;t &thorn;i person &middot; a-preue in &thorn;is stounde?"</L>
<L N="5329">"For I vnwarly," quod &thorn;e kyng &middot; "am to &yogh;oure will taken,</L>
<L>I suld &thorn;e slaa &thorn;are &thorn;ou sittis &middot; &amp; &thorn;an my-selfe eftir!"</L>
<L>"Now, be my croun," quod &thorn;e quene &middot; "as kni&yogh;tly &thorn;ou swaris;</L>
<L>Bot neuir-&thorn;e-lattir &yogh;it be li&yogh;t &middot; &amp; lete of &thorn;i sorowe.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has bro&yogh;t my son wife &middot; of bebricans handis,</L>
<L>And I sall surely &thorn;e saue &middot; vnsesid of &thorn;e berbrens.</L>
<L>For ware it knawen of &thorn;i come &middot; &thorn;ai walld &thorn;i cors schind,</L>
<L N="5336">For opressing of &thorn;e gud prince &middot; Porrus of Ynde.</L>
<L>And Caratros my kid son &middot; has couplid him to wyfe</L>
<L>&THORN;e do&yogh;tir of &thorn;is dere kynge &middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou to dethe bro&yogh;t."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at scho sesis &thorn;is sire &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e sale ledes,</L>
<L N="5340">Sendis eftir hire sons &middot; &amp; sobirly &thorn;am tretis</L>
<L>&THORN;is athill of ser Alexander &middot; as &thorn;ai were all halden,</L>
<L>At &thorn;ai suld menske him &amp; mirthe &middot; &amp; make him at esee.</L>
<L>"I knaw it wele," quod Caratros &middot; "my comly modire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my brothirs<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. brothird.</NOTE> brid &middot; has out of bands leuird,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e kyng, be &thorn;at cause &middot; has to &thorn;is kith sent;</L>
<L>Bot my wyfe will ga wode for wa &middot; bot I &thorn;is wee spill.
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>Ne ware he a messangere &middot; &amp; &yogh;it mare for &yogh;oure-selfe,</L>
<L>Sure suld him sowe for his sake &middot; at him has sent hedire.</L>
<L N="5349">So sall his maistir, &amp; I may &middot; be my dire saule,<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he &thorn;e fadire of my fere &middot; has in &thorn;e feld drepid."</L>
<L>"A!" quod &thorn;is lade, "leue son &middot; if we &thorn;is lede slo&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Suld we vs nymme any name &middot; o&yogh;t bot of sorowe?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, Cartros," quod Candoile &middot; "&thorn;is kni&yogh;t has me saued,</L>
<L>And I sal<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> lede him on lyue &middot; vn-to his lord tentis."</L>
<L N="5355">'Quat baitis &thorn;ou me so, my brothire &middot; with &thorn;i breme wordis,</L>
<L>List<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Lift.</NOTE> ye we stryfe in &thorn;is stede &middot; &amp; strike aithire o&thorn;ir?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;at kepe I no&yogh;t," quod Candoile &middot; "&yogh;it for na cas neuend,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;e langis to &thorn;at laike &middot; lo me here redy!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an callis Candace &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &middot; in consaille him takis,</L>
<L>Sees hire sons wald him sla &middot; &amp; radly scho pleynes;</L>
<L N="5361">'Lord Alexander, &thorn;ine are &middot; quare is &thorn;i wittis?</L>
<L>I prai &thorn;e for &thorn;i prouidence &middot; pesse now my childire."</L>
<L>&THORN;an bows &thorn;is baratour &middot; &thorn;ire brethire to stere,</L>
<L>Fand caratros &amp; candoile &middot; at knyfes to-drawen,</L>
<L N="5365">Bad, "blyns, bernes of &yogh;oure brathe &middot; &amp; of &yogh;our breme wordis;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e fare bot with folite &middot; quare ere &yogh;oure fyue wittis?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an carps he to ser Caratros &middot; &amp; kythis on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>Ser, if &thorn;ou lessen my life &middot; na lowere &thorn;ou wynnes.</L>
<L>For Alexander of his awen &middot; has many athill kni&yogh;tis</L>
<L>&THORN;at ere mare sekire at a-say &middot; &thorn;an slike seuen houndreth.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. henndreth, <I>altered to</I> houndreth.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5371">For if I ware fallen fey &middot; him forced bot littill.</L>
<L>For ware I a tresour to &thorn;at tulk &middot; trowe wele &thorn;i-selfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me so sodanly &thorn;at sire &middot; had no&yogh;t sent hedire,</L>
<L>With-outen wees me to warde &middot; nay, wene &thorn;ou &thorn;at neuir.</L>
<L N="5375">Bot if &thorn;e list on &thorn;at lede &middot; loke with &thorn;ine e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Sire Alexander &thorn;e athill &middot; &thorn;ine aldfadire bane,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thare bot graunt me to geue &middot; quat guds as I craue,
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>And I sall prestly &thorn;at prince &middot; present in-to &thorn;i handis."<MILESTONE N="93a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5379">&THORN;an ware &thorn;ire brethire full blithe &middot; &thorn;us ware &thorn;ai bath pesed,</L>
<L>And Candoile callis to &thorn;e king &middot; &amp; kindly him thankis,</L>
<L>"Had I &yogh;ow ay with me here &middot; happy ware I &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wald I wene with &yogh;our witt &middot; to wast all my fais."</L>
<L>With &thorn;at scho kende him a croun &middot; clustrid with gemmes,</L>
<L>With Amatists &amp; Adamands &middot; &amp; an athill mantill,</L>
<L>Sterind &amp; sti&yogh;t full of stanes &middot; sithin stelis to him cussis,</L>
<L>With othire preuates him plesis &middot; bad pas on with hele.</L>
<L>Nowe aires furth oure conquirour &middot; &amp; candoile him gidis,</L>
<L N="5388">Driues furth all &thorn;e dai &middot; till doun was &thorn;e son,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai come till a caue &middot; was out of course hoge,</L>
<L>Be-twene twa hillis in a hope &middot; &amp; herberd all ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"Sire," quod candoile &thorn;e kene &middot; &amp; to &thorn;e kynge said,</L>
<L>"All spritis in &thorn;is spelonk &middot; here speke &thorn;ai to-gedire,</L>
<L>Here is &thorn;aire comon consaile;" &middot; &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;e kyng heris,</L>
<L>Makis he gracis to his goddis &middot; &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e grofe entres.</L>
<L>Quen he was doun in &thorn;e depe &middot; he sa&yogh;e a dym cloude</L>
<L>Full of starand sternes &middot; and sti&yogh;tild in &thorn;e myddest</L>
<L N="5397">A grete grysely god &middot; on a gay trone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at li&yogh;t lemand e&yogh;en &middot; as lanterns he had.</L>
<L>Oure mode kyng was so maied &middot; myndles him semed:</L>
<L>"Haile, Alexander &thorn;e hende" &middot; quod &thorn;at hi&yogh;e dri&yogh;tin.</L>
<L>"Sire, qua ere &yogh;e?" said oure ser &middot; "Synches I hi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And to my powere vndire-putt &middot; is all &thorn;e playn werd.</L>
<L N="5403">For &thorn;i name a cite has &thorn;ou sesid<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sesis.</NOTE> &middot; bot &thorn;ou settis me na temple."</L>
<L>"Sire, if I mi&yogh;t merke to Messedone &middot; a Maistir I &thorn;e hi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Sall nane be like it in na lede;" &middot; "nay,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. nay nay.</NOTE> lange no&yogh;t &thorn;ar-eftir!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall neuir loke on &thorn;at land &middot; ga lawere &amp; be-hald."</L>
<L N="5407">&THORN;an kend him quare anothire cloude &middot; was full of bri&yogh;t sternes,
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>And quare a-nothire grym god &middot; was graythid on a sege.<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Sire, quat ert &thorn;ou," said &thorn;e segge &middot; "ser Sirapis, I-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e grond &amp; &thorn;e begininge &middot; of all &thorn;e godis oute."</L>
<L>"Now I be-seke &thorn;e, Serapis," &middot; said oure kyng &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Quat segge is sett me to slaa &middot; &thorn;e sothe &thorn;ou me tell."</L>
<L N="5413">"Sire, I haue neuend &thorn;e or now &middot; &thorn;at, ware &thorn;at note knawen</L>
<L>Till any douth of quat dome &middot; &thorn;en died I for sorowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>inserts</I> biggid, <I>struck through</I>.</NOTE> a blisfull bur&yogh;e &middot; biggid to &thorn;i name,</L>
<L>Quare many bernes sall debate &middot; &amp; bald emperouris,</L>
<L N="5417">&THORN;are sall &thorn;i berynes be bildid &middot; &amp; &thorn;i body grauen."</L>
<L>&THORN;an come vp oure kidd kyng &middot; and fra &thorn;e kni&yogh;t partis,</L>
<L>&thorn;us kaires he fro candele &middot; bad, 'kepe wele him dri&yogh;tin.'</L>
<L>Moues him on to his meny &middot; &amp; on &thorn;e morne eftir</L>
<L>&THORN;an dryues he furth with his dukis &middot; in-to a deyne entris,</L>
<L N="5422">A vale full of vermyn &middot; &amp; all of vile neddirs.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware crokid &amp; coynnt &middot; with corouns on hede,</L>
<L>As it smytten [ware] all of smythis &middot; of smaragdens fine.</L>
<L N="5425">&yogh;it ware &thorn;ai pasturde of pepir &middot; as &thorn;e prose tellis,</L>
<L>Of gyloffre &amp; of gingere &middot; els ioyed &thorn;aim na fodis.</L>
<L>For all ouire couerd was &thorn;e coue &middot; claggid with spices,</L>
<L>&THORN;at makis &thorn;ire wormes so wele &middot; &amp; woud in &thorn;aire kyndis,</L>
<L N="5429">&THORN;at ilka twelmonth a turne &middot; &thorn;ai turnay to-gedire,</L>
<L>Ilkane mellis with his make &middot; &amp; so &thorn;are many dies.</L>
<L>&THORN;an pas &thorn;ai thethen till a place &middot; of perlious bestis,</L>
<L>With clouen clees, sais &thorn;e clause &middot; as kynd of &thorn;e hoggs.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware thike &amp; threuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. theeuen, <I>altered to</I> threuen.</NOTE> wele &middot; thre foote o brede,</L>
<L>Quare-with &thorn;ai fa&yogh;t with in-fere &middot; &amp; fellid of his kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware so brefe at a blisch &middot; borely &amp; grym.</L>
<L N="5436">On ilka best a bares hede &middot; full of breme tuskis,</L>
<L>&thorn;us ware &thorn;ai fourmed all be-fore &middot; &amp; farand be-hynde</L>
<L>Like as it ware lepards &middot; &amp; lions with tailis.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;ar gedird out of gripis &middot; &amp; griffons emange,</L>
<L N="5440">&THORN;at felly flappid at &thorn;e faces &middot; of &thorn;e fell erles,
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>And euir ilka best was so bigge &middot; of body &amp; of wyng,<MILESTONE N="94a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t bere away a blonke &middot; &amp; a kni&yogh;t armed.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng was on his couresere &middot; to comforth his dukis,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e bald bucifalon &middot; eblande &thorn;aim he rydis,</L>
<L N="5445">Prekis fra place in-to place &middot; bad, "plukis vp &yogh;our hertis,"</L>
<L>And cherischest his chiftans &middot; with chelous wordis.</L>
<L>He baldis of his bachelers &middot; &amp; his bowmen he cheris,</L>
<L N="5448">To flay with flanes of &thorn;e fowlis &middot; &amp; &thorn;e fell bestis.</L>
<L>And it was done at his dome &middot; with-drewe &thorn;ai na langir,</L>
<L>Bath archere &amp; alblastis &middot; &amp; all &thorn;aim a-sailed.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bataile on bathe halfis &middot; brymly begynnys,</L>
<L>Oure seggis &amp; &thorn;e Synagyns &middot; semblid vnfaire;</L>
<L N="5453">Gripis gripis of oure gomes &middot; out of gilt sadils,</L>
<L>Tuk &thorn;am in &thorn;aire talons &middot; &amp; titt fra &thorn;aire blonkis.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it oure kyng with his kni&yogh;tis &middot; so kenely defendis,</L>
<L>And with his ginge out of grece &middot; &thorn;at he &thorn;e gree wynnes.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it was herid of his here &middot; twa hundreth &amp; ouire,</L>
<L>&thorn;us gafe vp &thorn;e gaste &middot; with gold on &thorn;ai heles.</L>
<L N="5459">&THORN;an ferd he furth till a flode &middot; &amp; &thorn;at a ferly hoge,</L>
<L>Twenti forelang &amp; ferre &middot; it had of full breede,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e strands of &thorn;e streme &middot; stode full of stith reedis,</L>
<L>Quare-of he beds at a braid &middot; him bargis to make.</L>
<L>Quen it was hewyn at his hest &middot; with heggis ouire-folden,</L>
<L N="5464">&THORN;an entirs in of his erles &middot; &amp; ouire &thorn;e ee passis.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at kith of oure kyng &middot; quen &thorn;ai his come wist,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai perid to him with presands &middot; &thorn;e proudis of &thorn;at land.</L>
<L>Sum spends on him of spon[ges]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn; spon, <I>followed by a small blank space. The Latin text has</I> spongias.</NOTE> &middot; a sparles nounbre,</L>
<L N="5468">Of mirre &amp; of mekill quat &middot; milke-quite<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The line is incomplete; add</I>&mdash;'&amp; purpre.' <I>Latin text</I>, albas et purpureas.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum men muscles him mett &middot; &amp; with so mekill schellis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sex pond mi&yogh;t of paise &middot; haue ni of watre.</L>
<L>Sum of seelis of &thorn;e see &middot; sendis to him cotis,
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>Sum bees at ware blode-rede &middot; &amp; borely wormes<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5473">As large as a mans lege &middot; &amp; lamprays of we&yogh;t</L>
<L>Twa hundreth pond ay a pece &middot; &amp; past it be fifty.</L>
<L>&YOGH;it was &thorn;ar wonand in &thorn;is watir &middot; as women it semed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ferly faire ware of face &middot; with haare to &thorn;aire heelis.</L>
<L N="5477">Ouire-stride &thorn;ar any strange man &middot; or be &thorn;ir strandis sailed,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai dro&yogh;e &thorn;am doun in-to &thorn;e depe &middot; &amp; drowned &thorn;aim for euire,</L>
<L>Or els &thorn;ai tillid &thorn;aim to &thorn;e trees &middot; as &thorn;e buke tellis,</L>
<L N="5480">And gert &thorn;aim laike with &thorn;aim so lange &middot; till &thorn;aim &thorn;e life wantis.</L>
<L>Oure men tuke of &thorn;aim twa &middot; was ten foote of hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Als bla&yogh;t as any bri&yogh;t snaw &middot; &amp; as biche sons<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> sous.</NOTE> tothed.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="26" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>Vicesimus sextus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an aires furth ser Alexander &middot; &amp; with his arte closis</L>
<L>Of terands of &thorn;ir tartaryns &middot; twa &amp; twenti kyngs.</L>
<L>He stekis &thorn;am vp with &thorn;ar stoures &middot; in a straite lawe,</L>
<L>And I sall neuen &yogh;ow &thorn;ar names &middot; if &yogh;e &thorn;aim neuire herd.</L>
<L>Gogg &amp; magogg &thorn;e grete &middot; he with &thorn;ir gomes pyndis,</L>
<L N="5488">Agekany &amp; Anafrage &middot; &amp; Almade bathe,</L>
<L>Sire Camour &amp; ser Cacany &middot; with all &thorn;ar kidd ostis,</L>
<L>And ane ser Clambert &thorn;e kene &middot; was kyng of &thorn;er ostis;</L>
<L>Gamarody &thorn;e goblyn &middot; a-nothire gryn<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> grym.</NOTE> sire,</L>
<L>Marthyney &thorn;e mi&yogh;tfull &middot; &amp; Magen his fere,</L>
<L N="5493">Appedanere, Olaathere &middot; &amp; Alane &thorn;e grete,</L>
<L>And ane ser na&thorn;y onone &middot; he in &thorn;e nabb speris.</L>
<L>He lockis in ane ser limy &middot; with a laith mey[n]he,</L>
<L>And raryfey, a riche ray &middot; he in &thorn;e roche stoppis,</L>
<L N="5497">Sire Filies, a fell kyng &middot; with all his fers kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L>And ane ser Bedwyn &thorn;e bald &middot; with many bri&yogh;t helmes.</L>
<L>Arteneus ane athill kemp &middot; als-so he in-parkis,<MILESTONE N="95a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5500">And ane ser Tarbyn, a tulke &middot; with many toore thousandis;
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="271"></L>
<L>Sire Saltary, a-nothire sire &middot; now is &thorn;e sowme reckend.</L>
<L>All &thorn;ire he closis in &thorn;at cliffe &middot; &amp; cairis on forthire</L>
<L>To &thorn;e occyan at &thorn;e erthes ende &middot; &amp; &thorn;ar in an Ilee he heres</L>
<L N="5504">A grete glauir &amp; a glaam &middot; of grekin tongis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bad he kni&yogh;tis &thorn;aim vnclethe &middot; &amp; to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at kithe swym,</L>
<L>Bot all at come in-to &thorn;at cole &middot; crabbis has &thorn;aim drenchid.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sewis furth &thorn;at souerayn &middot; ay by &thorn;a salt strandis</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e settynge of &thorn;e son &middot; in seson of wintir;</L>
<L>Sexti dais with his sowme &middot; sadly he ridis,</L>
<L N="5510">Ra&yogh;t on to &thorn;e reede See &middot; &amp; rerid &thorn;are his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. is his; <I>with</I> is <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> tentis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was a mi&yogh;ti montayne &middot; at to &thorn;e mone semed,</L>
<L>He gessis it gaynir to god &middot; &thorn;an to &thorn;e grounde vndire,</L>
<L>And slike a fonned fantasy &middot; &thorn;an fell in his hert,</L>
<L N="5514">How &thorn;at he liftid mi&yogh;t be fra &thorn;e lawe &middot; vn-to &thorn;e li&yogh;t sternes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an made he smythis to gaa smert &middot; &amp; smethe him a chaiere</L>
<L>Of blake iren &amp; of bigge &middot; &amp; bynde it with cheynes,</L>
<L N="5517">A sekire sege in to sitt &middot; &amp; sett him on-loft.</L>
<L>And foure Griffons full grym &middot; he in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at graythe festes;</L>
<L>He makis to hinge ouir &thorn;aire hede &middot; in hokis of iren</L>
<L>Flesch on ferrom &thorn;aim fra &middot; at &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t no&yogh;t to reches,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> reche.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make &thorn;aim freke to &thorn;e fli&yogh;t &middot; &thorn;at fode for to wyn,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai ware fastand be-fore &middot; halden for &thorn;e nanes.</L>
<L>Now is he won &thorn;ur&yogh;e &thorn;ar wingis &middot; vp to &thorn;e wale cloudis;</L>
<L N="5524">So hi&yogh;e to heuen &thorn;ai him hale &middot; in a hand-quile,</L>
<L>Midil-erth bot as a mylnestane &middot; na mare to him semed,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e watir of &thorn;e werd &middot; bot as a wrethen neddire.</L>
<L>&THORN;e vertu of &thorn;e verray god &middot; envirounis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The first</I> i <I>above the line</I>.</NOTE> him swythe,</L>
<L N="5528">And &thorn;an &thorn;ai fell on a fild &middot; as ferre fra his ost</L>
<L>As any freke mi&yogh;t founde &middot; in fiftene daies,</L>
<L>And he vnhurt with mikill vnhome &middot; he to his ost wynes.<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>A-nothire wondirfull witt &middot; &yogh;it worthid in his hert,</L>
<L>How he mi&yogh;t seke doun sounde &middot; in-to &thorn;e see bothom,</L>
<L N="5533">To see quat selcuthe is seet &middot; in &thorn;e salt watir,</L>
<L>How many kind of creatours &middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e cole duellis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an gert he gomes for to gang &middot; &amp; grayth him a tonn</L>
<L>Of grene glitterand glas &middot; with gerrethis of iren,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t sitt in him-selfe &middot; &amp; with his se&yogh;t persee</L>
<L N="5538">Ane &amp; othire &amp; all &thorn;ing &middot; at outwith it lengid.</L>
<L>Sone was it blawen at a braide &middot; &amp; bro&yogh;t him be-forne,</L>
<L>All boun as he badd &middot; &amp; bunden with cheynes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an of his bald bachelers &middot; &thorn;e biggist out callis,</L>
<L>And ra&yogh;t to &thorn;aim &thorn;ire rekenthis &middot; to rewle &amp; to hald.</L>
<L N="5543">He makis a conand with his kni&yogh;tis &middot; &amp; kend &thorn;aim &thorn;e time,</L>
<L>Howe lange him likid fra &thorn;e lande &middot; to leng in &thorn;e depe,</L>
<L>In at a wicket he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin.</I></NOTE> went &middot; &amp; wynly it speris;</L>
<L>Princes pointid it with pik &middot; &amp; he &thorn;e plunge entres.</L>
<L N="5547">&THORN;are sa&yogh;e he figours of fischis &middot; &amp; fourmes diuerse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kend he neuir so many kindis &middot; ne of so qwaynt hewis.</L>
<L>Sum ferd all on foure feete &middot; &amp; farand as bestis,</L>
<L>Bot quen &thorn;ai blischt on &thorn;is berne &middot; &thorn;an bade &thorn;ai na langir.</L>
<L N="5551">And o&thorn;ir sellis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. seer sellis; <I>with</I> seer <I>struck out</I>.</NOTE> he sa&yogh;e &middot; at sai wald he neuir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ware vnlikly to leue &middot; to any man wittis.</L>
<L>Sone so &thorn;e setnes was gane &middot; &thorn;at him-selfe made,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai dre&yogh;e him vp to &thorn;e drye &middot; &amp; he na dere sufird.</L>
<L>&THORN;an raikis he by &thorn;e reede see &middot; &amp; rides ay &thorn;e sannd,</L>
<L N="5556">Ferly ferre with his<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he, <I>altered to</I> his.</NOTE> folke &middot; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>repeats</I> &amp;.</NOTE> ficchid his tentis,</L>
<L>&THORN;are fande he bestis on &thorn;e brym &middot; with bemes as sawis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ware as bitand breme &middot; as bladis of swerdis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sett in a sadd sowme &middot; &amp; sailid his kni&yogh;tis,</L>
<L N="5560">Porris doun of his princes &middot; &amp; persys &thorn;ar schildis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it fellid his folke of &thorn;aim fey &middot; foure score hundreth,<MILESTONE N="96a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And foure hundreth, &amp; ferre &middot; be fifti, &thorn;ai drepid.
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="273"></L>
<L>&THORN;an driues he &thorn;ethin with his dukis &middot; in-to desert landis,</L>
<L N="5564">Is ri&yogh;t betwene &thorn;e reede see &middot; &amp; Arrabie costis,</L>
<L>A wilsom wast &amp; a wild &middot; &amp; wons full of neddirs,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware hedously hoge &middot; &amp; horned as Tupis.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai turred doun of his tulkis &middot; &amp; with &thorn;ar tyndis slo&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dre&yogh;est deele of &thorn;aim died &middot; of his dukis handis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an past he to a-no&thorn;ir place &middot; &amp; pi&yogh;t doun his tentis,</L>
<L N="5570">And fand a bataill of bestis &middot; as breme as &thorn;e first.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai ware of figour &amp; of fourme &middot; as fendis of hell,</L>
<L>With heuy hedis &amp; hoge &middot; as horses it were.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware tacchid full of tethe &middot; as tyndis ere of harows,</L>
<L>And fell flammes as of fire &middot; flo&yogh;e fra &thorn;aire mouthes.</L>
<L>A selly sowme of his seggis &middot; was slane or he wist,</L>
<L N="5576">And he &thorn;an hertis his here &middot; biddis, "hewis on, my childire;"</L>
<L>And ferly ferd of his folke &middot; was in &thorn;e fild strangild.</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;e dre&yogh;e of &thorn;a deuels &middot; &thorn;ai drenchid or &thorn;ai past.</L>
<L>&THORN;an fondis he furth with his folke &middot; in-to a fild entris,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar he logis with his lordis &middot; &amp; lengis for a quile.</L>
<L>For slike a fell infirmite &middot; was in his hors bunden,</L>
<L N="5582">Bucifalon &thorn;e bald stede &middot; &thorn;at he for bale dies.</L>
<L>&THORN;e berne blischis on his blonke &middot; &amp; se&yogh;es his breth faile,</L>
<L>Sighis seleuthly sare &middot; &amp; sadli he wepis,</L>
<L>For he had standen him in stede &middot; in stouris full hard,</L>
<L>Won him wirschip in were &middot; fra many wathe saued.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynge to &thorn;is carion &middot; he castis his e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Said, "fare wele, my faire foole &middot; &thorn;ou failid me neuire!</L>
<L N="5589">Sall now &thorn;i flesch here be freten &middot; with fowlis &amp; with wormes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has so do&yogh;tyly done? &middot; nay, dri&yogh;tin for-bede!"</L>
<L>&THORN;an bilds he &thorn;are a berynes &middot; &thorn;is beste in-to ligg,</L>
<L>Of schene schemerand gold &middot; as it a schrine ware,</L>
<L N="5593">A tombe as a tabernacle &middot; &amp; tildis vp a cite<MILESTONE N="96b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In reuerence of &thorn;at riche stede &middot; &amp; eftir him it callis.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ridis he to a Reuere &middot; a ruyde &amp; a hoge,
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>Detiraty &thorn;e depe &middot; &thorn;e men &thorn;are it callis;</L>
<L>Fyue thousand Olifants in feree &middot; &thorn;a frithmen him bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A hundreth Mille<NOTE PLACE="foot">I. e. thousand.</NOTE> heuy chargis &middot; ware hewen for &thorn;e were.</L>
<L N="5599">&THORN;an pas he to a proude place &middot; a palas of ioye,</L>
<L>Of Sexis, at sum time &middot; was senyour of Persy.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar fand he garettis all of gold &middot; &amp; gildin chaumbres,</L>
<L>And many a miracle in &thorn;e mote &middot; &thorn;at miche ware to reken.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar fand &thorn;ai bridis in &thorn;a bilds &middot; borely &amp; quite,</L>
<L>Of fe&thorn;ir fresch as any fame &middot; as ere &thorn;ir fedill dowfis,</L>
<L N="5605">&THORN;at see wald of a sekeman &middot; or any sorow ailid,</L>
<L>Que&thorn;ir he suld warisch of &thorn;at waa &middot; or of &thorn;e werd turne.</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ai blithly vp blenkid &middot; &amp; blischt on his face,</L>
<L>&THORN;an suld he couir of his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> care &middot; men knew by &thorn;e takens;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai chaungid opon chaunce &middot; his chere to be-hold,</L>
<L>With-outen doute he was dede &middot; &thorn;an durid he na langir.</L>
<L>Now bowis furth &thorn;is baratour &middot; &amp; Babiloyn he wynnys,</L>
<L N="5612">Brettenes &thorn;e bald kyng &middot; &amp; bringis him of lyue,</L>
<L>Ane Nabizanda was named &middot; &amp; a noble kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Was ane &thorn;e proudest of his pirs &middot; &amp; prince of his ward.</L>
<L>He lengis in lithis &amp; in lee &middot; to his lyues ende,</L>
<L N="5616">A seuen monethis in sonde &middot; &amp; sende out a pistill</L>
<L>To his modire in-to Messedone &middot; &amp; to his maistir als</L>
<L>Of his auntours, of his angwisch &middot; &amp; of his athill werkis,</L>
<L>And Aristotill be-lyue &middot; him anothire writis.</L>
<L N="5620">"To &thorn;e kyng of kyngis," quod &thorn;is clerke &middot; "comande I myselfe.</L>
<L>Sire, quen I waitid on &yogh;our werkis &middot; I wex all affraid</L>
<L>Sum grayne of godhede, I gesse &middot; was growen &yogh;ow within;<MILESTONE N="97a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has said &thorn;at neuir did segge &middot; ne sa&yogh;e bot &thorn;ine ane;
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="275"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it mi&yogh;t neuir, I lofe oure lorde &middot; my lege, &yogh;ow with|stande;</L>
<L>Sire, blissid be all &thorn;i bachelers &middot; at &thorn;e in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> bales helpid!"</L>
<L N="5626">And now fynes here a fitt &middot; &amp; folows a-nothire.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="27" TYPE="passus">
<HEAD><B>Vicesimus septimus passus Alexandri.</B></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oure bold kyng in Babiloun<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Baliloun.</NOTE> &middot; nowe bildis vp a trone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e postis with all &thorn;e apurtynance &middot; as pure as &thorn;e noble,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so wondirly wro&yogh;t &middot; of werkis diuerse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at slike a sege vndire son &middot; was neuire sene eftir.</L>
<L N="5631">So grete garisons of gold &middot; &thorn;e grekis in bro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Medis &amp; &thorn;e Messedons &middot; many horsis chargid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai out of ynde &amp; els-quare &middot; with olifants lede;</L>
<L>It wald haue wlated any wee &middot; &thorn;at welth to be-hald.</L>
<L>Twelfe cubettis fra &thorn;e cald erth &middot; he castis it on hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And xij degreces all of gold &middot; for gate vp of lordis;</L>
<L N="5637">And twyse sex Semylacris &middot; sesid he &thorn;ar-vndire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at held on hi&yogh;e with &thorn;aire handis &middot; all &thorn;ir heuy werke.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar was grauyn in &thorn;os gomes &middot; with grekin letteris,</L>
<L>And titild in &thorn;e tried names &middot; of his twelfe princes.</L>
<L>With ilk a statute &thorn;at &thorn;ar stude &middot; stoutely enarmed,</L>
<L>And euer-ilk a person a prince &middot; payntid was eftir.</L>
<L N="5643">All &thorn;e sete of &thorn;e sege &middot; was smaragdyns fyne,</L>
<L>Off tried topaces &amp; trewe &middot; tyrid was &thorn;e wawes,</L>
<L>A tabernacle ouir &thorn;e trone &middot; tildid vp on<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the margin</I>.</NOTE> loft,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an with stanes of ilka state &middot; wall &thorn;e stoure clustrid.</L>
<L N="5647">A charbocle as a chasse &middot; was in &thorn;e chefe boll,</L>
<L>&THORN;at brynt in bely-blind ni&yogh;t &middot; as bri&yogh;t as &thorn;e son,<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With Imagis vndire in ilka nend &middot; &amp; Impid in &thorn;e names</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;e prouynces &amp; &thorn;e places &middot; &thorn;at he was prince ouire.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai ware visid all in versis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. verser.</NOTE> &middot; in variant lettirs,</L>
<L>Sum in latens lare &middot; sum langage of grece,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="276"></L>
<L N="5653">Assisid all of sex foote &middot; &amp; sett in betwene,</L>
<L>Ay thre paire on a plate &middot; qware a poynt ristis.</L>
<L>Now sall I neuyn &yogh;ow &thorn;e names &middot; note &yogh;e &thorn;e wordis;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e pepill out of Panthi &middot; is plant in first,</L>
<L N="5657">Pruto, Picard, &amp; Pers &middot; &amp; Pamphalie<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Pamplalie.</NOTE> bathe,</L>
<L>Portingale &amp; Paiters &middot; it paies me trouage,</L>
<L>Arrabe &amp; Artoyes &middot; and Assie &thorn;e mare,</L>
<L>Abbeon &amp; Aufrike &middot; &amp; Acres anothire,</L>
<L N="5661">Effosym &amp; Ethiops &middot; &thorn;ire ebrues folke;</L>
<L>All Ermony &amp; Ewrope &middot; enterely me serues,</L>
<L>Ingland, Itaile, &amp; Yndee &middot; &amp; Ireland costis,</L>
<L>Meede &amp; Mesopotayme &middot; &amp; Massedoyne eke;</L>
<L N="5665">Turke, Tuscane, &amp; Troy &middot; and Tartary<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Tartasy.</NOTE> clene,</L>
<L>Surre, Sysyll, &amp; Saarde &middot; &amp; Syres all ouire;</L>
<L>Gyane, Garnad, &amp; Grece &middot; &amp; Gascoyne I haue,</L>
<L>Baxe, Bayon, &amp; Burdeux &middot; &amp; Bretayn &thorn;e graunt,</L>
<L N="5669">Capidos, &amp; Calde &middot; &thorn;e Canony pepill,</L>
<L>Russe, Romayn &amp; Ramys &middot; a rent &thorn;ai vs &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>All Calabree &amp; Corwaile &middot; oure coroun obien,</L>
<L>Bathe naples &amp; Norway &middot; &thorn;ire Nauernes all,</L>
<L>&THORN;e beeris<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic; perhaps for</I> heeris.</NOTE> out of Hungry &middot; &amp; out of haythen Spayn,</L>
<L>Frigie, Flandres, &amp; Fraunce &middot; &amp; Femony vs loutis,</L>
<L>Ascalioun, &amp; Arcagee &middot; all of vs haldis;</L>
<L>Tiree, &amp; Tasse, &amp; Tessale &middot; oure tributars ere,</L>
<L N="5677">Poliponens, &amp; Pentapol &middot; &amp; Palestyne &thorn;e riche.<NOTE PLACE="end"><P><I>The remainder of the story may be briefly paraphrased as follows from the</I> Historia de Preliis:&mdash;</P><P>Alexander next causes a golden crown to be made, adorned with precious stones, with an inscription.</P><P>A certain woman in Babylon is delivered of a monstrous child,
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="277"> the upper half of which is born dead. A soothsayer tells Alexander that it signifies his approaching death.</P><P>At that time there was a man in Macedon named Antipater, who conspired with others to kill Alexander. He designed to do so by poison.</P><P>Antipater procures very strong poison, and sends it to his son Cassander. Cassander instructs his brother Roboas (whom Alex|ander loved, but had chidden for a slight fault) how to convey the poison to Alexander.</P><P>Alexander makes a great feast in Babylon. Roboas puts the poison in a cup, and hands it to Alexander, who drinks it, and cries out, "Help, help!" In falling, his sword pierces his liver; yet he rises again, and bids his guests continue the feast.</P><P>Alexander asks Cassander for a feather, to cause vomiting, and Cassander hands it to him, dipped in poison, which only increases the malady. Alexander passes a sleepless night, during which his lamp goes out. He crawls along on hands and knees to drown him|self in the Euphrates. Roxana stops him, and replaces him in his bed, lamenting. Alexander sends for a notary to make his will.</P><P>The will instructs Aristotle to give a thousand talents of gold to the priests of Egypt. If Roxana gives birth to a boy, he is to be emperor; if to a girl, she is to be empress, married to some princely Macedonian, who is to be made emperor. Let Ptolemy have Egypt and marry Cleopatra; let Cleother have Ethiopia, Antiochus Syria, Arrideus Peloponnesus, Aristus India, Nicanor Seleucia, Ysmachas Hungary, Haulus Armenia, Lyochus Dalmatia and Sicily, Simon the notary Cappadocia and Pelagonia; lastly, let Cassander and Roboas have all as far as the river named Sol, and let their father Antipater have Cilicia.</P><P>When the will was made, there followed thunders and lightnings and great earthquakes, and all the world knew that his death was near. The Macedonians crowd round the palace, demanding to see him, and to know who is to be his successor. He names Perdiccas, to whom he commends Roxana and all his soldiers.</P><P>Then the Macedonians all begin to kiss him and to weep bitterly. Their lamentations are as low thunder, and even the sun is eclipsed.
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="278"></P><P>A certain Macedonian, named Solentius, asks what they shall do when Alexander is gone. They all deplore the great calamity, and think that the great empire will fall to ruins. Alexander directs his crown to be sent to the temple of Apollo, gives instructions for the embalming of his body, directs Ptolemy to erect to his memory a golden sepulchre in Alexandria, and dies.</P><P>After his death, his princes dress the body in imperial state. He is conveyed to Alexandria, and buried in a costly tomb.</P><P>Alexander was of middle height, with a long neck, bright eyes, and ruddy cheeks. The days of his life were thirty-two years and seven months. He began to war at eighteen, and in seven years subdued all the barbarian nations. He was born on the eighth of the kalends of January, and died on the fourth of the kalends of April. He built twelve cities (which are enumerated).</P><P>Alexander's tomb was of gold. It was visited by philosophers, of whom the first said: "Alexander has made his treasure of gold." The second said: "Yesterday all the world was not enough for him; to-day four ells of it suffice him." The third: "Yesterday he ruled the people, to-day the people rule him." The fourth: "Yesterday he could deliver many from death, to-day he could not deliver him|self." The fifth: "Yesterday he led an army out of the city, to-day he is led by it to his burial." The sixth: "Yesterday he pressed the ground, to-day the ground presses on him." The seventh: "Yesterday all nations feared him, to-day they despise him." The last: "Yesterday he had both friends and enemies, to-day all men are alike to him."<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare the Gesta Romanorum, ed. Herrtage (E. E. T. S.), p 516, no. xxxi.</NOTE></P></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>[<I>Here ends the fragment in the</I> Ashmole MS.]</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="story">
<HEAD>The Story of Alexander.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[THE following epitome of the life of Alexander, in English prose, is copied from the Dublin MS., beginning on fol. 45, back.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>Alexander the grete, &thorn;e sone of philip kyng of macedon, which philip regned vij &yogh;ere, and &thorn;e said alexander began to regne in the xviij &yogh;ere of hys age. And he said to hys peple in &thorn;is wise: "Fair lordez, I will in no wise be contrarye to your willes, ne to your dedes. But I schewe to you &thorn;at I hate frawdez &amp; maleces, &amp; as I haue loued you duryng my faders lyff, so will I do in tyme Commyng. And I bothe councell &amp; pray you that &yogh;e drede god, obeye hym as souerayn of all, And chese hym for kyng; &amp; be most obeyssiant to hym &thorn;at shall best purvay for &thorn;e gude astate of hys people, &amp; &thorn;at shall be most debonar &amp; mercifull to pure folkez &thorn;at beste<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;at beste &thorn;at best.</NOTE> woll kepe iustice &amp; &thorn;e right of &thorn;e feble ayenst the mighty; hym also that shall best dispoyse for &thorn;e publyke wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. publyke like wele.</NOTE> &amp; for no dilectacion of wordly<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>A correct form.</I></NOTE> plesaunce shall not be slowefull to kepe &amp; defende you, and by whom &yogh;e shall be defendytt, &amp; all euell &amp; harmez by &thorn;e meane of hys goode dedes shall be distroyed; And he &thorn;at most hardly shall put hym in devour to distroy your enmys; for suche ought to be chosen kyng and none other."
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="280"></P>
<P>And whan hys people had herd hys reasons aboue|said, &amp; knowen his grete discrecion, witte, &amp; vnder|stondyng, thei wer gretly amerveld, and answered to hym &thorn;us: "We haue herd &amp; vnderstand thy grete reasons, And haue resseyued &amp; resseyue thy good Councell, and theirfor we will &amp; beseche the that &thorn;ou regne vppon vs &amp; haue &thorn;e lordship vppon vs. Duryng &thorn;i lyf we hope &thorn;er is none that hase so wele deseruyd to be our kyng." And &thorn;us &thorn;ai chese hym to be &thorn;air king, and Coroned hym, &amp; yaff hym &thorn;air blessyngez, And prayd to god that he wold blesse &amp; maynt[en]e<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. maynte.</NOTE> hym. To whom he said: "I herd &thorn;e prayer that &yogh;e haue made for me, besechyng &thorn;at he wol stedfast &thorn;e loue of me in your hertes &amp; coragez, And &thorn;at by no maner of the delectacion he suffre me do &thorn;at thyng &thorn;at is ayen your profectez ne to my disworship."</P>
<P>And sone after he send letters to all hys princez &amp; good townez of all hys Royaume. And when [he] hed sent hys letters, one Dary, king of perce &amp; of medy, sent to alexandre for tribute like as he hed of hys fadre. And he sent hym word at &thorn;e henne &thorn;at layde &thorn;e gret egge was deyde. And after &thorn;is alexandre made grette conquestes, And conquerd Inde, he went to a cuntree called Bragman; the which when &thorn;ai wist of hys Comyng, &thorn;ai sent mony wise men to hym, whiche salute hym &amp; sayd: "Sir alexander, &thorn;ou hast no cause to werre vppon us, ne to euill willyng; For we be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. be ben.</NOTE> both meke &amp; poure, &amp; we haue no-&thorn;ing bott sapience, the whiche if you will haue, pray god &thorn;at he wyll gyff hir the; for by batayll &thorn;ou shalt neuer hafe hir." And when alexander herd hym say so, he made all hys oste to tarye, &amp; with few of hys knyghtez went within &thorn;e sayd cuntree, for to enquere further of &thorn;e trouth. And when he entred within &thorn;e same ground he found mony poore folkez, women &amp; chyldre all naked, gad|deryng 
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="281"> herbis in &thorn;e feldez. And he asked of &thorn;aim mony questions, to whiche &thorn;ai answerd wisely. And &thorn;an he bad &thorn;aim aske of hym some &thorn;ing &thorn;at might do &thorn;aim good &amp; to all &thorn;air people, and he wold gyff &thorn;aim it gladly. And &thorn;en &thorn;ai said: "Sir, we aixe &thorn;e none other &thorn;ing bot at &thorn;ou wol gyff vs euerlastyng lyfe." Thenne alexander answerd &amp; said: "howe might a man make other mennes liues euerlastyng whan he may not lennthe hys awne life one houre? And &thorn;at &yogh;e axie of me is in no mannez power &thorn;at leueth." Thenne &thorn;ai said to hym: "Seth &thorn;ou hase good know|legh therof, wher trayvelles &thorn;ou &thorn;i-self to distroye all the worlde and gadre all<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. and gadre alle (fol. 46 <I>b</I>) And to gedyr all.</NOTE> &thorn;e wordly tresours, And wotte not when &thorn;ou must lefe &thorn;aim?" Then Alex|ander sayd to hym: "I do nott all &thorn;is at &yogh;e say as of my-self. Butt god hath sent me thrugh all &thorn;e world for texalte<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. to texalte: (texalte = to exalte).</NOTE> and magnifye hys lawe and distroy all &thorn;em &thorn;at beleue not in hym."</P>
<P>And some tyme Alexander wente disgysed visityng hys lordez &amp; enquiryng of &thorn;air dedes. And on a tyme he Come in-to a towne of hys awne, And sawe two men of &thorn;e same towne bifore a iuge pletyng, of the which on said to &thorn;e Iuge: "Sir, I haue boght on house of thys man; And, long after, I haue founde in it a tresour vnder &thorn;e erthe, which is nott myne. And I haue offerd to deliuer it to hym: And he hath refusyd it; wherfore, Sir, I beseche the he be compellyd to take it, for alse moche as he knoweth it is not myne; for I haue no right &thorn;erto." Thenne the Iuge com|maund hys aduersarie parte to answere to &thorn;e same. And &thorn;en he sayd: "sir Iuge, that same tresour was neuer myne; but he hath edyfyed in &thorn;at place that was byfore comyn to all &thorn;oo that wold haue edyfyed ther-in. And &thorn;erfore I haue no right to take it."
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="282"> And &thorn;en &thorn;ai both required &thorn;e Iuge that he wold take it to hym-self; to qwom he answerd &amp; sayd: "sithen it is so that ye say that [ye] haue no right herto, ne he hath no right to whom &thorn;e herytage hath longed and yet bylongeth whar &thorn;e tresour was founden, how shuld I haue ony right &thorn;erto, that am bot a straunger in that caas, And neuer afore herd speke &thorn;erof? And ye wold excuse yow &thorn;erof &amp; yeue me &thorn;e charge of &thorn;e tresoure; which is euyll done." Thenne he askyd of &thorn;aim &thorn;at hed founde &thorn;e tresour, whether thay had ony children? and &thorn;e tone answerd &amp; sayd, he hed a son: and [he] asked &thorn;at other in like wyse, &amp; he sayd, he hed a doghter. And &thorn;en &thorn;e Iuge comaundyd to make a maryage bitwene &thorn;aim two, And at &thorn;ai shuld haue &thorn;e tresour by &thorn;at meane. And when Alexander herd &thorn;is Iugement,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The latter syllable (<I>ment</I>) is written in the middle of the lower margin of the leaf. Fol. 47 <I>begins with</I> he hed.</NOTE> he hed gret mervayle therof, and sayd &thorn;us to &thorn;e Iuge: "I trowe &thorn;er is nott in all &thorn;e world so rightwise a Iuge as &thorn;ou art." And the Iuge, &thorn;at knew hym nott, sayd &amp; asked of hym whether ony Iuge in hys cuntree wold haue done otherwyse: "ye, certanly," sayd alexander, "in many landez." Thenne &thorn;e Iuge, hauyng grete mervayll &thorn;erof, asked of hym whether it rayned and &thorn;e sone dyd shyne in tho landez; as he wold haue sayd, that it was mervayll &thorn;at god shuld send ony light or rayne or other goode thyngez to them that do nott right &amp; trew Iugement. And therfore Alexander had gretter meruayll than by|fore, And said, &thorn;er was bott few suche people vpon erth as &thorn;ai were in &thorn;at land.</P>
<P>And as alexander went owt of &thorn;at land, he passyd thurgh a cite in &thorn;e which all &thorn;e housez of &thorn;at Cyte were of one hight, &amp; byfore &thorn;e dure of euery hous was a grete pitte or graue; in whiche cite &thorn;er was no Iuge, wherof he had gret mervayll; and asked of &thorn;e inhabit|antis 
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="283"> therin wherof such thyngez shuld serue. The which answerd hym &amp; sayd: "First, for &thorn;e outragez<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So in</I> MS.; <I>read</I> outrageouz.</NOTE> hight of housez, loue &amp; Iustice can nott be long a towne emong &thorn;e people." And &thorn;ai sayd, &thorn;e pittez &amp; grauez wer &thorn;air awne housez, to &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ai shuld sone go to, and &thorn;er dwelle vnto &thorn;e day of Iugement. And as tochyng that thai hed no Iuge, &thorn;ai sayd, &thorn;ai made good Iustice of &thorn;em-self, wherfore &thorn;ai nede no Iuge. Thenne Alexander departed from &thorn;aim<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;aim them.</NOTE> right well pleasyd.</P>
<P>And afore hys deth, he wrote a letter vnto hys moder, desering hir to make no sorow for hym. And sone aftir Alexander died &amp; was putt in a coffre of gold, &amp; buried in alexandria with grete reuerence by princez &amp; o&thorn;er grete lordez that keped<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kepeth.</NOTE> &amp; fulfillyd hys testa|ment as he had ordeigned: thenne stert vp one of &thorn;e grettest lordez of &thorn;aim that kept<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. kepth.</NOTE> hym, and sayd &thorn;us: "Thay &thorn;at neuer . . . <NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>The rest of the story is lost</I>.]</NOTE></P>
</DIV1>
